window.EXAM_QUESTIONS = [{"id": 4, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The description of law as supplying tyranny with 'a vocabulary of compliance' chiefly suggests that", "options": {"A": "legal language is inherently violent.", "B": "tyrants invent new words to disguise their crimes.", "C": "labeling an order 'law' can pressure people into obeying it.", "D": "compliance is impossible without proper vocabulary."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The phrase is used to suggest that once an order is described as law, that label itself can pressure people into treating it as binding and obeying it. It is not used to claim that legal language is inherently violent or that tyrants must invent new terms, since the point concerns the persuasive effect of an existing word. The final option misreads the phrase as being about the practical impossibility of compliance rather than its psychological pull.", "passage_id": "P001", "passage_title": "The Content of Law", "passage_text": "Legal positivists insist that the validity of a law depends solely upon its pedigree: was it enacted by the body recognised as having authority to make law, following the procedures that constitution or convention prescribes? Whether the resulting rule is wise, just, or morally defensible is, on this view, a separate question entirely, one for moral philosophy rather than jurisprudence. A statute duly passed by parliament is law even if every serious person regards it as iniquitous, and a decree issued by a body with no such authority is not law however closely it tracks what morality demands.\n\nNatural lawyers reject this separation. For them, an enactment that flagrantly violates the basic requirements of morality forfeits its claim to be law at all; it may be backed by force, but force and law are not the same thing. The Nuremberg trials are the standard illustration: defendants who pleaded that they had merely obeyed the laws of their state were told, in effect, that no enactment authorising such conduct could count as law properly so called, whatever formal procedure had produced it. To call it law would be to grant it a dignity it does not deserve.\n\nThe positivist response is not that morality is irrelevant to law, only that it is irrelevant to the question of legal validity. A judge may, and often should, refuse to apply a rule she finds abhorrent, or campaign for its repeal, but she does this as a moral agent criticising a valid law, not by pretending the law was never made. Keeping the two questions distinct, positivists argue, has a clarifying function: it stops us disguising moral disagreement as a dispute about what the law is, and it stops tyrants borrowing the authority of law for edicts that deserve no such respectability.\n\nNatural lawyers reply that this clarity is bought at too high a price. If validity is purely a matter of pedigree, a state's officials can describe the vilest instructions as binding law and thereby demand the same deference owed to a tax code or a rule of the road. Separating the two questions, on this view, does not protect us from tyranny; it supplies tyranny with a vocabulary of compliance. The disagreement therefore turns less on whether morality matters to law, which both camps concede, than on whether an unjust rule can still be law at all."}, {"id": 9, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What example does the passage use to test whether all duties have a correlative right?", "options": {"A": "The right to a fair trial, used as a familiar illustration.", "B": "The duty not to assault another person, used to explain correlativity itself.", "C": "The right to free expression, mentioned only as background illustration.", "D": "Duties said to be owed to future generations or animals."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage uses duties said to be owed to future generations or non human animals as a test case for whether every duty must have a correlative rights holder. The other examples, such as the right to a fair trial or free expression, are used earlier merely to illustrate familiar rights language, not to test the correlativity thesis. The assault example is used to explain correlativity itself rather than to challenge it.", "passage_id": "P003", "passage_title": "Rights, Duties, and the Grammar of Justice", "passage_text": "It has become natural, at least in modern liberal societies, to state the demands of justice in the language of rights: the right to a fair trial, the right to free expression, the right to bodily integrity. Some philosophers argue that this vocabulary, however familiar, obscures rather than illuminates what justice actually requires, and that duties, not rights, are the more fundamental moral currency.\n\nConsider a right correlative to a duty: my right not to be assaulted is, on reflection, nothing more than everyone else's duty not to assault me, restated from my point of view. If this is so, then whenever we assert a right we are, whether we notice it or not, making a claim about what others owe, and the language of rights is simply a convenient shorthand for a prior structure of duties. Proponents of duty based ethics contend that starting from duties keeps moral attention where it belongs, upon the conduct each of us owes to others, rather than upon what each of us may demand for ourselves; a culture that speaks constantly of rights, they worry, breeds a demanding, self regarding citizenry, quick to insist and slow to give.\n\nRights theorists respond that the correlativity runs in the other direction as well, and that something important is lost if rights are treated as merely derivative. A duty not to assault presupposes some reason why the potential victim matters, why her interests generate a constraint on others' conduct in the first place; and that reason is most naturally expressed by saying that she has a right, grounded in her own standing as a person, not to be assaulted. On this view, duties are intelligible only because rights come first: we owe others our forbearance because they have a claim against us, and the claim is the more basic fact.\n\nThe dispute is not merely terminological, since it bears on hard cases where a plausible duty exists without any obvious rights holder to whom it is owed, such as duties said to be owed to future generations or to non human animals. If duties can exist independently of correlative rights, the rights first picture faces a genuine gap; if all duties ultimately answer to somebody's right, defenders of that picture must explain who holds the right that grounds our duty to protect people not yet born."}, {"id": 17, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'forfeits, on this view, much of what distinguishes his act from ordinary crime' is used to suggest that", "options": {"A": "evading arrest is a more serious crime than the original offence.", "B": "avoiding punishment blurs the line between conscientious protest and self interested lawbreaking.", "C": "all protestors who are arrested are guilty of ordinary crime.", "D": "the law treats disobedience and crime identically regardless of intent."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The phrase indicates that a protestor who avoids arrest undermines the very feature that separates conscientious civil disobedience from ordinary, self interested lawbreaking. It does not suggest that evading arrest is a worse offence than the original one, nor that all arrested protestors are criminals, nor that the law treats disobedience and crime identically. The point concerns how onlookers judge the protestor's motives, not formal legal classification.", "passage_id": "P005", "passage_title": "The Limits of Conscientious Refusal", "passage_text": "Civil disobedience is usually defined as a public, non violent breach of law, undertaken openly and with willingness to accept the legal penalty, intended to protest a law or policy believed to be seriously unjust. So defined, it is distinguished both from ordinary crime, which seeks to escape punishment and typically serves private ends, and from revolutionary violence, which aims to overthrow the legal order rather than appeal to its own professed principles.\n\nDefenders argue that a democracy which forbids all disobedience, however conscientious, mistakes formal legality for genuine legitimacy. A law passed by a majority can still trample a minority's basic interests, and where ordinary channels of protest and reform have been tried and have failed, a carefully limited breach of law may be the only way to force a complacent majority to confront an injustice it would otherwise ignore. The civil rights sit ins are the standard example: illegal, deliberately public, accepted with the willingness to be arrested, and aimed not at private gain but at exposing a law's injustice to a wider public whose conscience the protestors sought to engage.\n\nYet even sympathetic theorists insist that the description above marks out limits, not merely a permission. Willingness to accept punishment is treated as essential precisely because it signals that the protestor still accepts the legitimacy of the legal order as a whole, and is contesting only this law or policy, not law as such; a disobedient who evades arrest while claiming the mantle of civil disobedience forfeits, on this view, much of what distinguishes his act from ordinary crime. Similarly, the requirement of non violence is treated as more than a tactical preference: violent methods, defenders of the tradition argue, corrode the very trust between citizens on which any future peaceful resolution depends, and risk provoking repression that harms bystanders who never consented to the campaign.\n\nCritics press a harder question: why should conscientious lawbreakers accept limits that make their protest more costly to themselves, if the underlying injustice is severe enough to justify breaking the law at all? The standard reply is that the limits are not arbitrary burdens imposed on protestors but the very features that let onlookers distinguish principled resistance from self interest, and thereby let civil disobedience retain the persuasive, conscience appealing force that a lawless or violent alternative would forfeit."}, {"id": 20, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What is the standard reply to critics who question why conscientious lawbreakers should accept costly limits?", "options": {"A": "The limits exist mainly to protect the police from liability.", "B": "The limits are outdated and should be abandoned.", "C": "The limits are what allow onlookers to distinguish principled protest from self interest.", "D": "The limits guarantee that protestors will never be punished."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The standard reply given in the passage is that the limits on civil disobedience let onlookers distinguish principled resistance from self interested lawbreaking, preserving its persuasive force. The passage does not suggest the limits exist to protect police from liability or that they guarantee protestors avoid punishment, since willingness to accept punishment is central to the definition. Nor does it treat the limits as outdated, instead defending their continued necessity.", "passage_id": "P005", "passage_title": "The Limits of Conscientious Refusal", "passage_text": "Civil disobedience is usually defined as a public, non violent breach of law, undertaken openly and with willingness to accept the legal penalty, intended to protest a law or policy believed to be seriously unjust. So defined, it is distinguished both from ordinary crime, which seeks to escape punishment and typically serves private ends, and from revolutionary violence, which aims to overthrow the legal order rather than appeal to its own professed principles.\n\nDefenders argue that a democracy which forbids all disobedience, however conscientious, mistakes formal legality for genuine legitimacy. A law passed by a majority can still trample a minority's basic interests, and where ordinary channels of protest and reform have been tried and have failed, a carefully limited breach of law may be the only way to force a complacent majority to confront an injustice it would otherwise ignore. The civil rights sit ins are the standard example: illegal, deliberately public, accepted with the willingness to be arrested, and aimed not at private gain but at exposing a law's injustice to a wider public whose conscience the protestors sought to engage.\n\nYet even sympathetic theorists insist that the description above marks out limits, not merely a permission. Willingness to accept punishment is treated as essential precisely because it signals that the protestor still accepts the legitimacy of the legal order as a whole, and is contesting only this law or policy, not law as such; a disobedient who evades arrest while claiming the mantle of civil disobedience forfeits, on this view, much of what distinguishes his act from ordinary crime. Similarly, the requirement of non violence is treated as more than a tactical preference: violent methods, defenders of the tradition argue, corrode the very trust between citizens on which any future peaceful resolution depends, and risk provoking repression that harms bystanders who never consented to the campaign.\n\nCritics press a harder question: why should conscientious lawbreakers accept limits that make their protest more costly to themselves, if the underlying injustice is severe enough to justify breaking the law at all? The standard reply is that the limits are not arbitrary burdens imposed on protestors but the very features that let onlookers distinguish principled resistance from self interest, and thereby let civil disobedience retain the persuasive, conscience appealing force that a lawless or violent alternative would forfeit."}, {"id": 28, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What vulnerability does the passage say the hypothetical version of contract theory introduces?", "options": {"A": "It makes the theory too complicated for ordinary citizens to understand.", "B": "It cannot generate obligation in the way an actual promise does, only a standard of fairness.", "C": "It requires unanimous agreement among all current citizens to function.", "D": "It relies on evidence from anthropology that critics find unreliable."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage explains that because no one actually makes the hypothetical agreement, it cannot bind individuals the way a real promise would and can only indicate what a just arrangement would look like. It does not discuss complexity for ordinary citizens, a requirement of unanimous present-day agreement, or anthropological evidence, none of which the text raises. This is presented as the trade-off for escaping the historical-implausibility objection.", "passage_id": "P007", "passage_title": "Consent We Never Gave", "passage_text": "The idea that political obligation rests upon a social contract has always faced an awkward objection: no living citizen ever signed anything. We were born into a state, absorbed its language and customs before we could reason about them, and found ourselves subject to its laws long before any moment of deliberate agreement could have occurred. To describe obedience to the state as the fulfilment of a promise is, on this view, a polite fiction dressed up as political philosophy, useful perhaps for legitimizing authority after the fact but incapable of explaining why that authority binds us in the first place.\n\nDefenders of contract theory have long anticipated this objection and offered a subtler formulation in response. The contract, they say, need not be an historical event or an explicit signature; it can instead be understood as hypothetical, a thought experiment asking what terms free and reasonable people would accept if they were negotiating the basic structure of their society from a position of equality. On this reading, the contract is not a record of what actually happened but a standard against which existing arrangements can be tested. A law or institution is legitimate to the degree that it could plausibly have been agreed to by parties reasoning in good faith about their mutual advantage, not because any particular generation actually consented to it.\n\nThis move rescues the theory from historical implausibility, but it introduces a different vulnerability. A hypothetical agreement, precisely because no one actually made it, cannot generate obligation in the ordinary sense that a real promise does; it can only tell us what a just arrangement would look like, which is a different and more limited achievement. Critics therefore argue that hypothetical contract theory quietly abandons the original ambition of explaining why we are bound and settles instead for a theory of justice wearing the contract's borrowed clothes. Whether this is a fatal weakness or an acceptable trade depends on what one expects political philosophy to deliver: a genuine account of obligation binding each of us personally, or a workable standard by which institutions we did not choose might still be judged fair."}, {"id": 29, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the relativist's central objection to universal human rights as described in the passage?", "options": {"A": "Rights claimed to be universal actually reflect a particular Western historical trajectory imposed on other societies.", "B": "International institutions lack the funding to enforce rights consistently across every member state involved worldwide.", "C": "No society has ever agreed to abide by any catalogue of rights proposed by outside institutions.", "D": "Universalists have never attempted to justify their claims philosophically, relying instead purely on institutional authority alone."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The relativist argument set out in the first paragraph is that the specific rights now called universal emerged from a Western European and North American trajectory and are presented as neutral while actually being parochial and imposed. The passage never mentions institutional funding, universal non-agreement by any society, or an accusation that universalists never attempt justification, since the second paragraph shows them replying with one. The objection concerns the concealed particularity of origin, not enforcement or absence of argument.", "passage_id": "P008", "passage_title": "Whose Universal?", "passage_text": "Proponents of universal human rights claim to speak on behalf of every person, regardless of where she was born or what traditions shaped her upbringing. Critics from within the relativist tradition regard this claim with suspicion, arguing that the specific catalogue of rights now presented as universal, freedom of expression, gender equality, individual autonomy over marriage and religion, emerged from a particular historical trajectory in Western Europe and North America and cannot simply be exported to societies organized around different premises about the relationship between individual and community. What looks like a neutral, universal standard, the relativist argues, is in fact a parochial standard wearing the mask of neutrality, imposed on others through the moral authority of international institutions rather than negotiated with them.\n\nThe universalist reply does not deny that the language of rights has a traceable history, but it distinguishes the origin of an idea from its justification. That the abolition of slavery was first argued for in a particular place and time does not make the wrongness of slavery a merely local truth; a claim's cultural birthplace tells us nothing about whether the claim is correct. On this view, the fact that a right was first articulated in Europe is no more relevant to its universal validity than the fact that a mathematical theorem was first proved by a Greek tells us anything about whether the theorem holds in Asia.\n\nThe difficulty with this reply is that rights, unlike theorems, are not self-evidently true from first principles; they rest on contestable claims about human dignity, flourishing, and the proper scope of individual choice against communal obligation, claims that different traditions have answered differently for centuries without any of them being simply mistaken in the way a false mathematical proof is mistaken. The universalist cannot merely assert that her framework is correct and others parochial; she must show why competing accounts of the human good are wrong, and this is precisely the argument that appeals to origin or authorship can never supply. The debate therefore turns not on where an idea came from but on whether anyone, universalist or relativist, can offer a justification for it that does not simply presuppose the conclusion they already hold."}, {"id": 34, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Why does the passage say no uncontroversial metric exists for the cardinal version of proportionality?", "options": {"A": "Because different forms of harm and degrees of culpability cannot be converted onto one agreed scale.", "B": "Because judges are not adequately trained to apply sentencing guidelines.", "C": "Because sentencing laws differ too much between countries to compare.", "D": "Because juries rather than judges are responsible for determining sentence length."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage explains that harm can take physical, financial, or psychological forms that do not convert into one another, and culpability depends on multiple disputable factors like intention and capacity, so no single agreed measure can calibrate punishment to wrongdoing. It does not attribute the difficulty to judicial training, cross-country legal variation, or the jury's role in sentencing, none of which the text mentions. The problem identified is conceptual disagreement over measurement, not an institutional or procedural failing.", "passage_id": "P009", "passage_title": "The Measure of the Punishment", "passage_text": "The principle that punishment should be proportionate to the offence is so widely accepted that it rarely receives scrutiny, yet the moment one tries to specify what proportionality actually requires, the concept becomes considerably harder to pin down than its intuitive appeal suggests. Proportionality is sometimes treated as a simple ordinal ranking: more serious crimes should receive harsher sentences than less serious ones, and a sentencing scale should preserve this ordering throughout. This weak version of the principle is nearly impossible to reject, but it is also nearly empty, since it says nothing about how severe any particular sentence should actually be, only that the ranking between offences must be respected.\n\nA stronger, cardinal version of proportionality demands not merely that worse crimes receive worse punishment but that the punishment be calibrated to some independent measure of the wrongdoing's severity, so that the harshness of the sentence tracks, in some meaningful sense, the gravity of the harm done and the culpability of the offender. The difficulty is that no uncontroversial metric for this calibration exists. Harm can be measured in terms of physical injury, financial loss, or psychological damage, and these do not convert into one another on any agreed scale; culpability depends on intention, recklessness, provocation, and capacity, each of which admits of degree and dispute. Two reasonable observers, applying the same theory of proportionality in good faith, can therefore reach markedly different conclusions about how many years a particular offence deserves.\n\nSome theorists respond by abandoning the search for an absolute metric and instead anchor proportionality comparatively, asking only that similar offences committed with similar culpability receive similar sentences across cases, regardless of what the absolute level of severity should be. This comparative approach trades the ambition of justifying any particular sentence in isolation for the more modest goal of consistency across a system, and it is open to the objection that an entire sentencing scale could be uniformly too harsh or too lenient while still satisfying comparative proportionality perfectly. A system might treat like cases alike and still, taken as a whole, be radically unjust in the punishment it hands down to everyone within it."}, {"id": 36, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What objection does the passage raise against the comparative approach to proportionality?", "options": {"A": "It is too expensive for most court systems to implement in practice.", "B": "An entire sentencing scale could be uniformly too harsh or lenient while still satisfying it.", "C": "It ignores the culpability of offenders entirely when setting sentences.", "D": "It requires unanimous agreement among all judges in a jurisdiction."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The final paragraph states that a system could treat like cases alike and thereby satisfy comparative proportionality perfectly while still being, as a whole, radically unjust because the entire scale is set too harshly or too leniently. It does not raise cost of implementation, disregard for culpability, or a need for judicial unanimity, none of which the passage discusses. The objection targets the comparative approach's silence on absolute severity, not its administrative feasibility.", "passage_id": "P009", "passage_title": "The Measure of the Punishment", "passage_text": "The principle that punishment should be proportionate to the offence is so widely accepted that it rarely receives scrutiny, yet the moment one tries to specify what proportionality actually requires, the concept becomes considerably harder to pin down than its intuitive appeal suggests. Proportionality is sometimes treated as a simple ordinal ranking: more serious crimes should receive harsher sentences than less serious ones, and a sentencing scale should preserve this ordering throughout. This weak version of the principle is nearly impossible to reject, but it is also nearly empty, since it says nothing about how severe any particular sentence should actually be, only that the ranking between offences must be respected.\n\nA stronger, cardinal version of proportionality demands not merely that worse crimes receive worse punishment but that the punishment be calibrated to some independent measure of the wrongdoing's severity, so that the harshness of the sentence tracks, in some meaningful sense, the gravity of the harm done and the culpability of the offender. The difficulty is that no uncontroversial metric for this calibration exists. Harm can be measured in terms of physical injury, financial loss, or psychological damage, and these do not convert into one another on any agreed scale; culpability depends on intention, recklessness, provocation, and capacity, each of which admits of degree and dispute. Two reasonable observers, applying the same theory of proportionality in good faith, can therefore reach markedly different conclusions about how many years a particular offence deserves.\n\nSome theorists respond by abandoning the search for an absolute metric and instead anchor proportionality comparatively, asking only that similar offences committed with similar culpability receive similar sentences across cases, regardless of what the absolute level of severity should be. This comparative approach trades the ambition of justifying any particular sentence in isolation for the more modest goal of consistency across a system, and it is open to the objection that an entire sentencing scale could be uniformly too harsh or too lenient while still satisfying comparative proportionality perfectly. A system might treat like cases alike and still, taken as a whole, be radically unjust in the punishment it hands down to everyone within it."}, {"id": 49, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the author's central claim about the presumption of innocence?", "options": {"A": "It is a cost free rule that guarantees justice for all parties involved.", "B": "It should be abandoned for offences that are difficult to prove.", "C": "It is a deliberate wager accepting wrongful acquittals to avoid wrongful convictions.", "D": "It applies only to offences committed in private with no witnesses."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage describes the asymmetry underlying the presumption as a moral judgment that deliberately tolerates some wrongful acquittals in order to avoid the graver harm of wrongful convictions. This framing is made explicit in the closing paragraph, which calls the principle a considered wager rather than a costless rule. The other options either contradict the passage's stated position or attach a limitation to the principle that the passage does not include.", "passage_id": "P013", "passage_title": "The Price of the Presumption", "passage_text": "The presumption of innocence, the principle that an accused person is treated as innocent until proven guilty beyond reasonable doubt, is frequently described as the cornerstone of a fair criminal justice system. Its rationale is straightforwardly asymmetric: wrongly convicting an innocent person is considered a far graver injustice than wrongly acquitting a guilty one, so the system deliberately tilts the evidentiary burden toward the defence. This asymmetry is not a neutral technical rule but a moral judgment about which kind of error society is prepared to tolerate more readily.\n\nThat moral judgment carries a cost that is rarely stated as plainly as the principle itself. A high evidentiary threshold guarantees that some proportion of guilty defendants will walk free, not because the evidence against them was weak but because it fell short of the demanding standard the system requires. Victims and their families bear this cost directly, often watching a case collapse not for lack of a plausible culprit but for lack of proof meeting an exacting bar. Defenders of the presumption argue that this cost, however real, is preferable to the alternative, in which the state routinely imprisons people on the basis of suspicion rather than demonstrated guilt.\n\nA further complication arises in cases involving offences that are notoriously difficult to prove, such as certain sexual offences committed in private with no witnesses beyond the parties involved. Here the presumption of innocence, applied with full rigour, can produce acquittal rates that some commentators regard as evidence the system is systematically failing complainants rather than evidence the system is functioning as designed. Proposals to lower the evidentiary bar specifically for such offences have been floated periodically, but they run directly against the principle that the standard of proof should not vary according to the category of crime charged, since doing so would effectively presume guilt for anyone accused of that category.\n\nThe presumption of innocence is therefore best understood not as a rule without costs but as a considered wager, one that accepts a known rate of wrongful acquittal as the price of avoiding a much less tolerable rate of wrongful conviction. Whether that wager remains justified in categories of offence where proof is unusually difficult to obtain is a live question, but abandoning the uniform standard of proof to answer it would introduce a different and arguably graver injustice of its own."}, {"id": 53, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What distinction does the author propose to resolve tension within group rights?", "options": {"A": "A distinction between religious groups and indigenous nations.", "B": "A distinction between rights held by individuals and rights held by no one.", "C": "A distinction between rights recognised by the state and rights recognised by custom.", "D": "A distinction between restrictions necessary for group survival and those merely entrenching leadership."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage's final paragraph explicitly proposes distinguishing restrictions a group imposes to maintain its own existence from restrictions that merely entrench current leadership over dissenters. Only the former, it argues, can be justified by appeal to the collective good the group right protects. The other options describe distinctions the passage does not draw or introduces only in passing as background rather than as its proposed resolution.", "passage_id": "P014", "passage_title": "Whose Rights Are They?", "passage_text": "Liberal rights theory has traditionally located the bearer of rights in the individual person, on the ground that only individuals, not the groups to which they belong, are capable of suffering, choosing, or flourishing. On this view, a right claimed on behalf of a religious community or an indigenous nation is, properly understood, shorthand for a bundle of individual rights held by the community's members, and any apparent conflict between group rights and individual rights is really a conflict between the rights of some individuals and the rights of others.\n\nCritics of this reduction argue that certain goods cannot be secured by aggregating individual entitlements, however generously those entitlements are defined. A living language, for instance, depends on a critical mass of speakers using it in shared institutions, schools, courts, and public life; no individual right to speak a language in private conversation can protect the language from extinction if the surrounding community stops using it collectively. On this account, some rights, such as the right of a linguistic or cultural minority to maintain its institutions, are irreducibly collective, belonging to the group as such rather than distributable among its members.\n\nThis distinction matters because group rights, once recognised as genuinely collective, can come into direct tension with the rights of individual members of the very group being protected. A cultural group granted authority to regulate its own internal affairs may use that authority to restrict the choices of members who wish to leave the group, marry outside it, or reject its customs, precisely the kind of restriction that individual rights are meant to guard against. Defenders of group rights respond that a group without any capacity to maintain internal cohesion cannot survive long enough to protect anyone, member or otherwise, and that some degree of internal restriction is the price of the collective good the group right is meant to secure.\n\nResolving this tension requires distinguishing restrictions a group imposes to maintain its own existence from restrictions that merely entrench the power of its current leadership over dissenting members. The former can be defended as necessary to the collective good the right protects, while the latter cannot be justified by appeal to that good at all, since entrenching leadership serves no purpose beyond the leadership's own preservation. A workable theory of group rights therefore needs an internal limit, not merely an external one drawn against the wider state."}, {"id": 55, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "According to the passage, how might a cultural group's internal authority conflict with individual rights?", "options": {"A": "by requiring the group to disband entirely once internal disagreement arises.", "B": "by transferring all decision making power to the wider state.", "C": "by restricting members who wish to leave, marry outside, or reject the group's customs.", "D": "by preventing the group from maintaining any shared institutions whatsoever."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage states that a cultural group granted internal authority may restrict members who wish to leave the group, marry outside it, or reject its customs, exactly the kind of restriction individual rights are meant to guard against. This tension is presented as arising from within the group rather than from external interference by the state. The other options describe outcomes the passage does not attribute to this conflict.", "passage_id": "P014", "passage_title": "Whose Rights Are They?", "passage_text": "Liberal rights theory has traditionally located the bearer of rights in the individual person, on the ground that only individuals, not the groups to which they belong, are capable of suffering, choosing, or flourishing. On this view, a right claimed on behalf of a religious community or an indigenous nation is, properly understood, shorthand for a bundle of individual rights held by the community's members, and any apparent conflict between group rights and individual rights is really a conflict between the rights of some individuals and the rights of others.\n\nCritics of this reduction argue that certain goods cannot be secured by aggregating individual entitlements, however generously those entitlements are defined. A living language, for instance, depends on a critical mass of speakers using it in shared institutions, schools, courts, and public life; no individual right to speak a language in private conversation can protect the language from extinction if the surrounding community stops using it collectively. On this account, some rights, such as the right of a linguistic or cultural minority to maintain its institutions, are irreducibly collective, belonging to the group as such rather than distributable among its members.\n\nThis distinction matters because group rights, once recognised as genuinely collective, can come into direct tension with the rights of individual members of the very group being protected. A cultural group granted authority to regulate its own internal affairs may use that authority to restrict the choices of members who wish to leave the group, marry outside it, or reject its customs, precisely the kind of restriction that individual rights are meant to guard against. Defenders of group rights respond that a group without any capacity to maintain internal cohesion cannot survive long enough to protect anyone, member or otherwise, and that some degree of internal restriction is the price of the collective good the group right is meant to secure.\n\nResolving this tension requires distinguishing restrictions a group imposes to maintain its own existence from restrictions that merely entrench the power of its current leadership over dissenting members. The former can be defended as necessary to the collective good the right protects, while the latter cannot be justified by appeal to that good at all, since entrenching leadership serves no purpose beyond the leadership's own preservation. A workable theory of group rights therefore needs an internal limit, not merely an external one drawn against the wider state."}, {"id": 60, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'qualified only at its genuine edges' is used to convey that...", "options": {"A": "the obligation to obey law has been entirely dissolved by King's argument.", "B": "King's framework applies primarily to laws concerning property disputes.", "C": "only judges are permitted to determine which laws are unjust.", "D": "the general obligation to obey law remains mostly intact with narrow, specific exceptions."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Describing the obligation as qualified only at its genuine edges conveys that the general duty to obey law survives King's argument largely unchanged, with exceptions limited to a narrow and specific category. This phrasing signals continuity of the obligation rather than its dissolution. The other readings mistake a phrase about scope for a claim about total abolition, subject matter, or exclusive judicial authority.", "passage_id": "P015", "passage_title": "Obedience and Its Limits", "passage_text": "A long tradition in political philosophy holds that citizens owe some measure of obedience to the law simply because it is the law, independent of whether any particular statute strikes them as wise or just. This obligation is typically grounded not in the content of individual laws but in broader considerations, the benefits citizens receive from a functioning legal order, the fairness of accepting the burdens of a system from which one has taken the benefits, or the value of predictable coordination that only widespread compliance can secure.\n\nMartin Luther King's Letter from Birmingham Jail offers one of the most carefully argued challenges to an unqualified version of this obligation. King distinguished between just and unjust laws, defining an unjust law as one that a numerical or power majority imposes on a minority without that minority having had any part in enacting or being able to alter it, or one that is not binding on the majority itself. Crucially, King did not argue that unjust laws may simply be ignored; he insisted that a person breaking an unjust law must do so openly, lovingly, and with a willingness to accept the penalty, precisely in order to demonstrate the highest respect for law in general even while defying a particular statute.\n\nThis qualification matters because it separates civil disobedience from ordinary lawbreaking in a way that preserves rather than undermines the case for a general obligation to obey. A thief who evades detection asserts no principle beyond personal advantage, while a protester who accepts arrest and punishment for violating an unjust law appeals to a standard, justice, that the legal system itself claims to serve, thereby holding the system to its own professed ideals rather than rejecting the idea of law altogether.\n\nThe remaining difficulty is that reasonable people disagree, sometimes sharply, about which laws are unjust in King's sense, and a general permission to disobey any law one sincerely believes unjust would dissolve the coordinating function that gives law much of its value in the first place. King's framework survives this difficulty only because it demands more than sincere belief: it requires that the law in question demonstrably exclude the affected minority from the process of enacting or altering it, a comparatively narrow and testable condition rather than an open invitation to disobey whatever one personally dislikes. Understood this way, the obligation to obey ordinary law remains largely intact, qualified only at its genuine edges."}, {"id": 72, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The closing description of injustice becoming a routine feature rather than an occasional error is best read as achieving which effect?", "options": {"A": "It reassures the reader that collective punishment is a temporary and rare phenomenon.", "B": "It shifts blame for injustice entirely onto individual wrongdoers within the group.", "C": "It suggests the problem has already been solved by international humanitarian law.", "D": "It signals an escalation from isolated error to a systemic pattern of wrongdoing."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The contrast between an occasional error and a routine feature is used to mark a shift in scale, from something exceptional to something built into the ordinary operation of a system. This closing phrase intensifies the passage's warning rather than offering reassurance. It does not attribute the resulting injustice to individual offenders, nor does it suggest the issue is already resolved.", "passage_id": "P018", "passage_title": "The Injustice of Collective Punishment", "passage_text": "Collective punishment, the practice of imposing a penalty on a group for the wrongdoing of some of its members, has been condemned in international humanitarian law for over a century, yet it persists in more subtle forms even within societies that would never openly endorse it. Curfews imposed on an entire neighbourhood after disturbances attributed to a few residents, the withdrawal of privileges from a whole class because of one pupil's misconduct, the collective fining of a workforce for the acts of a handful of employees, all share a structure in which many bear a cost for wrongs they did not commit.\n\nThe central objection is one of desert. Punishment is supposed to be a response to what a person has done, tracking individual responsibility, and a system that instead distributes burdens across a group regardless of participation abandons this link entirely. It punishes the innocent alongside the guilty, and in doing so treats membership in a group, rather than conduct, as the relevant basis for suffering a sanction. This is precisely the feature that separates punishment from mere misfortune imposed by authority.\n\nDefenders of group sanctions sometimes argue that they serve a legitimate deterrent purpose that individual punishment cannot replicate, since a community aware that it will share the costs of a member's wrongdoing has an incentive to police itself, informing on offenders and discouraging the conduct in the first place. There is undoubtedly some truth in the claim that shared consequences can alter behaviour within a group. But an argument from deterrence is not an argument from justice, and a policy may succeed in changing conduct while still treating those it burdens wrongly. Efficiency in reducing future harm cannot, by itself, license punishing someone for an act in which they had no hand.\n\nThere is also a practical danger in normalising this reasoning, since a state willing to sanction groups for the acts of individuals has less incentive to develop the harder capacity, identifying and proving individual guilt, on which a fair system of justice ultimately depends. Once collective liability becomes an acceptable substitute for that harder task, the pressure to do the careful work of attributing responsibility to particular persons diminishes, and injustice to the innocent becomes not an occasional error but a routine feature of how order is kept."}, {"id": 77, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the traditional justification given in the passage for treating ignorance of the law as no excuse?", "options": {"A": "Most citizens are assumed to have studied the relevant statutes before acting.", "B": "Allowing the excuse would make uniform enforcement depend on proving what each citizen knew.", "C": "Ignorance of the law is considered morally equivalent to intentional wrongdoing.", "D": "Courts lack the time to hear arguments about a defendant's state of knowledge."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage explains that permitting the excuse would tie legal liability to how informed a particular citizen happened to be, and would burden prosecutors with the near impossible task of proving actual knowledge. Uniform application instead requires treating everyone as if they knew the law's content. The passage does not claim citizens have studied the statutes, treat ignorance as morally equivalent to intent, or ground the rule in court scheduling constraints.", "passage_id": "P020", "passage_title": "Ignorance of the Law and the Limits of Excuse", "passage_text": "The maxim that ignorance of the law is no excuse is one of the oldest and least examined principles of criminal justice. It is usually defended on grounds of necessity, if a defendant could escape liability simply by asserting that she did not know an act was prohibited, the law's authority would depend entirely on how well informed each citizen happened to be, and prosecutors would face the near impossible task of proving what a person knew rather than what she did. Uniform application of the law, on this reasoning, requires that everyone be treated as if they knew its content, whether or not this is true of any particular defendant.\n\nThe difficulty is that modern legal systems have grown so vast and technical that the assumption underlying the maxim, that a person of ordinary diligence could discover the relevant rule, no longer holds for large areas of regulation. A shopkeeper who unknowingly breaches an obscure licensing requirement buried in secondary legislation is not obviously in the same moral position as a person who commits an act universally understood to be wrong, such as theft or assault. The first has failed to master an administrative thicket that even specialists struggle to navigate, while the second has ignored a norm no reasonable person could claim not to know.\n\nSome jurisdictions have responded to this gap by permitting a defence where the law in question was not published or made reasonably available before the alleged offence, or where the defendant took genuine steps to ascertain the legal position and was misled by an official source. This narrower exception does not abandon the general rule so much as recognise that fair notice, not mere formal enactment, is what gives a prohibition its claim to bind the citizen who breaks it.\n\nA more sweeping proposal would extend excuse to any case where a defendant honestly and reasonably believed her conduct was lawful, regardless of the source of that belief. Such a rule risks inviting exactly the evidentiary chaos the traditional maxim was designed to avoid, since a defendant's claimed beliefs are notoriously difficult to verify or refute. The more defensible position lies between these extremes, preserving the general presumption of knowledge for conduct any reasonable citizen would recognise as wrong, while carving out room for excuse where the law itself has failed to give fair and accessible notice of what it demands."}, {"id": 83, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage suggest actually distinguishes a legal rule from a merely moral one?", "options": {"A": "A settled practice of citing, interpreting and adjusting behaviour by reference to it.", "B": "The certainty that violators will always be punished swiftly by some competent authority.", "C": "Formal ratification by an elected legislature acting according to a fixed constitutional procedure.", "D": "Universal agreement among all nations on its exact content and precise meaning."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The final sentence of the passage states this directly as the true test of legal status, rather than the presence of a policeman. It is offered as the criterion that international law satisfies through ongoing courtroom practice. The other options describe features that domestic law itself does not always possess, undermining their use as the defining test.", "passage_id": "P021", "passage_title": "Law Without a Sovereign", "passage_text": "It has long been fashionable among certain jurists to deny international law the title of law at all, on the ground that it lacks the one feature thought indispensable to any legal system: a sovereign body capable of compelling obedience. Domestic statutes are backed by police, courts and prisons; a treaty, by contrast, is backed by nothing more than the willingness of states to keep their word, and states, being sovereign, cannot be coerced in the way that individuals can. From this observation it is a short step to the conclusion that what passes for international law is really a set of moral or diplomatic conventions dressed up in legal vocabulary, obeyed only when obedience happens to suit the obeying party.\n\nThis argument, though superficially persuasive, rests on a narrower conception of law than the one lawyers actually use when describing their own domestic systems. Much of contract law, for instance, is followed daily by millions of citizens who never contemplate the possibility of a lawsuit, let alone imprisonment; compliance there is driven overwhelmingly by habit, reputation and the practical benefits of cooperation, not by fear of the bailiff. If we accept that domestic law can command such voluntary compliance and still count as law, it becomes difficult to explain why an identical pattern of voluntary compliance among states should be dismissed as something other than law merely because the compliers happen to be nations rather than individuals.\n\nThe critics will respond that domestic law always has coercion standing behind it as a last resort, however rarely invoked, whereas international law frequently has no such backstop at all. There is force in this reply, and it is true that certain areas of international law, particularly those governing the conduct of hostile states, remain notoriously difficult to enforce. Yet enforcement gaps of this kind are a matter of degree rather than kind: weak domestic states also struggle to enforce judgments against powerful factions within their own borders, and nobody concludes from this that their statutes cease to be law. What actually distinguishes a legal rule from a merely moral one is not the presence of a policeman but the existence of a settled practice of treating the rule as binding, of citing it, interpreting it and adjusting behaviour by reference to it. International law satisfies that test in courtroom after courtroom, even when the courtroom in question has no army to send."}, {"id": 84, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What is the effect of describing international law as \"dressed up in legal vocabulary\" in the first paragraph?", "options": {"A": "It signals neutral academic caution about a contested term.", "B": "It praises the sophistication of international legal drafting.", "C": "It conveys the sceptics' implication that the label of law is a disguise.", "D": "It suggests that international lawyers invented new vocabulary deliberately."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The phrase is presented as part of the sceptical position being summarised before the author challenges it. Describing something as merely dressed up implies that its outward form misrepresents its true, lesser nature. The word choice therefore conveys dismissiveness on the part of the critics rather than the author's own settled view, which the following paragraphs go on to contest.", "passage_id": "P021", "passage_title": "Law Without a Sovereign", "passage_text": "It has long been fashionable among certain jurists to deny international law the title of law at all, on the ground that it lacks the one feature thought indispensable to any legal system: a sovereign body capable of compelling obedience. Domestic statutes are backed by police, courts and prisons; a treaty, by contrast, is backed by nothing more than the willingness of states to keep their word, and states, being sovereign, cannot be coerced in the way that individuals can. From this observation it is a short step to the conclusion that what passes for international law is really a set of moral or diplomatic conventions dressed up in legal vocabulary, obeyed only when obedience happens to suit the obeying party.\n\nThis argument, though superficially persuasive, rests on a narrower conception of law than the one lawyers actually use when describing their own domestic systems. Much of contract law, for instance, is followed daily by millions of citizens who never contemplate the possibility of a lawsuit, let alone imprisonment; compliance there is driven overwhelmingly by habit, reputation and the practical benefits of cooperation, not by fear of the bailiff. If we accept that domestic law can command such voluntary compliance and still count as law, it becomes difficult to explain why an identical pattern of voluntary compliance among states should be dismissed as something other than law merely because the compliers happen to be nations rather than individuals.\n\nThe critics will respond that domestic law always has coercion standing behind it as a last resort, however rarely invoked, whereas international law frequently has no such backstop at all. There is force in this reply, and it is true that certain areas of international law, particularly those governing the conduct of hostile states, remain notoriously difficult to enforce. Yet enforcement gaps of this kind are a matter of degree rather than kind: weak domestic states also struggle to enforce judgments against powerful factions within their own borders, and nobody concludes from this that their statutes cease to be law. What actually distinguishes a legal rule from a merely moral one is not the presence of a policeman but the existence of a settled practice of treating the rule as binding, of citing it, interpreting it and adjusting behaviour by reference to it. International law satisfies that test in courtroom after courtroom, even when the courtroom in question has no army to send."}, {"id": 87, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What does the phrase \"romantic picture\" suggest about the author's attitude toward the defenders' historical examples?", "options": {"A": "That the examples are fabricated.", "B": "That the author fully endorses the defenders' account.", "C": "That the examples belong to an entirely separate legal tradition.", "D": "That the account is appealing but incomplete or idealised."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Calling the defenders' account a romantic picture signals that it is emotionally attractive while glossing over inconvenient complications, which the next sentence goes on to supply. This is a stylistic hinge that moves the passage from summarising one side to introducing its critique. The word does not suggest the examples are invented, merely that the framing built around them is one sided.", "passage_id": "P022", "passage_title": "The Conscience of the Jury Box", "passage_text": "Jury nullification occurs when a jury, satisfied beyond reasonable doubt that the defendant committed the act charged, nonetheless returns a verdict of not guilty because it judges that convicting would be unjust in the particular circumstances before it. Defenders of the practice point to a long and, in places, celebrated history: juries that refused to convict under harsh eighteenth century property statutes, or that acquitted defendants prosecuted under laws later recognised as morally indefensible. On this view, nullification is a democratic safety valve, allowing ordinary citizens to inject community standards of fairness into a system that might otherwise apply rules mechanically and, on occasion, cruelly.\n\nCritics reply that this romantic picture obscures a more troubling reality. A jury that nullifies is not applying community standards in any accountable sense; it is substituting its own unreviewable judgment for the judgment of a legislature that was itself elected to represent the community and that debated the relevant law openly before enacting it. Twelve individuals, deliberating in secret and answerable to no one, are handed the power to override that process on the strength of sympathies that may be generous in one case and prejudiced in another. History supplies uncomfortable examples of nullification working in precisely the opposite direction from the one its defenders like to celebrate, as when juries in earlier eras acquitted defendants accused of violence against unpopular minorities, plainly out of sympathy with the perpetrators rather than any considered sense of injustice in the law itself.\n\nThe deeper difficulty is that nullification cannot be confined to the cases its supporters have in mind. A power exercised invisibly, without reasons and without appeal, cannot be calibrated to activate only for laws that some later generation will regard as unjust. It is available equally to the juror who thinks a particular tax law is an inconvenience and to the juror who thinks a particular defendant simply does not deserve punishment because of who he is. Perhaps this unpredictability is a price worth paying for retaining a check on legislative overreach; perhaps it is not. What cannot be sustained is the claim that nullification is a tidy corrective mechanism, reliably steering outcomes toward justice rather than merely toward whatever a given jury happens to feel."}, {"id": 90, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the realists' central challenge to the formalist account, as presented in the passage?", "options": {"A": "That judges never read statutes before ruling.", "B": "That rules leave more room for judicial discretion than formalism admits.", "C": "That appellate courts should be abolished entirely.", "D": "That all judicial decisions are equally unpredictable."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage states the realists did not deny that judges cite rules but argued the rules rarely determine outcomes as tightly as formalists suggest. This challenge concerns the degree of constraint rules actually provide, particularly in hard cases, rather than a blanket claim about unpredictability everywhere. The passage also confines this challenge mainly to appellate level disputes rather than all decisions.", "passage_id": "P023", "passage_title": "Rules on Paper and Rules in Practice", "passage_text": "The formalist tells a comforting story about how judges decide cases. A dispute arrives, the relevant statute or precedent is identified, its language is parsed according to settled interpretive conventions, and the answer emerges through a process resembling deduction more than choice. On this account, the judge's personal views are, or ought to be, entirely irrelevant; the law itself, properly read, supplies the outcome, and the judge merely reports what that outcome is. The appeal of this picture is obvious. It preserves the idea that law is a body of stable, predictable rules rather than a shifting set of preferences dressed in robes, and it underwrites the claim that judicial decisions are legitimate because they are constrained rather than invented.\n\nThe legal realists of the early twentieth century mounted a sustained challenge to this story, not by denying that judges cite rules, but by insisting that the rules rarely determine outcomes as tightly as the formalist picture implies. Statutory language is frequently ambiguous, precedents can be read broadly or narrowly depending on which features of the earlier case a judge chooses to emphasise, and competing canons of interpretation often point in opposite directions within the very same dispute. Faced with this latitude, realists argued, judges reach a conclusion through something closer to intuition, shaped by temperament, background and a sense of what result seems fair, and only afterward construct a formal justification dressed in the vocabulary of deduction.\n\nIt would be a mistake to read the realist position as claiming that law is simply arbitrary, a mere mask for unconstrained judicial will. Realists generally accepted that rules narrow the range of plausible outcomes considerably, that professional norms and the discipline of appellate review restrain the wildest departures, and that most easy cases really are decided by straightforward rule application with little room for disagreement. Their target was narrower and more precise: the hard cases, the ones that reach appellate courts precisely because reasonable lawyers disagree about what the rule requires, are where the formalist story breaks down most visibly, and it is exactly these cases that shape the law students remember and the precedents that later courts must apply."}, {"id": 95, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage imply about whether courts maintain the distinction described in the final paragraph?", "options": {"A": "Courts have abolished victim impact statements as a result.", "B": "The passage treats this as an open question with mixed evidence.", "C": "The distinction has been proven impossible to apply in any court.", "D": "All courts apply the distinction perfectly and consistently."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage's closing sentence states directly that whether courts maintain this distinction as carefully as the theory demands is a separate question on which the evidence is mixed. This leaves the matter genuinely unresolved rather than settled in either direction. It does not claim courts have abolished the practice or that the distinction is unworkable everywhere.", "passage_id": "P024", "passage_title": "A Voice at Sentencing", "passage_text": "Victim impact statements, now a familiar feature of sentencing hearings in many jurisdictions, allow those harmed by a crime to describe to the court, often in their own words, how the offence has affected their lives. Advocates present this as a modest and overdue correction to a system that had historically treated the victim as little more than a witness, a source of evidence rather than a person with a stake in the outcome. Allowing the victim to speak, on this account, restores a measure of dignity that the adversarial process otherwise strips away, and gives the sentencing judge a fuller picture of the human consequences behind the abstract charge sheet.\n\nOpponents worry that this apparently humane innovation quietly imports something the criminal justice system was built to exclude: the intensity of the victim's suffering as a determinant of punishment. Two defendants who commit identical offences, causing identical physical harm, may face very different sentences if one victim is articulate, sympathetic and devastated in a way the court finds moving, while the other is reserved, less able to express loss, or simply less compelling as a witness to their own suffering. Punishment, the objection runs, should track the culpability of the offender and the seriousness of the act, matters that do not vary with the eloquence or misfortune of the person harmed, and a sentencing system that lets the latter influence the former risks treating like cases unlike.\nThere is a reply available to the advocate, though it requires some care. It is not that victim testimony should set the sentence, but that it can supply information genuinely relevant to culpability, such as whether the offender knew of a victim's particular vulnerability and exploited it, or whether the harm caused was substantially graver than an average case of the same offence would produce. Understood this way, the statement is not a plea for sympathy weighed against another victim's stoicism, but evidence bearing on facts a sentencing judge is already entitled to consider. Whether courts in practice maintain this distinction as carefully as the theory demands is a separate question, and one on which the available evidence is decidedly mixed."}, {"id": 100, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the function of the final sentence, which distinguishes hollow consent from \"ordinary hard bargains\"?", "options": {"A": "To argue that all hard bargains should be struck down by courts.", "B": "To suggest that unequal luck or skill is itself a bargaining defect.", "C": "To mark the intended limit of the doctrine so it does not swallow ordinary bargaining outcomes.", "D": "To conclude that the doctrine should be abolished entirely."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The sentence closes the passage by clarifying that the two element test is meant to leave untouched bargains that are merely hard fought rather than genuinely hollow in consent. This directly answers the critics' worry from the previous paragraph by showing the doctrine has a deliberately narrow intended reach. It does not argue for striking down all hard bargains or for abolishing the doctrine, both of which contradict the passage's overall defence of it.", "passage_id": "P025", "passage_title": "The Bargain Nobody Would Freely Strike", "passage_text": "Freedom of contract rests on a simple and attractive premise: two competent adults, each pursuing their own interests, will not agree to terms unless each expects to be better off than without the agreement, and the state has no business second guessing bargains that both parties freely chose. Courts that enforce contracts as written, whatever their content, present themselves as respecting autonomy rather than substituting their own judgment for that of the parties who actually negotiated the deal.\n\nThe doctrine of unconscionability exists because this premise, however attractive, does not describe every transaction that carries the outward form of a freely negotiated agreement. Consider a borrower facing an emergency, with no realistic alternative source of funds, who signs a loan agreement carrying terms that no one with genuine bargaining options would ever accept, or an elderly signatory whose diminished understanding of the document's terms is quietly exploited by a counterparty who drafted the language precisely to obscure its effect. In cases such as these, the label of consent conceals an absence of the very thing consent is supposed to guarantee, namely a genuine choice among realistic alternatives made with adequate understanding of what is being agreed.\n\nCritics of the doctrine object that unconscionability invites judges to rewrite bargains after the fact according to their own sense of fairness, undermining the predictability that makes contract law valuable in the first place. If a term can be struck down whenever a court later decides it was too harsh, then no contracting party can ever be fully certain which terms will actually be enforced, and the very stability the law of contract exists to provide is placed in jeopardy. This is a genuine cost, and courts applying the doctrine have generally tried to answer it by confining relief to cases combining two distinct elements, a serious defect in the process of bargaining, such as an absence of realistic alternatives or exploited incapacity, and a resulting term whose substance is so one sided that no informed party could sensibly have agreed to it. Requiring both elements together, rather than either alone, is intended to reserve the doctrine for bargains where consent was genuinely hollow, leaving ordinary hard bargains, freely struck between parties who simply had unequal luck or skill, untouched."}, {"id": 103, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What does the writer identify as the real distinguishing feature of a healthy separation of powers?", "options": {"A": "Three completely isolated branches with no shared functions.", "B": "A written constitution establishing rigid boundaries.", "C": "Mutual checks preventing any branch acting on its own authority.", "D": "An executive drawn directly from the legislature."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage states plainly that what separates a healthy system from a dysfunctional one is the presence of mutual checks rather than the absence of overlap. The idea of three completely isolated branches is explicitly rejected as a rigid, geometric ideal the writer moves away from, and a written constitution establishing rigid boundaries is never mentioned as a requirement. An executive drawn from the legislature describes a parliamentary feature offered only as one possible mechanism among others, not as the defining criterion itself.", "passage_id": "P026", "passage_title": "Separation of Powers", "passage_text": "The doctrine that governmental power ought to be divided among distinct branches is often traced to Montesquieu, though its practical value rests less on its pedigree than on a simple observation: those who write the rules, those who enforce them, and those who judge disputes arising from them are rarely trustworthy when combined in a single pair of hands. A legislature that could also prosecute its critics would soon legislate itself into permanence. An executive empowered to interpret the very statutes it enforces would face no meaningful restraint at all. It is not that lawmakers, ministers, and judges are especially prone to corruption as individuals; rather, institutions accumulate incentives, and unchecked power is corrosive regardless of who wields it.\n\nCritics of strict separation point out that modern government could not function if the branches were hermetically sealed from one another. Executives routinely propose legislation, judges effectively make law through interpretation, and legislatures conduct quasi-judicial proceedings such as impeachment. The American system, often held up as the purest embodiment of the doctrine, in fact relies on considerable overlap: the president nominates judges, the senate confirms them, and courts can strike down acts of congress. What separates a healthy system from a dysfunctional one, then, is not the absence of overlap but the presence of mutual checks, so that no single branch can act entirely on its own authority without the cooperation, or at least the tolerance, of another.\n\nThis reframing matters because it shifts attention away from a rigid, almost geometric ideal of three perfectly isolated boxes and toward a more dynamic picture: power distributed such that ambition counteracts ambition. A parliamentary system, in which the executive is drawn from and remains accountable to the legislature, might appear to violate separation altogether, yet it can achieve the same restraining effect through different means, such as votes of confidence, select committee scrutiny, and an independent judiciary that reviews administrative action. The lesson is that the mechanism matters less than the outcome: that no organ of the state should be able to govern by fiat, immune from correction by another organ with a genuinely independent basis of authority.\n\nThe danger, of course, is that constitutional design can only do so much. Where a legislature is dominated by a single party willing to defer to the executive on every matter, the formal separation of institutions may mask an effective concentration of power that no organizational chart would reveal."}, {"id": 106, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "How do defenders of judicial review respond to the charge that courts lack democratic legitimacy?", "options": {"A": "By arguing equal standing is a precondition for democracy, not a limit on it.", "B": "By claiming judges are directly accountable to the electorate.", "C": "By insisting supermajority requirements are unnecessary in a true democracy.", "D": "By conceding that judicial review is undemocratic but necessary anyway."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage reports that defenders reframe minority protection as a background condition for democracy to be genuine, rather than an external constraint on it, so protecting minorities is presented as earning the label democracy rather than limiting it. The suggestion that judges are directly accountable to the electorate is false, since no such accountability is described. The claim that supermajority requirements are unnecessary misstates the passage, which lists them as part of the conventional remedy, and the idea that defenders concede judicial review is undemocratic but necessary contradicts the actual argument, which denies rather than concedes that charge.", "passage_id": "P027", "passage_title": "Majoritarianism versus Minority Rights", "passage_text": "Democracy is frequently defined, in shorthand, as rule by the majority, yet this definition conceals a paradox that has troubled political theorists since antiquity: a majority, once vested with unlimited authority, can use democratic procedure to entrench permanent disadvantage upon a minority, thereby producing an outcome that is procedurally democratic but substantively oppressive. Tocqueville named this the tyranny of the majority, warning that the same moral force which legitimates democratic decision-making can, unchecked, crush dissenting or unpopular groups with a thoroughness that no single tyrant could match, since the majority's decisions carry the presumed sanction of the whole community.\n\nThe conventional remedy has been constitutionalism: entrenched rights, independent courts, and supermajority requirements for certain kinds of change, all designed to place some matters beyond the reach of ordinary majorities. Yet this remedy generates its own difficulty. If a court can strike down legislation passed by elected representatives in order to protect a minority interest, on what basis does that court's judgment carry greater democratic legitimacy than the legislature's? Defenders of judicial review answer that democracy is not merely a decision procedure but a set of background conditions, including the equal standing of all citizens, without which majority rule cannot claim to speak for the people at all. On this view, protecting minorities is not a limitation on democracy imposed from outside but a precondition without which the label democracy is not properly earned.\n\nCritics of this defense worry that it proves too much, since almost any policy disagreement can be redescribed as a question of fundamental equal standing, inviting judges to override elected choices under the guise of principle. A more modest position holds that only a narrow category of interests, those bound up with the basic ability to participate in political life at all, such as voting rights or freedom of political speech, warrant this kind of insulation, while ordinary policy disputes, however consequential, should remain subject to majority revision.\n\nWhatever position one adopts, the underlying tension cannot be dissolved entirely. Any workable democracy must find some means of allowing majorities to govern while denying them the power to abolish the very conditions that make future majorities meaningful, and no formula has yet closed that gap without leaving difficult cases at the margin."}, {"id": 110, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What problem does the passage identify with hypothetical consent as a solution?", "options": {"A": "It requires citizens to sign a written agreement they later forget.", "B": "It contradicts the functional theory of legitimacy entirely.", "C": "It replaces an actual choice with a speculative claim about what one would choose.", "D": "It applies only to citizens who were born abroad."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage states that hypothetical consent rescues the theory only by trading a factual claim for a speculative one, since reasoning about what someone would have agreed to is not the same as an actual choice made. The idea of a written agreement citizens later forget invents a document never mentioned in the text. The claim that this contradicts the functional theory entirely wrongly asserts a direct contradiction between the two theories when the passage instead treats them as separate traditions with separate weaknesses, and the suggestion that the objection applies only to citizens born abroad misapplies it, since the objection concerns all citizens regardless of birthplace.", "passage_id": "P028", "passage_title": "The Legitimacy of the State", "passage_text": "Every state claims the right to command obedience and to punish those who refuse it, yet the mere fact that a government possesses the power to compel compliance does not answer the separate question of whether it is entitled to do so. A robber who holds a gun to a traveller's head can extract compliance just as effectively as a tax authority, but only one of these exercises of power is generally regarded as legitimate. The difference, philosophers have long argued, must lie somewhere other than in the bare capacity to enforce demands.\n\nSocial contract theory locates that difference in consent: citizens are bound to obey because they have, in some sense, agreed to the arrangement, whether through an original founding compact, ongoing participation in political life, or the benefits they knowingly accept from living within the state's protection. The difficulty is that few citizens can point to any moment of actual agreement, and many are born into political communities whose terms they never had the opportunity to negotiate. Hypothetical consent, the idea that people would have agreed under fair conditions, rescues the theory from this objection only by trading a factual claim for a speculative one, since no amount of reasoning about what a person would have chosen substitutes for a choice they never in fact made.\n\nAn alternative tradition grounds legitimacy not in consent but in the state's function: a government is entitled to obedience insofar as it does what only a state can do, namely resolve disputes, provide common goods, and protect rights that would otherwise remain unenforceable amid competing private claims. On this functional account, legitimacy is a matter of degree rather than an all-or-nothing status, since a state that performs these tasks poorly, or that protects some citizens while abandoning others, possesses a correspondingly weaker claim on obedience, whatever its formal constitutional pedigree.\n\nNeither account fully escapes difficulty. Consent theories struggle to explain why birth within a territory should bind anyone at all, while functional theories risk collapsing legitimacy into mere effectiveness, implying that an efficient authoritarian regime might rival a floundering democracy in its claim to rule. What both traditions share, however, is the recognition that coercion alone, however smoothly administered, never supplies its own justification."}, {"id": 111, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "According to the functional account described, why might legitimacy vary between different governments?", "options": {"A": "Because it is graded according to how well a state performs its core functions.", "B": "Because legitimacy depends entirely on how a constitution was originally written.", "C": "Because only democratically elected governments can ever be legitimate.", "D": "Because legitimacy is fixed permanently once a state is founded."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage explains that on the functional account legitimacy is a matter of degree, so a state performing its tasks poorly or unevenly has a correspondingly weaker claim to obedience. The suggestion that legitimacy depends entirely on how a constitution was originally written misattributes the criterion to constitutional origin rather than to ongoing performance. The claim that only democratically elected governments can ever be legitimate is not supported, since the functional account is explicitly compatible with even authoritarian regimes having some claim to legitimacy, and the idea that legitimacy is fixed permanently once a state is founded contradicts the passage's emphasis on legitimacy varying rather than being fixed.", "passage_id": "P028", "passage_title": "The Legitimacy of the State", "passage_text": "Every state claims the right to command obedience and to punish those who refuse it, yet the mere fact that a government possesses the power to compel compliance does not answer the separate question of whether it is entitled to do so. A robber who holds a gun to a traveller's head can extract compliance just as effectively as a tax authority, but only one of these exercises of power is generally regarded as legitimate. The difference, philosophers have long argued, must lie somewhere other than in the bare capacity to enforce demands.\n\nSocial contract theory locates that difference in consent: citizens are bound to obey because they have, in some sense, agreed to the arrangement, whether through an original founding compact, ongoing participation in political life, or the benefits they knowingly accept from living within the state's protection. The difficulty is that few citizens can point to any moment of actual agreement, and many are born into political communities whose terms they never had the opportunity to negotiate. Hypothetical consent, the idea that people would have agreed under fair conditions, rescues the theory from this objection only by trading a factual claim for a speculative one, since no amount of reasoning about what a person would have chosen substitutes for a choice they never in fact made.\n\nAn alternative tradition grounds legitimacy not in consent but in the state's function: a government is entitled to obedience insofar as it does what only a state can do, namely resolve disputes, provide common goods, and protect rights that would otherwise remain unenforceable amid competing private claims. On this functional account, legitimacy is a matter of degree rather than an all-or-nothing status, since a state that performs these tasks poorly, or that protects some citizens while abandoning others, possesses a correspondingly weaker claim on obedience, whatever its formal constitutional pedigree.\n\nNeither account fully escapes difficulty. Consent theories struggle to explain why birth within a territory should bind anyone at all, while functional theories risk collapsing legitimacy into mere effectiveness, implying that an efficient authoritarian regime might rival a floundering democracy in its claim to rule. What both traditions share, however, is the recognition that coercion alone, however smoothly administered, never supplies its own justification."}, {"id": 113, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What central rhetorical move does the passage identify as defining populism?", "options": {"A": "Appealing to voters through emotional rather than policy-based campaigning during national election seasons.", "B": "Dividing society into a pure people and a corrupt elite, with one authentic spokesperson.", "C": "Promising economic redistribution to lower income groups through new state administered welfare programs.", "D": "Rejecting all forms of representative government outright in favour of direct unmediated rule."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage opens by identifying the core move as splitting society into two antagonistic camps, the people and the elite, with the movement claiming sole authentic representation of the former. The suggestion of emotional versus policy-based campaigning introduces a claim the passage never makes. The mention of economic redistribution is an unsupported assumption about content, and the claim of rejecting all representative government outright overstates the position, since the final paragraph explicitly distinguishes populism from simply rejecting representative government.", "passage_id": "P029", "passage_title": "Populism and Democracy", "passage_text": "Populism resists tidy definition, but most scholars agree on its central rhetorical move: the division of society into two homogeneous and antagonistic camps, the pure people on one side and a corrupt, self-serving elite on the other, with the populist leader or movement claiming to be the sole authentic voice of the former against the latter. This framing is not merely a campaign strategy but a distinctive theory of political legitimacy, one that regards the will of the people, understood as a single unified entity, as morally superior to any institution, procedure, or expert body that might stand in its way.\n\nThe appeal of this framing is not difficult to trace. Representative institutions, however necessary, inevitably create distance between citizens and decisions made in their name, and that distance breeds suspicion that intermediaries, whether politicians, bureaucrats, judges, or journalists, are pursuing agendas of their own rather than faithfully transmitting the popular will. Populist movements offer the seductive promise of closing that distance entirely, restoring an unmediated connection between leader and people that bypasses the checks which representative systems were designed to provide. Where those checks are experienced as obstruction rather than protection, the populist critique lands with considerable force.\n\nYet the same framing that gives populism its emotional power also supplies its greatest danger to democratic practice. If the people are conceived as a single, unified will, then any institution that constrains or delays that will, an independent judiciary, a free press, or a constitutionally protected minority, can be recast not as a legitimate safeguard but as an illegitimate obstacle placed between the people and their rightful rule. Pluralism, the recognition that citizens hold genuinely divergent and irreconcilable interests, is thereby denied rather than merely outvoted, since dissenters are cast as inauthentic members of the people rather than as fellow citizens with a rival view.\n\nThis is why serious critics distinguish populism from mere popularity or robust majoritarian politics. A movement can appeal to ordinary citizens against entrenched interests without denying the legitimacy of institutional checks; it becomes populist in the more troubling sense only when it insists that such checks are, by their very nature, betrayals of a singular popular will that admits no internal disagreement."}, {"id": 114, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "Why does the passage suggest representative institutions are vulnerable to the populist critique?", "options": {"A": "Because they are always controlled by corrupt officials.", "B": "Because they were designed without any input from ordinary citizens.", "C": "Because populist leaders control the media coverage of institutions.", "D": "Because the distance they create can breed suspicion of intermediaries."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The second paragraph explains that representative institutions inevitably create distance between citizens and decisions, and that distance breeds suspicion that intermediaries pursue their own agendas rather than transmitting the popular will faithfully. The claim that institutions are always controlled by corrupt officials asserts actual corruption as fact, which the passage does not claim, only that suspicion arises. The suggestion that institutions were designed without any citizen input is not discussed at all, and the claim that populist leaders control media coverage introduces a point absent from the text.", "passage_id": "P029", "passage_title": "Populism and Democracy", "passage_text": "Populism resists tidy definition, but most scholars agree on its central rhetorical move: the division of society into two homogeneous and antagonistic camps, the pure people on one side and a corrupt, self-serving elite on the other, with the populist leader or movement claiming to be the sole authentic voice of the former against the latter. This framing is not merely a campaign strategy but a distinctive theory of political legitimacy, one that regards the will of the people, understood as a single unified entity, as morally superior to any institution, procedure, or expert body that might stand in its way.\n\nThe appeal of this framing is not difficult to trace. Representative institutions, however necessary, inevitably create distance between citizens and decisions made in their name, and that distance breeds suspicion that intermediaries, whether politicians, bureaucrats, judges, or journalists, are pursuing agendas of their own rather than faithfully transmitting the popular will. Populist movements offer the seductive promise of closing that distance entirely, restoring an unmediated connection between leader and people that bypasses the checks which representative systems were designed to provide. Where those checks are experienced as obstruction rather than protection, the populist critique lands with considerable force.\n\nYet the same framing that gives populism its emotional power also supplies its greatest danger to democratic practice. If the people are conceived as a single, unified will, then any institution that constrains or delays that will, an independent judiciary, a free press, or a constitutionally protected minority, can be recast not as a legitimate safeguard but as an illegitimate obstacle placed between the people and their rightful rule. Pluralism, the recognition that citizens hold genuinely divergent and irreconcilable interests, is thereby denied rather than merely outvoted, since dissenters are cast as inauthentic members of the people rather than as fellow citizens with a rival view.\n\nThis is why serious critics distinguish populism from mere popularity or robust majoritarian politics. A movement can appeal to ordinary citizens against entrenched interests without denying the legitimacy of institutional checks; it becomes populist in the more troubling sense only when it insists that such checks are, by their very nature, betrayals of a singular popular will that admits no internal disagreement."}, {"id": 115, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What is the effect of describing the people, in populist rhetoric, as a \"single, unified will\"?", "options": {"A": "It emphasizes that populist movements are always more organized than their rivals.", "B": "It proves that populist leaders never hold genuine electoral support.", "C": "It shows how disagreement among citizens can be recast as inauthenticity.", "D": "It suggests that unified will is a goal shared by all democratic theories."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Casting the people as a single unified will allows the framing to treat any dissent as evidence that the dissenter is not a true member of the people at all, which is precisely the danger the third paragraph describes. Reading the phrase as being about organizational capacity rather than rhetorical framing misreads its purpose. The claim that populist leaders never hold genuine electoral support is an unsupported and overly strong claim, and the suggestion that a unified will is a goal shared by all democratic theories wrongly generalizes a populist assumption to traditions the passage treats as pluralist and therefore opposed to this idea.", "passage_id": "P029", "passage_title": "Populism and Democracy", "passage_text": "Populism resists tidy definition, but most scholars agree on its central rhetorical move: the division of society into two homogeneous and antagonistic camps, the pure people on one side and a corrupt, self-serving elite on the other, with the populist leader or movement claiming to be the sole authentic voice of the former against the latter. This framing is not merely a campaign strategy but a distinctive theory of political legitimacy, one that regards the will of the people, understood as a single unified entity, as morally superior to any institution, procedure, or expert body that might stand in its way.\n\nThe appeal of this framing is not difficult to trace. Representative institutions, however necessary, inevitably create distance between citizens and decisions made in their name, and that distance breeds suspicion that intermediaries, whether politicians, bureaucrats, judges, or journalists, are pursuing agendas of their own rather than faithfully transmitting the popular will. Populist movements offer the seductive promise of closing that distance entirely, restoring an unmediated connection between leader and people that bypasses the checks which representative systems were designed to provide. Where those checks are experienced as obstruction rather than protection, the populist critique lands with considerable force.\n\nYet the same framing that gives populism its emotional power also supplies its greatest danger to democratic practice. If the people are conceived as a single, unified will, then any institution that constrains or delays that will, an independent judiciary, a free press, or a constitutionally protected minority, can be recast not as a legitimate safeguard but as an illegitimate obstacle placed between the people and their rightful rule. Pluralism, the recognition that citizens hold genuinely divergent and irreconcilable interests, is thereby denied rather than merely outvoted, since dissenters are cast as inauthentic members of the people rather than as fellow citizens with a rival view.\n\nThis is why serious critics distinguish populism from mere popularity or robust majoritarian politics. A movement can appeal to ordinary citizens against entrenched interests without denying the legitimacy of institutional checks; it becomes populist in the more troubling sense only when it insists that such checks are, by their very nature, betrayals of a singular popular will that admits no internal disagreement."}, {"id": 116, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "How does the final paragraph's distinction between popularity and populism function in the passage's argument?", "options": {"A": "It narrows the criticism to movements that treat institutional checks as inherently illegitimate.", "B": "It concedes that all majoritarian movements are equally dangerous to democracy.", "C": "It suggests that popularity and populism are simply two words for the same phenomenon.", "D": "It argues that no movement can ever be popular without becoming populist."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The closing distinction refines the passage's critique so that it applies specifically to movements insisting institutional checks are betrayals of a singular popular will, rather than to any movement that is merely popular or majoritarian. The suggestion that this concedes all majoritarian movements are equally dangerous contradicts this narrowing, since the passage explicitly separates ordinary majoritarian appeal from the troubling sense of populism. Treating popularity and populism as simply two words for the same phenomenon directly contradicts the point of drawing a distinction at all, and the claim that no movement can ever be popular without becoming populist overstates the claim into an inevitability the passage never asserts.", "passage_id": "P029", "passage_title": "Populism and Democracy", "passage_text": "Populism resists tidy definition, but most scholars agree on its central rhetorical move: the division of society into two homogeneous and antagonistic camps, the pure people on one side and a corrupt, self-serving elite on the other, with the populist leader or movement claiming to be the sole authentic voice of the former against the latter. This framing is not merely a campaign strategy but a distinctive theory of political legitimacy, one that regards the will of the people, understood as a single unified entity, as morally superior to any institution, procedure, or expert body that might stand in its way.\n\nThe appeal of this framing is not difficult to trace. Representative institutions, however necessary, inevitably create distance between citizens and decisions made in their name, and that distance breeds suspicion that intermediaries, whether politicians, bureaucrats, judges, or journalists, are pursuing agendas of their own rather than faithfully transmitting the popular will. Populist movements offer the seductive promise of closing that distance entirely, restoring an unmediated connection between leader and people that bypasses the checks which representative systems were designed to provide. Where those checks are experienced as obstruction rather than protection, the populist critique lands with considerable force.\n\nYet the same framing that gives populism its emotional power also supplies its greatest danger to democratic practice. If the people are conceived as a single, unified will, then any institution that constrains or delays that will, an independent judiciary, a free press, or a constitutionally protected minority, can be recast not as a legitimate safeguard but as an illegitimate obstacle placed between the people and their rightful rule. Pluralism, the recognition that citizens hold genuinely divergent and irreconcilable interests, is thereby denied rather than merely outvoted, since dissenters are cast as inauthentic members of the people rather than as fellow citizens with a rival view.\n\nThis is why serious critics distinguish populism from mere popularity or robust majoritarian politics. A movement can appeal to ordinary citizens against entrenched interests without denying the legitimacy of institutional checks; it becomes populist in the more troubling sense only when it insists that such checks are, by their very nature, betrayals of a singular popular will that admits no internal disagreement."}, {"id": 124, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "Which best describes the passage's overall conclusion about the federalism versus centralism debate?", "options": {"A": "Centralism is proven superior for crisis management.", "B": "Federalism always produces better citizens than centralism.", "C": "The debate is purely a matter of administrative cost.", "D": "The outcome depends on empirical facts about citizen engagement, not abstract principle."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The closing sentence states directly that the debate turns on the empirical question of whether regional institutions can command real attention and loyalty, rather than on abstract principle. The other options overstate the case for one side or reduce the entire discussion to a single factor the passage treats as only part of the picture. The correct option captures the passage's actual, more cautious conclusion.", "passage_id": "P031", "passage_title": "The Case for Divided Power", "passage_text": "Those who defend federal arrangements often argue that dividing sovereignty between a central authority and constituent regions is not merely a practical compromise but a positive good in itself. The claim rests on more than administrative convenience; it holds that concentrating all legislative and fiscal power in a single capital invites both incompetence and tyranny, since no single body of legislators can possess sufficient local knowledge to govern effectively across a diverse territory, and no single body should be trusted with so much unchecked authority. Federalists therefore present their arrangement as a system of mutual restraint: central government checks the excesses of regional parochialism, while regional government checks the overreach of the centre.\n\nCritics of this view, the centralists, retort that federal systems purchase this supposed safety at an unacceptable price: administrative duplication, inconsistent standards of justice and welfare between regions, and a chronic incapacity to respond swiftly to national emergencies. When a pandemic or financial crisis strikes, they observe, it strikes the whole nation at once, and a government that must first negotiate with a dozen semi-sovereign provinces before acting is a government that will act too late. Better, they say, to accept the risks of concentrated power than the certainty of paralysis.\n\nThere is a further, subtler argument advanced by federalism's defenders, one that has little to do with efficiency at all. They contend that a federal structure cultivates a habit of political participation that centralism cannot replicate. Citizens who see their regional assemblies making real decisions, over education, policing, or local taxation, are citizens who come to regard government as something they shape rather than something merely imposed upon them. Centralism, on this account, produces subjects; federalism produces citizens who practise self-government in miniature before they are ever asked to exercise it on the national stage.\n\nYet this argument, however appealing, assumes a citizenry already disposed to engage with regional politics. Where regional assemblies are viewed with the same detachment as national ones, the promised apprenticeship in self-government simply fails to occur, and the federal structure delivers only its costs, duplication and unevenness, without its supposed civic benefit. The debate therefore turns less on abstract principle than on the empirical question of whether regional institutions can actually command the attention and loyalty of those they claim to serve."}, {"id": 125, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the main weakness identified in the marketplace of ideas argument?", "options": {"A": "It ignores that most speech is truthful.", "B": "It only applies to speeches made by demagogues.", "C": "It assumes listeners can calmly evaluate arguments, which is not always true.", "D": "It fails to consider legal restrictions on incitement."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage states that confidence in rational rebuttal presupposes an audience willing and able to weigh arguments dispassionately, and that critics reject this very assumption. The other options describe issues the passage never raises in this context or narrow the critique to a single example rather than the underlying flaw. Only the correct option identifies the assumption the critics actually target.", "passage_id": "P032", "passage_title": "Where Expression Should Stop", "passage_text": "Champions of an almost unlimited right to free expression frequently invoke the marketplace of ideas: falsehood and prejudice, they argue, are best exposed by open rebuttal rather than by suppression, and a society confident in its own reasoning has nothing to fear from even the most odious speaker. Silence a bigot, on this view, and you do not eliminate the bigotry, you merely drive it underground, where it festers unchallenged and returns eventually in a more virulent form. The remedy for bad speech, the formula runs, is always more speech, never enforced silence.\n\nYet this confidence in rational rebuttal presupposes an audience willing and able to weigh arguments dispassionately, and it is precisely this presupposition that critics of near-absolute free speech reject. Words, they observe, do not only persuade; they can also intimidate, humiliate, and, in the most direct cases, incite others to violence. A crowd whipped into fury by a demagogue is not engaged in calm deliberation, and the assurance that truth will eventually prevail offers scant comfort to the victim of a lynching carried out before the rebuttal arrives. On this reasoning, incitement to violence and speech calculated to terrorise a vulnerable group cannot be treated merely as unwelcome contributions to debate; they are acts, not arguments, and ought to be regulated as such.\n\nThe difficulty, both sides concede, lies in drawing the line without granting government an excuse to silence unpopular but harmless dissent. Any authority empowered to ban speech that causes offence will be tempted, sooner or later, to extend that power to speech that is merely inconvenient to those in office. History supplies ample warning: laws framed to protect public order have repeatedly been redeployed against strikers, satirists, and political opponents who posed no genuine threat to anyone. The narrower the category of prohibited speech, the safer the exception is from this kind of abuse, which is why most legal systems that restrict expression confine themselves to direct incitement and imminent threats rather than to speech that merely gives offence.\n\nWhat emerges from this exchange is not a tidy resolution but a shared recognition that the marketplace metaphor, however attractive, cannot by itself tell us where incitement ends and mere provocation begins; that boundary must be drawn by judgment, case by case, rather than by formula."}, {"id": 141, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to defenders of judicial review, as presented in the passage, what justifies the practice?", "options": {"A": "Unrestrained majorities can behave as oppressively as a monarch.", "B": "Judges possess superior legal training to legislators.", "C": "Constitutions are always written with perfect clarity.", "D": "Voters generally prefer courts to legislatures on rights issues."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage states that defenders argue a bare majority can be as tyrannical as any monarch if nothing restrains it, which is why entrenched rights are needed. The other options introduce ideas not attributed to this position, such as superior training or constitutional clarity, which the critics section actually disputes. Voter preference for courts is never mentioned as a justification anywhere in the passage.", "passage_id": "P036", "passage_title": "Judicial Review and Democratic Mandate", "passage_text": "Every functioning democracy must eventually confront an awkward paradox. The legislature, elected and answerable to voters at regular intervals, passes a statute. A court, staffed by judges who were never chosen by the public and who cannot be removed by it, then declares that statute void because it offends some higher constitutional principle. Defenders of this arrangement insist it is no paradox at all but rather the very safeguard that makes democracy worth having. A bare majority, they argue, can be as tyrannical as any monarch if nothing restrains it, and the whole point of entrenched rights is to place certain matters beyond the reach of transient popular passion.\n\nCritics reply that this reasoning smuggles in an elitism dressed as principle. If judges may override the considered judgment of elected representatives whenever they detect a violation of abstract rights, then sovereignty has quietly shifted from the ballot box to the bench. The problem is not that judges are corrupt or careless but that they are unaccountable in the one sense that matters most: no vote can dislodge them for reaching an unpopular decision. Worse, constitutional language is rarely so precise that it yields a single correct answer. Terms like equality, liberty, and due process are contested concepts, and a judge choosing among competing interpretations is making a political choice while wearing the costume of neutral adjudication.\n\nA middle position holds that judicial review is defensible only when narrowly confined to procedural fairness and the protection of groups too small or unpopular to defend themselves through ordinary politics. On this view, courts should hesitate before substituting their own judgment on contested matters of social policy, where reasonable people disagree and where the legislature has at least the virtue of being answerable to those it governs. The danger of this compromise, however, is that the line between procedure and substance is itself contestable, and courts asked to police only the boundary often find themselves drawn steadily inward.\n\nWhat remains true across every version of this debate is that neither pure majoritarianism nor pure judicial supremacy has ever been tried in its unadulterated form, nor would either survive long if it were. Every actual constitutional order is some negotiated blend of the two, and the interesting question is not which principle should win outright but where, in a given society, the balance ought to be struck and why."}, {"id": 157, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the basis of the nationalist's claim that special duties are owed to fellow citizens?", "options": {"A": "Citizens sign a formal document agreeing to mutual aid.", "B": "International law requires prioritizing compatriots.", "C": "Shared history, language, and institutions create bonds akin to family.", "D": "Cosmopolitans have proven such duties do not exist."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage states that a shared history, language, and set of institutions create bonds of obligation analogous to those within a family, which grounds the nationalist's claim of special duty. No formal signed agreement is mentioned anywhere in the passage, and international law is never invoked as the source of this obligation. The final option also misrepresents the structure of the passage, since cosmopolitans are shown disputing the nationalist view rather than proving it false.", "passage_id": "P040", "passage_title": "Nationalism versus Cosmopolitanism", "passage_text": "Few debates expose the tension between particular loyalty and universal obligation as starkly as the disagreement between nationalists and cosmopolitans. The nationalist holds that special duties attach to fellow citizens, duties that simply do not extend, or extend only weakly, to strangers beyond the border. On this view, a shared history, language, and set of institutions create bonds of obligation analogous to those within a family, and it is neither irrational nor immoral to prioritize compatriots when resources or attention are limited.\n\nThe cosmopolitan finds this reasoning suspect from the outset. Moral worth, on the cosmopolitan account, does not stop at an arbitrary line drawn on a map. A child born on one side of a border has done nothing to deserve dramatically greater life prospects than a child born on the other, and any theory of justice that treats national membership as morally decisive is, in this view, simply dressing up an accident of birth as though it were an earned claim. From here it follows that obligations of aid, and perhaps even of political inclusion, ought to be calibrated to need and capacity rather than to citizenship.\n\nThe nationalist rejoinder is not that cosmopolitan concern for distant strangers is wrong in itself, but that it underestimates the practical importance of the bonds it dismisses. Political communities capable of sustaining redistribution, mutual sacrifice, and democratic self-governance appear, historically, to require exactly the kind of thick shared identity that cosmopolitanism treats as morally arbitrary. Strip away national attachment entirely, the nationalist warns, and one may be left with fine universal principles but no workable community willing to act on them, since solidarity has rarely been sustained at a genuinely global scale.\n\nNeither camp, on close inspection, defends its position in the extreme form usually attributed to it. Most self-described nationalists concede some minimal duties to humanity as a whole, and most cosmopolitans concede that national institutions may be a practically useful, even if not morally fundamental, vehicle for delivering universal obligations. The dispute that remains, once the caricatures are cleared away, concerns not whether national and universal claims both matter, but which should bear the greater weight when the two genuinely conflict."}, {"id": 158, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the cosmopolitan mean by describing national membership as \"an accident of birth\"?", "options": {"A": "Most people are simply unaware that they even possess a certain nationality.", "B": "Where a person is born does not reflect any morally earned claim.", "C": "National borders change so frequently that they become entirely meaningless over time.", "D": "Citizenship laws differ so unpredictably between countries that comparison becomes entirely impossible."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage explains that a child has done nothing to deserve the life prospects attached to their place of birth, so treating national membership as morally decisive dresses up this accident as though it were earned. The phrase is not about awareness of one's own nationality or about the frequency of border changes, neither of which appears in the text. Differences in citizenship law between countries are also not mentioned as part of this argument.", "passage_id": "P040", "passage_title": "Nationalism versus Cosmopolitanism", "passage_text": "Few debates expose the tension between particular loyalty and universal obligation as starkly as the disagreement between nationalists and cosmopolitans. The nationalist holds that special duties attach to fellow citizens, duties that simply do not extend, or extend only weakly, to strangers beyond the border. On this view, a shared history, language, and set of institutions create bonds of obligation analogous to those within a family, and it is neither irrational nor immoral to prioritize compatriots when resources or attention are limited.\n\nThe cosmopolitan finds this reasoning suspect from the outset. Moral worth, on the cosmopolitan account, does not stop at an arbitrary line drawn on a map. A child born on one side of a border has done nothing to deserve dramatically greater life prospects than a child born on the other, and any theory of justice that treats national membership as morally decisive is, in this view, simply dressing up an accident of birth as though it were an earned claim. From here it follows that obligations of aid, and perhaps even of political inclusion, ought to be calibrated to need and capacity rather than to citizenship.\n\nThe nationalist rejoinder is not that cosmopolitan concern for distant strangers is wrong in itself, but that it underestimates the practical importance of the bonds it dismisses. Political communities capable of sustaining redistribution, mutual sacrifice, and democratic self-governance appear, historically, to require exactly the kind of thick shared identity that cosmopolitanism treats as morally arbitrary. Strip away national attachment entirely, the nationalist warns, and one may be left with fine universal principles but no workable community willing to act on them, since solidarity has rarely been sustained at a genuinely global scale.\n\nNeither camp, on close inspection, defends its position in the extreme form usually attributed to it. Most self-described nationalists concede some minimal duties to humanity as a whole, and most cosmopolitans concede that national institutions may be a practically useful, even if not morally fundamental, vehicle for delivering universal obligations. The dispute that remains, once the caricatures are cleared away, concerns not whether national and universal claims both matter, but which should bear the greater weight when the two genuinely conflict."}, {"id": 160, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What is the effect of the phrase \"once the caricatures are cleared away\" in the final paragraph?", "options": {"A": "It confirms that the debate has now been fully resolved.", "B": "It implies that nationalists have deliberately lied about their views.", "C": "It shows the writer dismissing cosmopolitanism as unworkable.", "D": "It suggests both positions, in their extreme forms, are commonly misrepresented."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The phrase follows the observation that most self-described nationalists and cosmopolitans concede ground the extreme versions of their positions supposedly deny, implying that the sharpest versions of each view are exaggerated caricatures rather than accurate descriptions of most adherents. It does not accuse nationalists of deliberate dishonesty, only of being commonly oversimplified in public debate. The passage also does not dismiss cosmopolitanism as unworkable, and it explicitly leaves open the remaining question of which claim should weigh more, so the debate is not presented as resolved.", "passage_id": "P040", "passage_title": "Nationalism versus Cosmopolitanism", "passage_text": "Few debates expose the tension between particular loyalty and universal obligation as starkly as the disagreement between nationalists and cosmopolitans. The nationalist holds that special duties attach to fellow citizens, duties that simply do not extend, or extend only weakly, to strangers beyond the border. On this view, a shared history, language, and set of institutions create bonds of obligation analogous to those within a family, and it is neither irrational nor immoral to prioritize compatriots when resources or attention are limited.\n\nThe cosmopolitan finds this reasoning suspect from the outset. Moral worth, on the cosmopolitan account, does not stop at an arbitrary line drawn on a map. A child born on one side of a border has done nothing to deserve dramatically greater life prospects than a child born on the other, and any theory of justice that treats national membership as morally decisive is, in this view, simply dressing up an accident of birth as though it were an earned claim. From here it follows that obligations of aid, and perhaps even of political inclusion, ought to be calibrated to need and capacity rather than to citizenship.\n\nThe nationalist rejoinder is not that cosmopolitan concern for distant strangers is wrong in itself, but that it underestimates the practical importance of the bonds it dismisses. Political communities capable of sustaining redistribution, mutual sacrifice, and democratic self-governance appear, historically, to require exactly the kind of thick shared identity that cosmopolitanism treats as morally arbitrary. Strip away national attachment entirely, the nationalist warns, and one may be left with fine universal principles but no workable community willing to act on them, since solidarity has rarely been sustained at a genuinely global scale.\n\nNeither camp, on close inspection, defends its position in the extreme form usually attributed to it. Most self-described nationalists concede some minimal duties to humanity as a whole, and most cosmopolitans concede that national institutions may be a practically useful, even if not morally fundamental, vehicle for delivering universal obligations. The dispute that remains, once the caricatures are cleared away, concerns not whether national and universal claims both matter, but which should bear the greater weight when the two genuinely conflict."}, {"id": 172, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What does the phrase \"turning a safeguard into a straitjacket\" suggest about over-rigid entrenchment?", "options": {"A": "That excessive rigidity converts a protective device into a restrictive burden.", "B": "That safeguards are always preferable to flexible rules.", "C": "That straitjackets were historically used in constitutional design.", "D": "That entrenchment has no real drawbacks worth considering."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The phrase conveys that a protection intended to guard against abuse can, if made too rigid, become an oppressive restriction that prevents a polity from adapting. It does not imply that safeguards are always better than flexible rules, since the whole paragraph is arguing for balance between the two. The reference to a straitjacket is figurative, not a historical claim, and the passage clearly does treat rigid entrenchment as carrying real drawbacks.", "passage_id": "P043", "passage_title": "Constitutional Constraints on Power", "passage_text": "A constitution that any passing majority could rewrite at will would scarcely deserve the name. Part of what distinguishes constitutional rules from ordinary legislation is precisely that they are designed to resist casual alteration, requiring supermajorities, extended delay, or the consent of multiple bodies before they can be changed. Critics of this arrangement find something puzzling, even undemocratic, in the idea that people living today should be bound by decisions made by predecessors who could not have anticipated present circumstances. Why, they ask, should the dead hand of an earlier generation restrict the choices of the living, who alone must bear the consequences of today's decisions?\n\nDefenders of entrenchment answer that the puzzle dissolves once one distinguishes between two different kinds of majority decision. An ordinary statute reflects the preferences of whichever coalition happens to hold power at a given moment, and is rightly changeable by the next such coalition. A constitutional provision, by contrast, is meant to express commitments that a polity makes to itself precisely because it distrusts the passions of any single moment, including its own future passions. Entrenchment, on this view, functions rather like a person who locks away a temptation the night before, anticipating that morning resolve will not survive an evening's craving; it is not an external constraint imposed by strangers but a form of self-binding chosen by the very people it restrains.\n\nThere remains a genuine difficulty in deciding how difficult amendment ought to be made. Provisions entrenched too loosely offer scant protection against the abuses they were designed to prevent, since a determined majority can simply amend its way around them. Provisions entrenched too rigidly risk freezing a polity into arrangements that no longer serve anyone well, turning a safeguard into a straitjacket. Constitutional design therefore faces a persistent trade-off between stability and adaptability, and reasonable systems differ sharply in where they strike the balance, some requiring near unanimous consent for change and others settling for somewhat more modest supermajorities. A further point often overlooked is that entrenchment does not only protect minorities from majorities; it also protects a society from its own future impulsiveness, in circumstances of panic or crisis when ordinary deliberation is least likely to produce sound judgment."}, {"id": 173, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the central difference between the delegate and trustee models described in the passage?", "options": {"A": "Whether representatives should be paid a salary.", "B": "Whether representatives should transmit constituent wishes or exercise independent judgment.", "C": "Whether elections should be held annually or less often.", "D": "Whether representatives should belong to political parties."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage defines the delegate model as requiring transmission of constituents' expressed wishes and the trustee model as requiring the representative's own considered judgment. Salary, election frequency, and party membership are not discussed anywhere in the passage as distinguishing the two models. The correct option captures precisely the contrast the passage draws between conduit and judgment based representation.", "passage_id": "P044", "passage_title": "Political Representation: Delegate or Trustee", "passage_text": "Every representative eventually confronts a moment when the preferences of those who elected them appear to diverge from what careful reflection suggests is the wiser course. How a representative should act in that moment separates two long-standing conceptions of the office. The delegate model holds that a representative is essentially a conduit, obliged to transmit the expressed wishes of constituents into the legislative chamber regardless of the representative's own view of the merits. The trustee model, by contrast, holds that constituents elect a person precisely for their judgment, and that a representative who simply mirrors current opinion, however transient or ill-informed, has failed to supply the very thing they were chosen to provide.\n\nEdmund Burke offered the classical statement of the trustee position when he told the electors of Bristol that their representative owed them not his industry only but his judgment, and that he would betray rather than serve them if he sacrificed that judgment to their opinion. Critics of this stance point out its uncomfortable proximity to paternalism: if representatives may override the stated wishes of those who elected them whenever they judge those wishes mistaken, the practical distinction between representation and rule by a self-selected elite becomes difficult to draw with any precision.\n\nDefenders of the delegate model reply that democratic legitimacy requires more than periodic elections after which representatives are free to act as they see fit until the next contest arrives. Yet strict delegation faces its own difficulty, since constituents rarely hold a single settled view on complex questions, and a representative attempting to mirror opinion precisely may find no coherent instruction to follow at all. In practice, most working systems settle for a hybrid: representatives are expected to attend closely to constituent opinion, particularly on matters directly affecting their district, while retaining discretion on questions of general policy where information, complexity, or urgency make faithful transmission of instantaneous opinion impractical or even dangerous. Modern legislatures often attempt to formalise this hybrid through mechanisms such as public consultations, town hall meetings, and constituent surveys, none of which bind the representative's final vote but all of which supply information that a purely abstract notion of judgment would otherwise lack."}, {"id": 181, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to the passage, what is the main flaw critics identify in how subsidiarity is often applied?", "options": {"A": "It is invoked to offload burdens without shifting real capacity.", "B": "It is rejected outright by most national governments.", "C": "It gives too much fiscal power to municipalities.", "D": "It ignores geography when setting local priorities."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage states that devolving responsibility for problems such as housing or flooding without devolving the levers that shape them shifts blame downward while resources stay centralised, which critics see as selective use of the principle. The claim that governments reject subsidiarity outright is not supported, since the passage only says its application is questioned. The claims about excessive fiscal power and about ignoring geography both misstate the concern, which is about mismatched responsibility and power rather than fiscal freedom or a disregard for local circumstance.", "passage_id": "P046", "passage_title": "Devolution and Subsidiarity", "passage_text": "The case for devolving power from central government to regions and municipalities is usually framed in the language of subsidiarity: the idea that authority should reside as close as possible to those affected by a decision, with higher tiers of government intervening only when a task genuinely exceeds local competence. Advocates argue that this arrangement respects both the diversity of local circumstance and the dignity of citizens who are, after all, better placed than distant ministries to judge what their own streets, schools and hospitals require. A council that sets its own transport priorities, the argument runs, will calibrate its choices to local congestion and local geography in a way that a national ministry, working from aggregate statistics, cannot.\n\nYet subsidiarity is not a self-executing formula, and its apparent modesty conceals a difficult empirical question: at what level does competence actually lie? Some problems that look local, such as housing shortages or river flooding, are in fact produced by forces that operate well beyond any single municipality, including national fiscal policy or the management of a whole river catchment. To devolve authority over such matters without also devolving the levers that shape them is to hand local bodies responsibility without the corresponding power, inviting blame to be shifted downward while resources remain fixed at the centre. Critics of enthusiastic devolution therefore contend that the principle is too often invoked selectively, used to justify shedding unwelcome burdens rather than genuinely relocating decision-making capacity.\n\nThere is also the question of equity between regions. A wealthier region, freed to set its own tax and spending priorities, may pull further ahead of a poorer one that lacks the same resource base, so that devolution, intended to bring government closer to the people, ends by widening the very disparities that a national framework was designed to correct. Defenders reply that some redistribution can be preserved through a national equalisation fund, while still allowing regions latitude over how funds are spent locally. What emerges from the dispute is not a rejection of subsidiarity as an ideal but a recognition that its proper application depends on a careful, case by case audit of where real competence and real resources actually lie, rather than on a general presumption that local is always better."}, {"id": 183, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What resolution does the passage propose to the tension between local autonomy and equity?", "options": {"A": "Returning all fiscal authority permanently to central government.", "B": "Abandoning subsidiarity as an unworkable ideal.", "C": "Combining a national equalisation mechanism with local spending discretion.", "D": "Requiring every region to adopt identical tax rates."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage notes that defenders propose preserving some redistribution through a national equalisation fund while still letting regions decide how the funds are spent locally, blending central support with local discretion. The claim of returning all fiscal authority to the centre goes further than anything proposed, since the passage never suggests reversing devolution entirely. The claim that subsidiarity is abandoned misreads the conclusion, which explicitly retains it as an ideal, and requiring identical tax rates is not mentioned and would itself remove the local latitude the passage values.", "passage_id": "P046", "passage_title": "Devolution and Subsidiarity", "passage_text": "The case for devolving power from central government to regions and municipalities is usually framed in the language of subsidiarity: the idea that authority should reside as close as possible to those affected by a decision, with higher tiers of government intervening only when a task genuinely exceeds local competence. Advocates argue that this arrangement respects both the diversity of local circumstance and the dignity of citizens who are, after all, better placed than distant ministries to judge what their own streets, schools and hospitals require. A council that sets its own transport priorities, the argument runs, will calibrate its choices to local congestion and local geography in a way that a national ministry, working from aggregate statistics, cannot.\n\nYet subsidiarity is not a self-executing formula, and its apparent modesty conceals a difficult empirical question: at what level does competence actually lie? Some problems that look local, such as housing shortages or river flooding, are in fact produced by forces that operate well beyond any single municipality, including national fiscal policy or the management of a whole river catchment. To devolve authority over such matters without also devolving the levers that shape them is to hand local bodies responsibility without the corresponding power, inviting blame to be shifted downward while resources remain fixed at the centre. Critics of enthusiastic devolution therefore contend that the principle is too often invoked selectively, used to justify shedding unwelcome burdens rather than genuinely relocating decision-making capacity.\n\nThere is also the question of equity between regions. A wealthier region, freed to set its own tax and spending priorities, may pull further ahead of a poorer one that lacks the same resource base, so that devolution, intended to bring government closer to the people, ends by widening the very disparities that a national framework was designed to correct. Defenders reply that some redistribution can be preserved through a national equalisation fund, while still allowing regions latitude over how funds are spent locally. What emerges from the dispute is not a rejection of subsidiarity as an ideal but a recognition that its proper application depends on a careful, case by case audit of where real competence and real resources actually lie, rather than on a general presumption that local is always better."}, {"id": 188, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "In context, what does the phrase 'thrashed out behind closed doors' suggest about coalition agreements?", "options": {"A": "That they are formed through visible public debate.", "B": "That they involve a private, effortful negotiation process.", "C": "That they are decided without any negotiation at all.", "D": "That they are ratified immediately after the election result."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The phrase conveys that coalition terms are hammered out privately and with considerable effort among party negotiators, away from public view, before an agreement is reached. The claim that coalitions are formed through visible public debate contradicts the clear implication of privacy in the phrase. The claim that no negotiation occurs misreads the vigorous effort the phrase implies, and the claim of immediate ratification after the election adds a timing detail the phrase itself does not convey.", "passage_id": "P047", "passage_title": "Party Systems and Coalition Government", "passage_text": "Defenders of two-party systems commonly point to their capacity to produce decisive, accountable government. When the electorate can choose between only two realistic contenders for office, they argue, the winning party governs with a clear mandate and a parliamentary majority sufficient to enact its programme, and voters know precisely whom to reward or punish at the next election. A multi-party system, by contrast, tends to produce a legislature in which no single party commands a majority, forcing negotiation among several groups whose combined platform may bear little resemblance to what any of them promised voters individually. Coalition agreements, thrashed out behind closed doors after the ballots are counted, can appear to substitute elite bargaining for the verdict of the electorate itself.\n\nSupporters of multi-party arrangements reply that this criticism mistakes tidiness for legitimacy. A two-party system, they observe, compresses a plural society's genuinely diverse interests into two broad coalitions, each of which is itself an internal compromise assembled before rather than after the election, only less visibly so. Voters in such a system frequently find no party that represents their actual views with any precision, and are left choosing the lesser of two imperfect options rather than expressing a considered preference. A multi-party system, they contend, allows smaller and more distinct currents of opinion, whether regional, religious or ideological, to gain direct representation, and compels the eventual governing coalition to build consensus across a wider spread of the electorate than a single majority party ever needs to.\n\nThe dispute, then, is not simply about which system delivers stronger government but about what representation is ultimately for. If its purpose is to translate the electorate's full diversity of opinion into the composition of the legislature as faithfully as possible, the multi-party model has the stronger claim. If its purpose is instead to produce a government capable of being clearly identified, judged and replaced by the voters who elected it, the two-party model retains a real advantage, since the price of proportional fidelity is often a coalition whose eventual policy owes as much to post-election horse-trading as to any single party's electoral platform."}, {"id": 191, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage imply about constitutions that formally guarantee judicial independence?", "options": {"A": "They can coexist with informal pressures that prevent true independence.", "B": "They are irrelevant to how courts actually behave.", "C": "They automatically produce genuine rule of law.", "D": "They are only found in rule by law systems."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage explains that a constitution may nominally guarantee judicial independence while patronage networks or the threat of removal quietly ensure courts never rule against the government, meaning formal guarantees can coexist with substantive control. The claim that such guarantees are irrelevant to court behaviour overstates the point, since the passage treats constitutional text as one relevant but insufficient indicator. The claim that such guarantees automatically produce genuine rule of law is directly contradicted by this reasoning, and the claim that they appear only in rule by law systems is unsupported, since either system could contain them.", "passage_id": "P048", "passage_title": "Rule of Law versus Rule by Law", "passage_text": "It has become common to describe authoritarian regimes as governing through law rather than under it, and the distinction, though easily stated, repays closer examination. Under the rule of law properly understood, legal rules bind the state as much as the citizen: officials may act only within powers conferred by law, courts stand ready to check executive overreach, and the content of legislation itself is expected to meet standards of generality, prospectivity and non-contradiction. Rule by law, in contrast, treats legal form as a technique of governance rather than a constraint upon it. Statutes are enacted and enforced with rigorous formality, courts operate and judgments are handed down, yet the entire apparatus remains at the disposal of whoever controls the state, to be adjusted, suspended or selectively applied whenever the ruling authority's interests require it.\n\nThe practical difficulty is that the two systems can look remarkably alike from the outside. Both produce statute books, court proceedings and published judgments, and both invoke the vocabulary of legality to describe what they do. The decisive test lies not in the presence of legal form but in whether the law can be turned against those who wrote it: whether an official or a ruling party can be made to lose a case, whether legislation can be struck down as exceeding constitutional limits, and whether courts retain genuine independence from the executive that appoints and pays them. Where such reversals are unthinkable, however elaborate the legal apparatus, what exists is rule by law wearing the costume of the rule of law.\n\nThis distinction carries a further implication that is easy to overlook: rule of law is not merely a matter of having independent courts on paper, since a constitution may nominally guarantee judicial independence while informal pressures, patronage networks or the threat of removal quietly ensure that courts never actually rule against the government. A regime's true character, on this view, is revealed less by its constitutional text than by the accumulated pattern of its actual judicial outcomes, particularly in the cases where government interests are most directly at stake."}, {"id": 194, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "Why does the passage present sunset clauses as shifting 'the burden of inertia'?", "options": {"A": "Because they eliminate the need for any legislative vote.", "B": "Because they permanently abolish the emergency power once enacted.", "C": "Because they transfer all decision-making to the judiciary.", "D": "Because they require active renewal rather than allowing default continuation."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage explains that sunset clauses make emergency legislation lapse automatically unless explicitly renewed by a full legislative vote, meaning inaction now ends the power rather than continuing it, which reverses the usual default. The claim that they eliminate the need for a legislative vote is the opposite of the mechanism described, which specifically requires a vote to renew. The claim of permanent abolition is incorrect since renewal remains possible, and the claim about transferring authority to the judiciary misattributes a role described separately for judicial review.", "passage_id": "P049", "passage_title": "Emergency Powers and Civil Liberties", "passage_text": "Every legal system confronted with a genuine emergency, whether a pandemic, a war or a natural catastrophe, faces the same structural temptation: to grant the executive branch powers that would be intolerable in ordinary times, on the promise that such powers will be exercised only for the emergency's duration and relinquished once it passes. The logic is not obviously mistaken. A government paralysed by ordinary procedural safeguards, requiring lengthy parliamentary debate before it can close a border or requisition hospital capacity, may respond too slowly to prevent catastrophic harm, and citizens have a reasonable interest in a state capable of acting decisively when genuine necessity demands it.\n\nThe difficulty lies in what history repeatedly demonstrates: emergency powers, once granted, prove far easier to extend than to withdraw. Officials who have grown accustomed to governing by decree rarely surrender that convenience willingly, and the very emergency that justified the initial grant can be redefined, prolonged or quietly reinterpreted to sustain it indefinitely. A curfew imposed to contain a specific outbreak becomes a standing feature of public order policy; a surveillance power authorised to track a particular threat is retained, its use expanded to purposes its original drafters never envisioned. The asymmetry is stark: acquiring emergency powers can take days, while dismantling them, once entrenched in bureaucratic routine and institutional habit, can take decades, if it happens at all.\n\nSeveral safeguards have been proposed to prevent this drift. Sunset clauses can require emergency legislation to lapse automatically after a fixed period unless explicitly renewed by a full legislative vote, shifting the burden of inertia away from those who benefit from the powers' continuation. Independent judicial review can test whether the factual basis for an emergency measure still exists rather than merely whether it existed at the moment of enactment. Parliamentary oversight committees, meeting regularly rather than only at the point of initial authorisation, can interrogate whether a power remains proportionate to a genuinely ongoing threat. None of these mechanisms eliminates the underlying temptation, but each raises the cost of retaining powers whose original justification has quietly expired, forcing the question of necessity to be asked again rather than assumed indefinitely."}, {"id": 198, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What is the sceptics' core objection to describing international cooperation as an extension of self-government?", "options": {"A": "It requires every state to adopt identical domestic policies.", "B": "It makes coordination on shared problems entirely impossible.", "C": "It shifts power toward institutions less accountable to a removable electorate.", "D": "It eliminates the need for international treaties altogether."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage explains that sceptics see a real transfer of power away from bodies citizens can remove through election toward institutions once removed from democratic accountability. The claim that cooperation becomes entirely impossible misstates the objection, since sceptics only argue that accountability is weaker, not that cooperation cannot occur. The claims requiring identical domestic policies and eliminating treaties altogether are not raised in the passage, which focuses on accountability rather than policy uniformity.", "passage_id": "P050", "passage_title": "Global Governance versus National Sovereignty", "passage_text": "The proliferation of international treaties, courts and regulatory bodies since the mid-twentieth century has been defended chiefly on the ground that many pressing problems, climate change, pandemic disease, financial contagion, simply do not respect national borders and therefore cannot be resolved by any state acting alone, however well-governed. On this view, ceding a measure of sovereign authority to bodies capable of coordinating a collective response is not a diminishment of self-government but its logical extension: a nation that jointly commits to enforceable emissions targets is not surrendering control so much as exercising it more effectively, since unilateral action against a problem of this scale would achieve little beyond token gestures.\n\nSceptics of this account object that the analogy between coordination and self-government conceals a real transfer of power away from bodies that citizens can remove through election and toward institutions that are, at best, once removed from democratic accountability. A treaty ratified by one government can bind its successors for decades, long after the electorate that might have endorsed it has changed its mind, and an international court's rulings are not subject to the ordinary mechanisms by which a domestic electorate corrects a policy it dislikes. The concern is not that international cooperation is inherently illegitimate, but that its institutional machinery tends to entrench commitments beyond the point where any living electorate has meaningfully consented to them.\n\nBetween these positions lies a harder question that neither side fully resolves: how to distinguish genuine coordination problems, where no state can achieve its own citizens' goals without binding cooperation, from matters that are merely convenient to internationalise because doing so insulates a policy from domestic political reversal. Proponents of global governance have an incentive to describe as many issues as possible in the former terms, since coordination problems justify the transfer of authority, while sceptics have a countervailing incentive to describe the same issues as matters properly reserved to national decision, since domestic reservation preserves electoral accountability. The honest answer is likely to vary issue by issue rather than resolve into a single settled principle applicable to all cases alike."}, {"id": 204, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'the arithmetic is not close' functions in the passage chiefly to", "options": {"A": "suggest that the surgeon miscalculated the number of patients.", "B": "introduce doubt about whether five organs were truly needed.", "C": "emphasize how easily the utilitarian conclusion follows from the raw numbers.", "D": "contrast the traveller's age with that of the patients."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The phrase highlights how straightforwardly the raw numbers, five against one, seem to dictate the utilitarian conclusion once welfare is simply totalled. It is used to set up the tension explored later in the passage, not to question the surgeon's counting or the traveller's age. The remaining options attribute meanings to the phrase that the surrounding sentences do not support.", "passage_id": "P051", "passage_title": "The Weight of the Rule", "passage_text": "Consider a surgeon who has five patients, each in need of a different organ, each certain to die within days without a transplant. By chance, a healthy traveller arrives at the clinic for a routine check-up. His organs are compatible with all five. If the surgeon kills him quietly and distributes his organs, five lives are saved at the cost of one. A strict utilitarian calculus, one that simply totals the units of welfare produced by an action, appears to endorse the killing: five saved outweighs one lost, and the arithmetic is not close.\n\nYet almost nobody who considers the case is prepared to sanction the surgeon. The near universal recoil is often explained by appeal to a deontological constraint: persons may not be used merely as instruments for the benefit of others, however great that benefit. The traveller has done nothing to forfeit his claim to bodily integrity, and treating him as a warehouse of spare parts denies him the status of an agent whose own life counts for something independent of its usefulness to anyone else. On this view, the wrongness of the killing does not depend on how the numbers come out; it is wrong in virtue of what is done to the traveller, not merely because of what results.\n\nDefenders of the utilitarian calculation are not without a reply. They can insist that our discomfort with the surgeon case reflects a failure of imagination rather than a sound moral principle, since we recoil at vivid, close up killing far more readily than at the diffuse, statistical deaths we tolerate every day through underfunded hospitals or unsafe roads. If five deaths from neglect trouble us less than one death from a scalpel, that asymmetry may say more about the psychology of harm than about its moral weight.\n\nStill, the asymmetry might instead be tracking something real: a distinction between failing to prevent harm and actively producing it, or between foreseeing a death as a side effect and bringing it about as the very means to a good end. Whether that distinction can bear the moral weight placed upon it, or whether it merely dresses up squeamishness in the language of principle, remains the question that separates the two traditions, and neither side has yet persuaded the other."}, {"id": 218, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The 'austere view' described in the passage holds that", "options": {"A": "the second driver alone deserves blame, since only she caused a death.", "B": "neither driver did anything wrong, since drinking is a personal choice.", "C": "the law should ignore reckless driving entirely.", "D": "the two drivers should be judged equally, since outcome depends on luck rather than choice."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The austere view described holds that since the drivers' conduct and intentions were identical, luck should not enter moral assessment at all, making the two equally blameworthy. It explicitly rejects the idea that only the driver who caused death deserves blame. The other options describe positions the passage attributes to neither response.", "passage_id": "P055", "passage_title": "The Drunk Driver Who Made It Home", "passage_text": "Imagine two drivers, both equally careless, each speeding home from a party after drinking more than they should have. The first driver reaches home without incident. The second driver, on an otherwise identical stretch of road, is unlucky: a child runs into the street, and the driver, unable to stop in time, kills her. The two drivers behaved in exactly the same way and made exactly the same choices, yet we typically judge them very differently. The first is guilty of reckless driving, perhaps deserving a fine; the second is guilty of causing death, and may face years in prison and a lifetime of guilt.\n\nThis asymmetry is puzzling because it seems to rest entirely on a factor neither driver controlled, namely whether a child happened to be crossing the road at the wrong moment. Philosophers who write about moral luck point out that our ordinary practices of praise and blame regularly track outcomes that depend on chance, even though we also hold, as a matter of principle, that people should only be judged for what lies within their control.\n\nOne response is to accept that this is simply an inconsistency in ordinary moral thinking, and to insist that the two drivers are, in fact, equally blameworthy, since their conduct and their intentions were identical; the outcome, being a matter of luck, should not enter the moral ledger at all. On this austere view, the law's harsher treatment of the second driver reflects an understandable desire for retribution proportional to harm, not a sound moral distinction.\n\nA second response defends the ordinary practice, arguing that outcomes are not morally irrelevant simply because they involve an element of chance, since it is the driver's own reckless choice that exposed the child to a risk that was, however unluckily, realised. On this view, the difference in blame is not arbitrary, because only one driver actually brought about a death, and bringing about a death, even partly through bad luck, is a different moral fact from merely risking one.\n\nNeither response fully dissolves the discomfort of the case, and the puzzle of moral luck persists precisely because both the instinct to excuse chance and the instinct to blame outcomes seem to have some claim on our judgment."}, {"id": 225, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What does the passage suggest is revealed by most people's discomfort with Kant's absolute rule against lying?", "options": {"A": "An underlying belief that lying is wrong because of its typical effects on others' decisions.", "B": "A general rejection of any moral theory associated with Kant.", "C": "Proof that lying can never be justified under any circumstances.", "D": "A preference for consequences over honesty in every situation."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage argues that widespread discomfort with Kant's absolute rule points to an implicit belief that lying's wrongness stems from denying someone information relevant to her decisions. This is presented as the buried assumption in everyday moral talk about honesty. The other options either misattribute the source of the discomfort or assert conclusions the passage does not draw.", "passage_id": "P057", "passage_title": "The Permissible Untruth", "passage_text": "Few moral rules seem so obviously right, and so routinely broken, as the injunction against lying. Kant's own position, notoriously, allowed no exceptions: to lie, even to a murderer demanding the whereabouts of an intended victim, was to treat the very possibility of trust between rational beings as expendable, and so was impermissible whatever the consequences. Most people recoil from this conclusion, and the recoil is instructive, because it exposes an assumption buried in everyday moral talk: that lying is wrong not in itself but because of what it typically does, namely deprive another person of information she needs to make her own decisions.\n\nIf that assumption is correct, then the so-called white lie occupies an uneasy middle ground. Telling a friend that her cooking was delicious, when it was merely adequate, withholds accurate information, yet it does not obviously wrong her, since the information withheld barely affects any decision she is likely to make. Deception offered to protect a fraudulent transaction withholds information that matters enormously to the decisions of the deceived party. The two acts share a formal structure, the deliberate creation of a false belief, but they differ sharply in the harm that structure produces, and a plausible ethics of honesty must track that difference rather than condemning both with equal severity.\n\nA sceptic might respond that this consequentialist gloss lets in too much: almost any lie can be redescribed as harmless if the liar is sufficiently confident, or self-serving, in her assessment of what the other person needs to know. The doctor who withholds a difficult diagnosis for the patient's own good may believe sincerely that no real decision is being obstructed, and yet may simply be substituting her own judgement for the patient's without permission. The line between protective omission and disguised manipulation is, on this view, far blurrier in practice than the tidy distinction between trivial and consequential lies would suggest, and the very confidence with which a liar judges her lie harmless should perhaps count against her rather than in her favour.\n\nWhat emerges is not a single clean rule but a standing tension: honesty matters because it protects other people's capacity to decide for themselves, yet the same protective reasoning can be recruited, often sincerely, to justify concealing exactly the information a person would have wanted."}, {"id": 234, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage suggest is problematic about defending healthcare-cost measures using paternalistic language?", "options": {"A": "Such measures can never be justified on any grounds whatsoever.", "B": "It may obscure the real justification and hinder public assessment of it.", "C": "It proves that externalities never justify any form of restriction.", "D": "It shows that paternalism and harm to others are identical concepts."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage notes that framing externality-based measures in paternalistic terms can obscure their real justification, making it harder for the public to judge whether the restriction is actually sound. This is presented as a problem of clarity rather than a claim about justification itself. The other options assert conclusions about justification that the passage does not draw.", "passage_id": "P059", "passage_title": "Protecting People From Themselves", "passage_text": "Public health measures routinely restrict choices that individuals would otherwise be free to make: seatbelt laws, taxes on sugary drinks, bans on certain recreational drugs, mandatory vaccination for school entry. Each intervention can be defended on straightforwardly paternalistic grounds, that the state is entitled to override a person's own judgement about her own welfare because that judgement is, in the relevant respect, unreliable or short-sighted. Critics of paternalism reply that this reasoning proves too much, since almost any risky but self-regarding choice, from extreme sports to an unhealthy diet, could be restricted on the same basis, and a state willing to override individual judgement this readily has abandoned any serious commitment to autonomy.\n\nDefenders of intervention typically respond by narrowing their claim rather than abandoning it. Not every self-regarding risk justifies restriction, they argue, only those where the ordinary conditions for competent choice are absent or badly degraded, as when addictive substances hijack the very faculties a person would need to resist them, or when advertising and product design are engineered specifically to exploit predictable cognitive biases. On this narrower view, paternalism is justified not because the state simply knows better, but because the choice being protected was never truly autonomous to begin with, having been produced by manipulation rather than reflection.\n\nThis narrower defence still leaves a hard case unresolved. Public health measures aimed at externalities, such as the strain that unhealthy lifestyles place on collectively funded healthcare systems, are not really paternalistic at all in the strict sense, since they can be justified by appeal to harm to others rather than harm to the chooser herself. Yet they are frequently defended using paternalistic language, framed as being for the individual's own good, which may obscure the real basis for the restriction and make it harder for the public to assess whether the underlying justification is sound.\n\nThe upshot is that paternalism in public health is rarely a single argument but a bundle of distinct justifications, some resting on compromised autonomy, others on collective cost, that get run together under one convenient label, with the effect that objections properly aimed at one strand are too often treated as refuting all of them at once."}, {"id": 235, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What is the passage's overall conclusion about paternalism in public health?", "options": {"A": "It is a single, coherent argument resting entirely on compromised autonomy.", "B": "It should be abandoned entirely in favour of unrestricted personal choice.", "C": "It is justified only when it protects collectively funded healthcare systems.", "D": "It combines distinct justifications that are often treated as one argument."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The final paragraph states that paternalism in public health is a bundle of distinct justifications running together under one label, rather than a single unified argument. This is why objections to one strand are mistakenly treated as refuting the whole position. The remaining options reduce this bundled picture to a single, narrower claim not supported by the text.", "passage_id": "P059", "passage_title": "Protecting People From Themselves", "passage_text": "Public health measures routinely restrict choices that individuals would otherwise be free to make: seatbelt laws, taxes on sugary drinks, bans on certain recreational drugs, mandatory vaccination for school entry. Each intervention can be defended on straightforwardly paternalistic grounds, that the state is entitled to override a person's own judgement about her own welfare because that judgement is, in the relevant respect, unreliable or short-sighted. Critics of paternalism reply that this reasoning proves too much, since almost any risky but self-regarding choice, from extreme sports to an unhealthy diet, could be restricted on the same basis, and a state willing to override individual judgement this readily has abandoned any serious commitment to autonomy.\n\nDefenders of intervention typically respond by narrowing their claim rather than abandoning it. Not every self-regarding risk justifies restriction, they argue, only those where the ordinary conditions for competent choice are absent or badly degraded, as when addictive substances hijack the very faculties a person would need to resist them, or when advertising and product design are engineered specifically to exploit predictable cognitive biases. On this narrower view, paternalism is justified not because the state simply knows better, but because the choice being protected was never truly autonomous to begin with, having been produced by manipulation rather than reflection.\n\nThis narrower defence still leaves a hard case unresolved. Public health measures aimed at externalities, such as the strain that unhealthy lifestyles place on collectively funded healthcare systems, are not really paternalistic at all in the strict sense, since they can be justified by appeal to harm to others rather than harm to the chooser herself. Yet they are frequently defended using paternalistic language, framed as being for the individual's own good, which may obscure the real basis for the restriction and make it harder for the public to assess whether the underlying justification is sound.\n\nThe upshot is that paternalism in public health is rarely a single argument but a bundle of distinct justifications, some resting on compromised autonomy, others on collective cost, that get run together under one convenient label, with the effect that objections properly aimed at one strand are too often treated as refuting all of them at once."}, {"id": 239, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What difficulty does the passage identify as facing retributivism?", "options": {"A": "It may license suffering that serves no discernible purpose in some cases.", "B": "It cannot explain why offenders deserve any punishment at all.", "C": "It relies entirely on deterrence to justify any punishment imposed.", "D": "It has no answer to the problem of incapacitating dangerous offenders."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage notes that insisting on deserved punishment regardless of consequences can license suffering that serves no discernible purpose in a particular case, a cost few retributivists are comfortable accepting. This is presented as retributivism's own uncomfortable difficulty rather than a flaw in consequentialism. The other options describe problems not raised against retributivism in the text.", "passage_id": "P060", "passage_title": "Must Punishment Deter to Be Just?", "passage_text": "It is often assumed that punishment earns its moral legitimacy by reducing future crime, whether by deterring the punished individual from reoffending, deterring others who might be tempted to similar conduct, or simply incapacitating a dangerous person for a period of time. On this consequentialist picture, a punishment that produced no reduction in future offending at all would be difficult to justify, since it would impose suffering on the offender without securing any of the benefits that are supposed to offset that cost.\n\nRetributivists reject this picture at its foundation. On their view, punishment is justified because the offender deserves it, having voluntarily broken a rule she knew applied to her, and this desert-based justification holds regardless of whatever downstream effect the punishment happens to have on crime rates. If deterrence turned out to be entirely ineffective, a strict retributivist would still regard punishing the guilty as required, since the point of punishment is to restore a moral balance disturbed by the offence rather than to engineer any particular future outcome.\n\nThe disagreement is not merely theoretical. Consider a policy that punishes an offender more severely than her culpability alone would seem to warrant, purely because doing so is thought to deter others; a consequentialist committed only to reducing crime has no principled objection available, provided the deterrent effect is real, whereas a retributivist has an immediate and decisive one, since punishment calibrated to anything other than the offender's own desert treats her merely as a means to controlling other people's behaviour. This is precisely the worry that Kantian retributivists press hardest: using one person's suffering instrumentally to influence a third party violates her standing as an end in herself, however much crime might thereby be prevented.\n\nYet retributivism faces its own uncomfortable question, since insisting that deserved punishment be imposed regardless of consequences can appear to license suffering that serves no discernible purpose in a given case, and few retributivists are entirely happy conceding that the resulting suffering counts as a cost worth accepting. Most existing positions therefore combine the two logics in practice, treating desert as a constraint on how much punishment may be imposed while still permitting considerations of deterrence to help decide what form that permitted punishment should take."}, {"id": 245, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the function of the pond example within the overall argument of the passage?", "options": {"A": "It shows that expensive shoes are morally more important than they seem.", "B": "It establishes that proximity and cost do not excuse us from helping.", "C": "It proves that all obligations to strangers are impossible to fulfil.", "D": "It demonstrates that most people refuse to help a drowning child."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The pond example is used to secure agreement that we must help even at a cost, and the passage then extends this by asking why distance should matter when proximity and cost apparently do not. This establishes the premise from which the wider demand on our resources is derived. It is not meant to suggest people refuse to help, nor to make a claim about footwear, but to isolate proximity and cost as morally irrelevant factors.", "passage_id": "P062", "passage_title": "How Much Do We Owe Strangers", "passage_text": "A well known thought experiment asks us to imagine passing a shallow pond in which a child is drowning. Almost everyone agrees that we are obliged to wade in and save the child, even at the cost of ruining an expensive pair of shoes. The philosopher who popularised this example then asks why our obligations should stop at the edge of the pond. If proximity and cost are morally irrelevant, as they seem to be in the pond case, then the money we might spend on shoes, or on holidays, or on any comfort beyond bare necessity, is money we are obliged to send to strangers whose lives it could save, wherever in the world they happen to live.\n\nThe argument has considerable force, since it is hard to identify a principled reason why distance alone should discharge an obligation that proximity would clearly impose. Yet many find the conclusion nearly impossible to accept in practice, not merely inconvenient but somehow wrong in a way that demands explanation. One response holds that morality, properly understood, permits agents some latitude to pursue their own projects and attachments, a latitude the argument's strict impartiality refuses to grant. On this view, a theory that requires every person to treat their own child, their own career and their own modest pleasures as worth no more than the identical claims of any stranger has mistaken what morality is for, since it leaves no room for a life a person could recognise as their own.\n\nA second, less sweeping response accepts the underlying logic but resists the scale of its demand, arguing that we owe strangers a great deal more than convention currently allows without owing them literally everything beyond subsistence. This position tries to preserve the pond case's insight, that unearned distance is not a moral shield, while denying that the insight scales without limit once multiplied across billions of needy strangers.\n\nNeither response is without cost. The first risks licensing complacency by treating personal projects as a trump card against clear and remediable suffering. The second must explain, without arbitrary line drawing, exactly where the demand should stop, a task the pond case was designed precisely to make difficult."}, {"id": 246, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to the passage, what problem does the first response to the argument risk creating?", "options": {"A": "It risks making the pond example logically inconsistent.", "B": "It risks proving that strangers deserve more help than family.", "C": "It risks making personal projects an excuse to ignore suffering.", "D": "It risks showing that no one has any obligations at all."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage states directly that the first response risks licensing complacency by treating personal projects as a trump card against clear and remediable suffering. This is presented as a cost of granting agents latitude to pursue their own attachments. It does not concern the internal logic of the pond example itself, nor does it claim strangers deserve more help than family or that obligations vanish entirely.", "passage_id": "P062", "passage_title": "How Much Do We Owe Strangers", "passage_text": "A well known thought experiment asks us to imagine passing a shallow pond in which a child is drowning. Almost everyone agrees that we are obliged to wade in and save the child, even at the cost of ruining an expensive pair of shoes. The philosopher who popularised this example then asks why our obligations should stop at the edge of the pond. If proximity and cost are morally irrelevant, as they seem to be in the pond case, then the money we might spend on shoes, or on holidays, or on any comfort beyond bare necessity, is money we are obliged to send to strangers whose lives it could save, wherever in the world they happen to live.\n\nThe argument has considerable force, since it is hard to identify a principled reason why distance alone should discharge an obligation that proximity would clearly impose. Yet many find the conclusion nearly impossible to accept in practice, not merely inconvenient but somehow wrong in a way that demands explanation. One response holds that morality, properly understood, permits agents some latitude to pursue their own projects and attachments, a latitude the argument's strict impartiality refuses to grant. On this view, a theory that requires every person to treat their own child, their own career and their own modest pleasures as worth no more than the identical claims of any stranger has mistaken what morality is for, since it leaves no room for a life a person could recognise as their own.\n\nA second, less sweeping response accepts the underlying logic but resists the scale of its demand, arguing that we owe strangers a great deal more than convention currently allows without owing them literally everything beyond subsistence. This position tries to preserve the pond case's insight, that unearned distance is not a moral shield, while denying that the insight scales without limit once multiplied across billions of needy strangers.\n\nNeither response is without cost. The first risks licensing complacency by treating personal projects as a trump card against clear and remediable suffering. The second must explain, without arbitrary line drawing, exactly where the demand should stop, a task the pond case was designed precisely to make difficult."}, {"id": 247, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "How does the second response described in the passage differ from the first?", "options": {"A": "It accepts the argument's logic but limits how far the demand extends.", "B": "It rejects the pond example as an unreliable moral test entirely.", "C": "It argues that strangers have no legitimate moral claims on us.", "D": "It insists that distance always discharges any obligation completely."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The second response is described as accepting the underlying logic that unearned distance is not a moral shield while resisting the conclusion that the demand scales without limit across billions of strangers. This contrasts with the first response, which challenges the impartiality of the argument itself rather than merely its scope. Neither response denies that strangers have some claim on us or that the pond example carries force.", "passage_id": "P062", "passage_title": "How Much Do We Owe Strangers", "passage_text": "A well known thought experiment asks us to imagine passing a shallow pond in which a child is drowning. Almost everyone agrees that we are obliged to wade in and save the child, even at the cost of ruining an expensive pair of shoes. The philosopher who popularised this example then asks why our obligations should stop at the edge of the pond. If proximity and cost are morally irrelevant, as they seem to be in the pond case, then the money we might spend on shoes, or on holidays, or on any comfort beyond bare necessity, is money we are obliged to send to strangers whose lives it could save, wherever in the world they happen to live.\n\nThe argument has considerable force, since it is hard to identify a principled reason why distance alone should discharge an obligation that proximity would clearly impose. Yet many find the conclusion nearly impossible to accept in practice, not merely inconvenient but somehow wrong in a way that demands explanation. One response holds that morality, properly understood, permits agents some latitude to pursue their own projects and attachments, a latitude the argument's strict impartiality refuses to grant. On this view, a theory that requires every person to treat their own child, their own career and their own modest pleasures as worth no more than the identical claims of any stranger has mistaken what morality is for, since it leaves no room for a life a person could recognise as their own.\n\nA second, less sweeping response accepts the underlying logic but resists the scale of its demand, arguing that we owe strangers a great deal more than convention currently allows without owing them literally everything beyond subsistence. This position tries to preserve the pond case's insight, that unearned distance is not a moral shield, while denying that the insight scales without limit once multiplied across billions of needy strangers.\n\nNeither response is without cost. The first risks licensing complacency by treating personal projects as a trump card against clear and remediable suffering. The second must explain, without arbitrary line drawing, exactly where the demand should stop, a task the pond case was designed precisely to make difficult."}, {"id": 248, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What does the phrase 'a task the pond case was designed precisely to make difficult' suggest about the second response's challenge?", "options": {"A": "The pond case was never intended to raise any difficulty at all.", "B": "Locating a non arbitrary limit is hard because of how the argument works.", "C": "The pond case makes it easy to know exactly where help should stop.", "D": "Difficulty only arises because the pond case is poorly constructed."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "This closing phrase implies that the very structure of the pond argument, built to strip away proximity and cost as morally relevant distinctions, is what makes it so hard to justify any particular stopping point for the demand. The word precisely signals that this is not an accidental byproduct but the intended effect of the thought experiment. It therefore suggests the difficulty is built into the argument's design rather than a flaw in its construction or a sign it was never meant to challenge anyone.", "passage_id": "P062", "passage_title": "How Much Do We Owe Strangers", "passage_text": "A well known thought experiment asks us to imagine passing a shallow pond in which a child is drowning. Almost everyone agrees that we are obliged to wade in and save the child, even at the cost of ruining an expensive pair of shoes. The philosopher who popularised this example then asks why our obligations should stop at the edge of the pond. If proximity and cost are morally irrelevant, as they seem to be in the pond case, then the money we might spend on shoes, or on holidays, or on any comfort beyond bare necessity, is money we are obliged to send to strangers whose lives it could save, wherever in the world they happen to live.\n\nThe argument has considerable force, since it is hard to identify a principled reason why distance alone should discharge an obligation that proximity would clearly impose. Yet many find the conclusion nearly impossible to accept in practice, not merely inconvenient but somehow wrong in a way that demands explanation. One response holds that morality, properly understood, permits agents some latitude to pursue their own projects and attachments, a latitude the argument's strict impartiality refuses to grant. On this view, a theory that requires every person to treat their own child, their own career and their own modest pleasures as worth no more than the identical claims of any stranger has mistaken what morality is for, since it leaves no room for a life a person could recognise as their own.\n\nA second, less sweeping response accepts the underlying logic but resists the scale of its demand, arguing that we owe strangers a great deal more than convention currently allows without owing them literally everything beyond subsistence. This position tries to preserve the pond case's insight, that unearned distance is not a moral shield, while denying that the insight scales without limit once multiplied across billions of needy strangers.\n\nNeither response is without cost. The first risks licensing complacency by treating personal projects as a trump card against clear and remediable suffering. The second must explain, without arbitrary line drawing, exactly where the demand should stop, a task the pond case was designed precisely to make difficult."}, {"id": 249, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the key claim made by the first response to the challenge of determinism?", "options": {"A": "Responsibility requires that decisions be entirely free of prior causes.", "B": "Responsibility depends on whether a decision flowed from the agent's own character.", "C": "Responsibility disappears entirely once determinism is accepted as true.", "D": "Responsibility only applies to crimes that involve financial gain."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The first response argues that what matters for responsibility is whether a decision flowed from the agent's own values, reasoning and character rather than from coercion, not whether the decision was itself uncaused. This allows responsibility to survive even if determinism is true. It is not restricted to financial crimes, and it explicitly rejects the idea that freedom from causation is the relevant standard.", "passage_id": "P063", "passage_title": "Blame Without Freedom", "passage_text": "If every event, including every human decision, is the inevitable product of prior causes stretching back before any of us were born, it becomes puzzling why we should hold anyone morally responsible for what they do. The embezzler, on this picture, no more chose his crime in some ultimate sense than a stone chooses to roll downhill, since both outcomes follow necessarily from antecedent conditions that neither stone nor embezzler had any hand in creating. To many, this thought is genuinely destabilising, since it seems to threaten not just legal punishment but the entire practice of praise, blame, gratitude and resentment that structures ordinary life.\n\nOne response denies that determinism, even if true, undermines responsibility, on the grounds that what matters for responsibility is not whether a decision was caused but whether it flowed from the agent's own values, reasoning and character rather than from external coercion or compulsion. On this view, the embezzler remains responsible because the theft expressed something about him, his priorities and his willingness to deceive, and this remains true whether or not those priorities were themselves shaped by causes reaching back to his upbringing. Responsibility, on this account, is compatible with determinism because it was never really about the absence of causation in the first place.\n\nA second, more sceptical response insists that this redescription simply relocates the problem rather than solving it. If the agent's values and character are themselves fully determined by factors he did not choose, then tracing the theft back to those values does not show he is responsible, only that responsibility has been pushed one step further back to conditions equally beyond his control. On this view, the ordinary practice of blame may need to be revised, not abolished outright but tempered by an awareness that the wrongdoer's formation was never within his own command.\n\nWhat both positions share is a refusal to treat the question as merely academic. The stakes are practical as well as theoretical, since how a society punishes, forgives and educates depends heavily on which of these pictures of the agent it accepts, even when the underlying metaphysical dispute about causation remains unresolved."}, {"id": 253, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the central distinction that the doctrine of double effect relies upon?", "options": {"A": "The distinction between actions performed by doctors and by other professionals.", "B": "The distinction between patients who consent and patients who do not consent.", "C": "The distinction between painkillers and other forms of medical treatment.", "D": "The distinction between an effect that is intended and one merely foreseen."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage explains that the doctrine distinguishes effects intended as a means or end from effects merely foreseen as a side consequence of pursuing a permissible aim. This distinction is what allows the two surgeons to be judged differently despite an identical outcome. Neither consent, profession, nor the type of drug administered is presented as the operative distinction.", "passage_id": "P064", "passage_title": "Foreseen but Not Intended", "passage_text": "Consider two surgeons, each facing a patient who will certainly die without intervention. The first administers a dose of painkiller large enough to ease terrible suffering, knowing the same dose will hasten the patient's death as a side effect. The second, faced with a different patient, administers a lethal dose specifically in order to end the patient's suffering by ending the patient's life. Many people report a strong intuition that the first act is permissible, perhaps even admirable, while the second is a form of killing that requires far greater justification, even though the patient dies in both cases and the doctor foresees death in both cases.\n\nThe doctrine of double effect attempts to explain this intuition by distinguishing between effects that are intended as a means or an end and effects that are merely foreseen as a side consequence of pursuing a different, permissible end. On this view, the first surgeon intends only to relieve pain, and merely foresees, without intending, that death will follow; the second surgeon intends death itself as the mechanism by which suffering is relieved. Since only the second act treats death as part of the plan rather than an unwanted side effect, only the second requires the weightier justification associated with intentional killing.\n\nCritics argue that this distinction is harder to draw than it appears, since intentions can be redescribed to fit whichever conclusion the doctor already favours. A surgeon who wishes to justify a lethal dose could describe his intention narrowly as relieving pain, treating death as a mere unavoidable accompaniment, in exactly the same words used to describe the first case. If the doctrine depends on a description the agent supplies about his own mental state, and that description cannot be independently verified, the doctrine risks becoming a permission slip for anyone willing to phrase their intention carefully.\n\nDefenders respond that intentions are not simply reports we choose at will but are partly fixed by what an agent would do if circumstances changed, such as whether the first surgeon would have administered the same dose had it somehow relieved pain without causing death. This test, they suggest, gives the distinction more content than a critic's suspicion allows."}, {"id": 259, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the purpose of introducing the bystander and whistleblower examples in the final paragraph?", "options": {"A": "To show the dispute about motive extends beyond the charity case.", "B": "To prove conclusively that motive never matters in any situation.", "C": "To demonstrate that whistleblowers are always motivated by spite.", "D": "To argue that bystanders should never attempt to rescue strangers."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "These examples are introduced to show that the same underlying dispute, about how much a murky or self interested motive should count against an agent whose act produced a good outcome, arises well beyond the specific case of charitable donation. They generalise the argument rather than settle it in either direction. The passage does not claim whistleblowers are always spiteful or that rescues should be avoided.", "passage_id": "P065", "passage_title": "Good Intentions, Bad Outcomes", "passage_text": "Two donors each give a large sum to a charity. The first gives because she has carefully studied the evidence and believes the money will save more lives there than anywhere else. The second gives an identical sum, to the identical charity, purely because a photograph in the newspaper moved her and she wished to be rid of an uncomfortable feeling. Suppose, as it happens, both donations produce exactly the same benefit. A view that judges actions solely by their outcomes must say the two donors have done something of equal moral worth, since the world is left equally improved in either case. Many people resist this conclusion, feeling that the first donor deserves a kind of moral credit the second does not, even though neither can be blamed for what she did.\n\nOne way to defend the outcome focused view is to insist that we are conflating two separate questions, namely whether an act was good and whether the agent who performed it is admirable. The donation itself, considered simply as an event in the world, is equally beneficial regardless of motive, and it is only when we shift to evaluating the donor's character that motive becomes relevant. On this reading, both donors performed an equally good act, but only the first displays a virtue, namely due diligence, that the second happens to lack.\n\nA rival view holds that this separation is artificial, since the very thing we are trying to assess when we call an act morally right is inseparable from why it was done. On this account, an act performed from mere sentiment, however beneficial by accident, is not equivalent to one performed from a reasoned commitment to helping, because rightness is not simply a property of results but of the reasoning that produced them.\n\nThe dispute matters beyond charity, since it bears on how we judge a bystander who saves a drowning stranger to impress an onlooker, or a whistleblower who exposes wrongdoing partly from spite. In each case, the outcome may be unambiguously good while the motive remains murky, and how much that murkiness should count against the agent is precisely what is contested."}, {"id": 263, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What problem does the passage identify with the deprivation account of why killing is wrong?", "options": {"A": "It applies equally well to both animals and plants.", "B": "It cannot explain why painless killing ever causes suffering.", "C": "It implies killing humans without articulated future plans is permissible.", "D": "It relies entirely on legal rather than moral reasoning."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage explains that if only frustrated forward-looking desires make killing wrong, then killing humans lacking such desires would seem equally acceptable, a conclusion the passage says almost nobody accepts. This is presented as an awkward parallel that the account must address. The other options describe problems not raised in the text.", "passage_id": "P066", "passage_title": "The Carnivore's Dilemma", "passage_text": "Jeremy Bentham's question was not whether animals can reason or converse, but whether they can suffer. This reframing shifted the terrain of debate: if moral standing rests on the capacity to experience pain rather than on intellectual sophistication, then a great many practices that inflict suffering on creatures for the sake of taste or convenience look difficult to defend. The rearing of animals in conditions that maximise yield rather than welfare, and their slaughter for products that could in principle be replaced by other foods, seem to fail any test built on the reduction of suffering.\n\nYet a critic might concede all of this and still resist the conclusion that eating animals is wrong, by distinguishing two separate objections. One objection targets suffering, the other targets killing itself. Suppose an animal were reared with scrupulous care and killed instantly and without pain. The suffering objection would then have nothing to bite on, yet many people still feel that something has been lost. Some philosophers argue this residual unease is misplaced, since what makes killing a person tragic is the frustration of that person's forward-looking plans and projects, a capacity many animals plausibly lack in the relevant sense.\n\nThis deprivation account, however, generates an awkward parallel. If what matters is only the thwarting of articulated future-directed desires, then killing a human being who, through injury or infancy, has no such articulated desires would seem equally permissible, a conclusion almost nobody accepts. Defenders of the account must therefore either bite this bullet or supplement it with some further principle, perhaps the mere capacity for such a future, or membership of a kind that typically possesses it, that distinguishes the two cases without simply presupposing that humans count and animals do not.\n\nThe dispute over animal flesh therefore cannot be resolved by appeal to suffering alone, however central that appeal has been to reform movements. It ultimately forces us back onto a harder and more general question that vegetarians and carnivores alike tend to dodge: what precisely makes the killing of a sentient creature wrong, when it is wrong, and whether that feature is present, absent, or merely diminished in the animals we routinely eat."}, {"id": 265, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Why did Kant classify beneficence toward strangers as an imperfect rather than a perfect duty?", "options": {"A": "Because strangers have no moral standing whatsoever in Kantian ethics.", "B": "Because beneficence conflicts directly with all perfect duties.", "C": "Because Kant denied that charity could ever be praiseworthy.", "D": "Because it requires a general policy of help without owing any particular instance."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage explains that Kant required a general policy of helping others while denying that any specific stranger could demand help in a given instance. This latitude in application is what places beneficence among imperfect rather than perfect duties. The other options misstate Kant's position, since the passage explicitly says charity is praiseworthy on his view, not that strangers lack standing or that duties conflict.", "passage_id": "P067", "passage_title": "Almsgiving and Obligation", "passage_text": "Kant distinguished between perfect duties, which admit no exception and can be demanded of every rational agent, and imperfect duties, which leave latitude in how and when they are discharged. Beneficence toward strangers fell, for Kant, into the second category: we must adopt a general policy of helping others where we reasonably can, but no particular stranger can insist that we help them in this instance rather than another. Charity, on this view, is praiseworthy precisely because it is not owed, which is what allows the giver's action to count as virtuous rather than merely compliant.\n\nA rival tradition inverts this picture entirely. If a person is dying of starvation while another possesses food far beyond what sustains a comfortable life, the argument runs, the surplus holder does something closer to theft than to generosity by withholding it. On this account, the moral distance we place between failing to feed a starving stranger and directly harming one is an accident of proximity and vividness, not a genuine difference in the weight of obligation. If distance and unfamiliarity carried no independent moral weight, refusing to give would sit alongside more familiar violations of duty rather than beside mere failures of virtue.\n\nThe practical stakes of this disagreement are considerable. Treating giving as supererogatory, an act above and beyond what morality strictly requires, permits admiration for the generous without condemnation of the ungenerous, whereas treating it as owed licenses blame, and perhaps even enforceable redistribution, wherever comfortable people decline to part with their surplus. Advocates of the duty view therefore face a demanding question of scale: if withholding surplus from one starving stranger is wrong, it is unclear on what principled ground withholding smaller surpluses from the far larger number of the world's poor could be permitted.\n\nDefenders of the virtue view respond that morality must leave room for agents to pursue their own projects and attachments, and that a duty capacious enough to absorb most disposable income collapses this distinction, turning an entire life into an instrument of others' needs. Whichever position one adopts, the dispute reveals that calling an act charitable rather than obligatory is never a neutral description; it already presupposes an answer to how much a stranger's need can rightly claim from us."}, {"id": 271, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What conclusion does the passage draw about discounting future welfare purely because of temporal distance?", "options": {"A": "It is fully justified because future people cannot yet make claims.", "B": "It is required in order to make the non-identity problem tractable.", "C": "It is as arbitrary as discounting welfare based on geographic distance.", "D": "It is only appropriate when applied to resource depletion specifically."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage draws an explicit comparison, concluding that discounting welfare merely because it lies in the future is as arbitrary as discounting it merely because it lies far away in space. Neither temporal nor spatial distance is presented as a good reason to assign someone less moral weight. The other options either overstate the justification for discounting or narrow the conclusion to a scope the passage does not impose.", "passage_id": "P068", "passage_title": "Debts to the Unborn", "passage_text": "It is common to speak of obligations to future generations, as when a government is criticised for depleting resources or destabilising a climate that people not yet born will have to inhabit. The intuition seems straightforward: just as it would be wrong to leave a ruined inheritance to one's own children, it seems wrong to leave a ruined planet to the children of strangers who have not yet been conceived.\n\nThis intuition runs into a puzzle once we notice how thoroughly our present choices determine who exists at all. Policies affecting energy, timing of parenthood, and countless other variables alter which particular sperm meets which particular egg, so that a different policy would not merely give the same future people a better life, it would result in different people being born entirely. If the individuals harmed by a depleting policy would never have existed under the alternative, careful policy, it becomes difficult to say that any specific person has been made worse off by our choice, since the alternative for them was never existence at all but nonexistence.\n\nDefenders of obligations to the future respond that this puzzle, sometimes called the non-identity problem, shows only that we must stop evaluating policies by comparison to specific individuals. Instead we should judge a policy by the aggregate quality of life it tends to produce, regardless of which particular people end up living it. A policy that reliably produces widespread hardship is criticisable on this impersonal measure even if no named person can point to themselves as a victim who would otherwise have fared better.\n\nA further question concerns whether the mere passage of time gives us licence to discount future welfare, treating benefits and harms decades away as counting for less than identical benefits and harms occurring now. Most who consider the question conclude that such discounting is as arbitrary as discounting the welfare of people merely because they live far away geographically; distance in time, like distance in space, seems a poor basis for assigning someone less moral weight. What remains contested is not whether the future counts, but precisely how much weight impersonal considerations of this kind should carry against the interests of people who are already alive and asking something of us now."}, {"id": 272, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "In the final paragraph, what does the word \"impersonal\" convey about the considerations being weighed against present interests?", "options": {"A": "They are not tied to any specific, identifiable individual.", "B": "They are considered less important than personal relationships.", "C": "They apply exclusively to government institutions rather than individuals.", "D": "They have already been rejected by most philosophers."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The term is used to describe considerations that assess outcomes by aggregate quality of life rather than by reference to any particular, nameable person who is made worse off. This is precisely the move made earlier in the passage to escape the non-identity problem. The other options introduce a hierarchy, an institutional restriction, or a rejection that the passage's use of the word does not support.", "passage_id": "P068", "passage_title": "Debts to the Unborn", "passage_text": "It is common to speak of obligations to future generations, as when a government is criticised for depleting resources or destabilising a climate that people not yet born will have to inhabit. The intuition seems straightforward: just as it would be wrong to leave a ruined inheritance to one's own children, it seems wrong to leave a ruined planet to the children of strangers who have not yet been conceived.\n\nThis intuition runs into a puzzle once we notice how thoroughly our present choices determine who exists at all. Policies affecting energy, timing of parenthood, and countless other variables alter which particular sperm meets which particular egg, so that a different policy would not merely give the same future people a better life, it would result in different people being born entirely. If the individuals harmed by a depleting policy would never have existed under the alternative, careful policy, it becomes difficult to say that any specific person has been made worse off by our choice, since the alternative for them was never existence at all but nonexistence.\n\nDefenders of obligations to the future respond that this puzzle, sometimes called the non-identity problem, shows only that we must stop evaluating policies by comparison to specific individuals. Instead we should judge a policy by the aggregate quality of life it tends to produce, regardless of which particular people end up living it. A policy that reliably produces widespread hardship is criticisable on this impersonal measure even if no named person can point to themselves as a victim who would otherwise have fared better.\n\nA further question concerns whether the mere passage of time gives us licence to discount future welfare, treating benefits and harms decades away as counting for less than identical benefits and harms occurring now. Most who consider the question conclude that such discounting is as arbitrary as discounting the welfare of people merely because they live far away geographically; distance in time, like distance in space, seems a poor basis for assigning someone less moral weight. What remains contested is not whether the future counts, but precisely how much weight impersonal considerations of this kind should carry against the interests of people who are already alive and asking something of us now."}, {"id": 275, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage suggest about forgiveness extended unconditionally, without acknowledgment from the wrongdoer?", "options": {"A": "It may reflect a failure of self-respect rather than a virtue.", "B": "It is impossible according to most philosophical accounts.", "C": "It is the only form of forgiveness that counts as genuine.", "D": "It automatically transforms into condoning the wrongdoer's act."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage states that forgiveness given without any acknowledgment or repair from the wrongdoer may reflect a willingness to treat one's own injuries as too insignificant to merit an accounting, which it links to a failure of self-respect rather than virtue. This is offered as a corrective to the popular view that forgiveness is always admirable regardless of context. The other options either deny the possibility of such forgiveness or misidentify it with condoning, which the passage has already distinguished.", "passage_id": "P069", "passage_title": "The Limits of Pardon", "passage_text": "Forgiveness is widely praised as a moral achievement, a release from the corrosive grip of resentment that is said to benefit the one who forgives at least as much as the one forgiven. On this popular picture, the sooner and more completely a person lets go of anger toward a wrongdoer, the more admirable their character appears, and reluctance to forgive is treated as a lingering fault to be overcome rather than a reasonable response to injury.\n\nCritics of this picture argue that it flattens an important distinction between forgiveness that is earned and forgiveness that is simply given away. Resentment, on this view, is not merely an unpleasant sensation to be managed but a form of moral protest, a way of registering that a wrong has been done and that the wrongdoer is answerable for it. To forgive before a wrongdoer has acknowledged the harm, understood its weight, or made any effort at repair risks silencing that protest prematurely, and can communicate to the wrongdoer, and to onlookers, that the injury was not serious enough to require any response from them at all.\n\nA further clarification separates forgiveness from mere condoning. Forgiveness is typically understood as directed at a person, a relinquishing of hostility toward the wrongdoer as an individual, whereas condoning involves approving of or excusing the act itself. A victim can therefore forgive the person who wronged them while still regarding the act as seriously and unambiguously wrong, which shows that forgiveness need not, by itself, minimise the offence.\n\nTaken together, these considerations suggest that forgiveness is not automatically virtuous simply by occurring. Forgiveness offered in response to genuine acknowledgment and repair looks like the moral achievement its defenders describe, but forgiveness extended unconditionally, without any such response from the wrongdoer, may reflect something closer to a failure of self-respect than to virtue, a willingness to treat one's own injuries as too insignificant to merit an accounting. The popular insistence that forgiveness is always admirable therefore obscures a real question about what, if anything, forgiveness ought to be conditioned upon."}, {"id": 277, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the passage's main claim about the nature of loyalty owed to an institution?", "options": {"A": "Loyalty is a fiction invented solely to secure employee obedience.", "B": "Loyalty is unconditional and cannot be forfeited by any institution.", "C": "Loyalty applies only to relationships between colleagues, never to institutions.", "D": "Loyalty is genuine but conditional on the institution's basic decency."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage argues that loyalty arising from real relationships and shared undertakings is a genuine value, but one that institutions can forfeit through concealment of fraud, endangerment of the public, or punishing internal complaints. This conditionality is what allows whistleblowing to be compatible with, rather than a betrayal of, loyalty properly understood. The other options either dismiss loyalty as pure fiction or treat it as absolute, both of which the passage explicitly rejects.", "passage_id": "P070", "passage_title": "Speaking Out of Turn", "passage_text": "Employees who expose wrongdoing within their own organisations are frequently met with the accusation of disloyalty before anyone examines whether the accusation itself is disloyalty or something worse dressed up as a virtue. Loyalty is often invoked as though it were a free-standing obligation, sufficient on its own to settle whether an employee ought to have stayed silent, regardless of what the silence protected.\n\nA more careful view treats loyalty as a genuine value arising from real relationships and shared undertakings, rather than a mere fiction used to secure obedience. Colleagues who have built something together, or an institution that has invested in an employee's development, can plausibly generate obligations beyond those owed to strangers. Yet this value is not unconditional. Loyalty is owed to institutions and colleagues in proportion to their own basic decency, and an institution that conceals fraud, endangers the public, or punishes those who raise concerns internally has already forfeited much of the claim it might otherwise have had on an employee's silence.\n\nA separate and largely practical difficulty concerns who bears the cost of exposing wrongdoing. The person who reports misconduct typically risks their career, their relationships with former colleagues, and sometimes their legal standing, while the benefits of exposure, a safer product, an honest market, an accountable institution, are dispersed across a public that bears almost none of that personal cost. This asymmetry raises an uncomfortable question about whether it is fair to rely on individual conscience to correct institutional wrongdoing, or whether the persistence of this asymmetry is itself evidence that institutional channels for reporting concerns have failed.\n\nThis last point suggests a further distinction worth preserving, between reporting concerns internally and disclosing them publicly. Public disclosure carries greater reputational and legal risk for the institution and a wider audience for the wrongdoing, and is generally thought justified only once internal channels have been tried in good faith and have proven either exhausted or captured by the very interests the report would expose. Loyalty, properly understood, never required silence in the face of serious harm; it required, at most, a fair chance for the institution to correct itself first."}, {"id": 279, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "Under what condition does the passage suggest that public disclosure of wrongdoing, rather than internal reporting, becomes justified?", "options": {"A": "As soon as any employee personally disagrees with institutional policy.", "B": "Once internal channels have been tried in good faith and proven exhausted or captured.", "C": "Only after the institution has already been prosecuted successfully.", "D": "Whenever the wrongdoing involves a large rather than a small organisation."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage states that public disclosure is generally justified only once internal channels have been attempted in good faith and have proven either exhausted or captured by the interests the report would expose. This preserves a preference for internal correction before resorting to wider exposure. The other options substitute personal disagreement, prior prosecution, or organisational size for the condition the passage actually specifies.", "passage_id": "P070", "passage_title": "Speaking Out of Turn", "passage_text": "Employees who expose wrongdoing within their own organisations are frequently met with the accusation of disloyalty before anyone examines whether the accusation itself is disloyalty or something worse dressed up as a virtue. Loyalty is often invoked as though it were a free-standing obligation, sufficient on its own to settle whether an employee ought to have stayed silent, regardless of what the silence protected.\n\nA more careful view treats loyalty as a genuine value arising from real relationships and shared undertakings, rather than a mere fiction used to secure obedience. Colleagues who have built something together, or an institution that has invested in an employee's development, can plausibly generate obligations beyond those owed to strangers. Yet this value is not unconditional. Loyalty is owed to institutions and colleagues in proportion to their own basic decency, and an institution that conceals fraud, endangers the public, or punishes those who raise concerns internally has already forfeited much of the claim it might otherwise have had on an employee's silence.\n\nA separate and largely practical difficulty concerns who bears the cost of exposing wrongdoing. The person who reports misconduct typically risks their career, their relationships with former colleagues, and sometimes their legal standing, while the benefits of exposure, a safer product, an honest market, an accountable institution, are dispersed across a public that bears almost none of that personal cost. This asymmetry raises an uncomfortable question about whether it is fair to rely on individual conscience to correct institutional wrongdoing, or whether the persistence of this asymmetry is itself evidence that institutional channels for reporting concerns have failed.\n\nThis last point suggests a further distinction worth preserving, between reporting concerns internally and disclosing them publicly. Public disclosure carries greater reputational and legal risk for the institution and a wider audience for the wrongdoing, and is generally thought justified only once internal channels have been tried in good faith and have proven either exhausted or captured by the very interests the report would expose. Loyalty, properly understood, never required silence in the face of serious harm; it required, at most, a fair chance for the institution to correct itself first."}, {"id": 293, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "The passage suggests that the willingness to accept legal punishment is significant because it", "options": {"A": "guarantees the protest will succeed.", "B": "is required by international law.", "C": "proves the protester is acting violently.", "D": "signals continued recognition of the legal system's general authority."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage states that accepting punishment is what distinguishes the civil disobedient from the revolutionary or the ordinary criminal, since it signals continued acceptance of the legal system's general authority while contesting a specific application of it. It makes no claim about international legal requirements or guaranteed success. The remaining options either invent claims or contradict the definition of non-violence given for civil disobedience.", "passage_id": "P074", "passage_title": "Civil Disobedience and the Question of Authority", "passage_text": "Civil disobedience occupies an uneasy position between ordinary lawbreaking and legitimate political protest. Rawls defined it as a public, non-violent, conscientious breach of law undertaken to bring about a change in law or policy, distinguished from mere criminality by its appeal to the community's shared sense of justice and by the willingness of participants to accept the legal consequences of their actions. This willingness to accept punishment is often treated as the feature that separates the civil disobedient from the revolutionary or the ordinary criminal, since it signals that the protester still recognises the general authority of the legal system even while contesting one of its particular applications.\n\nCritics of this framing argue that it smuggles in an unwarranted deference to existing legal authority, one that may be especially convenient for those already comfortable within a just enough system to have the luxury of playing by its rules even while breaking them. Movements confronting deeply entrenched injustice, the argument runs, may reasonably refuse to accept punishment as the price of protest, since doing so implicitly concedes that the system retains legitimate authority to punish resistance to its own worst features. The Underground Railroad's conductors did not turn themselves in to slave catchers as a token of respect for a legal order they rightly regarded as fundamentally corrupt.\n\nA further question concerns the line between civil disobedience and violent resistance. Defenders of strict non-violence argue that violence undermines the very moral claim on which civil disobedience rests, since it substitutes coercion for persuasion and abandons the attempt to appeal to fellow citizens' sense of fairness. Others counter that a rigid insistence on non-violence can itself be a demand made more easily by those not bearing the immediate brunt of the injustice being protested, and that history contains cases in which limited property destruction, as distinct from harm to persons, achieved results that patient non-violent appeal alone had not. Neither view denies that civil disobedience must remain answerable to some standard beyond mere effectiveness; the disagreement concerns which standard that should be, and who is entitled to set it."}, {"id": 301, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the main weakness the author identifies in the therapy-versus-enhancement argument made by proponents of germline editing?", "options": {"A": "It treats a difference in the certainty of harm as if it were no difference at all.", "B": "It assumes that all parents necessarily share identical, fixed values about what constitutes a good life.", "C": "It significantly overstates how expensive current gene editing technology actually remains for most wealthy parents today.", "D": "It ignores that metabolic disorders are actually extremely rare occurrences within most modern clinical practice settings."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage argues that averting a clear pathology differs meaningfully from selecting for traits whose worth is contested and depends on parental values the child may not share. The proponents collapse this into a mere matter of degree, which the author treats as the central flaw. The rarity of metabolic disorders and the cost of technology are not the objections raised.", "passage_id": "P076", "passage_title": "The Engineered Child", "passage_text": "Proponents of germline gene editing present the technology as a natural extension of parental care. If a couple can screen embryos for a fatal metabolic disorder, the argument runs, why should they be forbidden from adjusting a gene linked to resistance against a common infection, or one thought to influence height or temperament? The distinction between therapy and enhancement, on this view, is a matter of degree rather than kind, and any line drawn between the two is arbitrary and will eventually be abandoned as the technology becomes cheaper and more precise.\n\nThis argument moves too quickly. The metabolic disorder case involves averting a condition that virtually everyone would regard as an unambiguous harm, one that curtails the child's future range of choices regardless of what kind of life she comes to value. Height, temperament, and even disease resistance are different: their worth depends on a picture of the good life that the parents hold now, which the child may not share once she is old enough to hold views of her own. To engineer a trait on the assumption that it will suit her is to gamble with a future person's autonomy using values she never endorsed.\n\nA further worry concerns fairness rather than autonomy. Even if we set aside the question of whether it is wrong to select for traits, unequal access to the relevant technology would translate directly into unequal life prospects, since traits such as disease resistance or cognitive stamina confer real advantages in competitive settings. A regime in which only wealthy parents can afford such editing would harden existing social stratification into biology itself, making inherited privilege appear to be a natural and therefore unchallengeable fact.\n\nNone of this establishes that germline editing should be banned outright. It suggests instead that regulation should track the distinction the enthusiasts wish to erase: interventions that remove a clear and serious pathology sit on stronger ground than those that merely select among traits whose value is contested. Legislators tempted to defer to technological momentum, on the assumption that a line will blur eventually anyway, mistake a prediction about future practice for a reason to abandon a defensible principle now. The fact that a boundary may one day be eroded is not an argument against maintaining it while it still does useful work."}, {"id": 302, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to the passage, why might unequal access to gene editing be especially troubling?", "options": {"A": "It would make disease resistance impossible to achieve through other means.", "B": "It would embed existing social advantage into biology and make it seem natural.", "C": "It would eliminate the therapy versus enhancement distinction entirely.", "D": "It would prevent any regulation of the technology from being enforced."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The author warns that unequal access would translate social privilege into biological advantage, making inherited status appear to be a natural fact rather than a social arrangement that could be challenged. This is presented as a distinct fairness concern, separate from the autonomy argument. The other options misstate or invent claims not found in the text.", "passage_id": "P076", "passage_title": "The Engineered Child", "passage_text": "Proponents of germline gene editing present the technology as a natural extension of parental care. If a couple can screen embryos for a fatal metabolic disorder, the argument runs, why should they be forbidden from adjusting a gene linked to resistance against a common infection, or one thought to influence height or temperament? The distinction between therapy and enhancement, on this view, is a matter of degree rather than kind, and any line drawn between the two is arbitrary and will eventually be abandoned as the technology becomes cheaper and more precise.\n\nThis argument moves too quickly. The metabolic disorder case involves averting a condition that virtually everyone would regard as an unambiguous harm, one that curtails the child's future range of choices regardless of what kind of life she comes to value. Height, temperament, and even disease resistance are different: their worth depends on a picture of the good life that the parents hold now, which the child may not share once she is old enough to hold views of her own. To engineer a trait on the assumption that it will suit her is to gamble with a future person's autonomy using values she never endorsed.\n\nA further worry concerns fairness rather than autonomy. Even if we set aside the question of whether it is wrong to select for traits, unequal access to the relevant technology would translate directly into unequal life prospects, since traits such as disease resistance or cognitive stamina confer real advantages in competitive settings. A regime in which only wealthy parents can afford such editing would harden existing social stratification into biology itself, making inherited privilege appear to be a natural and therefore unchallengeable fact.\n\nNone of this establishes that germline editing should be banned outright. It suggests instead that regulation should track the distinction the enthusiasts wish to erase: interventions that remove a clear and serious pathology sit on stronger ground than those that merely select among traits whose value is contested. Legislators tempted to defer to technological momentum, on the assumption that a line will blur eventually anyway, mistake a prediction about future practice for a reason to abandon a defensible principle now. The fact that a boundary may one day be eroded is not an argument against maintaining it while it still does useful work."}, {"id": 308, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What does the phrase \"the emotional satisfaction\" of blame suggest about the author's attitude toward the demand for a single culpable party?", "options": {"A": "That the demand answers a psychological need rather than an accurate description of causation.", "B": "That the demand is a legitimate legal requirement that should be preserved.", "C": "That the demand is shared equally by engineers, deployers, and regulators.", "D": "That the demand has already been fully satisfied by current regulatory practice."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "By describing the appeal of a single culpable party as emotionally satisfying rather than accurate, the author signals that this demand reflects a psychological preference rather than a faithful account of how harm arises from layered decisions. The passage explicitly favours the diffuse account as more honest, which undercuts the legal framing offered by one of the alternative readings. Nothing in the text indicates the demand has been satisfied or is shared equally among the parties.", "passage_id": "P077", "passage_title": "Blame Without a Driver", "passage_text": "When an autonomous vehicle brakes too late and injures a pedestrian, or a hospital algorithm recommends withholding treatment from a patient who later dies, there is a strong pull toward asking who is to blame. The pull is understandable but often misdirected, because the moral vocabulary of blame was built for agents who can be said to have chosen otherwise, and it sits awkwardly on systems whose behaviour emerges from data, weighting, and code that no single person fully anticipated.\n\nOne response is to insist that responsibility simply migrates upward, resting entirely with the engineers who built the system or the executives who deployed it. There is something right in this, since these parties did make choices, about training data, about acceptable error rates, about whether to deploy at all. Yet pressed too far, this response becomes a kind of moral overreach: it treats every downstream outcome of a complex, adaptive system as if it had been foreseen and endorsed by its designers in the way an ordinary decision is foreseen and endorsed by the person who makes it. Engineers can reasonably answer for the design choices they made and the testing they did or failed to do, but not for every particular outcome the system later produces in situations they never modelled.\n\nA second response denies that anyone is fully responsible, treating the harm as a kind of accident with no author, similar to a landslide. This is equally unsatisfying, because it removes the incentive for care in design and deployment that responsibility ascriptions exist to preserve. If no one answers for outcomes, there is little pressure to test more rigorously or to disclose known limitations honestly.\n\nA more defensible position distributes responsibility across the chain of decisions that made deployment possible, without collapsing it into either extreme. Engineers answer for the foreseeable consequences of design choices, deployers answer for the adequacy of oversight and disclosure, and regulators answer for the standards they set or failed to set. What this approach abandons is the demand for a single culpable party, the demand that gives blame its emotional satisfaction but that autonomous systems, by their nature, can rarely supply. Accepting a diffuse and layered form of responsibility is less satisfying than pointing at one person, but it is a more honest description of how these harms actually come about."}, {"id": 311, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "How does the author respond to the claim that only those with something to hide need fear surveillance?", "options": {"A": "By arguing that the harm depends on a chilling effect on everyone, not on wrongdoing being uncovered.", "B": "By agreeing that the claim is correct for the majority of citizens.", "C": "By pointing out that surveillance systems rarely function as intended.", "D": "By suggesting that only political dissidents are affected by observation."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The author directly rejects the claim, explaining that the harm of surveillance arises from its chilling effect on the law-abiding majority rather than from any wrongdoing it might expose. This is explicitly extended beyond dissidents to include ordinary behaviour and association. The passage does not discuss the technical reliability of surveillance systems in this context.", "passage_id": "P078", "passage_title": "The Watched Street", "passage_text": "Advocates of expanded public surveillance frequently appeal to a simple exchange: citizens trade a measure of privacy for a measure of safety, and since safety is valued so highly, the trade should be regarded as an easy one. This framing, however, obscures more than it reveals, because it treats privacy as a discrete commodity that can be handed over in fixed quantities, when in fact privacy functions less like a possession and more like a condition that makes certain forms of freedom possible in the first place.\n\nConsider what changes when a street is comprehensively monitored, not merely by a camera at a corner but by networked systems capable of tracking movement, associating faces with names, and building a record of where a person goes and how often. The resident under such observation may commit no crime and suffer no direct harm, yet her behaviour is likely to change regardless, because the awareness of being watched narrows the range of association and expression she is willing to risk. Political dissent, unconventional friendships, and simple eccentricity all tend to recede under sustained observation, not because they are forbidden but because visibility itself carries a cost that people are rational to avoid.\n\nDefenders of surveillance sometimes respond that only those who have committed offences need worry about being watched, since only they have anything to hide. This response misunderstands what is at stake. The harm of surveillance does not depend on wrongdoing being uncovered; it depends on the chilling effect that pervasive observation exerts on everyone, including the law-abiding majority who might otherwise have taken small risks in how they speak, associate, or live.\n\nNone of this settles the question of whether particular surveillance measures are justified, since some genuine safety gains are real and some risks to liberty are modest. It does mean that the language of a simple trade misdescribes the stakes, and that any honest assessment must weigh not only crimes prevented but also the quieter erosion of the willingness to take social and political risks, an erosion that is real even when no camera ever produces evidence against a single person."}, {"id": 316, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What is the function of the phrase \"as if it did not exist\" in the final paragraph?", "options": {"A": "It criticises regulators for denying that new technologies carry any risk.", "B": "It suggests that irreversible harms are rare enough to be safely ignored.", "C": "It highlights how the precautionary principle disregards the risk side of inaction.", "D": "It implies that scientific uncertainty can eventually be eliminated entirely."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The phrase points to how a general application of the precautionary principle effectively treats the risks of inaction as nonexistent, ignoring one side of the comparison the author insists must be weighed properly. It is not aimed at denying risk from new technologies, nor does it claim irreversible harms are rare or that uncertainty can be eliminated. The sentence closes the passage's call for symmetrical treatment of both risks.", "passage_id": "P079", "passage_title": "Caution as a Principle", "passage_text": "The precautionary principle holds, roughly, that when an action carries a risk of serious or irreversible harm, the absence of full scientific certainty should not be used as a reason to postpone measures that could prevent that harm. Applied to novel technologies, this principle is often invoked to justify delaying deployment until safety has been established beyond reasonable doubt. Its appeal lies in an asymmetry that seems intuitively compelling: the cost of wrongly restricting a beneficial technology appears smaller than the cost of wrongly permitting a harmful one.\n\nThis asymmetry, however, is less stable than it first appears. Delay is not a neutral default state in which nothing happens while evidence accumulates; it is itself a choice with costs, some of which are also serious and irreversible. A medical treatment withheld pending further trials may mean that patients who could have been helped instead suffer the harm of forgone treatment, a harm just as real as the one the principle aims to prevent, merely distributed differently and often less visibly, since the people harmed by delay rarely appear in any headline about caution having failed.\n\nThe deeper difficulty is that the precautionary principle, taken at face value, offers no method for weighing one irreversible risk against another; it simply instructs decision makers to avoid the risk of action, without telling them how to compare it against the risk of inaction. Applied consistently, it would counsel against almost any new technology, since novelty is nearly always accompanied by some uncertainty, and applied selectively, it becomes a tool for justifying whatever conclusion a regulator had already reached on other grounds.\n\nNone of this shows that caution is misplaced. It shows that caution cannot substitute for the harder work of comparing the specific risks of action and inaction in a given case, weighing their likelihood, severity, and reversibility rather than invoking a general principle that treats one side of the ledger as if it did not exist. A regulator who takes uncertainty seriously must take it seriously on both sides of the decision, not only on the side that involves permitting something new."}, {"id": 317, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What does the author identify as the strongest objection to enhancement, as opposed to the objection commonly attributed to critics?", "options": {"A": "That enhancement is inherently unnatural and therefore always morally wrong regardless of any surrounding context.", "B": "That enhancement undermines fairness when outcomes are meant to be compared on a common footing.", "C": "That enhancement technologies remain not yet reliable or safe enough for widespread everyday practical use.", "D": "That enhancement always produces measurably worse outcomes overall than ordinary unaided personal effort alone."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage explicitly distinguishes the caricatured objection based on naturalness from the stronger objection grounded in fairness, which arises specifically in contexts where a shared standard is supposed to compare people on equal terms. Reliability of technology and comparative outcomes are not raised as the basis for the strongest objection. This distinction sets up the exam example that follows.", "passage_id": "P080", "passage_title": "An Uneven Start", "passage_text": "Debates about cognitive and physical enhancement are often framed as contests between those who welcome self-improvement and those who cling to an arbitrary notion of the natural. This framing flatters one side of the debate while caricaturing the other, since the strongest objections to enhancement rarely rest on the claim that departing from an unaided baseline is inherently wrong. They rest instead on a concern about fairness in contexts where outcomes are meant to be compared on a common footing.\n\nConsider a competitive examination designed to identify the most capable candidates for a scarce set of positions. If some candidates can afford a cognitive enhancement that measurably improves memory retention or sustained attention, while others cannot, the examination no longer measures the same thing for everyone who sits it. It becomes, in part, a measure of access to enhancement rather than of underlying aptitude, even though the scores themselves look identical in form. The unfairness here has nothing to do with tampering with nature and everything to do with quietly changing what a shared standard is actually assessing.\n\nA reply sometimes offered is that unequal access already pervades education, through private tutoring, better schools, and family resources that shape a candidate's starting point long before any exam. If society tolerates these inequalities, the reply continues, it is inconsistent to object specifically to enhancement. This reply has some force but proves less than it claims. Existing inequalities in preparation are already a serious problem that arguably deserves more correction than it receives, not a precedent that licenses adding a new and more direct form of unequal advantage on top of them. Two wrongs of the same kind do not make the practice acceptable; they make the case for addressing both.\n\nA more productive response than dismissing enhancement outright is to distinguish contexts where fairness of comparison matters acutely, such as competitive selection, from contexts where it matters less, such as private pursuits of memory or fitness with no comparative stakes attached. Enhancement is not a single practice with a single moral status; its acceptability depends heavily on whether the setting in which it occurs depends on people being compared against a standard assumed to be common to all."}, {"id": 330, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Which claim does the passage use survey evidence to challenge?", "options": {"A": "That scientific consensus depends on converging independent findings.", "B": "That distrust of institutions is unrelated to political or social identity.", "C": "That public skepticism results mainly from a lack of scientific knowledge.", "D": "That repeating data can never change any sceptic's mind under any circumstance."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage cites surveys showing that skepticism correlates poorly with scientific literacy and strongly with social identity, which undermines the common assumption that skepticism is mainly a knowledge deficit. This evidence is introduced specifically to counter the view that showing people more data would resolve their doubts. The passage does not use this evidence to make a claim about whether repetition can ever work, only that it addresses the wrong cause for many sceptics.", "passage_id": "P083", "passage_title": "The Gap Between Knowing and Believing", "passage_text": "Scientific consensus on questions such as vaccine safety or the human contribution to climate change is rarely the product of a single decisive experiment. It instead accumulates from thousands of independent studies, conducted by researchers with competing incentives and institutional loyalties, whose findings converge despite having no coordinated reason to agree with one another. This convergence, rather than any individual finding, is what gives such consensus its epistemic weight, since it is difficult to explain thousands of independent errors all pointing in the same direction.\n\nPublic skepticism toward this consensus is often dismissed by scientists as simple ignorance, a failure to understand data that would resolve itself if only the public were shown enough graphs. Yet surveys repeatedly find that skepticism correlates poorly with scientific literacy and strongly with the values and social identities of the communities a person belongs to. A skeptic who cannot explain a single mechanism of vaccine action may nonetheless hold a coherent, if mistaken, view that tracks the trusted voices in their own social network rather than any deficit in reasoning ability.\n\nThis suggests that the persuasive strategies favoured by scientific institutions, chiefly the repetition of data and the correction of factual misconceptions, address a cause of skepticism that is not, for many sceptics, the actual cause of their doubt. If distrust flows from a sense that scientific institutions are aligned with social groups or political projects one already distrusts, then no additional graph will dissolve it, because the graph was never the source of the disagreement in the first place.\n\nNone of this implies that the underlying science is therefore in genuine doubt, nor that expertise should be treated as merely one perspective among equally valid others. It implies instead that closing the gap between expert consensus and public belief is a problem of trust and social identity as much as one of information, and that treating it purely as an information deficit will continue to produce interventions that fail for reasons their designers do not anticipate.\n\nA more promising approach, on this account, would work through the trusted messengers a community already listens to, rather than attempting to bypass them with centrally produced material. This shifts the burden away from producing ever more precise data and toward the slower, less measurable work of rebuilding institutional credibility within communities where it has eroded."}, {"id": 331, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The description of a sceptic's view as 'coherent, if mistaken' in paragraph 2 is best read as", "options": {"A": "an endorsement of the scientific accuracy of the sceptic's position.", "B": "an acknowledgment that the view follows a logic of its own despite being factually wrong.", "C": "a suggestion that all sceptical views are equally justified as expert consensus.", "D": "a claim that the sceptic has carefully studied the relevant scientific literature."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The phrase concedes that a sceptical belief can be internally consistent, tracking trusted social sources in a logical way, while still being factually incorrect about the underlying science. It is not an endorsement of the belief's truth, since the passage pairs coherence with the qualifier that the view is mistaken. Nor does the passage suggest such views carry equal standing with expert consensus, since it explicitly denies that expertise should be treated as merely one perspective among others.", "passage_id": "P083", "passage_title": "The Gap Between Knowing and Believing", "passage_text": "Scientific consensus on questions such as vaccine safety or the human contribution to climate change is rarely the product of a single decisive experiment. It instead accumulates from thousands of independent studies, conducted by researchers with competing incentives and institutional loyalties, whose findings converge despite having no coordinated reason to agree with one another. This convergence, rather than any individual finding, is what gives such consensus its epistemic weight, since it is difficult to explain thousands of independent errors all pointing in the same direction.\n\nPublic skepticism toward this consensus is often dismissed by scientists as simple ignorance, a failure to understand data that would resolve itself if only the public were shown enough graphs. Yet surveys repeatedly find that skepticism correlates poorly with scientific literacy and strongly with the values and social identities of the communities a person belongs to. A skeptic who cannot explain a single mechanism of vaccine action may nonetheless hold a coherent, if mistaken, view that tracks the trusted voices in their own social network rather than any deficit in reasoning ability.\n\nThis suggests that the persuasive strategies favoured by scientific institutions, chiefly the repetition of data and the correction of factual misconceptions, address a cause of skepticism that is not, for many sceptics, the actual cause of their doubt. If distrust flows from a sense that scientific institutions are aligned with social groups or political projects one already distrusts, then no additional graph will dissolve it, because the graph was never the source of the disagreement in the first place.\n\nNone of this implies that the underlying science is therefore in genuine doubt, nor that expertise should be treated as merely one perspective among equally valid others. It implies instead that closing the gap between expert consensus and public belief is a problem of trust and social identity as much as one of information, and that treating it purely as an information deficit will continue to produce interventions that fail for reasons their designers do not anticipate.\n\nA more promising approach, on this account, would work through the trusted messengers a community already listens to, rather than attempting to bypass them with centrally produced material. This shifts the burden away from producing ever more precise data and toward the slower, less measurable work of rebuilding institutional credibility within communities where it has eroded."}, {"id": 335, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to paragraph 3, where do some philosophers argue the ethical question should actually be located?", "options": {"A": "In the specific DNA sequence being altered by the editing technique.", "B": "In whether a government regulator has approved the procedure in advance.", "C": "In the severity of the condition and the choice available to the child later.", "D": "In whether the technique has previously been used for cosmetic purposes."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Paragraph 3 argues that the moral question should turn on the severity of the condition being addressed and the degree of choice available to the child once born, rather than on the technique used to perform the edit. This is precisely why these philosophers regard the therapy and enhancement label as inadequate, since it focuses on the method rather than these contextual factors. Locating the question in the DNA sequence itself is the approach the passage says these philosophers reject, since paragraph 2 shows identical sequences can serve different purposes.", "passage_id": "P084", "passage_title": "Where Therapy Ends and Enhancement Begins", "passage_text": "Editing the genome of a human embryo to correct a mutation that would otherwise cause a severe inherited disease is, for most ethicists, morally distinguishable from editing an embryo to increase height, intelligence or muscular strength. The distinction rests on a line between therapy, which restores a person to a species typical baseline of functioning, and enhancement, which pushes a person beyond that baseline into territory no member of the species previously occupied. Regulators in most jurisdictions that permit embryo editing at all have adopted some version of this line as the boundary of what is currently lawful.\n\nThe difficulty is that the line is far blurrier in practice than the definition suggests. A mutation that causes a debilitating disease in one carrier may produce only a mild, manageable version of the same condition in another, so that editing it out looks like therapy for one family and something closer to a preference for an easier life for the other. Height offers a starker case still, since a treatment developed to correct a genuine growth hormone disorder is, at the level of the DNA sequence altered, indistinguishable from a treatment used simply to make a child taller than they would otherwise have been.\n\nSome philosophers therefore argue that the therapy and enhancement distinction, however useful as a rough guide for legislators, cannot bear the moral weight it is asked to carry, because it locates the ethical question in the technique rather than in the reasons a particular family has for using it. On this view, the same edit could be defensible or troubling depending entirely on the severity of the condition being addressed and the degree of choice available to the child once born, considerations the therapy and enhancement label does not itself capture.\n\nOthers resist abandoning the distinction altogether, warning that without some baseline concept of species typical functioning, regulation would have no principled stopping point and would instead depend entirely on case by case judgements that wealthy parents could more easily navigate than poor ones. The disagreement, then, is less about individual cases than about whether a workable general rule is worth the blurred edges it inevitably produces."}, {"id": 363, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage imply about the outcome of most drugs that pass early-phase testing?", "options": {"A": "Most go on to fail because they are found ineffective or unsafe.", "B": "Most are withdrawn for reasons unrelated to their medical performance.", "C": "Most eventually receive full regulatory approval within a few years.", "D": "Most are abandoned because manufacturers cannot afford further trials."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The text states directly that the great majority of compounds passing the first hurdle fail at later stages precisely because they prove useless or harmful, which is offered as the reason a dying patient is not choosing between a cure and delay. Nothing in the passage attributes this failure rate to cost or to unrelated withdrawal reasons. The claim about full approval within a few years is unsupported and runs against the point being made.", "passage_id": "P091", "passage_title": "The Right to Try", "passage_text": "A terminally ill patient who has exhausted every approved therapy will often ask, reasonably enough, why the state should stand between her and a drug that might save her life. So-called right-to-try laws answer that question by allowing such patients to obtain experimental treatments that have passed only the earliest phase of clinical testing, before any regulator has judged them safe or effective. The appeal of the argument rests on a simple picture of autonomy: it is my body and my death, so the choice of what to put into it should be mine alone, particularly once conventional medicine has nothing left to offer.\n\nThat picture, however, understates how little is actually known at the point when right-to-try becomes relevant. Early-phase trials are designed to answer questions about toxicity, not about whether a drug works, and the great majority of compounds that pass this first hurdle fail at later stages precisely because they turn out to be useless or harmful. A dying patient is therefore not choosing between a proven cure and bureaucratic delay; she is choosing to gamble, often at considerable financial cost to herself or her family, on a substance about which almost nothing reliable is known. The choice may still be hers to make, but calling it informed consent flatters a decision that is closer to a leap in the dark.\n\nThere is a further difficulty that autonomy-based arguments tend to pass over in silence. Manufacturers who supply drugs outside a formal trial gain nothing scientifically from the transaction: no controlled data is generated, no dosage is refined, and no future patient is helped by the attempt. Meanwhile the same manufacturer can point to a growing list of right-to-try patients as evidence of demand, strengthening its hand in negotiations with regulators and insurers quite apart from any therapeutic benefit achieved. The individual patient's private tragedy becomes, without her necessarily intending it, a public argument for looser rules that will affect countless patients who never volunteered for the experiment.\n\nNone of this shows that dying patients should be refused access to unproven treatments. It shows only that the debate cannot be settled by appeal to autonomy alone, since autonomy presupposes a chooser who understands roughly what is being chosen, and in this case that understanding is precisely what is missing."}, {"id": 371, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase \"backwards\" in the first paragraph is used to suggest that a fear-driven climate strategy might", "options": {"A": "cost more money than a strategy driven by careful cost analysis.", "B": "favour avoiding the more memorable risk over averting the greater overall harm.", "C": "be reversed entirely within a single election cycle.", "D": "ultimately increase public support for fossil fuels specifically."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The sentence contrasts vividness with magnitude, warning that a strategy shaped by the more vivid fear of nuclear accidents risks getting the tradeoff backwards relative to the larger, less visible harm from fossil fuel pollution. This is a claim about prioritising the wrong risk, not a claim about cost, political reversal, or a specific boost to fossil fuel popularity. Those readings introduce ideas the sentence does not contain.", "passage_id": "P093", "passage_title": "Splitting the Atom of the Argument", "passage_text": "Few technologies provoke a reaction as immediate and as poorly calibrated to actual risk as nuclear power. Ask most people to compare the dangers of a coal plant with those of a reactor and they will, often without hesitation, name the reactor as more dangerous, despite decades of data showing that particulate pollution from fossil fuel combustion kills far more people every year than the entire history of civilian nuclear accidents combined. The imbalance in perception is not irrational in the sense of being groundless; catastrophic, visible, and long-lived events such as meltdowns register more vividly in memory than the slow, diffuse harm of pollution-related disease. But vividness is not the same as magnitude, and a climate strategy built on the more vivid fear rather than the larger harm risks getting the tradeoffs backwards.\n\nThe case for nuclear power in a decarbonising world rests on a feature no other low-carbon source currently matches: it supplies large amounts of electricity continuously, regardless of weather, at a fraction of the land use required by solar or wind farms of equivalent output. Renewables remain indispensable, but their intermittency means that a grid relying on them alone still needs either extensive storage, which is expensive and not yet available at the necessary scale, or a dispatchable backup, which today usually means natural gas. Nuclear offers a dispatchable backup that emits almost no carbon at the point of generation, a combination nothing else on the table currently provides.\n\nThis is not an argument that nuclear power is risk-free, nor that every objection to it is merely a matter of misplaced fear. Waste storage remains a genuine unsolved problem measured in millennia rather than decades, and the capital cost and construction time of new reactors have in practice made them a slower and pricier route to decarbonisation than advertised. A serious climate policy has to weigh these real costs against the real cost of continuing to burn fossil fuels while storage technology matures, rather than treating the historical dread of nuclear accidents as though it settled the comparison in advance.\n\nThe honest position, then, is neither uncritical enthusiasm nor reflexive rejection, but a demand that both sides of the ledger be measured by the same standard: actual harm averted against actual harm caused, not the harm that happens to be easiest to picture."}, {"id": 376, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What two requirements does the passage set for any successful account of gradual moral status?", "options": {"A": "Identifying a morally significant change and avoiding convenient alignment with existing legal lines.", "B": "Proving that sentience begins at conception and that personhood begins at birth.", "C": "Winning support from a majority of scientists and a majority of the public simultaneously.", "D": "Rejecting all forms of legal regulation of pregnancy entirely."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The closing paragraph states plainly that any account of gradual moral status must identify a change that is morally significant rather than merely biological, and must resist letting that change conveniently match whatever legal line policy already draws. The passage never claims sentience begins at conception, which would contradict the sentience-based view described earlier, nor does it mention any requirement involving majority scientific or public support. It also does not call for rejecting legal regulation of pregnancy altogether.", "passage_id": "P094", "passage_title": "Lines Drawn in Early Pregnancy", "passage_text": "Debates over the moral status of the early fetus often proceed as though the only two available positions are full personhood from conception and no moral status at all before birth, and much of the heat in the wider argument comes from each side treating the other's position as occupying this most extreme form. Yet very few serious participants in the debate actually hold either extreme, and the more interesting question, largely ignored by slogans on both sides, is what grounds a gradual view according to which moral status increases over the course of gestation rather than switching on at a single moment.\n\nOne common basis for such a gradual view appeals to the development of the capacity for sentience, the ability to have experiences that matter from the inside, including the experience of pain. Before the nervous system has developed sufficiently, on this view, there is simply no subject present to be wronged, whatever biological potential exists. After that threshold is crossed, even though personhood in the full sense may still be absent, there is now someone whose interests can be set back, and this marks a morally significant change even if it does not, by itself, settle every downstream question about permissible treatment.\n\nCritics of the sentience-based view object that it makes moral status hostage to a fact, the precise developmental point at which sentience begins, that is itself uncertain and contested among scientists. If our moral conclusions shift depending on where researchers currently place that threshold, the theory seems to rest on a foundation more unstable than its proponents like to admit. A more sympathetic reading, however, would note that many uncontroversial moral distinctions, between reversible and irreversible harm, for instance, likewise depend on empirical facts that were once uncertain and were revised as knowledge improved, without this instability being thought to undermine the distinctions themselves.\n\nWhat can be said with more confidence is that any account of gradual moral status has to do two things at once: identify a change that is morally significant rather than merely biological, and resist the temptation to make that significant change coincide, conveniently, with whatever legal line current policy already draws."}, {"id": 382, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the main function of the fourth paragraph in the overall argument?", "options": {"A": "It identifies the deeper problem that numerical scores can disguise social judgments as objective facts.", "B": "It concedes outright that algorithms are entirely and unambiguously superior to all human judges.", "C": "It introduces an entirely new topic that is unrelated to the earlier paragraphs discussed.", "D": "It merely summarises statistics about reoffending rates without adding any new analytical point."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The final paragraph draws together the earlier concerns by arguing that the real danger lies in a score's appearance of objectivity masking the social judgments baked into it. This is presented as the passage's central warning rather than a new or separate point. The other options do not reflect the paragraph's actual content or its concluding role.", "passage_id": "P096", "passage_title": "The Calculus of Risk", "passage_text": "Courts in several jurisdictions now consult risk-assessment software when deciding bail, sentencing, or parole. These tools convert a defendant's history, age, and social circumstances into a single score predicting the likelihood of reoffending. Proponents argue the appeal is obvious: a human judge, however conscientious, carries fatigue, mood, and unexamined prejudice into every ruling, whereas an algorithm applies the same formula to every case with mechanical consistency. If consistency is a virtue in the administration of justice, then a system that treats like cases alike, rather than according to the temperament of whichever judge happens to preside, would seem to represent an unambiguous improvement.\n\nThe difficulty is that consistency and fairness are not synonyms. An algorithm trained on historical arrest and conviction data will reproduce the patterns embedded in that data, including patterns produced by decades of uneven policing. If certain neighbourhoods have been patrolled more heavily than others, residents of those neighbourhoods will appear disproportionately in the training data, and the algorithm will learn to treat their postcode as a proxy for risk. The software does not know it is doing this; it simply finds the statistical regularities that were placed in front of it. The resulting predictions can therefore encode exactly the biases that were meant to be engineered away, while wearing the borrowed authority of mathematics.\n\nDefenders of these tools respond that the alternative is not a neutral baseline but an already-biased human system, and that at least an algorithm's reasoning can be audited, whereas a judge's private assumptions cannot. This is a fair point, yet it assumes the audit will actually happen, and that the commercial developers of these tools will permit outside scrutiny of proprietary code. In practice, many risk-assessment systems remain closed to the defendants whose futures they help decide, so the promised transparency is more often asserted than delivered.\n\nWhat should trouble us most is not that machines make mistakes, since human judges plainly do too, but that a numerical score confers a spurious sense of objectivity on a judgment that remains, underneath its decimal points, a social one. Removing a human decision-maker from the loop does not remove the human choices that shaped the data; it merely relocates them somewhere less visible, and considerably harder to challenge on appeal."}, {"id": 384, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "In context, what is the effect of describing a risk score as wearing \"the borrowed authority of mathematics\"?", "options": {"A": "It compares the algorithm to a historical figure.", "B": "It praises mathematics as an inherently trustworthy discipline.", "C": "It implies the score was calculated incorrectly.", "D": "It suggests the score's mathematical form lends it undeserved credibility."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The phrase frames the score's numerical appearance as something adopted rather than earned, implying it gains unwarranted trust simply by looking precise and mathematical. This reinforces the paragraph's broader claim that objectivity here is spurious rather than genuine. The other options misread the phrase as either a literal error claim or an endorsement of mathematics itself.", "passage_id": "P096", "passage_title": "The Calculus of Risk", "passage_text": "Courts in several jurisdictions now consult risk-assessment software when deciding bail, sentencing, or parole. These tools convert a defendant's history, age, and social circumstances into a single score predicting the likelihood of reoffending. Proponents argue the appeal is obvious: a human judge, however conscientious, carries fatigue, mood, and unexamined prejudice into every ruling, whereas an algorithm applies the same formula to every case with mechanical consistency. If consistency is a virtue in the administration of justice, then a system that treats like cases alike, rather than according to the temperament of whichever judge happens to preside, would seem to represent an unambiguous improvement.\n\nThe difficulty is that consistency and fairness are not synonyms. An algorithm trained on historical arrest and conviction data will reproduce the patterns embedded in that data, including patterns produced by decades of uneven policing. If certain neighbourhoods have been patrolled more heavily than others, residents of those neighbourhoods will appear disproportionately in the training data, and the algorithm will learn to treat their postcode as a proxy for risk. The software does not know it is doing this; it simply finds the statistical regularities that were placed in front of it. The resulting predictions can therefore encode exactly the biases that were meant to be engineered away, while wearing the borrowed authority of mathematics.\n\nDefenders of these tools respond that the alternative is not a neutral baseline but an already-biased human system, and that at least an algorithm's reasoning can be audited, whereas a judge's private assumptions cannot. This is a fair point, yet it assumes the audit will actually happen, and that the commercial developers of these tools will permit outside scrutiny of proprietary code. In practice, many risk-assessment systems remain closed to the defendants whose futures they help decide, so the promised transparency is more often asserted than delivered.\n\nWhat should trouble us most is not that machines make mistakes, since human judges plainly do too, but that a numerical score confers a spurious sense of objectivity on a judgment that remains, underneath its decimal points, a social one. Removing a human decision-maker from the loop does not remove the human choices that shaped the data; it merely relocates them somewhere less visible, and considerably harder to challenge on appeal."}, {"id": 387, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the passage's central concern regarding funding priorities?", "options": {"A": "De-extinction research is too cheap to be taken seriously.", "B": "Habitat corridors are less important than genetic engineering.", "C": "Only governments should fund de-extinction projects.", "D": "Resources devoted to reviving extinct species could instead protect currently declining ones."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The third paragraph directly states that money and attention spent on reconstructing extinct animals is money not spent on protecting living, declining species such as elephants. This is framed as an opportunity cost rather than a claim about absolute cost or government responsibility. The remaining options misrepresent or invert this stated concern.", "passage_id": "P097", "passage_title": "Bringing Back What We Erased", "passage_text": "Advances in genetic engineering have made it plausible, within a generation, to reconstruct animals that have not walked the earth for centuries or millennia, from the woolly mammoth to the passenger pigeon. The prospect exercises a peculiar hold on the public imagination, blending the promise of scientific redemption with something closer to wonder at seeing the impossible made real. Yet the case for de-extinction rests on an assumption worth examining: that recreating a species undoes, even partially, the original loss.\n\nA genome is not an ecosystem. The mammoth vanished alongside a particular Ice Age steppe, shaped by climate, predators, and vegetation that no longer exist in that configuration. An animal engineered to resemble a mammoth, inserted into a modern Siberian landscape, would not be returning to its former niche so much as being placed into an entirely new experiment, one whose ecological consequences cannot be predicted from laboratory work alone. Advocates counter that some reintroductions, such as grazing megafauna reshaping tundra vegetation, might even help counteract permafrost thaw, so the experiment could prove beneficial rather than merely reckless.\n\nA further concern is one of priorities. De-extinction projects are technically dazzling and therefore attract funding, media coverage, and philanthropic enthusiasm that might otherwise support the unglamorous, continuous work of protecting species that are still alive but declining. Every dollar spent reconstructing a mammoth is a dollar not spent on habitat corridors for existing elephants, whose populations are shrinking now, in real time, for want of exactly that kind of unglamorous investment. It would be a strange irony if the spectacle of resurrection accelerated the very extinctions it was meant to answer.\n\nNone of this proves de-extinction is wrong in principle. It may be that a de-extinct mammoth, however imperfect a copy, teaches us something about Ice Age ecology that no other method could. But the technology's champions too often speak as though reversing extinction were simply a matter of willpower and sufficient funding, when the harder question is whether an ecosystem, once unravelled, can meaningfully be rewoven around a single reconstructed thread."}, {"id": 390, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "How do opponents of a kidney market respond to the comparison with hazardous labour?", "options": {"A": "They agree entirely with the analogy and therefore fully support completely unrestricted kidney sales for all applicants.", "B": "They argue the irreversibility of organ removal and existing limits on contractual freedom distinguish the two cases.", "C": "They claim instead that hazardous labour of every kind should also be banned immediately and completely.", "D": "They flatly deny that poor people ever take any genuinely hazardous jobs at all."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The final paragraph counters the hazardous-labour analogy by noting that most such labour does not involve permanently losing a body part, and that societies already limit certain contracts regardless of consent, such as indentured servitude. This distinguishes organ sale from ordinary risky employment rather than treating them as equivalent. The other options do not reflect the nuanced distinction the passage draws.", "passage_id": "P098", "passage_title": "The Price of a Kidney", "passage_text": "Every year, thousands of patients die waiting for a kidney that never arrives, while a healthy person could survive with only one. This gap between need and supply has led some economists to propose a regulated market in which donors would be paid for a kidney, subject to medical screening and legal safeguards. Such a market, they argue, would simply extend to organs the same logic already applied to blood plasma and, in some countries, to surrogacy, where financial compensation coexists with regulation rather than replacing it entirely.\n\nOpponents reply that a market in kidneys is different in kind, not merely degree, from a market in plasma, because a kidney cannot be replenished by the body and its sale carries irreversible risk. Under financial pressure, the argument runs, it is overwhelmingly the poor who would sell, meaning the supposed choice offered by the market is less a genuine exercise of autonomy than a symptom of desperation dressed in the language of consent. A transaction technically voluntary can still be substantively coerced if refusing it means being unable to pay rent or feed one's children.\n\nDefenders of a regulated market respond that this objection, taken to its logical end, would also forbid the poor from taking any physically demanding or hazardous job, since low-wage labourers already accept risk under financial pressure that wealthier applicants would decline. If we permit dangerous mining or construction work because banning it would remove income from people who need it, consistency seems to demand we at least consider permitting kidney sales on similar grounds, rather than singling out organs for special prohibition.\n\nThe counter to this is that most hazardous labour, however exploitative, does not involve the permanent, irreversible removal of a body part, and that the state already restricts certain transactions, such as the sale of oneself into indentured servitude, precisely because unlimited contractual freedom can produce outcomes society judges unacceptable regardless of consent. Whether kidney sale belongs alongside hazardous labour or alongside indentured servitude, on this view, is not a question economics alone can settle. It is, at bottom, a disagreement about which forms of desperation a state is willing to formalise into contract, and which it must instead refuse to recognise as bargains at all."}, {"id": 393, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "According to the passage, why might a human soldier be better able than an algorithm to distinguish a wedding from a militia gathering?", "options": {"A": "Because soldiers reportedly receive training on far more historical combat data than algorithms.", "B": "Because algorithms are always significantly faster at processing information than human perception itself.", "C": "Because a human can register subtle contextual cues that a pattern-trained system may miss.", "D": "Because algorithms reportedly cannot process any visual battlefield information whatsoever at all."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The second paragraph attributes this advantage to a human capacity for recognising contextual cues beyond what an algorithm trained on prior patterns has learned to detect. This is presented as a limitation of pattern-based training rather than a claim about data volume or processing speed. The other options invent claims the passage does not make.", "passage_id": "P099", "passage_title": "War Without a Human Hand", "passage_text": "Weapons systems capable of selecting and engaging targets without a human issuing the final command are no longer speculative; several militaries have already tested such systems, and a handful reportedly deployed them in limited combat. Supporters describe them as a means of removing the frailties of human perception, exhaustion, and panic from the most consequential decision a person can make, arguing that a machine, unclouded by fear or the desire for revenge, might in principle apply the laws of armed conflict more faithfully than a soldier under fire ever could.\n\nCritics respond that the laws of armed conflict were written for human judgment precisely because they require the weighing of proportionality and necessity in circumstances no rule can fully anticipate. A soldier deciding whether to fire on a building can, at least in principle, recognise a wedding rather than a militia gathering by registering subtle contextual cues that a targeting algorithm, trained on prior patterns, may simply fail to register at all. The absence of fear is not obviously a virtue if it is accompanied by an absence of the very moral perception that fear, among other things, can sharpen.\n\nA further objection concerns accountability. When a human pulls a trigger, a chain of responsibility runs from that individual through the chain of command, however imperfectly it is enforced in practice. When an algorithm selects a target and a civilian dies, it becomes far harder to locate a single responsible party, since the error might lie in the training data, the sensor, the software engineer, or the commanding officer who approved deployment. Diffusing responsibility across so many hands can, in effect, dissolve it altogether, leaving no one who can meaningfully be held to account.\n\nDefenders insist this problem is not unique to autonomous weapons but afflicts any sufficiently complex modern military system, and that accountability gaps should be closed through better logging and oversight rather than by abandoning a technology that might, on balance, reduce casualties. Whether that trade is acceptable turns on a question neither side can answer by appeal to technology alone: whether a reduction in error is worth the price of no longer being able to say, clearly, whose judgment failed when the error occurred."}, {"id": 402, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Which of the following best describes the writer's own position on judging historical figures?", "options": {"A": "All historical figures should be judged by identical modern standards.", "B": "No judgement of the past is ever legitimate or useful.", "C": "Figures should be judged against dissenting voices available in their own time.", "D": "Only figures who freed slaves themselves deserve praise."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The writer suggests that the relevant test is not whether a historical figure met a standard invented later, but whether he ignored a competing view voiced by people around him at the time. This positions the argument as neither blanket condemnation by modern standards nor a blanket refusal to judge at all. The other options describe more extreme positions that the passage explicitly avoids taking.", "passage_id": "P101", "passage_title": "Judging the Dead", "passage_text": "Defenders of statues to slaveholding founders and colonial administrators frequently offer a single retort to those who would tear them down: it is unfair to judge the past by the standards of the present, since the men in question were merely creatures of their age, no more able to see beyond its horizons than a fish can see the water in which it swims. This argument has an appealing symmetry, since it appears to extend to historical figures the same charity we would wish applied to our own descendants, who may one day condemn us for eating meat or flying in aeroplanes. Yet the argument collapses under scrutiny, because it rests on a false premise: that the moral consensus of any given era was uniform, and that no contemporary voice offered a rival vision.\n\nIn truth, slavery was fiercely contested throughout the eighteenth century by abolitionists, freed slaves and even some slaveholders who freed their own human property in a fit of conscience. Colonial rule was denounced by missionaries, radicals and, not infrequently, by the colonised themselves, whose objections were recorded, published and in some cases read by the very administrators who dismissed them. To say that a slaveholder could not have known better is to erase these dissenting voices from the historical record, and to flatten a plural, argumentative past into a single monolithic outlook that suits the convenience of the defender.\n\nNone of this licenses the opposite error, that of imagining ourselves morally superior simply by virtue of living later. Future generations will doubtless find something in our own conduct to condemn, and smugness about our present enlightenment is no more warranted than the excuse of inherited ignorance. What the presentism charge misses is not that judgement is impossible, but that judgement was already available at the time, articulated by people the historical figure in question could have listened to and chose not to. The question worth asking of a slaveholding founder is therefore not whether he violated a standard invented two centuries later, but whether he ignored one that his own contemporaries were shouting at him. Answered honestly, that question rarely exonerates its subject."}, {"id": 406, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The writer's central claim about the relationship between economic hardship and revolution is that hardship:", "options": {"A": "requires a prior ideological framework to become revolutionary.", "B": "is sufficient on its own to produce organised rebellion.", "C": "has no bearing whatsoever on whether revolution occurs.", "D": "only matters in regions with a strong printing industry."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage argues that economic hardship functions as fuel requiring a prior circulation of ideas reframing suffering as injustice before it can ignite into revolt. Without that framework, the writer suggests, hardship tends to produce quieter responses rather than organised rebellion. The remaining options either overstate hardship's independent power or dismiss its role entirely, neither of which matches the writer's nuanced claim.", "passage_id": "P102", "passage_title": "The Spark and the Kindling", "passage_text": "It has become a truism of social science that revolutions are born of hunger, that when bread prices rise and wages stagnate, the poor eventually rise with them. The appeal of this account lies in its simplicity: it requires no reference to pamphlets, philosophers or foreign example, only to the ledger of prices and the physiology of an empty stomach. Yet the historical record refuses to cooperate with such tidy arithmetic. France in 1789 was not, by the measures available to us, appreciably poorer than France a generation earlier, and many of the regions that rose first were not among the most economically distressed. What had changed was not the harvest but the conversation, as ideas once confined to salons and correspondence between a handful of educated men had, by the 1780s, seeped into pamphlets, newspapers and the coffee houses of provincial towns.\n\nEconomic grievance, on this reading, functions less as a cause of revolution than as a kind of kindling that ideological contagion is required to ignite. Bad harvests and rising bread prices are common throughout history, occurring in decades that produce no revolt whatsoever, which suggests that scarcity alone lacks the explanatory power often credited to it. What is comparatively rare, and what precedes revolution with striking regularity, is the prior circulation of a language that reframes suffering as injustice rather than misfortune, and reframes the sufferer as a citizen with a claim rather than a subject with a grievance. Without that vocabulary, hardship tends to produce resignation, migration or banditry, not organised rebellion aimed at institutions.\n\nThis is not to claim that material conditions are irrelevant, since a population with full granaries is harder to mobilise than one facing want. It is instead to insist that the necessary spark is intellectual before it is economic, and that historians who search only account books for the origins of upheaval will find plenty of misery in centuries that never produced a single revolution. The distribution of ideas, not the distribution of bread, decides which miseries become revolutionary."}, {"id": 413, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What evidence does the writer offer to challenge the view that colonial borders are merely a historical curiosity?", "options": {"A": "Postcolonial governments have redrawn most borders since independence.", "B": "European powers apologised for the borders at later conferences.", "C": "Ethnic communities were consulted before the borders were finalised.", "D": "Many recent civil wars and secessions occur along these inherited lines."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The writer points to the fact that many civil wars and secessionist movements over the last fifty years have occurred along colonial-era border lines, treating this pattern as evidence against the idea that such borders are a merely historical matter. This pattern is presented as showing an ongoing, active connection between colonial mapmaking and present conflict. The other options describe things the passage does not claim happened.", "passage_id": "P104", "passage_title": "Lines on a Map", "passage_text": "Few colonial legacies are as stubbornly persistent as the border, drawn by an administrator with a ruler and a map showing rivers but not peoples, and inherited almost unaltered by the postcolonial states that succeeded the empires which drew it. The borders of much of Africa and the Middle East were fixed at conferences attended by European powers with scant regard for the ethnic, linguistic and religious communities the lines happened to bisect or, in other cases, forcibly combine. It has become fashionable to treat this as a historical curiosity, a regrettable but distant episode with little bearing on present conflict, yet the evidence points the other way: a substantial share of the civil wars and secessionist movements of the last half century have occurred precisely along these inherited seams, where a colonial line split a people that considered itself one, or joined together peoples with no shared institutions of governance.\n\nThe border is only the most visible of these inheritances. Less discussed, but arguably more consequential, is the survival of colonial legal codes governing land tenure, in which customary and communal forms of ownership were reclassified as unowned or vacant land available for grant to settlers and companies. Many postcolonial states, rather than dismantling these codes at independence, retained them largely intact, since the departing colonial administration typically trained the very lawyers and civil servants who would staff the new government, and reform of the land law would have required dismantling the bureaucratic apparatus these officials depended upon for their own authority. The result is that disputes over land in much of the formerly colonised world continue to be adjudicated under statutes drafted by and for a foreign occupying power, statutes never designed with the interests of the occupied population in mind.\n\nNone of this is to suggest that postcolonial governments bear no responsibility for the conflicts and inequities that have followed, since many have entrenched or exploited these inherited structures for their own purposes rather than reforming them. It is instead to insist that the label colonial past undersells the matter, since a border on a map or a clause in a land statute is not the past at all but an active, operating part of the present legal order."}, {"id": 414, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Why, according to the passage, did many postcolonial states retain colonial land tenure codes?", "options": {"A": "Communal land ownership was considered more efficient under the new codes.", "B": "The officials who staffed new governments had been trained under those codes.", "C": "International courts required former colonies to preserve the original statutes.", "D": "Settlers and companies threatened violence if the codes were altered."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage explains that departing colonial administrations trained the lawyers and civil servants who went on to staff postcolonial governments, giving those officials a stake in preserving the legal apparatus that underpinned their own authority. This is offered as the reason land tenure codes were often retained rather than reformed at independence. The other options introduce causes the passage does not mention.", "passage_id": "P104", "passage_title": "Lines on a Map", "passage_text": "Few colonial legacies are as stubbornly persistent as the border, drawn by an administrator with a ruler and a map showing rivers but not peoples, and inherited almost unaltered by the postcolonial states that succeeded the empires which drew it. The borders of much of Africa and the Middle East were fixed at conferences attended by European powers with scant regard for the ethnic, linguistic and religious communities the lines happened to bisect or, in other cases, forcibly combine. It has become fashionable to treat this as a historical curiosity, a regrettable but distant episode with little bearing on present conflict, yet the evidence points the other way: a substantial share of the civil wars and secessionist movements of the last half century have occurred precisely along these inherited seams, where a colonial line split a people that considered itself one, or joined together peoples with no shared institutions of governance.\n\nThe border is only the most visible of these inheritances. Less discussed, but arguably more consequential, is the survival of colonial legal codes governing land tenure, in which customary and communal forms of ownership were reclassified as unowned or vacant land available for grant to settlers and companies. Many postcolonial states, rather than dismantling these codes at independence, retained them largely intact, since the departing colonial administration typically trained the very lawyers and civil servants who would staff the new government, and reform of the land law would have required dismantling the bureaucratic apparatus these officials depended upon for their own authority. The result is that disputes over land in much of the formerly colonised world continue to be adjudicated under statutes drafted by and for a foreign occupying power, statutes never designed with the interests of the occupied population in mind.\n\nNone of this is to suggest that postcolonial governments bear no responsibility for the conflicts and inequities that have followed, since many have entrenched or exploited these inherited structures for their own purposes rather than reforming them. It is instead to insist that the label colonial past undersells the matter, since a border on a map or a clause in a land statute is not the past at all but an active, operating part of the present legal order."}, {"id": 418, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "Why does the writer mention the survival of Greek and Arabic manuscripts?", "options": {"A": "To argue that the scientific revolution could not have relied on ancient texts.", "B": "To show that manuscript preservation was guaranteed by wealthy patrons.", "C": "To prove that censorship never posed a threat to classical knowledge.", "D": "To illustrate how easily a key precondition for change might have been lost."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage uses the fragile survival of Greek and Arabic manuscripts to show how a precondition for the scientific revolution could easily have been lost to fire, censorship or neglect. This example supports the broader argument that major historical shifts depended on contingent events rather than guaranteed outcomes. The other options misstate what the passage claims about these manuscripts.", "passage_id": "P105", "passage_title": "The Manuscript That Might Have Burned", "passage_text": "Whig history, the idea that the past is a more or less steady march toward greater liberty, prosperity and enlightenment, has been so thoroughly discredited among professional historians that one might assume its underlying assumption, the inevitability of progress, had been discredited along with it. Yet a softer version of the same assumption persists even among historians who would never call themselves Whigs, in the habit of describing outcomes as though they were bound to occur once the underlying conditions were in place, as if the Renaissance had to happen once Italian city states grew wealthy, or industrialisation had to happen once Britain possessed coal and capital.\n\nThis habit understates how easily the sequence of events that produced these outcomes might have broken down at any number of points. The printing press, without which the Reformation and the wider spread of literacy are difficult to imagine, depended on a specific set of metallurgical and mercantile conditions in one German city that were not obviously destined to combine when and where they did. The scientific revolution owed a debt to the survival, translation and rediscovery of particular Greek and Arabic manuscripts, any of which might easily have been lost to fire, censorship or simple neglect during the intervening centuries. Even industrialisation, often treated as the inevitable outcome of British coal deposits, required a specific and fragile combination of patent law, available credit and skilled artisans that other coal-rich regions of Europe did not happen to possess at the same moment.\n\nTo insist on contingency is not to claim that nothing can be explained, nor that historical outcomes are wholly random, since identifiable conditions plainly made certain developments more likely than others. It is instead to resist the comforting illusion that the path actually taken was the only path available, an illusion that flatters the present by suggesting it was somehow owed to us by the logic of history itself. The historian who takes contingency seriously must be prepared to imagine, without excessive strain, a world in which the manuscript burned, the metallurgist died young, and the industrial revolution began a century later in a different country, or not at all."}, {"id": 421, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The writer's main argument about founding myths is that they are:", "options": {"A": "accurate memories preserved carelessly by later generations.", "B": "retrospective constructions shaped by present political needs.", "C": "spontaneous folk traditions with no identifiable authors.", "D": "deliberate lies with no genuine social function."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage argues that founding myths are assembled after the fact by identifiable people serving present purposes rather than remembered spontaneously by a whole population. It explicitly rejects the idea of an organic communal memory, attributing the editing to textbook committees and monument builders. It also resists the claim that myths are mere lies, since it acknowledges they perform a genuine cohesive function despite their constructed origin.", "passage_id": "P106", "passage_title": "The Manufacture of Founding Myths", "passage_text": "Every nation tells a story about its own birth, and almost none of these stories survive close historical scrutiny. The Founding Fathers of the American republic did not, in the main, think of themselves as forging a timeless covenant of liberty; many were preoccupied with tariffs, debt and the practical business of holding thirteen quarrelsome colonies together. The heroic narrative of principled revolution was substantially assembled decades later, by historians and politicians who needed a usable past to justify present arrangements. This is not an accident of imperfect memory but something closer to a deliberate act of construction, undertaken by people who had every reason to prefer a flattering account of their origins to an accurate one.\n\nIt is tempting to think of collective memory as a kind of communal recollection, as though a whole population simply remembers its past the way an individual remembers a childhood. But nations do not have minds, and what passes for national memory is in fact an edited compilation, produced by textbook committees, monument builders and ceremony designers, most of whom were not present for the events they commemorate. The inconvenient episodes, the compromises, the violence done to those excluded from the story, are pruned away not because they are forgotten but because they are unhelpful to whoever is doing the telling at that moment.\n\nNone of this means that founding myths are simply lies to be discarded once exposed. Societies plainly draw real cohesion from shared narratives, and a population stripped of any unifying story might find it harder to sustain the mutual trust that large scale cooperation requires. Yet cohesion purchased through curated fiction is a fragile inheritance, since the myth eventually meets citizens whose own experience contradicts it, and who reasonably conclude that the whole apparatus of national self understanding was built to serve someone else's convenience. The proper response to this is neither reverent acceptance nor dismissive debunking, but a persistent institutional habit of asking who benefits from the version of the past currently on offer. A founding story that cannot survive that question was never really a memory in the first place, only a well timed piece of persuasion wearing memory's clothes."}, {"id": 423, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "According to the passage, what evidence suggests founding myths are constructed rather than remembered?", "options": {"A": "the heroic narrative emerged decades after the events it describes.", "B": "contemporary citizens overwhelmingly reject national narratives.", "C": "historians agree unanimously on which events matter.", "D": "tariffs and debts were never mentioned in later accounts."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage states directly that the heroic narrative of revolution was assembled decades after the founding generation, by later historians and politicians rather than participants. This delay between the events and their heroic retelling is offered as the key evidence against organic memory. Nothing in the passage claims universal historian agreement or widespread citizen rejection of national stories.", "passage_id": "P106", "passage_title": "The Manufacture of Founding Myths", "passage_text": "Every nation tells a story about its own birth, and almost none of these stories survive close historical scrutiny. The Founding Fathers of the American republic did not, in the main, think of themselves as forging a timeless covenant of liberty; many were preoccupied with tariffs, debt and the practical business of holding thirteen quarrelsome colonies together. The heroic narrative of principled revolution was substantially assembled decades later, by historians and politicians who needed a usable past to justify present arrangements. This is not an accident of imperfect memory but something closer to a deliberate act of construction, undertaken by people who had every reason to prefer a flattering account of their origins to an accurate one.\n\nIt is tempting to think of collective memory as a kind of communal recollection, as though a whole population simply remembers its past the way an individual remembers a childhood. But nations do not have minds, and what passes for national memory is in fact an edited compilation, produced by textbook committees, monument builders and ceremony designers, most of whom were not present for the events they commemorate. The inconvenient episodes, the compromises, the violence done to those excluded from the story, are pruned away not because they are forgotten but because they are unhelpful to whoever is doing the telling at that moment.\n\nNone of this means that founding myths are simply lies to be discarded once exposed. Societies plainly draw real cohesion from shared narratives, and a population stripped of any unifying story might find it harder to sustain the mutual trust that large scale cooperation requires. Yet cohesion purchased through curated fiction is a fragile inheritance, since the myth eventually meets citizens whose own experience contradicts it, and who reasonably conclude that the whole apparatus of national self understanding was built to serve someone else's convenience. The proper response to this is neither reverent acceptance nor dismissive debunking, but a persistent institutional habit of asking who benefits from the version of the past currently on offer. A founding story that cannot survive that question was never really a memory in the first place, only a well timed piece of persuasion wearing memory's clothes."}, {"id": 429, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The writer's main contention is that successful social movements depend primarily on:", "options": {"A": "pre-existing organisational infrastructure rather than spontaneous crowd size.", "B": "the emotional intensity of a single triggering event.", "C": "unplanned eruptions of mass participation alone.", "D": "the charisma of individual protest leaders."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage argues that lasting change is more reliably produced by organisation built before a crowd ever gathers than by the sheer scale of spontaneous participation. It uses the Montgomery bus boycott to show that apparent spontaneity concealed months of prior planning. Charisma of individual leaders is not identified as the decisive factor in the passage's argument.", "passage_id": "P108", "passage_title": "Why Movements Win", "passage_text": "Popular imagination tends to credit successful social movements to a single electrifying moment: a crowd converging spontaneously on a square, a spark of outrage that no one planned catching fire across a population. This picture is emotionally satisfying and almost always historically incomplete. Behind nearly every movement that achieved lasting change sits an unglamorous scaffolding of organisation built long before the crowds appeared: trained volunteers, rehearsed tactics, funding networks, communication channels and leadership structures capable of directing energy once it had been released. The American civil rights campaigns of the 1950s and 1960s are frequently remembered as a series of spontaneous acts of individual courage, yet the Montgomery bus boycott succeeded because a carpool system, a legal strategy and disciplined nonviolent training had been prepared in advance, not improvised in the moment.\n\nBy contrast, movements that rely primarily on the scale of spontaneous participation, however impressive their numbers, tend to dissipate once the initial surge of attention fades. Mass protests that erupt without a durable organisational backbone frequently struggle to translate visibility into concrete institutional change, because no structure exists to negotiate, to sustain pressure over months or years, or to survive the inevitable moment when public attention moves elsewhere. Size generates headlines; organisation converts headlines into legislation.\n\nThis is not to deny that spontaneous mass action plays a genuine role. Sudden eruptions of participation can dramatically expand the pool of sympathetic bystanders, recruit new members, and force issues onto a public agenda that organisers alone might never have managed. The error lies in treating that expansion as sufficient by itself, rather than as raw material that organisation must then shape into durable pressure. Movements without any spontaneous element risk irrelevance, since they never grow large enough to matter, but movements without organisational infrastructure risk exactly the opposite failure, burning brightly and then leaving no lasting trace. The historical record, examined soberly rather than through the flattering lens of retrospective legend, favours patient infrastructure over sudden combustion as the more reliable predictor of which movements actually change the institutions they target."}, {"id": 430, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the Montgomery bus boycott example illustrate in the passage?", "options": {"A": "that spontaneous courage alone secured lasting institutional change.", "B": "that prior planning and logistics underpinned an apparently spontaneous protest.", "C": "that legal strategy was irrelevant to the boycott's outcome.", "D": "that nonviolent training was invented during the boycott itself."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage states that the boycott succeeded because a carpool system, legal strategy and nonviolent training were prepared in advance rather than improvised during the protest. This directly contradicts the popular image of the boycott as a purely spontaneous act of courage. The example is used specifically to demonstrate that visible spontaneity often rests on invisible preparation.", "passage_id": "P108", "passage_title": "Why Movements Win", "passage_text": "Popular imagination tends to credit successful social movements to a single electrifying moment: a crowd converging spontaneously on a square, a spark of outrage that no one planned catching fire across a population. This picture is emotionally satisfying and almost always historically incomplete. Behind nearly every movement that achieved lasting change sits an unglamorous scaffolding of organisation built long before the crowds appeared: trained volunteers, rehearsed tactics, funding networks, communication channels and leadership structures capable of directing energy once it had been released. The American civil rights campaigns of the 1950s and 1960s are frequently remembered as a series of spontaneous acts of individual courage, yet the Montgomery bus boycott succeeded because a carpool system, a legal strategy and disciplined nonviolent training had been prepared in advance, not improvised in the moment.\n\nBy contrast, movements that rely primarily on the scale of spontaneous participation, however impressive their numbers, tend to dissipate once the initial surge of attention fades. Mass protests that erupt without a durable organisational backbone frequently struggle to translate visibility into concrete institutional change, because no structure exists to negotiate, to sustain pressure over months or years, or to survive the inevitable moment when public attention moves elsewhere. Size generates headlines; organisation converts headlines into legislation.\n\nThis is not to deny that spontaneous mass action plays a genuine role. Sudden eruptions of participation can dramatically expand the pool of sympathetic bystanders, recruit new members, and force issues onto a public agenda that organisers alone might never have managed. The error lies in treating that expansion as sufficient by itself, rather than as raw material that organisation must then shape into durable pressure. Movements without any spontaneous element risk irrelevance, since they never grow large enough to matter, but movements without organisational infrastructure risk exactly the opposite failure, burning brightly and then leaving no lasting trace. The historical record, examined soberly rather than through the flattering lens of retrospective legend, favours patient infrastructure over sudden combustion as the more reliable predictor of which movements actually change the institutions they target."}, {"id": 433, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The writer's central argument about the presentism objection to statue removal is that it:", "options": {"A": "correctly identifies removal as an unjustified act of judgement.", "B": "wrongly treats the statue's original erection as free of judgement.", "C": "applies equally and fairly to both installation and removal.", "D": "has no rhetorical force and is rarely used in debate."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage argues that the presentism objection assumes the original erection of a statue was a neutral historical act, when in fact it was itself a selective judgement shaped by present day interests. This exposes an unjustified asymmetry between how erection and removal are treated. The passage explicitly acknowledges the objection's rhetorical force rather than dismissing it as rarely used.", "passage_id": "P109", "passage_title": "Statues, Judgement and the Presentism Trap", "passage_text": "Whenever a public statue becomes the subject of controversy, a familiar objection appears within days: removing it, we are told, amounts to judging the past by the standards of the present, an exercise in presentism that flatters the judges while doing nothing but erase inconvenient history. This objection has rhetorical force, but it rests on an assumption that does not survive examination, namely that the statue's original erection was itself an innocent, standards free act rather than a judgement of its own.\n\nConsider that most contested monuments were not raised in the immediate aftermath of the events they commemorate, but decades or even a century later, often during periods of deliberate political consolidation. Confederate memorials in the American South were disproportionately erected not in the 1860s but in the early twentieth century, precisely when Jim Crow segregation was being entrenched, and again during the mid-century civil rights era, when they served as pointed assertions of resistance to racial equality. These were not neutral acts of historical preservation; they were themselves highly selective judgements, made by particular people with particular present day interests, about which version of the past deserved permanent public honour.\n\nTo call the removal of such statues presentism while treating their installation as simple historical fact is therefore an asymmetry that cannot be justified. Both acts, erecting and removing, are judgements made by people living in a present moment, weighing the past against values they currently hold. The question worth asking is not whether we are permitted to judge, since judgement was always occurring, but whether the particular judgement being made now is better reasoned and more honestly argued than the one it replaces.\n\nNone of this settles every individual case, since reasonable people can disagree about which specific monuments merit removal, relocation to a museum, or contextual reinterpretation through an added plaque. But the presentism charge, deployed as a blanket objection to any reassessment of public monuments, functions less as a serious argument than as a device for freezing whichever judgement happened to be made first, however partisan its original motives, and exempting it alone from further scrutiny."}, {"id": 451, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What can be inferred about how Whig history treats historical figures?", "options": {"A": "it judges them by how closely they anticipated present day values.", "B": "it treats them as entirely unaware of their own historical context.", "C": "it praises them mainly for opposing the political parties of their time.", "D": "it regards them as more rational than people living today."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage states directly that under this teleological framing, actors in the past are judged by how closely they anticipated present values. This is distinct from claiming they were unaware of their context, which the passage does not assert. The passage says nothing about political party opposition or about historical figures being judged more rational than contemporary people.", "passage_id": "P113", "passage_title": "Against the Ascending Line", "passage_text": "The Whig interpretation of history, so named for its origins in nineteenth century political writing, casts the past as a more or less steady ascent toward greater liberty, tolerance and rational governance, with the present standing as the natural culmination of forces that were, in retrospect, always working toward it. This narrative remains seductive because it flatters the observer: to view history as progress is implicitly to view one's own era as its vindication. But the historical record, examined without this comforting filter, offers far less support for linear improvement than the Whig account requires.\n\nConsider the frequency with which supposed gains have been reversed rather than consolidated. Legal protections for civil liberties have expanded and contracted repeatedly within single countries across a few generations, often driven by economic anxiety or war rather than any deepening moral consensus. Periods celebrated as enlightened have coexisted with atrocities their own participants judged unremarkable. To read only the advances and treat the reversals as aberrations is to select evidence to fit a conclusion decided in advance, rather than to follow where the evidence actually leads.\n\nThe deeper flaw in Whig history is not merely selective emphasis but its underlying assumption of direction. It presumes that history has a destination, that earlier periods exist chiefly as staging posts toward later ones, and that actors in the past can therefore be judged by how closely they anticipated present values. This teleological framing strips historical figures of the genuine uncertainty in which they acted and converts contingent, often accidental outcomes into an inevitable unfolding. Events that could easily have gone otherwise are retrospectively dressed as necessary steps.\n\nNone of this is an argument for despair, nor a claim that no improvement has occurred in any domain. It is instead a caution against the specific intellectual habit of assuming that improvement, where it has occurred, was guaranteed, continuous, or destined to continue. A historian's task is to explain how particular outcomes came about amid genuine alternatives, not to narrate a march whose ending was known from the start. Abandoning the Whig frame does not diminish history; it restores to it the uncertainty that makes it worth studying seriously."}, {"id": 455, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage suggest about the timing of major commemorations?", "options": {"A": "it is chosen at random with no relation to current events.", "B": "it often coincides with periods of domestic political tension.", "C": "it is determined solely by the original historical date.", "D": "it is always delayed until controversy has fully subsided."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage notes that the timing of major commemorations frequently aligns suspiciously well with periods of domestic tension, implying deliberate political use. This directly contradicts the idea that timing is random or determined only by the original date. There is no claim in the passage that commemorations are delayed until controversy subsides.", "passage_id": "P114", "passage_title": "The Ceremony of Memory", "passage_text": "Every nation observes anniversaries: the founding of a state, a decisive battle, the passing of a constitution. These rituals are typically presented as acts of remembrance, solemn returns to events whose significance is self-evident and whose meaning has remained constant since the day they occurred. In practice, however, commemorations are less acts of memory than acts of composition, assembled anew by each generation to serve purposes that have comparatively little to do with fidelity to the past.\n\nThe selectivity involved is rarely acknowledged in the ceremonies themselves. A centenary of national independence, for instance, will foreground unifying episodes of collective sacrifice while quietly omitting the internal divisions, coerced participation, or contested aftermath that accompanied the actual event. Commemoration therefore performs a kind of editing, in which awkward complexity is smoothed into a narrative that can be sung, marched to, or printed on a coin without controversy. The version of the past that is publicly ritualised is chosen for its usefulness to the present, not for its completeness.\n\nThis usefulness is often explicitly political. Governments facing internal fracture have long turned to anniversaries as instruments of cohesion, since a shared ceremony can manufacture the appearance of common identity even where none reliably exists. The timing of major commemorations frequently aligns suspiciously well with periods of domestic tension, suggesting that the ritual is deployed as much to manage the present as to honour the past. Historians who point out the constructed nature of a given commemoration are often accused of undermining national unity, which is itself revealing: it implies that the unity in question depends on the myth remaining unexamined.\n\nNone of this means commemoration is inherently dishonest or that shared rituals serve no legitimate purpose; societies plausibly need some common reference points to function. The concern is rather that commemorations are widely mistaken for neutral acts of remembering when they are in fact acts of selection, shaped by present political needs and defended precisely because their constructed character is left unstated. Recognising this does not require abandoning national rituals, only approaching them with the same scrutiny applied to any other instrument of persuasion."}, {"id": 458, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage suggest about pension systems and war reparations?", "options": {"A": "they were abandoned once administrative complexity became apparent.", "B": "they are fundamentally different from reparations for historical injustice.", "C": "they prove that moral claims are always weaker than practical ones.", "D": "they show that complex entitlement problems need not block a remedy."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage cites these schemes as examples where comparable problems of tracing entitlement across time were confronted without the remedy being abandoned. This directly contradicts the claim that such schemes were abandoned due to complexity. The passage draws these examples as parallels rather than as fundamentally different cases, and it does not use them to rank moral claims against practical ones.", "passage_id": "P115", "passage_title": "The Accounting Objection", "passage_text": "Public debate over reparations for historical injustice, whether concerning transatlantic slavery, colonial expropriation or forced displacement, is conducted overwhelmingly in the language of practicality. Opponents ask who exactly would receive payment given the passage of generations, how liability could be fairly apportioned among institutions that no longer resemble their historical predecessors, and where the necessary funds would be found without imposing new burdens on citizens who bear no personal responsibility for the original wrong. These are treated as decisive objections, sufficient on their own to close the matter before any moral argument is heard.\n\nYet this framing quietly substitutes a technical problem for an ethical one, and in doing so avoids the question reparations advocates actually raise. Practical difficulties of identification and distribution are real, but they are the kind of difficulty that accompanies almost any large scale remedy for injustice, including ones societies have implemented without treating administrative complexity as disqualifying. Pension systems, war reparations between states, and compensation schemes for historical abuses within institutions have all confronted comparable problems of tracing entitlement across time, and none was abandoned solely because the accounting was difficult.\n\nThe more revealing feature of practicality based objections is how consistently they arrive already fully formed, regardless of which specific reparations proposal is under discussion, suggesting that the practical language functions less as genuine analysis and more as a socially acceptable substitute for refusing the underlying moral claim. It is considerably easier to say that a scheme is unworkable than to say plainly that one does not believe present generations owe anything for past wrongs from which they may still, indirectly, benefit.\n\nA moral case for reparations, by contrast, does not depend on resolving every administrative detail in advance, since moral obligations are not ordinarily suspended merely because fulfilling them is complicated. If the underlying wrong and its continuing effects are accepted as real, the practical questions become matters to be solved in the design of a scheme rather than grounds for dismissing its premise. Treating reparations debates as fundamentally technical rather than moral therefore protects the objection from ever having to confront the claim it is actually resisting."}, {"id": 459, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What can be inferred about why practical objections 'arrive already fully formed'?", "options": {"A": "they are applied consistently regardless of the specific proposal's details.", "B": "they are carefully researched anew for each individual proposal.", "C": "they are proposed only by economists with no political motive.", "D": "they change substantially depending on which country is discussed."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage notes that these objections appear consistently regardless of which specific reparations proposal is under discussion, which the writer takes as a sign they are not genuine case by case analysis. This directly contradicts the idea that each objection is freshly researched for the particular proposal. The passage also does not attribute these objections specifically to economists or claim they vary by country.", "passage_id": "P115", "passage_title": "The Accounting Objection", "passage_text": "Public debate over reparations for historical injustice, whether concerning transatlantic slavery, colonial expropriation or forced displacement, is conducted overwhelmingly in the language of practicality. Opponents ask who exactly would receive payment given the passage of generations, how liability could be fairly apportioned among institutions that no longer resemble their historical predecessors, and where the necessary funds would be found without imposing new burdens on citizens who bear no personal responsibility for the original wrong. These are treated as decisive objections, sufficient on their own to close the matter before any moral argument is heard.\n\nYet this framing quietly substitutes a technical problem for an ethical one, and in doing so avoids the question reparations advocates actually raise. Practical difficulties of identification and distribution are real, but they are the kind of difficulty that accompanies almost any large scale remedy for injustice, including ones societies have implemented without treating administrative complexity as disqualifying. Pension systems, war reparations between states, and compensation schemes for historical abuses within institutions have all confronted comparable problems of tracing entitlement across time, and none was abandoned solely because the accounting was difficult.\n\nThe more revealing feature of practicality based objections is how consistently they arrive already fully formed, regardless of which specific reparations proposal is under discussion, suggesting that the practical language functions less as genuine analysis and more as a socially acceptable substitute for refusing the underlying moral claim. It is considerably easier to say that a scheme is unworkable than to say plainly that one does not believe present generations owe anything for past wrongs from which they may still, indirectly, benefit.\n\nA moral case for reparations, by contrast, does not depend on resolving every administrative detail in advance, since moral obligations are not ordinarily suspended merely because fulfilling them is complicated. If the underlying wrong and its continuing effects are accepted as real, the practical questions become matters to be solved in the design of a scheme rather than grounds for dismissing its premise. Treating reparations debates as fundamentally technical rather than moral therefore protects the objection from ever having to confront the claim it is actually resisting."}, {"id": 462, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "According to the passage, movements that mobilise quickly through digital networks often:", "options": {"A": "gain more funding than movements organised in the traditional way.", "B": "fail to build committees and leadership structures needed to sustain pressure.", "C": "attract more support from those already in power.", "D": "spread more slowly than movements organised through pamphlets."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage explains that movements that mobilise quickly online often disperse quickly because they never built the committees or leadership structures that older movements had to construct slowly. This is presented as the price paid for rapid formation. The other options are not supported by the passage and in some cases contradict its stated comparison with earlier movements.", "passage_id": "P116", "passage_title": "Technology and the Limits of Mobilisation", "passage_text": "Every generation convinces itself that the newest device has rewritten the rules of political change. Pamphlets, it is said, made the American Revolution possible; the telegraph shaped nationalist uprisings across nineteenth century Europe; television carried the civil rights movement into living rooms; and now the smartphone has supposedly reduced the cost of assembling a crowd to almost nothing. This narrative is seductive because it is partly true, but it obscures the more difficult fact that no communications tool has ever, by itself, converted grievance into lasting reform.\n\nConsider what happens once the initial crowd disperses. A hashtag can summon tens of thousands of people to a square within days, a feat unimaginable to the organisers of a nineteenth century strike, who had to canvass door to door for months. Yet many of the mobilisations that spread fastest through digital networks have proven the most fragile, dissolving once the immediate provocation fades because they never built the committees, funding structures or negotiating leadership that older movements were forced to construct slowly. Rapid formation, in other words, is frequently purchased at the price of durable structure.\n\nThe movements historians remember as transformative, from abolitionism to the Indian independence campaign, combined access to whatever communications technology existed with something technology cannot supply: a disciplined organisation capable of sustaining pressure over years, absorbing setbacks, and negotiating with those in power once the crowds had gone home. The telegraph and the pamphlet were instruments in the hands of such organisations, not substitutes for them.\n\nNone of this means technology is irrelevant. It certainly changes who can be reached, how quickly, and at what cost, and it can expose abuses that would once have remained hidden. But the temptation to treat each new medium as the decisive variable flatters the present at the expense of the past, implying that earlier activists succeeded despite primitive tools rather than because of patient, unglamorous organisation. The uncomfortable lesson is that visibility and velocity are not the same as power, and a movement that mistakes the former for the latter risks mistaking a viral moment for a victory."}, {"id": 467, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'a uniform darkness waiting for modern light' is used to criticise:", "options": {"A": "historians who argue that no moral progress has occurred.", "B": "courts that judge doctors by contemporary professional standards.", "C": "abolitionists who published arguments before the slave trade ended.", "D": "the assumption that the past was uniformly ignorant until the present arrived."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The phrase criticises the assumption that the past was uniformly ignorant before the present arrived to correct it. It appears at the close of a passage arguing that genuine moral argument occurred within past societies. The other options misattribute the target of this criticism.", "passage_id": "P117", "passage_title": "Judging the Past by Its Own Evidence", "passage_text": "It has become fashionable to insist that historical figures must be judged only by the standards of their own age, and equally fashionable, in reaction, to insist that certain conduct is simply wrong regardless of when it occurred. Both positions, pursued to their logical conclusion, are evasions. A more honest method borrows from law rather than from moral philosophy, asking not what we now believe but what a reasonable, informed person living at the time could have known and chosen to do differently.\n\nCourts routinely judge past conduct against contemporaneous standards without collapsing into either relativism or presentism. A nineteenth century doctor is not held liable for failing to use a treatment that had not yet been discovered, but is held liable for ignoring hygiene practices that his own professional peers already recognised and published. The same test can be applied to political and commercial figures accused of complicity in slavery, exploitation or conquest: did credible contemporaries, using the information available at the time, argue against the practice, and did the figure in question have a realistic opportunity to act on that argument?\n\nThis test does not excuse historical wrongdoing merely because it was widespread. Abolitionist argument existed throughout the era of the Atlantic slave trade, published, debated and in some cases enacted into law well before its final abolition, which means that defenders of the trade cannot claim total ignorance of an alternative. Equally, the test refuses to convict a medieval monarch of failing to anticipate a concept of human rights that had no coherent articulation until centuries later, since no contemporary vocabulary existed from which he could have drawn instruction.\n\nThe advantage of this legal analogy is that it forces the critic to do real historical work rather than simply importing today's statute book into the past. It requires identifying what was actually known, argued and possible at the time, rather than assuming that villainy and virtue were distributed exactly as our own century happens to distribute them. That discipline is harder than either blanket condemnation or blanket forgiveness, but it is the only approach that treats the past as a place where genuine moral argument occurred, rather than as a uniform darkness waiting for modern light."}, {"id": 477, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The writer's preferred model of historical change is best described as:", "options": {"A": "a spiral that returns to recurring problems while still tracing genuine long term gains.", "B": "a straight line moving consistently from tyranny toward liberty.", "C": "a wheel in which no lasting change of any kind ever occurs.", "D": "a series of unrelated events with no discernible pattern at all."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The writer's preferred model treats history as a spiral that repeatedly returns to problems of power and complacency while still tracing genuine gains in specific respects. This is presented as more defensible than either a pure line or a pure circle. The other options describe models the passage explicitly argues against.", "passage_id": "P120", "passage_title": "Line, Circle or Spiral", "passage_text": "The assumption that history moves in a single upward line, from darkness toward enlightenment, from tyranny toward liberty, is comforting and almost entirely a modern invention. Most societies that have left a written record of their own understanding of time, from classical Rome to imperial China, imagined history as a wheel: empires rise, grow corrupt, and fall, only for the pattern to begin again under a different banner. It was only in the last three centuries, buoyed by genuine advances in science and material comfort, that a confident minority of societies began to insist that decline was optional and progress was the default direction of human affairs.\n\nThe trouble with the linear view is not that it is wholly wrong, since certain measures, life expectancy, literacy, the spread of technical knowledge, genuinely have moved in one direction over the long run. The trouble is that it quietly smuggles in the assumption that political and moral gains are equally permanent, when the historical record suggests the opposite: republics have collapsed into empires, empires into anarchy, and eras of tolerance into eras of persecution, often within a single lifetime and often in societies that believed themselves to be at the vanguard of progress.\n\nThe cyclical view corrects this complacency but risks an opposite error, that of denying any real change occurs at all. A society that has acquired antibiotics, printing and constitutional government is not simply repeating the fourteenth century with different costumes. What recurs is not the exact configuration of events but certain recognisable pressures, the tendency of concentrated power to corrupt its holders, the tendency of prosperity to breed the complacency that later undoes it, operating on a substrate that is not static but slowly accumulating genuine, if fragile, gains.\n\nThe most defensible position, then, treats history as a spiral rather than either a line or a circle: a shape that returns repeatedly to familiar problems of power, corruption and complacency, while nonetheless tracing a slow upward path in specific measurable respects. Anyone who forgets the spiral's circular component risks the naive confidence that undid earlier ages of apparent progress, and anyone who forgets its upward component risks a fatalism that excuses inaction on the grounds that nothing ever truly changes."}, {"id": 481, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The writer's central claim about ceremonial commemoration is that it:", "options": {"A": "prevents any public acknowledgement of past wrongdoing.", "B": "can substitute for, rather than complete, honest reckoning.", "C": "is invariably a cynical exercise staged by political leaders.", "D": "proves that a society has already answered its difficult questions."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage argues that ceremonies often domesticate trauma and are mistaken for resolution rather than actually providing it. It explicitly denies that commemoration is worthless or purely cynical, ruling out the harshest reading. It also treats the idea that ceremony proves a matter settled as a popular misconception the writer is criticising, not endorsing.", "passage_id": "P121", "passage_title": "The Uses of Forgetting", "passage_text": "Every nation tells itself a story about its own past, and every such story depends as much on what is left out as on what is included. It is tempting to assume that the darkest episodes in a country's history are simply suppressed, buried under layers of official silence until a braver generation excavates them. But this account, comforting as it is, mistakes the mechanism by which collective forgetting actually operates. Far more common, and far more insidious, is a process not of silence but of substitution: the traumatic event is not denied so much as absorbed into a narrative that domesticates it, wrapping the wound in ceremony until the ceremony itself becomes the memory.\n\nConsider how nations mark anniversaries of massacres, famines or expulsions. A monument is erected, a minute of silence observed, a wreath laid by a head of state. These acts are not nothing; they represent an advance on outright denial. Yet they can also function as a kind of closure that forecloses further inquiry. Once a society has performed its grief publicly, it often feels entitled to regard the matter as settled, the debt paid, the ledger closed. The very existence of a commemorative plaque becomes evidence, in the popular mind, that the difficult questions have already been answered, when in fact they have merely been ritualised.\n\nThis is why selective remembering can be more corrosive than silence. Outright denial invites challenge; it is a claim that can be falsified, a gap that agitators can point to and demand be filled. Ceremonial memory, by contrast, disarms its critics in advance, since anyone who insists that more remains to be reckoned with can be accused of ingratitude toward a nation that has already, visibly, mourned. The critic is made to seem the one who cannot let go, rather than the nation that has arranged never quite to look directly at what happened.\n\nNone of this means that commemoration is worthless or cynical. Many of those who build the monuments genuinely wish to honour the dead. But intention is not the same as effect, and a society should ask not only whether it remembers but what kind of remembering it has settled for. A past that has been ceremonially closed is not necessarily a past that has been honestly examined, and the distinction matters more than most public rituals allow us to admit."}, {"id": 499, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'dressed now in the more comfortable language of fusion' suggests that:", "options": {"A": "modern clothing styles reflect colonial hierarchies.", "B": "fusion cuisine is the clearest example of cultural hierarchy.", "C": "the language of fusion is scientifically inaccurate.", "D": "old hierarchies are given a more palatable, disguising vocabulary."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The image of dressing suggests that the same underlying hierarchy persists but is presented in softer, more acceptable terms through the language of fusion. This reinforces the passage's broader claim that celebratory language can obscure continuing inequality. It is a figurative use of dress, not a literal comment on clothing or a claim about cuisine specifically.", "passage_id": "P125", "passage_title": "The Uneven Blend", "passage_text": "It has become fashionable, in recent decades, to celebrate the cultural mixtures produced by colonialism as evidence of resilience and creative fusion: new cuisines, new musical forms, new literatures written in the coloniser's language but bent to unfamiliar purposes. There is truth in this celebration, and it is a welcome corrective to an older narrative that treated colonised societies as merely damaged, their cultures diluted or destroyed. But the celebratory account, taken on its own, risks smoothing over a harder fact, which is that hybridity produced under conditions of conquest is rarely a meeting of equals, and the resulting blend usually preserves, rather than erases, the hierarchy that produced it.\n\nConsider language. A novelist writing in the former imperial tongue may indeed bend that language to new rhythms, insert untranslated words, disrupt its grammar until it carries meanings its original speakers never intended. This is real creative achievement. Yet the fact remains that such a writer typically reaches an international audience, and often domestic prestige, precisely because the work is legible to readers of the former colonial language, while writing in an indigenous language, however innovative, struggles for translation, publication and recognition. The hybrid text is celebrated in part because one of its ingredients still carries more institutional power than the other; the mixture is not symmetrical, however much the metaphor of blending implies a fair combination.\n\nThe same asymmetry appears in cuisine, dress, religion and law, where elements drawn from the coloniser's culture frequently retain an association with modernity, education and status, while elements drawn from the colonised culture are folded in as flavour, texture or decoration rather than as structuring principle. To call this simply enrichment is to mistake the persistence of hierarchy for its dissolution.\n\nNone of this means hybrid cultures are inauthentic or that their creators are dupes; people make vital, original work from whatever materials history hands them, and there is no pure alternative to return to. But an honest account of cultural mixture in former colonies must hold both truths together: that genuine creativity has occurred, and that the terms on which the mixing happens are still frequently set by the old imperial hierarchy, dressed now in the more comfortable language of fusion."}, {"id": 503, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What is the function of the final paragraph in relation to the rest of the passage?", "options": {"A": "It reverses the argument developed earlier by conceding that markets are generally superior to regulation.", "B": "It introduces an entirely new topic unrelated to the preceding discussion of harm.", "C": "It proves that regulation is always well designed and free from unintended costs.", "D": "It qualifies the argument by acknowledging regulation's flaws while maintaining its central claim."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The final paragraph admits that regulation can be poorly targeted and costly, which tempers rather than abandons the argument built in the earlier paragraphs. It then restates the core claim that markets alone often fail to prevent harm in time, showing the concession does not undo the main conclusion. The passage neither reverses its position nor claims regulation is flawless, so the more absolute readings misrepresent the paragraph's balanced tone.", "passage_id": "P126", "passage_title": "Markets, Harm, and the Limits of Regulation", "passage_text": "Defenders of free markets often argue that voluntary exchange, left to its own devices, tends to eliminate harmful practices more reliably than statutory intervention. A firm that poisons its customers, the argument runs, will lose those customers once the harm becomes known, and will therefore have every incentive to correct its behaviour before regulators ever intervene. Reputation, on this view, functions as a disciplining mechanism at least as powerful as any inspector armed with a rulebook, and it operates continuously rather than at the periodic intervals of a compliance audit.\n\nThis account, however, rests on an assumption that harm will be discovered promptly and attributed accurately to its source, and that the injured party will be capable of withdrawing custom before suffering irreversible damage. Many of the harms that regulation exists to prevent, such as those arising from contaminated water supplies, defective pharmaceuticals, or unsafe structural materials, manifest only after long latency periods, during which thousands of transactions may have already occurred. By the time reputational consequences arrive, the damage done is frequently permanent, and no subsequent boycott can restore health already lost or lives already ended.\n\nA further difficulty concerns the asymmetry of information between producer and consumer. The very reason a firm might cut corners on safety is that the resulting deficiencies are difficult for an outsider to detect; a buyer cannot inspect the metallurgy of a component or the microbiology of a foodstuff before purchase. Regulation substitutes for this missing capacity by requiring disclosure and testing that no individual consumer could feasibly perform, and by imposing penalties before, rather than only after, harm has spread widely.\n\nNone of this establishes that regulation is always well designed or costlessly administered; poorly targeted rules can stifle innovation and burden small enterprises disproportionately, and a regulator captured by the very industry it oversees may enforce standards no more rigorously than an indifferent market would. But the claim that markets alone suffice to prevent harm understates how often the mechanisms of detection and redress arrive too late, and how often the information required for consumers to punish wrongdoing is precisely what wrongdoing conceals. A more realistic assessment therefore treats reputation and regulation as complementary safeguards, each compensating for weaknesses the other cannot address alone."}, {"id": 504, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "In context, the phrase 'disciplining mechanism' is used to convey which idea?", "options": {"A": "A formal legal process by which courts punish firms for proven wrongdoing.", "B": "A voluntary code of conduct that firms agree to follow among themselves.", "C": "An informal market force that pressures firms to behave well through reputational risk.", "D": "A government inspection regime that operates at scheduled intervals."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The phrase describes reputation acting as a continuous market pressure on firms, contrasted directly with the periodic work of inspectors in the same sentence. It is used to characterise an informal, ongoing incentive rather than any formal legal or governmental process. The other options describe mechanisms the passage explicitly separates from reputation, such as compliance audits or inspection regimes, so they misread the term.", "passage_id": "P126", "passage_title": "Markets, Harm, and the Limits of Regulation", "passage_text": "Defenders of free markets often argue that voluntary exchange, left to its own devices, tends to eliminate harmful practices more reliably than statutory intervention. A firm that poisons its customers, the argument runs, will lose those customers once the harm becomes known, and will therefore have every incentive to correct its behaviour before regulators ever intervene. Reputation, on this view, functions as a disciplining mechanism at least as powerful as any inspector armed with a rulebook, and it operates continuously rather than at the periodic intervals of a compliance audit.\n\nThis account, however, rests on an assumption that harm will be discovered promptly and attributed accurately to its source, and that the injured party will be capable of withdrawing custom before suffering irreversible damage. Many of the harms that regulation exists to prevent, such as those arising from contaminated water supplies, defective pharmaceuticals, or unsafe structural materials, manifest only after long latency periods, during which thousands of transactions may have already occurred. By the time reputational consequences arrive, the damage done is frequently permanent, and no subsequent boycott can restore health already lost or lives already ended.\n\nA further difficulty concerns the asymmetry of information between producer and consumer. The very reason a firm might cut corners on safety is that the resulting deficiencies are difficult for an outsider to detect; a buyer cannot inspect the metallurgy of a component or the microbiology of a foodstuff before purchase. Regulation substitutes for this missing capacity by requiring disclosure and testing that no individual consumer could feasibly perform, and by imposing penalties before, rather than only after, harm has spread widely.\n\nNone of this establishes that regulation is always well designed or costlessly administered; poorly targeted rules can stifle innovation and burden small enterprises disproportionately, and a regulator captured by the very industry it oversees may enforce standards no more rigorously than an indifferent market would. But the claim that markets alone suffice to prevent harm understates how often the mechanisms of detection and redress arrive too late, and how often the information required for consumers to punish wrongdoing is precisely what wrongdoing conceals. A more realistic assessment therefore treats reputation and regulation as complementary safeguards, each compensating for weaknesses the other cannot address alone."}, {"id": 509, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the central objection the critics raise against meritocracy in the passage?", "options": {"A": "Meritocracy has never actually been attempted in any real society.", "B": "Talented individuals are always identified correctly under meritocratic systems.", "C": "Meritocracy produces worse outcomes in fields such as medicine and engineering.", "D": "Meritocracy legitimises inequality by ignoring how unequal conditions shape who appears meritorious."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage explains that a child's ability to develop and demonstrate talent depends heavily on wealth related conditions such as housing, nutrition, and schooling. Critics argue this means meritocratic selection often rewards prior advantage rather than pure ability, while still appearing fair on its surface. The passage does not claim meritocracy has never been tried, that identification of talent is always accurate, or that it worsens technical outcomes in specific fields.", "passage_id": "P128", "passage_title": "The Trouble with Rewarding Merit", "passage_text": "The meritocratic ideal holds that social and economic rewards should track ability and effort rather than birth, connection, or inherited status. Its appeal lies partly in its apparent fairness: a system that promotes the talented and hardworking over the well-born seems self-evidently more just than one that entrenches privilege regardless of capability. Advocates further argue that meritocracy benefits society as a whole, since allocating skilled individuals to demanding roles according to competence rather than pedigree should improve outcomes across medicine, engineering, and governance alike.\n\nCritics respond that meritocracy, for all its promise, tends to legitimise inequalities it did not create and cannot fully correct. Talent itself is unevenly distributed by genetic and environmental accident, and the conditions that allow talent to flourish, such as stable housing, nutritious food, and encouraging schooling, are themselves distributed according to existing wealth. A child born into poverty may possess exceptional ability yet never develop it to a level that a meritocratic system can recognise or reward, while a less able child born into comfort receives every advantage needed to appear meritorious by the time selection occurs.\n\nThere is a further, subtler charge: that meritocracy licenses successful people to believe their success is wholly self-made, and by the same logic invites them to regard the unsuccessful as simply deficient in ability or effort. This attitude, critics argue, corrodes the sense of common fate that once underpinned support for social insurance and public services, since those who consider their position earned outright feel less obligation toward those who have fared worse. A society that believes rewards are perfectly matched to desert may therefore become less generous rather than more, even as it becomes no fairer in practice than the aristocratic systems it replaced.\n\nMeritocracy's defenders need not abandon the ideal to accept this critique, but they must concede that formal equality of opportunity, absent genuine equality in the conditions that allow ability to develop, produces a hierarchy that merely relabels privilege as merit rather than eliminating it. What would need to change, on this reading, is not the principle of rewarding ability but the prior distribution of the resources that allow ability to be nurtured in the first place."}, {"id": 514, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Why have courts questioned the classification of gig workers as independent contractors?", "options": {"A": "Because platforms have openly and repeatedly conceded that their workers are actual employees.", "B": "Because independent contractor status is banned outright across nearly all legal jurisdictions.", "C": "Because gig workers themselves consistently prefer employee status over any scheduling flexibility offered.", "D": "Because the practical control platforms exercise resembles that of an employer rather than an intermediary."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage describes courts examining factors such as price setting, penalties for declining jobs, and account deactivation without appeal, finding that these amount to a degree of control typical of an employer. This practical control, rather than any admission by platforms or a general illegality of contractor status, is what has driven reclassification rulings. The passage also does not claim gig workers uniformly prefer employee status over flexibility.", "passage_id": "P129", "passage_title": "Flexibility and Its Costs in the Gig Economy", "passage_text": "Platform companies that connect self-employed workers with customers through smartphone applications typically describe their model as offering flexibility that conventional employment cannot match. A driver or courier can log on and off at will, work across multiple platforms simultaneously, and decline jobs without needing permission from a manager. For workers who value control over their own schedule, whether because of caring responsibilities, studies, or a preference for variable hours, this arrangement can represent a genuine improvement over the rigidity of a fixed shift.\n\nThe difficulty is that the same classification which grants this flexibility, that of independent contractor rather than employee, also strips workers of protections that employment law has developed over more than a century. Contractors typically have no entitlement to a minimum wage calculated across all hours worked, no paid holiday, no sick pay, and no protection against arbitrary termination of the kind that unfair dismissal law provides. Platforms have argued that offering such protections would be inconsistent with the self-employed status their workers supposedly hold, since employment rights and contractor freedoms are, in law, generally treated as a package that cannot be selectively combined.\n\nCourts in several jurisdictions have begun to question whether this framing accurately describes the underlying relationship. Where a platform sets the price a worker may charge, penalises workers for declining too many jobs, and can deactivate a worker's account without appeal, the practical control it exercises resembles that of an employer far more than that of a mere intermediary connecting independent businesses. Judges have accordingly ruled in a number of cases that such workers are better classified as workers or employees, entitled to at least some of the protections the platforms had sought to withhold.\n\nThe resulting picture is one in which flexibility and protection are not as inherently opposed as platforms have claimed, since the loss of security experienced by gig workers stems less from the nature of flexible work itself than from a deliberate choice about how such work is classified. Reforming that classification, rather than eliminating flexibility, is what many of these rulings and the debates surrounding them ultimately point toward."}, {"id": 516, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'a package that cannot be selectively combined' is used to express which idea attributed to platforms?", "options": {"A": "Employment rights and contractor freedoms are treated as an all or nothing legal bundle.", "B": "Workers may choose any combination of rights they prefer under current law.", "C": "Platforms offer a fixed set of benefits identical across all workers.", "D": "Courts have ruled that rights and freedoms must always be combined together."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The phrase appears in the platforms' argument that granting employee-style protections would be inconsistent with contractor status, implying that in law the two sets of features come as a single bundle rather than a menu of options. It expresses the platforms' position rather than a settled legal rule or a court ruling. The passage in fact goes on to show courts questioning this very framing, which the other options fail to capture accurately.", "passage_id": "P129", "passage_title": "Flexibility and Its Costs in the Gig Economy", "passage_text": "Platform companies that connect self-employed workers with customers through smartphone applications typically describe their model as offering flexibility that conventional employment cannot match. A driver or courier can log on and off at will, work across multiple platforms simultaneously, and decline jobs without needing permission from a manager. For workers who value control over their own schedule, whether because of caring responsibilities, studies, or a preference for variable hours, this arrangement can represent a genuine improvement over the rigidity of a fixed shift.\n\nThe difficulty is that the same classification which grants this flexibility, that of independent contractor rather than employee, also strips workers of protections that employment law has developed over more than a century. Contractors typically have no entitlement to a minimum wage calculated across all hours worked, no paid holiday, no sick pay, and no protection against arbitrary termination of the kind that unfair dismissal law provides. Platforms have argued that offering such protections would be inconsistent with the self-employed status their workers supposedly hold, since employment rights and contractor freedoms are, in law, generally treated as a package that cannot be selectively combined.\n\nCourts in several jurisdictions have begun to question whether this framing accurately describes the underlying relationship. Where a platform sets the price a worker may charge, penalises workers for declining too many jobs, and can deactivate a worker's account without appeal, the practical control it exercises resembles that of an employer far more than that of a mere intermediary connecting independent businesses. Judges have accordingly ruled in a number of cases that such workers are better classified as workers or employees, entitled to at least some of the protections the platforms had sought to withhold.\n\nThe resulting picture is one in which flexibility and protection are not as inherently opposed as platforms have claimed, since the loss of security experienced by gig workers stems less from the nature of flexible work itself than from a deliberate choice about how such work is classified. Reforming that classification, rather than eliminating flexibility, is what many of these rulings and the debates surrounding them ultimately point toward."}, {"id": 520, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'resting more on projection than on demonstrated outcome' most nearly means that the debate", "options": {"A": "Has been settled through extensive historical data from past automation waves.", "B": "Relies entirely on the personal opinions of policymakers rather than evidence.", "C": "Cannot be resolved because both sides refuse to consider new evidence.", "D": "Depends on predictions about the future rather than on evidence already observed."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The phrase appears at the very end of the passage, summarising that neither side can point to demonstrated outcomes because large scale cognitive automation has not yet fully occurred, leaving arguments dependent on forecasts. It signals that the disagreement is forward looking rather than grounded in settled historical data. The other options wrongly claim the matter has been settled by history, reduce the debate to mere opinion, or suggest an unwillingness to consider evidence that the passage does not state.", "passage_id": "P130", "passage_title": "Universal Basic Income and the Automation Challenge", "passage_text": "As machine learning and robotics extend into tasks once thought to require distinctly human judgment, from diagnosing illness to drafting legal documents, proponents of universal basic income argue that a fundamentally new policy response is required. Previous waves of automation, they concede, displaced workers from particular trades but ultimately created new occupations elsewhere in the economy, allowing labour markets eventually to absorb those displaced. The current wave, on this view, threatens to differ in scope and speed, potentially eliminating cognitive as well as manual tasks faster than new roles can plausibly emerge to replace them.\n\nA universal basic income, an unconditional payment made to every citizen regardless of employment status, is proposed as a means of severing the link between income and paid work that has structured industrial societies for two centuries. Its supporters argue that such a payment would preserve dignity and consumer demand even in a future where a shrinking share of the population is required to produce the goods and services that everyone needs, since demand for those goods would otherwise collapse alongside employment.\n\nSceptics counter that the historical pattern of new occupations replacing old ones has repeated so consistently across two centuries of automation that there is little firm evidence the present wave will prove genuinely exceptional. They further object that an income high enough to live on, paid to every citizen without conditions, would carry a fiscal cost so large that funding it would likely require tax increases that themselves discourage the very work and investment the economy depends upon to generate that funding in the first place.\n\nProponents reply that this objection assumes automation's effects can be met using only the tools that served earlier transitions, when the scale of displacement anticipated this time may be different enough in kind to justify a correspondingly different response. Whether that assumption about scale is correct remains an empirical question that current evidence cannot yet settle decisively, since large scale automation of cognitive work is still at an early stage, leaving both sides of the debate resting more on projection than on demonstrated outcome."}, {"id": 522, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Which best captures the author's attitude toward the economist mentioned in paragraph two?", "options": {"A": "Full agreement with both the economist's arithmetic and his conclusions.", "B": "Outright rejection of the economist's figures as inaccurate.", "C": "Sympathy, since the economist has no better alternative to offer.", "D": "Acceptance of the economist's calculations paired with criticism of his indifference to distribution."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The author explicitly separates the accuracy of the growth figures from the question of who bears the cost, accepting the former while objecting to the latter. This shows a targeted criticism rather than a wholesale dismissal of the economist's reasoning. The remaining options either overstate agreement or invent a rejection of the figures themselves.", "passage_id": "P131", "passage_title": "The Ledger of Globalization", "passage_text": "The standard defence of globalization runs as follows: when capital, goods and labour move freely across borders, total output rises, prices fall for consumers everywhere, and poorer nations gain access to markets that were once closed to them. Measured in aggregate, the case looks unanswerable. World income has grown, extreme poverty has receded on a scale unmatched in human history, and consumer goods that were once luxuries are now unremarkable fixtures of ordinary households. Yet aggregate figures conceal as much as they reveal, because they average together experiences that have almost nothing in common with one another.\n\nConsider two figures produced by the same process. A factory owner in a wealthy country relocates production to a lower-wage economy, and the shareholders of that firm see their returns improve. Meanwhile, a machinist who spent twenty years mastering a trade in the factory now closed finds that his skills, once a secure asset, have no ready market. He is, in the strict accounting sense, part of the same growth story as the shareholder, but the two could hardly experience the change more differently. The economist who insists that both cases wash out in the national growth figures is not wrong about the arithmetic; he is merely indifferent to the distribution.\n\nThis indifference matters because the costs and benefits of openness are not randomly scattered through society. They fall along fairly predictable lines: owners of capital and highly mobile professionals tend to gain, while workers whose skills are tied to a single industry or region tend to lose, often permanently, since retraining and relocation are neither costless nor guaranteed to succeed. To describe this pattern as a temporary adjustment, as many defenders of open markets do, is to assume a capacity for renewal that the displaced frequently do not possess, whether from age, geography or the simple scarcity of comparable jobs nearby.\n\nNone of this establishes that closing borders would improve matters; protectionism has its own casualties, often less visible but no less real, among consumers and export industries. What it does establish is that the debate cannot be settled by citing the size of the aggregate gain, since the question that actually divides people is not whether the pie has grown but who has been left holding an emptier slice."}, {"id": 539, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What is the author's overall conclusion regarding anti-gouging laws?", "options": {"A": "That efficiency concerns are entirely and completely irrelevant to the whole debate at hand, contrary to popular belief.", "B": "That anti-gouging laws should be repealed everywhere immediately without any exception whatsoever, regardless of local circumstances.", "C": "That the moral objection to gouging is entirely mistaken and can simply be dismissed and ignored altogether.", "D": "That any adequate response must weigh supply benefits of higher prices against the moral cost of profiting from emergencies."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The final paragraph explicitly calls for weighing the real supply benefits of higher prices against the real moral cost of extraordinary gain during emergencies, rather than dismissing either side. This is a balanced conclusion, not a call for universal repeal or a dismissal of moral concerns. It also does not claim efficiency is irrelevant, since the passage treats it as one half of the necessary weighing.", "passage_id": "P135", "passage_title": "Prices in a Crisis", "passage_text": "When a hurricane knocks out power and floods roads, the price of bottled water, generators and plywood in the affected area often rises sharply within hours, sometimes to many multiples of the pre-storm rate. A vocal majority response to this phenomenon is moral outrage, and most jurisdictions that experience frequent disasters have enacted laws against such price increases, commonly described as price gouging. The economic case against these laws is well rehearsed: prices are signals, and suppressing them removes the incentive for suppliers both inside and outside the affected region to rush scarce goods to where they are needed most, while simultaneously encouraging hoarding by early buyers who face no financial disincentive to take more than they need.\n\nThere is real force to this argument, and it explains why many economists who otherwise disagree on policy converge on opposing anti-gouging laws. Yet the argument, taken alone, treats the matter as though it were purely a question of efficient allocation, when for most people the objection to price gouging is not primarily about efficiency at all. It is about the perceived exploitation of desperation, a sense that extracting an unusually large payment from someone facing an emergency they did not create and cannot avoid is a distinct kind of wrong, separate from whatever the transaction does to the overall supply of water or plywood.\n\nThis intuition need not be dismissed as mere economic ignorance. Societies routinely treat certain transactions as impermissible or restricted even when they might be allocatively efficient, from the sale of organs to the sale of votes, on the grounds that some forms of exchange corrode the norms that hold a community together in moments when solidarity matters most. Whether price gouging belongs in this category is a genuinely contestable question, not one that the efficiency argument can settle by itself, since it does not even attempt to address it.\n\nThe more defensible position, then, is not that the anti-price-gouging instinct is simply wrong, but that any adequate response to it must weigh the real supply benefits of higher prices against the real cost, moral rather than economic, of allowing emergencies to become occasions for extraordinary private gain."}, {"id": 544, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What effect does the phrase \"comforting fiction\" have in the final sentence?", "options": {"A": "It shows the author agrees that no one else is affected by inheritance.", "B": "It suggests the author is quoting an official government report.", "C": "It signals that the author regards the no-effect view as false but reassuring to hold.", "D": "It implies the fiction was invented by reformers rather than defenders of inheritance."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Calling the idea a fiction marks it as untrue, while calling it comforting explains why people continue to believe it despite the evidence given earlier in the passage. This phrase captures the author's rejection of the view that inheritance affects no one else. The other readings misassign who holds or invented the view described in the passage.", "passage_id": "P136", "passage_title": "The Lottery of Birth", "passage_text": "Defenders of inheritance tend to argue from a single, apparently unanswerable premise: a person who has earned money honestly is entitled to give it to whomever they choose, including their children. To deny this right, the argument runs, is to treat property as though it belonged to the state rather than to the individual who created it. There is something to this. A society that confiscated wages at death would strain the very incentive to work and save that makes prosperity possible in the first place.\n\nYet the premise smuggles in an assumption that deserves scrutiny: that the transaction being defended is a private matter between two consenting parties, the giver and the receiver, with no third party affected. This is false. Every unearned advantage one child receives is, in a competitive economy, a disadvantage imposed on every child who does not receive it. Positions in universities, professions and property markets are finite. When inheritance allows one contender to arrive already equipped with capital, connections and a paid off mortgage, it does not merely help that contender; it displaces someone else who arrives with nothing but ability. The recipient's gain is real, but so is the unchosen loss suffered by a stranger who never entered into any transaction at all.\n\nThis does not mean inheritance should be abolished. Few institutions are so thoroughly woven into family life, and an outright ban would likely be evaded or resented into irrelevance. But it does mean that the usual defense, resting entirely on the giver's freedom, is incomplete. A complete justification would have to explain why the freedom of the giver should outweigh the claims of those who compete against the receiver, not merely assert that the giver possesses the freedom.\n\nSome reformers conclude that steep taxation on inherited wealth is the answer, restoring a portion of the advantage to general use. Others favor capital grants to those who inherit nothing, funded by such taxes, so that the starting line is less uneven without touching the right to bequeath. Both proposals accept the premise that inheritance is not simply a private gift but a public event with losers as well as winners, and design policy around that fact rather than around the comforting fiction that no one else is affected."}, {"id": 547, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "Why does the author use the word \"quietly\" to describe how a tariff imposes cost on consumers?", "options": {"A": "To suggest that tariffs are illegal and therefore concealed from regulators.", "B": "To emphasize that consumers approve of the cost once it is explained to them.", "C": "To indicate that tariffs are gradually being phased out over time.", "D": "To highlight that the cost is real but hidden inside prices rather than openly debated."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The repeated use of quietly contrasts with the visible, funded program the author proposes instead, underscoring that a tariff's cost to consumers is genuine but not openly acknowledged or voted on. This word choice reinforces the passage's central contrast between hidden and transparent costs. The other readings introduce ideas about legality or timing that the passage never raises.", "passage_id": "P137", "passage_title": "Open Borders for Goods", "passage_text": "Every argument for tariffs begins with a real and visible cost: a factory closes, workers lose jobs they trained for over decades, and a town that depended on that factory withers. Free trade's defenders answer with a diffuse and less visible benefit: prices fall for everyone, and resources move toward industries where the country holds a genuine advantage. Because the cost is concentrated and photographable while the benefit is spread thinly across millions of shoppers, the political argument is won by whichever side can make its case vivid, and protectionism usually can.\n\nThis asymmetry of visibility, however, says nothing about which policy is actually better. A policy is not sound merely because its victims are easy to interview. The consumers who pay slightly more for shoes, cars and food because of a tariff rarely notice the individual overcharge, yet summed across a national population the transfer from consumers to protected producers can dwarf the wages saved in the protected industry. Economists who study these transfers consistently find that each job preserved by a tariff costs consumers several times that job's annual salary in higher prices.\n\nNone of this means displaced workers deserve to be ignored. It means the honest response to their loss is not a tariff that quietly taxes every purchaser to shield one industry, but a visible, funded program of retraining, relocation support or transitional income, paid for openly rather than hidden inside the price of goods. Such a program forces society to weigh the true cost of protecting workers against other public priorities, instead of imposing that cost invisibly on shoppers who never voted for it and may not even know it exists.\n\nCritics of this view object that retraining programs frequently fail, leaving workers stranded without either their old job or a viable new one. This is a fair challenge to the design of specific programs, not to the underlying principle. A retraining scheme can be redesigned or better funded; a tariff, by contrast, quietly reallocates income from the many to the few for as long as it remains in force, regardless of whether it was ever debated as a form of taxation at all."}, {"id": 554, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What does the comparison of housing to healthcare and education achieve in the passage?", "options": {"A": "It proves that housing markets and health systems are regulated by the same agencies.", "B": "It illustrates the rights-based view by grouping housing with other goods considered essential to dignity.", "C": "It shows that housing, unlike healthcare, has never been subject to government funding.", "D": "It suggests that education should be privatized in the same way as housing."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The comparison is used to explain the logic of the rights-based position, which treats housing as belonging to a category of essential goods that society guarantees regardless of market price, alongside healthcare and education. This is an illustrative analogy rather than a claim about shared regulation or funding history. The other options misread the purpose of the comparison.", "passage_id": "P139", "passage_title": "A Roof Is Not a Return", "passage_text": "Housing occupies an unusual position among the things people buy and sell, because it is simultaneously an investment asset, whose value ideally rises, and a basic necessity, whose price ideally stays low enough for ordinary people to afford. These two goals point in opposite directions, and much of the confusion in housing policy comes from politicians promising both at once: that homeowners will see their property appreciate steadily while first-time buyers will find homes increasingly affordable. Both cannot be true in the same market at the same time, since a home's affordability to a new buyer is simply the inverse of its value to an existing owner.\n\nTreating housing purely as a commodity, priced like any other good by supply and demand, has an internal logic. Supply constrained by planning restrictions, land scarcity and local objection to new construction, combined with steady demand from a growing population, produces rising prices in the ordinary way that any scarce good becomes more expensive. On this view the solution is straightforwardly to build more, loosen restrictive zoning and let supply catch up with demand until prices settle.\n\nTreating housing as a right, by contrast, holds that shelter is so fundamental to a life of basic dignity that its provision should not depend entirely on market outcomes, any more than emergency medical care should. On this view a purely supply-driven solution is too slow and too uncertain for people who need housing now, and it justifies rent controls, social housing built and maintained by public funds, or subsidies targeted at the poorest renters regardless of what happens to overall supply.\n\nThe two positions are not simply a disagreement about economics; they rest on different views of what a home is for. A commodity view treats housing as fundamentally similar to any other asset whose price should be left to find its own level. A rights-based view treats housing as similar to healthcare or education, goods so essential that a decent society guarantees some baseline regardless of market price. Most functioning housing systems in practice borrow from both, building market housing alongside a subsidized floor, which suggests that the honest debate is not which view is correct but where the line between them should sit."}, {"id": 555, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What can be inferred from the observation that most functioning housing systems borrow from both views?", "options": {"A": "Real-world policy debates tend to be about where to draw the line rather than choosing one pure view.", "B": "The commodity and rights-based views are entirely and fundamentally incompatible with one another in actual practice.", "C": "Rent controls have reportedly been abandoned entirely in every single country that ever once tried them.", "D": "Supply-side solutions have proven completely and utterly ineffective wherever they have ever actually been tested."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage concludes that most systems mix market housing with a subsidized floor, and frames the honest debate as being about where the line between the two approaches should sit, not which single view is correct. This directly supports the idea that practical debate concerns balance rather than exclusive choice. The other options overstate or contradict what the passage says.", "passage_id": "P139", "passage_title": "A Roof Is Not a Return", "passage_text": "Housing occupies an unusual position among the things people buy and sell, because it is simultaneously an investment asset, whose value ideally rises, and a basic necessity, whose price ideally stays low enough for ordinary people to afford. These two goals point in opposite directions, and much of the confusion in housing policy comes from politicians promising both at once: that homeowners will see their property appreciate steadily while first-time buyers will find homes increasingly affordable. Both cannot be true in the same market at the same time, since a home's affordability to a new buyer is simply the inverse of its value to an existing owner.\n\nTreating housing purely as a commodity, priced like any other good by supply and demand, has an internal logic. Supply constrained by planning restrictions, land scarcity and local objection to new construction, combined with steady demand from a growing population, produces rising prices in the ordinary way that any scarce good becomes more expensive. On this view the solution is straightforwardly to build more, loosen restrictive zoning and let supply catch up with demand until prices settle.\n\nTreating housing as a right, by contrast, holds that shelter is so fundamental to a life of basic dignity that its provision should not depend entirely on market outcomes, any more than emergency medical care should. On this view a purely supply-driven solution is too slow and too uncertain for people who need housing now, and it justifies rent controls, social housing built and maintained by public funds, or subsidies targeted at the poorest renters regardless of what happens to overall supply.\n\nThe two positions are not simply a disagreement about economics; they rest on different views of what a home is for. A commodity view treats housing as fundamentally similar to any other asset whose price should be left to find its own level. A rights-based view treats housing as similar to healthcare or education, goods so essential that a decent society guarantees some baseline regardless of market price. Most functioning housing systems in practice borrow from both, building market housing alongside a subsidized floor, which suggests that the honest debate is not which view is correct but where the line between them should sit."}, {"id": 573, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What complication does the passage raise against the simple boycott argument?", "options": {"A": "Boycotts are illegal in most garment producing countries.", "B": "Consumers in wealthy countries never actually participate in boycotts.", "C": "Factory wages are always higher than any other available work.", "D": "Withdrawing demand can push workers into worse alternatives rather than improving their situation."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage cites documented cases where factory closures following consumer pressure left workers with worse options than the jobs lost, complicating the assumption that reduced demand automatically benefits them. This evidence is used to question, not dismiss, the underlying moral concern. The other options misstate the passage's claims about legality, participation, or universal wage comparisons.", "passage_id": "P144", "passage_title": "Cheap Clothes and the Question of Complicity", "passage_text": "It has become common to describe the purchase of inexpensive, mass produced clothing as a form of complicity in exploitation, on the reasoning that a consumer who benefits from a low price sustained by dangerous factory conditions and poverty wages shares some responsibility for those conditions. The argument has intuitive force, yet it deserves closer examination before it is accepted as a basis for individual guilt or for boycotts aimed at correcting it.\n\nEconomists studying garment producing regions have repeatedly found that factory jobs, however harsh by the standards of wealthy countries, frequently pay more than the rural agricultural work or informal labour they replace, and that closing factories in response to consumer pressure has in several documented cases pushed workers into worse alternatives rather than better ones. This does not excuse dangerous conditions or suppressed wages, but it complicates the assumption that withdrawing demand straightforwardly helps the worker whose interests the boycott claims to represent. A consumer boycotting a factory from a comfortable distance rarely bears any of the cost of the worker's next, possibly worse, option.\n\nA more defensible form of the complicity argument targets not consumption itself but the refusal of retailers and consumers to demand verifiable standards, safety inspections, minimum wage compliance, and freedom of association, while still permitting the trade to continue. On this account, responsibility lies less in buying the garment than in accepting, without question, supply chains that could be made safer at a cost most consumers in wealthy countries could easily absorb through marginally higher prices. This version preserves the moral force of the original complaint while avoiding the paternalism of assuming that the correct response is simply to stop trading with poorer countries altogether.\n\nThe distinction matters because policies built on the wrong diagnosis can cause real harm. A retailer withdrawing entirely from a factory following bad publicity may satisfy a consumer's conscience while leaving workers worse off, whereas sustained pressure for enforceable standards, backed by willingness to pay slightly more, addresses the underlying condition without removing the livelihood altogether. Genuine concern for garment workers, in other words, is better expressed through patient and specific demands than through a single dramatic gesture aimed chiefly at easing the conscience of the shopper making it."}, {"id": 583, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage suggest is the reason software and fashion flourished under weak patent protection?", "options": {"A": "Imitation encouraged firms to keep innovating rather than relying on one protected design.", "B": "These industries received government subsidies instead of patent protection.", "C": "Patent law was never extended to cover these two industries at any point.", "D": "Consumers preferred imitated products because they were cheaper."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage states directly that imitation spurred firms in these industries to keep innovating rather than resting on one protected design, which explains their success under weak patent protection. This reasoning rests on continued competitive pressure rather than any subsidy or consumer preference. No mention is made of subsidies, an absolute absence of patent law, or consumer cost preferences, so those options go beyond what the text supports.", "passage_id": "P146", "passage_title": "The Patent Paradox", "passage_text": "Patents are commonly defended as the mechanism that makes invention worthwhile. Without the temporary monopoly a patent confers, so the argument runs, the vast expense of research and development could never be recouped, since a rival could simply copy the finished product the moment it appeared and undercut the inventor on price. On this view, patents do not restrict innovation but create it, converting an activity that would otherwise be irrational, since the fruits of your labour immediately become common property, into one that promises a return.\n\nYet the historical record complicates this tidy story. Several of the industries most celebrated for their pace of innovation, including software in its early decades and parts of the fashion trade, flourished under weak or absent patent protection, apparently because imitation spurred firms to keep innovating rather than resting on a single protected design. Meanwhile, some of the fiercest patent litigation occurs not between original inventors defending a breakthrough but between incumbents wielding broad, vaguely worded patents to deter newcomers from entering a market at all. In such cases the patent functions less as a reward for creativity and more as a barrier erected after the fact, its value lying in the threat of a lawsuit rather than in any technology it protects.\n\nA further complication concerns cumulative invention. Almost every significant technology builds on earlier work, and a patent system that grants strong, long-lasting rights over foundational techniques can make it more expensive, not less, for later inventors to improve upon them. The biotechnology sector illustrates this starkly: patents covering basic genetic techniques have in some instances been shown to slow the very research they were meant to encourage, as laboratories negotiate licensing fees rather than experiment freely.\n\nNone of this establishes that patents are without merit. Certain industries, pharmaceuticals prominent among them, involve development costs so enormous and imitation costs so trivial that some period of exclusivity seems difficult to dispense with entirely. The more defensible position, perhaps, is not that patents should be abolished but that their length, breadth and ease of acquisition should be calibrated industry by industry, since a single blunt instrument applied uniformly across sectors as different as software and pharmaceuticals is unlikely to serve the purpose for which patents were first devised."}, {"id": 584, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "In context, the phrase 'tidy story' is used to suggest that the pro-patent argument is", "options": {"A": "entirely fabricated and without any historical basis.", "B": "supported by overwhelming consensus among economists.", "C": "more complicated than the historical evidence allows.", "D": "neater and simpler than the actual historical evidence supports."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Describing the pro-patent argument as a 'tidy story' signals that it presents invention and reward too neatly compared with what the historical evidence actually shows. The word choice implies oversimplification rather than falsehood, since the passage still grants patents some merit later on. The alternative readings either overstate the criticism as outright fabrication or misread the phrase as suggesting added complexity rather than false simplicity.", "passage_id": "P146", "passage_title": "The Patent Paradox", "passage_text": "Patents are commonly defended as the mechanism that makes invention worthwhile. Without the temporary monopoly a patent confers, so the argument runs, the vast expense of research and development could never be recouped, since a rival could simply copy the finished product the moment it appeared and undercut the inventor on price. On this view, patents do not restrict innovation but create it, converting an activity that would otherwise be irrational, since the fruits of your labour immediately become common property, into one that promises a return.\n\nYet the historical record complicates this tidy story. Several of the industries most celebrated for their pace of innovation, including software in its early decades and parts of the fashion trade, flourished under weak or absent patent protection, apparently because imitation spurred firms to keep innovating rather than resting on a single protected design. Meanwhile, some of the fiercest patent litigation occurs not between original inventors defending a breakthrough but between incumbents wielding broad, vaguely worded patents to deter newcomers from entering a market at all. In such cases the patent functions less as a reward for creativity and more as a barrier erected after the fact, its value lying in the threat of a lawsuit rather than in any technology it protects.\n\nA further complication concerns cumulative invention. Almost every significant technology builds on earlier work, and a patent system that grants strong, long-lasting rights over foundational techniques can make it more expensive, not less, for later inventors to improve upon them. The biotechnology sector illustrates this starkly: patents covering basic genetic techniques have in some instances been shown to slow the very research they were meant to encourage, as laboratories negotiate licensing fees rather than experiment freely.\n\nNone of this establishes that patents are without merit. Certain industries, pharmaceuticals prominent among them, involve development costs so enormous and imitation costs so trivial that some period of exclusivity seems difficult to dispense with entirely. The more defensible position, perhaps, is not that patents should be abolished but that their length, breadth and ease of acquisition should be calibrated industry by industry, since a single blunt instrument applied uniformly across sectors as different as software and pharmaceuticals is unlikely to serve the purpose for which patents were first devised."}, {"id": 610, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Why does the passage reject the humanities' claim to a monopoly on ethical reasoning and sensitivity to ambiguity?", "options": {"A": "Because ethical failures have involved humanists as much as scientists, and some scientific fields require similar tolerance for ambiguity.", "B": "Because scientific training is objectively and demonstrably far more rigorous than any humanities training could ever be.", "C": "Because the humanities have largely stopped teaching ethics as a proper academic subject at all.", "D": "Because historians and philosophers have repeatedly proven many of the field's major scientific claims entirely false."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage argues that grave ethical failures were abetted by humanists as readily as scientists, and that disciplines confronting experimental ethics cultivate comparable tolerance for ambiguity, undermining any claimed monopoly. It does not assert that either field is more rigorous than the other, nor does it suggest humanities departments have stopped teaching ethics. The point about disproving scientific claims is not made anywhere in the text.", "passage_id": "P153", "passage_title": "Two Cultures Revisited", "passage_text": "It has become a habit of public commentary to speak of the humanities as though they were a single beleaguered kingdom under siege from an advancing science, its borders shrinking with every budget cycle. The habit obscures more than it reveals. Funding for literature and history departments has indeed contracted relative to engineering and computer science in many universities, but the reasons are not simply that science is more valuable; they include enrolment patterns driven by employers, government funding formulas tied to research grants that the sciences attract more easily, and a broader cultural anxiety about economic precarity that makes any subject without an obvious career pipeline look like a luxury few families feel able to afford.\n\nDefenders of the humanities sometimes respond by claiming a monopoly on qualities that scientific training supposedly lacks, such as ethical reasoning, historical perspective, or sensitivity to ambiguity. This claim does not survive close inspection. Many of the twentieth century's gravest ethical failures were abetted by humanists as readily as by scientists, and many scientific disciplines, particularly those confronting the ethics of experimentation, cultivate exactly the tolerance for ambiguity that humanists claim as their own. The honest case for the humanities cannot rest on the pretence that scientists are ethically or intellectually impoverished; it must instead identify what the humanities do that other disciplines, including the sciences, do not typically attempt at all.\n\nThat distinct contribution is easier to describe than to defend in funding terms. The humanities train students to read a text, an institution, or an argument as something constructed by people with interests, blind spots, and rhetorical aims, rather than as a neutral transmission of fact. This skill matters enormously to a society governed by argument and persuasion, yet it produces no patent, no product, and no easily quantified return, which is precisely why it struggles in a funding environment built around measurable output.\n\nThe two cultures are not, then, natural rivals possessing incompatible virtues. They are disciplines competing for scarce institutional resources under a metric that happens to suit one of them better than the other, a circumstance that says more about how universities are funded than about which pursuit is more worth having."}, {"id": 616, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What does the word \"unfalsifiable\" contribute to the passage's description of corrosive distrust?", "options": {"A": "It highlights that the theory cannot be disproven by any possible evidence, unlike genuine scientific claims.", "B": "It implies the theory is universally accepted by the public.", "C": "It means the theory has never been stated in public before.", "D": "It suggests the theory has been scientifically tested and confirmed."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "\"Unfalsifiable\" signals that no evidence could ever count against the theory, since any expert evidence is pre-emptively dismissed as self-interested, which is precisely why the passage treats this as a flaw rather than a strength. This is the reverse of being scientifically confirmed. The word carries no implication about universal public acceptance or about whether the theory has previously been voiced.", "passage_id": "P154", "passage_title": "The Revolt Against Expertise", "passage_text": "Every profession that claims specialised knowledge eventually faces a public that suspects the claim is self-serving. Economists are accused of designing policy to protect economists, doctors of protecting the guild rather than the patient, and climate scientists of manufacturing consensus to secure funding. Some of this suspicion is corrosive nonsense, but not all of it, and the difficulty for anyone defending expertise is that the corrosive and the reasonable versions of the complaint look identical from the outside, since both take the form of asking why the public should defer to people whose incentives are not perfectly aligned with the public's own.\n\nThe reasonable version rests on a real historical record. Experts have been wrong with great confidence before, sometimes catastrophically, and the institutions that credential expertise have on occasion protected their own errors more zealously than they protected the public the errors harmed. A citizen who recalls such episodes is not being irrational in demanding independent scrutiny of expert claims rather than simple deference. Distrust, on this reading, functions as a corrective, forcing experts to show their working rather than invoking credentials as a substitute for evidence.\n\nThe corrosive version, however, treats all expertise as equally suspect regardless of the evidence behind it, on the theory that any claim to specialised knowledge is really just a bid for status or funding. This move has a seductive symmetry, since it cannot be refuted by producing more expert evidence, which the theory has already dismissed as self-interested by definition. It thereby immunises itself against exactly the kind of correction that made the reasonable version of scepticism valuable in the first place, collapsing a useful check into an unfalsifiable posture.\n\nWhat distinguishes the reasonable complaint from the corrosive one is not the emotion behind it, since both can be voiced with equal conviction, but whether it remains open to being answered by evidence. A society that cannot tell the two apart risks discarding a genuine corrective alongside a piece of unfalsifiable cynicism, leaving experts free of scrutiny in the very cases where scrutiny would matter most, and the public defenceless against a conspiracy theory in the cases where deference to evidence would matter more."}, {"id": 618, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "According to the passage, why is refusing a platform to a discredited theory not the same as political interference?", "options": {"A": "Because discredited theories are always completely illegal for any professor to teach.", "B": "Because political interference only ever applies to decisions involving direct government funding.", "C": "Because universities have absolutely no legal right to restrict any teaching whatsoever.", "D": "Because the rejection comes from disciplinary peers rather than a government or external agenda."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage draws the distinction on the basis of who is doing the rejecting, arguing that when the rejection comes from disciplinary peers through ordinary scholarly contest rather than from a government or funding body with an external agenda, it is not the kind of interference academic freedom was designed to prevent. It does not claim discredited theories are illegal, nor that political interference is limited to funding matters. The passage also never suggests universities lack any legal authority to restrict teaching.", "passage_id": "P155", "passage_title": "The Limits of the Lectern", "passage_text": "Academic freedom is usually defended as an unqualified good, a shield protecting scholars from political interference so that inconvenient truths can be pursued wherever the evidence leads. This defence is largely correct, and history supplies ample warning of what happens when governments decide in advance what conclusions research is permitted to reach. Yet the defence, stated without qualification, obscures a genuine question that universities cannot avoid answering in practice: whether freedom to pursue research also entails freedom to promote conclusions that have been repeatedly tested and rejected by the relevant scholarly community.\n\nThe difficulty is that no institution can remain neutral on this question, however much it might wish to. A university that permits a professor to teach, under the banner of academic freedom, a theory that specialists in the field regard as thoroughly discredited is not thereby protecting open inquiry; it is lending its authority to a conclusion the field itself has already rejected through the ordinary business of contest and evidence. Refusing a platform to such a theory is not political interference of the kind academic freedom was designed to prevent, since the rejection here comes from disciplinary peers rather than from a government or a funding body with an external agenda to protect.\n\nThe genuine danger lies in confusing this distinction, in either direction. Confusing legitimate disciplinary judgement with external interference invites administrators to shield discredited theories under the banner of freedom, on the mistaken premise that any refusal to teach something is inherently a political act. Confusing external interference with legitimate disciplinary judgement invites the opposite error, allowing a government or donor to dress up a politically motivated demand as mere quality control and thereby capture a decision that should belong to scholars alone.\n\nAcademic freedom, properly understood, is therefore not a right to be shielded from all judgement whatsoever, but a right to be judged by one's disciplinary peers rather than by political authority. The line between the two forms of judgement is not always easy to draw in practice, but the difficulty of drawing it is not a reason to pretend the distinction does not exist, since erasing it would leave the concept doing no real work at all."}, {"id": 621, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to the passage, why does a rising proportion of top grades reduce the informativeness of a grade as a signal?", "options": {"A": "Because employers no longer trust examination boards to mark fairly.", "B": "Because a signal's value depends on its capacity to separate distinct groups.", "C": "Because top grades were never intended to measure ability accurately.", "D": "Because students now prepare more systematically than before."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A signal's value lies in its capacity to separate the exceptional from the merely competent, so when nearly everyone receives a top grade that dividing function is lost. The claim about distrust in marking misattributes the problem, and the suggestion that top grades were never meant to measure ability contradicts the passage's account of what grades are for. The point about more systematic preparation describes a proposed cause of rising grades rather than the reason the signal itself weakens.", "passage_id": "P156", "passage_title": "The Signal Lost in the Grade", "passage_text": "Over the past four decades the proportion of top grades awarded at every stage of formal education, from school examinations to university degrees, has risen steadily and without interruption. Commentators disagree sharply about what this trend means, but they agree on one thing: a grade is not merely a private reward for the student who receives it. It is a public signal, transmitted to employers, admissions tutors and the wider labour market, about a capacity that cannot otherwise be directly observed. The value of any signal depends on its capacity to discriminate, to separate the exceptional from the merely competent. When the proportion of top grades climbs from one in twenty to one in three, the signal does not simply become more generous; it becomes less informative, because the very function of a grade is to divide a population into distinguishable groups.\n\nDefenders of rising grades offer a rival explanation, one that does not depend on any weakening of standards. Teaching methods have genuinely improved, they argue, past papers are more widely available, and students prepare more systematically than earlier generations did. On this account, the rise in top grades reflects a real rise in attainment, a composition effect rather than a standards effect, and to call it inflation is to beg the very question at issue. This defence is not obviously wrong, and it would be too quick to dismiss it. Yet it struggles to explain why, whenever an examination board attempts to hold the proportion of top grades constant by adjusting boundaries, results still climb the following year under a different guise, as though something other than improved teaching were at work.\n\nWhat is rarely disputed, whichever explanation one favours, is who bears the cost of a diluted signal. The most able students, who would once have been clearly distinguished from their competent but unremarkable peers, now find themselves indistinguishable on paper from a much larger cohort. Employers and admissions tutors, denied a reliable filter, resort to cruder proxies: the reputation of the institution attended, the postcode of the applicant, the polish of an interview performance. These proxies correlate closely with existing social advantage. The paradox of grade inflation, then, is that a policy which appears to reward more students equally may in practice restore precisely the older, less meritocratic forms of selection that grades were introduced to displace."}, {"id": 624, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "In context, what does the phrase \"under a different guise\" most nearly suggest about the pattern the author describes?", "options": {"A": "That examination boards deliberately falsify their published results.", "B": "That grade boundaries are set randomly from one year to the next.", "C": "That the same underlying pressure reappears in a new, disguised form.", "D": "That students learn to disguise weak answers as strong ones."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The phrase follows a description of boundaries being adjusted to hold results steady, only for results to climb again in a new way, implying the same underlying pressure persists but takes a different visible shape. The idea that examination boards deliberately falsify results introduces an accusation the passage does not make. The suggestions that boundaries are set randomly or that students merely disguise weak answers misread the phrase as being about randomness or student behaviour rather than the recurrence of an underlying trend.", "passage_id": "P156", "passage_title": "The Signal Lost in the Grade", "passage_text": "Over the past four decades the proportion of top grades awarded at every stage of formal education, from school examinations to university degrees, has risen steadily and without interruption. Commentators disagree sharply about what this trend means, but they agree on one thing: a grade is not merely a private reward for the student who receives it. It is a public signal, transmitted to employers, admissions tutors and the wider labour market, about a capacity that cannot otherwise be directly observed. The value of any signal depends on its capacity to discriminate, to separate the exceptional from the merely competent. When the proportion of top grades climbs from one in twenty to one in three, the signal does not simply become more generous; it becomes less informative, because the very function of a grade is to divide a population into distinguishable groups.\n\nDefenders of rising grades offer a rival explanation, one that does not depend on any weakening of standards. Teaching methods have genuinely improved, they argue, past papers are more widely available, and students prepare more systematically than earlier generations did. On this account, the rise in top grades reflects a real rise in attainment, a composition effect rather than a standards effect, and to call it inflation is to beg the very question at issue. This defence is not obviously wrong, and it would be too quick to dismiss it. Yet it struggles to explain why, whenever an examination board attempts to hold the proportion of top grades constant by adjusting boundaries, results still climb the following year under a different guise, as though something other than improved teaching were at work.\n\nWhat is rarely disputed, whichever explanation one favours, is who bears the cost of a diluted signal. The most able students, who would once have been clearly distinguished from their competent but unremarkable peers, now find themselves indistinguishable on paper from a much larger cohort. Employers and admissions tutors, denied a reliable filter, resort to cruder proxies: the reputation of the institution attended, the postcode of the applicant, the polish of an interview performance. These proxies correlate closely with existing social advantage. The paradox of grade inflation, then, is that a policy which appears to reward more students equally may in practice restore precisely the older, less meritocratic forms of selection that grades were introduced to displace."}, {"id": 627, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to the final paragraph, what does adopting contextual admissions implicitly reveal about a university?", "options": {"A": "That the university favours a view of its purpose as cultivating potential.", "B": "That the university has abandoned academic standards altogether.", "C": "That the university believes all applicants are equally able.", "D": "That the university has run out of available places."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Contextual admissions, which weigh achievement against the circumstances producing it, imply a view of the university's purpose as developing potential rather than merely certifying existing ability. The claim that standards have been abandoned altogether is an accusation the passage attributes to critics rather than a conclusion it endorses. The remaining claims, that all applicants are seen as equally able or that the university has run out of places, are not made in the paragraph.", "passage_id": "P157", "passage_title": "The Ethics of the Narrow Gate", "passage_text": "Every selective university operates a gate through which only a fraction of applicants may pass, and every gate of this kind invites the same uncomfortable question: on what basis may an institution justify turning away applicants who are, on any ordinary measure, well qualified? The standard answer appeals to scarcity. Places are limited, resources such as teaching time and laboratory space cannot expand indefinitely, and some method of allocation is therefore unavoidable. This answer explains why a gate exists, but it does not by itself justify any particular design of that gate, since scarcity is compatible with allocation by lottery, by fee, or by need, as well as by academic merit.\n\nThe case for merit-based selection typically rests on a claim about desert: those who have worked hardest and achieved most deserve the opportunity that a scarce place represents. Yet this claim sits uneasily beside a body of evidence showing how strongly prior academic achievement is shaped by circumstances the applicant did not choose, among them the quality of schooling available locally, the presence of educated parents able to offer guidance, and simple financial security during examination years. If achievement is substantially the product of unchosen advantage, then a selection process built purely around it risks rewarding privilege while appearing to reward effort, a confusion the language of merit tends to obscure rather than expose.\n\nA further complication concerns what universities are for. If a university's purpose is chiefly to certify and reward existing ability, then selecting the most able applicants by whatever measure best predicts future performance is a coherent policy. If, however, a university's purpose includes cultivating potential that has not yet been given room to develop, a rather different policy follows: one that looks past raw attainment toward what an applicant might achieve given the resources the institution itself provides. Universities that adopt contextual admissions, weighing an applicant's achievement against the circumstances in which it was produced, are implicitly choosing the second account of purpose over the first. Critics who denounce such schemes as a lowering of standards are, whether they acknowledge it or not, taking a side in this deeper and rarely stated disagreement about what a university education is actually for."}, {"id": 638, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to the second paragraph, why do unscripted exchanges matter to many educators?", "options": {"A": "They allow lecturers to avoid preparing a fixed structure for their sessions.", "B": "They make online courses unnecessary for every subject.", "C": "They are the mechanism by which understanding is tested and deepened in real time.", "D": "They reduce the total amount of material a course needs to cover."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "These exchanges are described as the mechanism by which understanding is tested, corrected and deepened in ways a recorded transmission cannot replicate. Saying they let lecturers avoid preparing any fixed structure misattributes a lack of preparation to what is in fact a valued pedagogical process. The remaining claims, that they make online courses unnecessary for every subject or reduce the total material to cover, are not supported by the paragraph.", "passage_id": "P160", "passage_title": "The Room That Cannot Be Streamed", "passage_text": "The rapid expansion of online learning platforms has revived an old debate in a new register: can instruction delivered through a screen substitute fully for instruction delivered in a shared physical room? Proponents point to undeniable advantages. Recorded lectures can be paused, replayed and consulted at whatever hour suits the learner, removing constraints of geography and timetable that have long excluded students unable to relocate or attend fixed sessions. Measured purely against the transmission of information, a well produced online course can rival, and sometimes exceed, the clarity of a live lecture delivered once and never revisited.\n\nWhat this comparison omits is that formal education has never been solely, or even primarily, a matter of transmitting information from one party to another. Much of what a good seminar or tutorial achieves happens in the unscripted exchange between participants: the question asked mid explanation that reveals a misunderstanding the instructor had not anticipated, the visible confusion on a classmate's face that prompts a lecturer to try a different approach, the argument that develops unpredictably because several minds are responding to one another in real time rather than to a fixed recording. These exchanges are not incidental decoration around the real business of teaching; for many educators they are the real business, the mechanism by which understanding is tested, corrected and deepened in ways a recorded transmission cannot replicate.\n\nIt would be a mistake to conclude from this that online learning has no legitimate place, since for many subjects and many learners the flexibility it offers outweighs what is lost in spontaneous exchange, and hybrid formats increasingly attempt to combine recorded content with live discussion sessions. The more defensible claim is narrower: that wherever a discipline depends heavily on the unpredictable back and forth of live inquiry, rather than on the steady transmission of settled material, no amount of technical refinement to the recorded format will fully substitute for the room in which that inquiry actually happens. The question to ask of any course, then, is not whether it is delivered online or in person, but how much of its value depends on the kind of exchange only a shared, unscripted room can supply."}, {"id": 644, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The word stubbornly in describing reasoning skill as domain specific chiefly conveys which idea?", "options": {"A": "Researchers are reluctant to accept findings about domain specificity.", "B": "Domain specificity is a recent and still contested scientific discovery.", "C": "The domain bound nature of reasoning resists efforts to teach it generally.", "D": "Students are unwilling to apply reasoning skills across different subjects."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Stubbornly personifies the trait as resistant to change, indicating that reasoning remains tied to its subject matter despite attempts to abstract it into a general skill. It describes a property of reasoning itself rather than the attitude of researchers or students. The word signals persistence against efforts at generalisation, which fits the surrounding argument about transfer failing.", "passage_id": "P161", "passage_title": "Thinking About Thinking", "passage_text": "Proponents of a discrete curriculum subject called critical thinking proceed from an assumption that deserves closer scrutiny than it usually receives: that the capacity to reason well is a transferable skill, extractable from any particular body of knowledge and taught in the abstract, rather like grammar or arithmetic. On this view, a student who has mastered the identification of logical fallacies, the evaluation of evidence, and the construction of valid arguments in a dedicated classroom will carry these tools intact into history, science, or everyday life, applying them with equal facility regardless of subject matter.\n\nThere are reasons to doubt this. Cognitive scientists have repeatedly found that reasoning skill is stubbornly domain specific: a physicist adept at spotting flawed causal inference in a paper on particle decay may reason no better than a novice when confronted with a flawed argument about tax policy, precisely because expert reasoning is bound up with a rich, particular understanding of the subject at hand, not with a general purpose toolkit sitting apart from it. If this is right, then a course that teaches critical thinking as a free standing subject, detached from any particular discipline, risks producing students who can recite the names of fallacies without being able to recognise them when they actually arise in a geography essay or a news report.\n\nThe more promising alternative, on this reasoning, is not to abandon the goal of better reasoning but to relocate it: embedding the deliberate teaching of argument evaluation within existing subjects, so that a history teacher explicitly draws attention to the weighing of primary sources and a science teacher to the logic of controlled variables. This demands more of subject teachers, who must now teach their discipline and its underlying reasoning simultaneously, and it forfeits the tidy appeal of a syllabus that can be written, examined, and inspected as a single block. But it is answerable to the evidence about how reasoning actually transfers, or rather fails to, whereas the discrete subject is answerable chiefly to administrative convenience. Whatever the merits of a standalone course as a signal that reasoning matters, the harder empirical question, whether it produces students who reason better outside the classroom in which they learned it, remains largely unresolved and inconvenient for its advocates."}, {"id": 651, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "The author's suggestion about where funding should be directed implies which conclusion?", "options": {"A": "University fees should be raised further to fund earlier schooling instead.", "B": "Widening participation efforts are unlikely to succeed under any policy.", "C": "Income contingent loans should be abolished in favour of upfront fees.", "D": "Interventions before university age address the inequality more directly than fee abolition."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage recommends directing spending at the stages before university, where the attainment gap actually opens, rather than at fee abolition, implying earlier intervention is more directly effective. It does not call for raising fees or abolishing income contingent loans. Nor does it suggest that widening participation is doomed regardless of approach.", "passage_id": "P163", "passage_title": "Who Should Pay for the Lecture Hall", "passage_text": "The case for abolishing university tuition fees is often presented as a matter of fairness: education, the argument runs, is a public good whose benefits extend well beyond the individual graduate, and a system that requires students to borrow heavily in order to attend deters precisely those from poorer backgrounds whom a fair society should be most concerned to admit. Free tuition, funded from general taxation, replaces a personal debt with a collective obligation, and in doing so removes what looks like a straightforward barrier to opportunity.\n\nThe difficulty with this account is that it treats the fee itself as the operative barrier, when the evidence on who actually enrols suggests a more complicated picture. In systems that already offer income contingent loan repayment, where nothing is paid upfront and repayment is scaled to future earnings, the remaining gap in university attendance between richer and poorer students tends to owe less to fear of debt than to disparities in prior school attainment, information about the application process, and confidence that a place is genuinely available to them. Abolishing fees outright, funded by taxpayers generally, then transfers resources toward a population, university entrants, that remains disproportionately drawn from wealthier households, since it is precisely those households whose children are likeliest to attend regardless of the funding model chosen.\n\nNone of this establishes that fees are costless or that current loan arrangements are optimally designed; income contingent repayment can still be poorly calibrated, and genuine barriers of confidence and information plainly deserve remedy. Some of these barriers form years before any application is submitted, rooted in the expectations a household holds about whether higher education is a plausible path at all, and no adjustment to the fee schedule reaches that far upstream. But it does suggest that the intuitive equation of tuition fees with unfairness, and of their abolition with fairness, is too quick. A policy aimed at widening participation might do better to direct spending at the stages before university, where the attainment gap actually opens, than at a fee structure whose removal chiefly benefits students who were already likely to attend, leaving the underlying inequality in access largely undisturbed while the tax bill for everyone else quietly grows."}, {"id": 654, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "The proposed layered compromise implies that centralised control is most justified in which area?", "options": {"A": "Enrichment projects and elective subjects chosen by individual schools.", "B": "Subjects that vary most according to local geography and interest.", "C": "Foundational subjects on which subsequent learning depends.", "D": "Areas where teachers have the greatest discretion to adapt content."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage states that the compromise captures the equity argument for centralisation where it is strongest, in the foundational subjects on which later learning depends. Enrichment and elective content are instead assigned to local or school level decision. Areas of greatest teacher discretion are explicitly linked to local control rather than centralisation.", "passage_id": "P164", "passage_title": "One Syllabus or Many", "passage_text": "A national curriculum, prescribed centrally and applied uniformly across every school in a jurisdiction, promises a particular kind of fairness: a child's access to core content in mathematics, science, and literacy does not depend on the accident of which town or which school happens to enrol her, since the same material, broadly speaking, is guaranteed everywhere. It also permits meaningful comparison between schools, since inspectors, parents, and researchers are measuring performance against a common standard rather than against locally invented and mutually incommensurable ones.\n\nLocal control of curriculum content is defended on almost the opposite ground: that a single national syllabus, however well designed in the abstract, cannot be equally well suited to a rural community whose pupils might benefit from applied agricultural science and a dense urban district whose pupils face entirely different circumstances and interests. Centralisation, on this account, achieves uniformity at the cost of relevance, imposing a single template on communities whose needs diverge, and it removes from teachers, who are best placed to see what actually engages their own pupils, the discretion to adapt.\n\nThe dispute is frequently framed as a stark binary, uniform national content against locally devised alternatives, but the more defensible position for most systems lies in a layered compromise: a core, centrally specified minimum in foundational subjects, ensuring that no child is denied basic numeracy or literacy by geography, combined with a substantial margin left to local or school level decision for enrichment content, applied projects, and elective subjects. Such a structure captures the equity argument for centralisation where it is strongest, in the foundational subjects on which later learning depends, while conceding the relevance argument for local control where it is strongest, in enrichment areas where a single national template genuinely serves communities unevenly. Critics of compromise solutions often complain that they satisfy no one fully, but a policy area in which both stated concerns, fairness of access and relevance to circumstance, are independently well founded is not obviously a case in which one side ought simply to prevail over the other. Treating the dispute as a contest with a single winner assumes that fairness and relevance cannot both be served by the same system, an assumption the layered structure is designed specifically to avoid."}, {"id": 655, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The argument for local control of curriculum rests mainly on the claim that:", "options": {"A": "National standards make meaningful comparison between schools impossible.", "B": "A single syllabus cannot suit communities with genuinely different needs.", "C": "Teachers should have no obligation to teach any core subject.", "D": "Rural and urban schools should be funded through separate systems."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage explains that local control advocates argue a single national syllabus cannot be equally well suited to communities with different circumstances, such as rural and urban districts. The comparison benefit of national standards is attributed to the opposing side, not disputed here. Funding structures and obligations regarding core subjects are not raised as part of this argument.", "passage_id": "P164", "passage_title": "One Syllabus or Many", "passage_text": "A national curriculum, prescribed centrally and applied uniformly across every school in a jurisdiction, promises a particular kind of fairness: a child's access to core content in mathematics, science, and literacy does not depend on the accident of which town or which school happens to enrol her, since the same material, broadly speaking, is guaranteed everywhere. It also permits meaningful comparison between schools, since inspectors, parents, and researchers are measuring performance against a common standard rather than against locally invented and mutually incommensurable ones.\n\nLocal control of curriculum content is defended on almost the opposite ground: that a single national syllabus, however well designed in the abstract, cannot be equally well suited to a rural community whose pupils might benefit from applied agricultural science and a dense urban district whose pupils face entirely different circumstances and interests. Centralisation, on this account, achieves uniformity at the cost of relevance, imposing a single template on communities whose needs diverge, and it removes from teachers, who are best placed to see what actually engages their own pupils, the discretion to adapt.\n\nThe dispute is frequently framed as a stark binary, uniform national content against locally devised alternatives, but the more defensible position for most systems lies in a layered compromise: a core, centrally specified minimum in foundational subjects, ensuring that no child is denied basic numeracy or literacy by geography, combined with a substantial margin left to local or school level decision for enrichment content, applied projects, and elective subjects. Such a structure captures the equity argument for centralisation where it is strongest, in the foundational subjects on which later learning depends, while conceding the relevance argument for local control where it is strongest, in enrichment areas where a single national template genuinely serves communities unevenly. Critics of compromise solutions often complain that they satisfy no one fully, but a policy area in which both stated concerns, fairness of access and relevance to circumstance, are independently well founded is not obviously a case in which one side ought simply to prevail over the other. Treating the dispute as a contest with a single winner assumes that fairness and relevance cannot both be served by the same system, an assumption the layered structure is designed specifically to avoid."}, {"id": 658, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The word untethered used to describe judgment exercised without technique mainly conveys that such judgment is:", "options": {"A": "More creative and therefore preferable to technique based teaching.", "B": "Impossible for any teacher to exercise under real classroom conditions.", "C": "Supported by evidence but simply applied inconsistently.", "D": "Disconnected from anything shown reliably to work."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Untethered describes improvisation as detached, meaning judgment exercised without technique lacks connection to methods known to work reliably. This is presented as a shortcoming rather than a virtue, so it does not suggest such judgment is preferable or more creative. The passage does not claim such judgment is impossible, only that it is disconnected from reliable evidence when technique is absent.", "passage_id": "P165", "passage_title": "Craft or Discipline", "passage_text": "To ask whether teaching is an art or a science is to invite a false choice dressed up as a serious question, yet the framing persists because each side of it captures something real. Those who insist that teaching is fundamentally a science point to a growing body of research, on retrieval practice, spaced repetition, and the sequencing of worked examples, that identifies techniques producing reliably better learning outcomes across many classrooms and many kinds of pupil, quite independently of the particular teacher delivering them. On this view, a teacher who ignores this evidence in favour of personal instinct is not being admirably individual but simply less effective than one who is not.\n\nThose who insist that teaching is fundamentally an art point to something the research, however extensive, cannot fully specify: the judgment required to read a particular classroom in a particular moment, to sense that a technique validated on average is landing badly with this group of adolescents on this wet Tuesday afternoon, and to adapt accordingly. No manual of evidence based technique tells a teacher when to depart from it, because the departure is itself a response to particulars that no study, however large its sample, can anticipate in advance.\n\nThe two positions are not actually in competition, since evidence based technique supplies the material that judgment is exercised upon, and judgment without technique is merely improvisation untethered from anything known to work reliably. A teacher who has internalised the research on effective instruction, and who then exercises the discretion to depart from it when a particular class demands it, is drawing on both capacities at once, and it is hard to see what would be gained by insisting that only one of them be honoured with the name of the profession's true nature. The persistence of the debate probably owes less to any genuine incompatibility between art and science than to the institutional consequences that follow from each label, since calling teaching a science invites standardised training and inspection regimes that a craft based description would resist, and it is this practical stake, rather than the philosophical question itself, that keeps the argument alive."}, {"id": 659, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "The passage's final sentence implies that the art versus science debate persists mainly because of:", "options": {"A": "A lack of sufficient research into either teaching approach.", "B": "Institutional consequences attached to each label, rather than the philosophical question itself.", "C": "Disagreement among researchers about what retrieval practice actually involves.", "D": "The unwillingness of teachers to adopt any evidence based technique."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The final sentence attributes the debate's persistence to institutional consequences, such as calling teaching a science inviting standardised training and inspection regimes, rather than to the philosophical question itself. This is explicitly contrasted with a lack of research or disagreement over specific techniques. Unwillingness among teachers to adopt technique is not mentioned as a cause of the debate's persistence.", "passage_id": "P165", "passage_title": "Craft or Discipline", "passage_text": "To ask whether teaching is an art or a science is to invite a false choice dressed up as a serious question, yet the framing persists because each side of it captures something real. Those who insist that teaching is fundamentally a science point to a growing body of research, on retrieval practice, spaced repetition, and the sequencing of worked examples, that identifies techniques producing reliably better learning outcomes across many classrooms and many kinds of pupil, quite independently of the particular teacher delivering them. On this view, a teacher who ignores this evidence in favour of personal instinct is not being admirably individual but simply less effective than one who is not.\n\nThose who insist that teaching is fundamentally an art point to something the research, however extensive, cannot fully specify: the judgment required to read a particular classroom in a particular moment, to sense that a technique validated on average is landing badly with this group of adolescents on this wet Tuesday afternoon, and to adapt accordingly. No manual of evidence based technique tells a teacher when to depart from it, because the departure is itself a response to particulars that no study, however large its sample, can anticipate in advance.\n\nThe two positions are not actually in competition, since evidence based technique supplies the material that judgment is exercised upon, and judgment without technique is merely improvisation untethered from anything known to work reliably. A teacher who has internalised the research on effective instruction, and who then exercises the discretion to depart from it when a particular class demands it, is drawing on both capacities at once, and it is hard to see what would be gained by insisting that only one of them be honoured with the name of the profession's true nature. The persistence of the debate probably owes less to any genuine incompatibility between art and science than to the institutional consequences that follow from each label, since calling teaching a science invites standardised training and inspection regimes that a craft based description would resist, and it is this practical stake, rather than the philosophical question itself, that keeps the argument alive."}, {"id": 669, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Why does the passage argue that admissions criteria can disadvantage less privileged applicants even without conscious bias?", "options": {"A": "Admissions officers openly prefer wealthier applicants.", "B": "The criteria correlate with forms of prior advantage already unevenly distributed.", "C": "Universities set quotas favouring certain schools by name.", "D": "Less privileged applicants rarely wish to apply at all."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage explains that criteria such as school quality, coaching access, and family familiarity correlate strongly with prior advantage, so the applicant pool is already shaped unequally before any decision is made. This produces skewed outcomes without requiring any deliberate bias from admissions staff. The other options attribute the effect to intentions or mechanisms the passage never mentions.", "passage_id": "P168", "passage_title": "The Sorting Mechanism", "passage_text": "It is often said that elite universities are engines of social mobility, taking talented individuals from modest backgrounds and equipping them to rise. The claim is not baseless: such institutions can and do transform the prospects of particular students who pass through their gates. But a claim about individual transformation is not the same as a claim about the system as a whole, and it is the latter that matters when we ask whether these institutions reduce inequality overall.\n\nConsider what an elite university actually does at the point of admission. It selects a small number of applicants from a much larger pool, using criteria that, however carefully designed, correlate strongly with prior advantage: the quality of schooling received, the availability of coaching for interviews and entrance tests, the confidence instilled by a family already familiar with such institutions. A selection process of this kind will tend to admit a disproportionate share of already-advantaged applicants even when no one making decisions harbours any conscious bias, simply because the applicant pool itself has been shaped by unequal preparation long before any admissions officer sees a single form.\n\nOnce a cohort has been admitted, the university confers on its graduates a credential that functions, in the labour market, as a signal of quality that recruiters trust and reward disproportionately. This is precisely where the mobility narrative and the inequality narrative diverge. The credential does lift the individuals who receive it, often dramatically, which is why the mobility story is not simply false. Yet by concentrating this valuable signal in the hands of those already best placed to obtain it, the institution simultaneously widens the gap between those who hold the credential and those who never had a realistic chance of competing for it in the first place.\n\nThe honest conclusion, then, is neither that elite universities do nothing for social mobility nor that they straightforwardly reduce inequality. It is that they can do both at once: lifting individuals while entrenching, at the level of the whole society, the very stratification that produced their applicant pool to begin with. Recognising this double effect does not tell us what, if anything, should be done about admissions policy, but it does mean the mobility narrative alone cannot settle the question of whether such institutions are, on balance, a force for greater equality."}, {"id": 670, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "How does the passage characterise the relationship between individual mobility and overall inequality?", "options": {"A": "Individual mobility always eliminates overall inequality eventually.", "B": "Mobility for individuals disproves any claim of systemic inequality.", "C": "Overall inequality has no connection to individual outcomes.", "D": "An institution can raise individuals up while widening the wider gap."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The final paragraph states elite universities can do both at once, lifting particular individuals while entrenching stratification across society as a whole. This is offered as the honest, dual conclusion rather than a simple denial of either narrative. The other options collapse this dual relationship into a false either-or that the passage explicitly rejects.", "passage_id": "P168", "passage_title": "The Sorting Mechanism", "passage_text": "It is often said that elite universities are engines of social mobility, taking talented individuals from modest backgrounds and equipping them to rise. The claim is not baseless: such institutions can and do transform the prospects of particular students who pass through their gates. But a claim about individual transformation is not the same as a claim about the system as a whole, and it is the latter that matters when we ask whether these institutions reduce inequality overall.\n\nConsider what an elite university actually does at the point of admission. It selects a small number of applicants from a much larger pool, using criteria that, however carefully designed, correlate strongly with prior advantage: the quality of schooling received, the availability of coaching for interviews and entrance tests, the confidence instilled by a family already familiar with such institutions. A selection process of this kind will tend to admit a disproportionate share of already-advantaged applicants even when no one making decisions harbours any conscious bias, simply because the applicant pool itself has been shaped by unequal preparation long before any admissions officer sees a single form.\n\nOnce a cohort has been admitted, the university confers on its graduates a credential that functions, in the labour market, as a signal of quality that recruiters trust and reward disproportionately. This is precisely where the mobility narrative and the inequality narrative diverge. The credential does lift the individuals who receive it, often dramatically, which is why the mobility story is not simply false. Yet by concentrating this valuable signal in the hands of those already best placed to obtain it, the institution simultaneously widens the gap between those who hold the credential and those who never had a realistic chance of competing for it in the first place.\n\nThe honest conclusion, then, is neither that elite universities do nothing for social mobility nor that they straightforwardly reduce inequality. It is that they can do both at once: lifting individuals while entrenching, at the level of the whole society, the very stratification that produced their applicant pool to begin with. Recognising this double effect does not tell us what, if anything, should be done about admissions policy, but it does mean the mobility narrative alone cannot settle the question of whether such institutions are, on balance, a force for greater equality."}, {"id": 678, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What is the author's response to the critics who worry that talk of 'foundational knowledge' disguises old hierarchies?", "options": {"A": "The worry should be scrutinised on a case by case basis rather than used to reject standards altogether.", "B": "The worry is entirely baseless, reflects no genuine concern, and should therefore be dismissed outright without scrutiny.", "C": "The worry proves conclusively that all curricula are secretly and inherently hierarchical beneath their stated aims.", "D": "The worry means schools should stop teaching any foundational subjects regardless of their transferable pedagogical value."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage acknowledges the worry is not groundless and vigilance is reasonable, but argues the answer is to scrutinise the standard rather than abandon the idea that curricula need standards at all. This is a measured response rather than outright dismissal or full agreement. The other options overstate the author's position in one direction or the other.", "passage_id": "P170", "passage_title": "Not All Equal", "passage_text": "A certain democratic instinct runs through much contemporary thinking about curricula: the idea that no body of knowledge should be ranked above another, since ranking implies a judgment about whose culture, whose interests, and whose questions matter most. This instinct has done real good, correcting curricula that once ignored entire traditions of thought and treated a narrow canon as though it were simply knowledge itself, rather than one selection among many possible ones. But taken to its logical extreme, the instinct produces a conclusion that few of its proponents would actually accept if stated plainly: that a curriculum has no principled basis for choosing anything over anything else.\n\nIn practice, no curriculum can teach everything, and the moment a choice must be made between two bodies of knowledge, some standard for choosing is required, whether or not it is acknowledged. Such standards need not be crude assertions of superiority. A subject might be judged more worth teaching because it equips students with tools that transfer to many other domains, because it is foundational to further study within a field, or because engaging with it cultivates a habit of careful reasoning not equally cultivated elsewhere. These are not claims that one culture is superior to another; they are claims about pedagogical function, about what a particular piece of knowledge does for the learner who acquires it.\n\nCritics of this view worry that talk of foundational or transferable knowledge is simply a disguise for old hierarchies, smuggled back in under a technical vocabulary. The worry is not groundless, since such language has certainly been used that way before, and vigilance against it is reasonable. But the answer to a standard's past misuse is to scrutinise the standard, not to abandon the idea that curricula require standards at all, since a curriculum that refuses to distinguish more from less useful knowledge for a given purpose has not become neutral. It has simply stopped being able to explain itself.\n\nThe task facing educators, then, is not to choose between hierarchy and equality in some abstract sense, but to build defensible, purpose-specific reasons for the choices a finite curriculum always forces them to make."}, {"id": 683, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "Based on the passage, how would the author most likely view a class debate over a theory believed only by a small, uninformed minority?", "options": {"A": "Largely unjustified, since the dissent lacks intellectual quality.", "B": "Fully justified, since all disagreements deserve equal classroom time.", "C": "Justified only if the minority view happens to be correct.", "D": "Unjustified unless the teacher personally holds the minority view."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage states that some claims are dissented from only by the ignorant or self-interested, and that treating every controversy as automatically worthy of class time abandons the judgment education should cultivate. This implies the author would see little value in staging a debate over a view lacking serious argumentative backing. The passage never suggests that correctness or the teacher's personal belief determines whether a debate is worthwhile.", "passage_id": "P171", "passage_title": "The Uses of Disagreement", "passage_text": "It has become fashionable to argue that a genuinely liberal education must expose students to views they find abhorrent, on the theory that untested convictions are worth less than convictions that have survived contact with an intelligent adversary. There is something to this. A student who has never had to defend a position against a capable opponent may hold that position by habit rather than by reason, and habit is a poor foundation for anything that might later be challenged by circumstance. Yet the argument, pressed too far, mistakes exposure for engagement. Merely hearing an opposing view is not the same as grappling with it, and a curriculum that prides itself on presenting both sides of every question can produce not resilient thinkers but exhausted relativists, persuaded that no position is any better than another because none has been allowed to win.\n\nThe deeper difficulty is that not all disagreements are equally instructive. There is educational value in making a student wrestle with a serious argument for a view she rejects, provided the argument is a good one; there is considerably less value in staging a debate merely because a dissenting position exists. Some claims are dissented from only by the ignorant or the self-interested, and a teacher who treats every controversy as automatically worthy of classroom time abdicates the very judgment that education is supposed to cultivate. The student does not need to refute every crank theory in order to hold her own views intelligently; she needs to have tested them against the strongest available objection, which is not always the most popular one.\n\nThis suggests that the real requirement is not exposure to opposing views as such, but exposure to opposing arguments of sufficient quality that meeting them demands genuine intellectual work. A school that shields its students from any challenge to prevailing opinion fails them, certainly, but so does one that treats disagreement as intrinsically valuable regardless of its source or rigor. What matters is not the presence of an opposite number but the quality of the resistance he offers. An education that mistakes noise for dialectic will leave its graduates well practiced in tolerance and poorly practiced in thought, having confused the ritual of debate with the discipline of reasoning that debate is supposed to serve."}, {"id": 685, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "The example of a surgeon consulting a reference text is used to illustrate", "options": {"A": "why professional exams should always be open-book assessments.", "B": "how rarely doctors actually need to recall information instantly.", "C": "why some knowledge must be immediately retrievable without delay.", "D": "that surgeons are held to unfairly high testing standards."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The surgeon example is offered to show that some situations demand knowledge be so thoroughly internalised that it can be recalled instantly, since delay would be dangerous. This supports the broader claim that timed exams can serve as a proxy for this kind of readiness rather than as a rehearsal of everyday practice. The passage does not argue for open-book exams, minimise the need for recall, or comment on fairness to surgeons specifically.", "passage_id": "P172", "passage_title": "What the Clock Is For", "passage_text": "Critics of timed examinations frequently observe that the professional world rarely demands that anyone solve a problem in forty-five minutes without access to reference material, and conclude from this that timed testing measures nothing more useful than a talent for working under artificial pressure. The observation is accurate as far as it goes, but the conclusion does not follow from it, because it assumes that an examination's purpose is to simulate the conditions of later practice. In fact the timed exam is rarely intended as a rehearsal for professional life; it is intended as a forcing mechanism, a device for compelling a candidate to demonstrate command of material rather than mere familiarity with it.\n\nThere is a meaningful difference between knowing where to find an answer and knowing the answer well enough to produce it without hesitation. A surgeon consulting a reference text mid-operation would be alarming not because reference texts are shameful but because certain knowledge must be so thoroughly internalised that recall is instantaneous, since the situations in which it is needed rarely tolerate delay. The timed exam, at its best, is a proxy for this kind of readiness. It does not claim that every subject requires instant recall in adult life, only that some measure of the depth and fluency of a candidate's understanding is best revealed when she cannot pause to look anything up.\n\nNone of this defends every timed exam as currently constructed. Many such tests reward speed of handwriting or fluency in exam technique as much as they reward understanding, and a candidate who has simply practised more past papers may outperform one with deeper but less rehearsed knowledge. This is a genuine flaw, and one that examination boards ought to take seriously when designing questions and allocating time. But the flaw is a defect in execution, not evidence that timed assessment is conceptually misguided. The proper response is to design exams whose time pressure isolates genuine understanding rather than test-taking fluency, not to abandon the clock altogether on the mistaken assumption that its only function is to imitate a workplace that does not, in fact, need imitating."}, {"id": 686, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "How does the author respond to the criticism that timed exams do not resemble real professional conditions?", "options": {"A": "By arguing exams are not meant to simulate later professional practice.", "B": "By denying that professional conditions ever involve any time pressure.", "C": "By claiming most professionals actually work under strict deadlines.", "D": "By insisting that reference materials are rarely useful in practice."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage concedes that professionals rarely face such tight time constraints but argues this criticism assumes exams are meant to rehearse professional conditions, which the author denies is their purpose. Instead, the timed format is described as a forcing mechanism for revealing depth of understanding. The passage does not deny time pressure exists in some professions, nor does it dismiss the general usefulness of reference materials.", "passage_id": "P172", "passage_title": "What the Clock Is For", "passage_text": "Critics of timed examinations frequently observe that the professional world rarely demands that anyone solve a problem in forty-five minutes without access to reference material, and conclude from this that timed testing measures nothing more useful than a talent for working under artificial pressure. The observation is accurate as far as it goes, but the conclusion does not follow from it, because it assumes that an examination's purpose is to simulate the conditions of later practice. In fact the timed exam is rarely intended as a rehearsal for professional life; it is intended as a forcing mechanism, a device for compelling a candidate to demonstrate command of material rather than mere familiarity with it.\n\nThere is a meaningful difference between knowing where to find an answer and knowing the answer well enough to produce it without hesitation. A surgeon consulting a reference text mid-operation would be alarming not because reference texts are shameful but because certain knowledge must be so thoroughly internalised that recall is instantaneous, since the situations in which it is needed rarely tolerate delay. The timed exam, at its best, is a proxy for this kind of readiness. It does not claim that every subject requires instant recall in adult life, only that some measure of the depth and fluency of a candidate's understanding is best revealed when she cannot pause to look anything up.\n\nNone of this defends every timed exam as currently constructed. Many such tests reward speed of handwriting or fluency in exam technique as much as they reward understanding, and a candidate who has simply practised more past papers may outperform one with deeper but less rehearsed knowledge. This is a genuine flaw, and one that examination boards ought to take seriously when designing questions and allocating time. But the flaw is a defect in execution, not evidence that timed assessment is conceptually misguided. The proper response is to design exams whose time pressure isolates genuine understanding rather than test-taking fluency, not to abandon the clock altogether on the mistaken assumption that its only function is to imitate a workplace that does not, in fact, need imitating."}, {"id": 688, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What concession does the author make regarding current timed examinations?", "options": {"A": "They should be replaced entirely with untimed coursework assessment.", "B": "Some reward exam technique or handwriting speed over understanding.", "C": "They are impossible to design without favouring wealthier candidates.", "D": "Most candidates find them less stressful than open-book formats."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The author acknowledges that many timed exams reward speed of handwriting or exam technique rather than genuine understanding, allowing a heavily rehearsed candidate to outperform a more knowledgeable one. This is presented as a flaw in execution requiring better design, not as grounds for abandoning timed assessment altogether. The passage never proposes replacing exams with coursework, discusses wealth disparities, or compares stress levels between formats.", "passage_id": "P172", "passage_title": "What the Clock Is For", "passage_text": "Critics of timed examinations frequently observe that the professional world rarely demands that anyone solve a problem in forty-five minutes without access to reference material, and conclude from this that timed testing measures nothing more useful than a talent for working under artificial pressure. The observation is accurate as far as it goes, but the conclusion does not follow from it, because it assumes that an examination's purpose is to simulate the conditions of later practice. In fact the timed exam is rarely intended as a rehearsal for professional life; it is intended as a forcing mechanism, a device for compelling a candidate to demonstrate command of material rather than mere familiarity with it.\n\nThere is a meaningful difference between knowing where to find an answer and knowing the answer well enough to produce it without hesitation. A surgeon consulting a reference text mid-operation would be alarming not because reference texts are shameful but because certain knowledge must be so thoroughly internalised that recall is instantaneous, since the situations in which it is needed rarely tolerate delay. The timed exam, at its best, is a proxy for this kind of readiness. It does not claim that every subject requires instant recall in adult life, only that some measure of the depth and fluency of a candidate's understanding is best revealed when she cannot pause to look anything up.\n\nNone of this defends every timed exam as currently constructed. Many such tests reward speed of handwriting or fluency in exam technique as much as they reward understanding, and a candidate who has simply practised more past papers may outperform one with deeper but less rehearsed knowledge. This is a genuine flaw, and one that examination boards ought to take seriously when designing questions and allocating time. But the flaw is a defect in execution, not evidence that timed assessment is conceptually misguided. The proper response is to design exams whose time pressure isolates genuine understanding rather than test-taking fluency, not to abandon the clock altogether on the mistaken assumption that its only function is to imitate a workplace that does not, in fact, need imitating."}, {"id": 702, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The objection that the benefit based account 'proves too much' suggests that...", "options": {"A": "the account correctly identifies every nation's duties.", "B": "applying the account consistently would generate obligations too broad to guide policy.", "C": "the account wrongly denies that any obligations exist.", "D": "the account only applies to environmental, not institutional, benefits."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The objection points out that if benefiting from historical advantages generates obligation, then almost every comfort a wealthy nation enjoys would count as grounds for some duty, making the resulting obligations impossible to measure or apply consistently. This breadth is treated as a weakness because it leaves policymakers without a clear guide to present day decisions. The criticism therefore targets the practical usefulness of the theory rather than denying that benefit can matter at all.", "passage_id": "P176", "passage_title": "Inherited Debts", "passage_text": "The question of who bears responsibility for climate change, and to what past emissions oblige the present, is rarely settled by appeal to historical fact alone. It is tempting to reason that nations which industrialised earliest, and thereby emitted the greatest cumulative volume of greenhouse gases, owe a debt to those industrialising now, whose growth is constrained by the same atmospheric ceiling that earlier industrialisation helped to lower. Yet this framing, however intuitively appealing, rests on an assumption that responsibility can be transferred across generations as cleanly as a financial liability passes between debtor and creditor. Individuals living in Britain today did not choose to burn coal in 1850, and many will point out that moral responsibility, unlike a mortgage, is not typically thought to attach to people who had no part in the original decision.\n\nA more defensible position distinguishes between blame and obligation. Even if present generations cannot be blamed for emissions produced before their birth, they may still be obliged to act, not because they are guilty, but because they are the beneficiaries of the infrastructure, wealth and technological head start that those emissions purchased. On this view, obligation follows benefit rather than culpability. A person who unknowingly receives stolen goods is not a thief, but few would say she has no duty to return what she holds once she learns its provenance.\n\nCritics of this benefit based account object that it proves too much. Almost every advantage enjoyed by a wealthy nation, from its universities to its legal institutions, can be traced back through some chain of historical injustice or environmental cost. If benefit alone generates obligation, the resulting duties would be so extensive and so difficult to quantify that the theory offers little practical guidance to policymakers deciding, this year, how much a given country should reduce emissions or pay into a climate fund.\n\nWhat the debate reveals, more than any settled answer, is that climate justice cannot be resolved by historical accounting alone. Some further principle, whether of capacity to pay, of urgency, or of shared future risk, must be smuggled in before the ledger of the past can be translated into a demand for action in the present. Until that principle is made explicit, appeals to historical responsibility will continue to persuade some and leave others entirely unmoved."}, {"id": 713, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The passage's discussion of the two arguments for valuing biodiversity is intended chiefly to show that...", "options": {"A": "only the instrumental argument has any practical policy relevance.", "B": "both arguments are ultimately reducible to the same underlying claim.", "C": "cultural artefacts and species should be protected using identical methods.", "D": "the arguments converge in most cases but diverge sharply at the margins."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage shows that the instrumental and non-instrumental arguments for valuing biodiversity usually support the same conservation policies, allowing their differences to be overlooked in ordinary practice. It then identifies a specific case, a species with no ecological function, where the two arguments give opposite recommendations. This is used to show that their apparent agreement breaks down at the margins.", "passage_id": "P179", "passage_title": "Counting What We Lose", "passage_text": "Estimates of the current rate of species extinction vary widely, partly because so much of the world's biodiversity, particularly among insects, fungi and marine invertebrates, has never been comprehensively catalogued in the first place. It is one thing to notice that a species has disappeared once its decline has already attracted scientific attention, and quite another to establish how many species vanished before anyone had described them at all. This asymmetry means that headline figures, however alarming, are likely to understate rather than overstate the true scale of loss, since the undocumented dead cannot appear in any tally.\n\nEven setting aside this measurement difficulty, debates about why biodiversity loss matters tend to divide along a familiar line. One argument treats species as valuable instrumentally, as components of ecosystems that provide services, pollination, water filtration, soil formation, upon which human welfare directly depends. Removing a species is then bad chiefly insofar as it degrades a system that people rely upon, a claim that can in principle be tested by measuring the functional consequences of a given loss.\n\nA second argument treats the loss of a species as a distinct kind of harm regardless of any measurable service it performs, on the grounds that an evolutionary lineage millions of years in the making represents something irreplaceable, comparable in kind to the destruction of a unique cultural artefact rather than to the depletion of an interchangeable resource. This view does not need to show that a beetle's disappearance harms any human interest to regard its extinction as a loss worth mourning and, where possible, preventing.\n\nThese two arguments frequently point toward the same policy, protecting habitat and reducing pressure on vulnerable populations, which allows the disagreement between them to be papered over in practice. But they diverge sharply at the margins. If only instrumental value mattered, a species with no discernible ecological function and no prospect of future utility would warrant no particular effort to save it. The second argument resists this conclusion entirely, and it is at precisely this margin, where a species offers no obvious service to anyone, that the difference between the two positions ceases to be merely theoretical and becomes a live question for conservation policy."}, {"id": 722, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The statistic about fewer than a hundred corporate and state producers is used to", "options": {"A": "prove that individual choices have zero effect on emissions.", "B": "show that government regulation of industry has already failed.", "C": "suggest that emissions data collected by researchers is unreliable.", "D": "support the claim that responsibility for emissions is concentrated."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "This figure is introduced directly after the author argues that emissions are organised by a small number of firms rather than diffuse consumer behaviour. It functions as evidence for the concentration of responsibility rather than as a claim about regulatory failure or data quality. Nothing in the surrounding text suggests the author doubts the reliability of the figure or intends to reduce individual effect to zero.", "passage_id": "P181", "passage_title": "Whose Hands Are Dirty?", "passage_text": "It has become fashionable to calculate one's carbon footprint, to feel a private guilt about the flight taken or the steak eaten, as though the sum of such choices explains the trajectory of the planet's climate. This framing, however comforting to those who wish to believe that virtue is within individual reach, misdescribes the structure of the problem it purports to address.\n\nFossil fuel extraction and combustion are not simply the aggregate of billions of consumer decisions; they are organised, financed and lobbied for by a comparatively small number of firms whose profitability depends on continued demand. A well documented body of research attributes a majority of industrial emissions since the mid twentieth century to fewer than a hundred corporate and state producers. To insist that meaningful change begins at the level of the individual shopping basket is therefore not merely optimistic but, in a subtler way, exculpatory of the actors whose decisions actually determine the scale and pace of extraction.\n\nNone of this absolves the individual entirely. Personal choices, multiplied across a population, do shift markets, and consumer pressure has occasionally forced producers to alter practice. But there is a difference between saying that individual behaviour has some marginal effect and saying that it is the primary lever by which the crisis will be resolved. The latter claim, so often repeated in advertising campaigns for reusable bags and electric vehicles, conveniently shifts the burden of proof and the burden of guilt onto those with the least structural power to alter the system, while leaving intact the regulatory and financial arrangements that permit continued extraction at scale.\n\nThe more honest position is that individual restraint matters mainly as a signal, a way of building the political will needed to support systemic remedies: carbon pricing, the phasing out of subsidies for fossil fuel producers, binding international targets with enforcement mechanisms. Without such structural change, the sum of a million careful consumers will not alter the arithmetic of global emissions, because the institutions that decide how much carbon is extracted and burned will remain, for the most part, untouched by the moral seriousness of individual restraint."}, {"id": 723, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "In the final paragraph, individual restraint is best understood, according to the author, as", "options": {"A": "a means of generating political support for structural reform.", "B": "the most effective way to reduce emissions directly.", "C": "an outdated strategy no longer worth pursuing at all.", "D": "equally important as corporate regulation in solving the crisis."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The author describes restraint as mattering mainly as a signal that helps build the political will needed for structural remedies such as carbon pricing and binding targets. This framing treats personal restraint as instrumental to reform rather than as a direct solution in itself. The passage does not claim restraint is obsolete or that it carries weight equal to regulation, since it insists the arithmetic of emissions depends on institutions rather than consumers.", "passage_id": "P181", "passage_title": "Whose Hands Are Dirty?", "passage_text": "It has become fashionable to calculate one's carbon footprint, to feel a private guilt about the flight taken or the steak eaten, as though the sum of such choices explains the trajectory of the planet's climate. This framing, however comforting to those who wish to believe that virtue is within individual reach, misdescribes the structure of the problem it purports to address.\n\nFossil fuel extraction and combustion are not simply the aggregate of billions of consumer decisions; they are organised, financed and lobbied for by a comparatively small number of firms whose profitability depends on continued demand. A well documented body of research attributes a majority of industrial emissions since the mid twentieth century to fewer than a hundred corporate and state producers. To insist that meaningful change begins at the level of the individual shopping basket is therefore not merely optimistic but, in a subtler way, exculpatory of the actors whose decisions actually determine the scale and pace of extraction.\n\nNone of this absolves the individual entirely. Personal choices, multiplied across a population, do shift markets, and consumer pressure has occasionally forced producers to alter practice. But there is a difference between saying that individual behaviour has some marginal effect and saying that it is the primary lever by which the crisis will be resolved. The latter claim, so often repeated in advertising campaigns for reusable bags and electric vehicles, conveniently shifts the burden of proof and the burden of guilt onto those with the least structural power to alter the system, while leaving intact the regulatory and financial arrangements that permit continued extraction at scale.\n\nThe more honest position is that individual restraint matters mainly as a signal, a way of building the political will needed to support systemic remedies: carbon pricing, the phasing out of subsidies for fossil fuel producers, binding international targets with enforcement mechanisms. Without such structural change, the sum of a million careful consumers will not alter the arithmetic of global emissions, because the institutions that decide how much carbon is extracted and burned will remain, for the most part, untouched by the moral seriousness of individual restraint."}, {"id": 728, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The author's argument would be most weakened by evidence that", "options": {"A": "reactor accidents receive disproportionate media coverage relative to their harm.", "B": "coal mining causes more deaths per unit of energy than nuclear power.", "C": "nuclear waste storage technology continues to improve over time.", "D": "battery storage has become cheap and abundant enough to replace baseline power needs."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The author's case for nuclear power depends heavily on the claim that battery storage is currently too expensive to bridge the gaps left by intermittent renewables. If storage became cheap and abundant enough to fully meet baseline power needs, the central justification for accepting nuclear risk would largely disappear. The other options are consistent with, or actively support, the author's existing argument rather than undermining it.", "passage_id": "P182", "passage_title": "The Reactor and the Reckoning", "passage_text": "Opposition to nuclear power among environmentalists has long rested on a set of associations, meltdown, waste, weapons proliferation, that sit uneasily with the calm statistical case for its safety. Compared with coal, gas or even the mining required for solar panel components, nuclear generation produces remarkably little harm per unit of electricity delivered, whether measured in deaths, land use or lifecycle emissions. Yet the public conversation about nuclear energy is rarely conducted in these comparative terms; it is conducted in the shadow of a small number of accidents whose vividness has outpaced their statistical significance.\n\nThis is not to say that scepticism about nuclear power is baseless. Construction costs have a poor record of staying within budget or schedule, and the political will required to site new reactors, together with the decades needed to bring them online, sits awkwardly with the urgency of the climate timeline. A reactor commissioned today may not deliver a single watt before the middle of the century in some jurisdictions, by which point cheaper and faster renewable alternatives may have closed much of the gap nuclear was meant to fill.\n\nThe more serious case for nuclear power, then, is not that it is flawless but that intermittent renewables, however rapidly they are deployed, still require a reliable baseline of power for the periods when the wind does not blow and the sun does not shine. Battery storage at the scale required to bridge such gaps remains, for now, prohibitively expensive and resource intensive. Nuclear power, whatever its financial and temporal costs, offers a low carbon source of exactly this kind of steady, weather independent generation, one that does not depend on the accident of a calm evening or a cloudy afternoon to keep hospitals lit and factories running.\n\nTo dismiss nuclear power on the grounds of its association with catastrophe, then, is to mistake a psychological reaction for an engineering judgement. The rational question is not whether nuclear power carries risk, all energy generation does, but whether its risks, properly weighed against those of the alternatives and against the risk of continued fossil fuel dependence, are worth accepting in the service of a rapid and reliable transition away from carbon."}, {"id": 733, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "The comparison to a luxury emission such as a pleasure flight is used to", "options": {"A": "show that all meat consumption is exactly equivalent to air travel in emissions.", "B": "prove that flying is more environmentally harmful than eating meat.", "C": "illustrate the reasoning of those who consider meat consumption morally indefensible.", "D": "suggest that both flying and eating meat should be banned by law."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The comparison is introduced right after the author describes those who conclude meat eating is wrong, and it mirrors the logic of condemning an unnecessary, avoidable contribution to environmental harm. It functions as an illustration of that group's reasoning rather than a factual claim about relative emissions levels. The passage never proposes legal bans, and it does not equate all meat consumption with air travel, since it later complicates that blanket view.", "passage_id": "P184", "passage_title": "What's on the Plate", "passage_text": "Livestock farming occupies a disproportionate share of the environmental ledger. It is responsible, by most credible estimates, for somewhere between a tenth and a fifth of global greenhouse gas emissions, depending on how land use change is counted, and it consumes a share of fresh water and arable land that vastly exceeds its contribution to human caloric intake. Beef in particular is a remarkably inefficient way of turning sunlight, via grass and grain, into food energy, requiring many times the land and water of an equivalent quantity of plant protein.\n\nFrom these facts, some draw a straightforward moral conclusion: that eating meat, or at least eating it at anything like current levels, is not merely imprudent but wrong, in roughly the way that any needless and substantial contribution to planetary harm is wrong. The comparison sometimes offered is to a luxury emission, a transatlantic flight taken for pleasure rather than necessity, which few would defend once its environmental cost is made explicit.\n\nThis argument, though forceful, moves rather quickly past a genuine complication: not all meat production is equal, and not all land suited to grazing is suited to growing crops. Much of the world's pastureland is marginal, too dry, too steep or too poor in soil quality to support arable farming, yet perfectly capable of supporting grazing animals. In such regions, livestock may convert otherwise unusable land into a source of protein that could not be produced by any plant based alternative grown on that same land. The blanket claim that meat consumption is environmentally indefensible therefore risks conflating an intensively farmed feedlot animal, fed on grain that could have fed people directly, with an animal raised on land that could feed no one at all if left to crops.\n\nNone of this rescues industrial meat production as currently practised in wealthy countries, where the overwhelming majority of livestock is grain fed and land use is far from marginal. But it does suggest that the ethical verdict on eating meat cannot be delivered in the abstract, only in light of how, and where, a particular animal was raised, and by asking that question the debate becomes considerably harder to settle with a single slogan."}, {"id": 738, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase proves less than it appears to suggests that the opponents' objection is", "options": {"A": "initially persuasive but ultimately insufficient to defeat the case for reparations.", "B": "entirely without merit from the very outset of the argument.", "C": "stronger than the author's own argument for reparations.", "D": "based on a straightforward factual error about historical emissions."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The author concedes the objection has some force before stating it proves less than it appears to, signalling that the objection carries surface plausibility but does not ultimately succeed. This is confirmed when the author goes on to reframe reparations around unjust enrichment rather than blame. The passage does not dismiss the objection as baseless, treat it as stronger than the reparations case, or attribute it to a factual error.", "passage_id": "P185", "passage_title": "Who Pays for the Damage", "passage_text": "The case for climate reparations rests on a deceptively simple observation: the nations that industrialised earliest, and therefore emitted the most carbon over the longest period, are largely not the nations now suffering the earliest and most severe consequences of a warming climate. Low lying island states, drought stricken regions of the Sahel, flood prone deltas in South Asia, these areas have contributed a negligible fraction of cumulative global emissions yet face displacement, crop failure and the loss of habitable land on a timescale far more urgent than that facing the wealthy economies whose historical emissions did the most to cause the crisis.\n\nOpponents of reparations argue that it is unfair to hold present day citizens of industrialised nations morally and financially liable for emissions produced by their ancestors, often before the harms of carbon dioxide were scientifically understood at all. A taxpayer in a wealthy country today, on this view, did not choose to industrialise using coal in the nineteenth century and should not be billed for a decision made by people long dead who could not have known its consequences.\n\nThis objection has some force but proves less than it appears to. Reparations, as usually proposed, are not primarily a claim about individual moral guilt but about the transfer of wealth that was itself generated, in substantial part, by the very activity now causing harm. Wealthy nations did not merely emit carbon; they built the industrial and financial advantage they retain today partly on the back of that emission, and their citizens continue to benefit from infrastructure, technology and accumulated capital that resulted from it. The claim is closer to one about unjust enrichment than about personal culpability for a choice never made.\n\nWhether such a claim justifies the specific mechanisms so far proposed, direct payments, technology transfer, debt forgiveness, is a separate question from whether some transfer is owed at all. But the ignorance defence, however emotionally persuasive, addresses only the question of blame, not the question of who has ended up holding the benefit and who has ended up holding the cost, and it is this second question that any serious settlement will eventually have to confront."}, {"id": 740, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Which of the following, if true, would most strengthen the opponents' objection described in the second paragraph?", "options": {"A": "wealthy nations' infrastructure was built substantially using profits from carbon intensive industry.", "B": "low lying island states have contributed a negligible share of global emissions.", "C": "wealthy nations' current prosperity depends entirely on factors unrelated to historical industrialisation.", "D": "technology transfer would help poorer nations adapt to climate change."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The author's rebuttal depends on wealthy nations still benefiting from advantages built through historical emissions, so evidence that current prosperity is unconnected to that industrialisation would undercut the unjust enrichment argument and leave the ignorance defence standing. Option A actually reinforces the author's rebuttal rather than the opponents' objection. Options B and D are consistent with the passage's existing case for reparations rather than a challenge to it.", "passage_id": "P185", "passage_title": "Who Pays for the Damage", "passage_text": "The case for climate reparations rests on a deceptively simple observation: the nations that industrialised earliest, and therefore emitted the most carbon over the longest period, are largely not the nations now suffering the earliest and most severe consequences of a warming climate. Low lying island states, drought stricken regions of the Sahel, flood prone deltas in South Asia, these areas have contributed a negligible fraction of cumulative global emissions yet face displacement, crop failure and the loss of habitable land on a timescale far more urgent than that facing the wealthy economies whose historical emissions did the most to cause the crisis.\n\nOpponents of reparations argue that it is unfair to hold present day citizens of industrialised nations morally and financially liable for emissions produced by their ancestors, often before the harms of carbon dioxide were scientifically understood at all. A taxpayer in a wealthy country today, on this view, did not choose to industrialise using coal in the nineteenth century and should not be billed for a decision made by people long dead who could not have known its consequences.\n\nThis objection has some force but proves less than it appears to. Reparations, as usually proposed, are not primarily a claim about individual moral guilt but about the transfer of wealth that was itself generated, in substantial part, by the very activity now causing harm. Wealthy nations did not merely emit carbon; they built the industrial and financial advantage they retain today partly on the back of that emission, and their citizens continue to benefit from infrastructure, technology and accumulated capital that resulted from it. The claim is closer to one about unjust enrichment than about personal culpability for a choice never made.\n\nWhether such a claim justifies the specific mechanisms so far proposed, direct payments, technology transfer, debt forgiveness, is a separate question from whether some transfer is owed at all. But the ignorance defence, however emotionally persuasive, addresses only the question of blame, not the question of who has ended up holding the benefit and who has ended up holding the cost, and it is this second question that any serious settlement will eventually have to confront."}, {"id": 743, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the example of the European Union's early experience with cap-and-trade illustrate?", "options": {"A": "That free allocation of permits can undermine the intended incentive of the scheme.", "B": "That legislated tax rates are always immune to political interference.", "C": "That cap-and-trade schemes raise more predictable revenue than carbon taxes.", "D": "That emissions ceilings are impossible to enforce once trading begins."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage uses the European Union's experience to show that giving away permits for free can flood the market and weaken the price signal meant to discourage emissions. It does not claim that legislated tax rates are entirely free from political pressure, since the passage argues both instruments are vulnerable to capture. Nor is the example about revenue predictability or about whether ceilings can be enforced, both of which are separate points made elsewhere in the passage.", "passage_id": "P186", "passage_title": "Pricing Carbon: Two Instruments Compared", "passage_text": "Two policy instruments dominate contemporary debate over how governments might curb greenhouse gas emissions: the carbon tax and the cap-and-trade scheme. Both operate on the same underlying premise, that the atmosphere's capacity to absorb carbon dioxide is a scarce resource and that market mechanisms, properly designed, can allocate that scarcity more efficiently than direct regulation. Yet the two diverge sharply in what they hold fixed and what they leave to fluctuate, a distinction that proponents on each side treat as decisive.\n\nA carbon tax fixes the price of emitting a tonne of carbon dioxide and allows the quantity emitted to respond to that price; a cap-and-trade scheme fixes the quantity of permitted emissions and allows the price of permits to respond to demand. Economists who favour the tax argue that businesses need predictable costs to plan long-term investment in cleaner technology, and that a stable, legislated price achieves this in a way that a fluctuating permit market cannot. Volatility, on this view, is not a neutral feature of markets but an active deterrent to the very capital expenditure that decarbonisation requires.\n\nAdvocates of cap-and-trade respond that certainty of price is the wrong thing to prize, given that what actually matters for the climate is the total volume of emissions released, not the cost per unit. A tax, however well calibrated, is a guess about what price will produce the desired reduction, and guesses can be wrong in either direction. A cap, by contrast, guarantees the environmental outcome directly, since the number of permits issued is the ceiling on emissions, whatever price emerges from trading among firms that hold them.\n\nBoth camps concede a further complication. A tax raises revenue predictably, which governments may recycle into rebates or green investment, whereas a cap-and-trade scheme's revenue depends on how permits are allocated, whether auctioned or given away, and this allocation has repeatedly proven vulnerable to lobbying by incumbent polluters seeking free permits. Critics of cap-and-trade point to the European Union's early experience, in which an oversupply of free permits depressed the carbon price for years and blunted the scheme's incentive effect almost entirely, a failure that a legislated tax rate would not have permitted, since the rate does not depend on a secondary market's equilibrium.\n\nNeither instrument, then, is immune to political capture; the question is only where that capture is likely to do the most damage, to the price signal or to the emissions ceiling itself."}, {"id": 748, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "Describing farmland as treated by some advocates as 'a blank canvas' serves mainly to", "options": {"A": "suggest that farmland has no ecological value worth preserving.", "B": "convey the criticism that rewilding overlooks farmland's existing social and economic life.", "C": "praise rewilding advocates for their creative vision of the countryside.", "D": "indicate that farmland is physically empty of any human activity."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The phrase is used by critics to capture their complaint that rewilding proposals can treat farmland as though it were unused and available for a fresh start, ignoring the working communities and economies already present there. It is not a comment on farmland's ecological value, nor is it offered as praise for creative vision. The phrase is figurative rather than a literal claim that farmland is empty of people.", "passage_id": "P187", "passage_title": "Rewilding and the Claims of Farmland", "passage_text": "Rewilding, the deliberate withdrawal of human management from a landscape so that natural processes can resume, has moved from a fringe conservationist idea to a mainstream policy proposal within a generation. Its advocates argue that centuries of agricultural intensification have left many rural landscapes ecologically impoverished, and that restoring apex predators, natural flooding patterns and mixed woodland can reverse biodiversity loss more effectively than piecemeal conservation of individual species. The difficulty is that the land available for such restoration is rarely empty; it is usually farmed, and often has been for generations.\n\nOpponents of large-scale rewilding do not typically dispute its ecological logic so much as its social cost. Upland and marginal farms, they note, already operate on thin margins, and many communities depend on farming not merely for income but for a continuity of identity built up over long family histories. Removing land from production, even land of marginal agricultural value, can hollow out the rural economy that depends on it, from feed merchants to livestock auctions to the schools that keep villages viable. Rewilding's champions, on this view, treat farmland as a blank canvas rather than as a working, populated landscape with its own claims to legitimacy.\n\nRewilding advocates reply that this framing understates the extent to which current agricultural subsidy already amounts to public underwriting of an unprofitable activity, particularly on the poorest upland soils, where output per hectare is lowest and environmental damage, through overgrazing and soil erosion, is often highest. If public money is being spent regardless, they argue, it should be redirected toward outcomes, such as flood mitigation, carbon storage and biodiversity, that the market does not otherwise reward, rather than toward propping up marginal production that would not survive without support.\n\nA further complication is that rewilding and farming are not always in zero-sum competition. Silvopasture, mixed hedgerow management and the reintroduction of beavers to manage watercourses have all been shown to coexist with continued grazing, sometimes improving yields by reducing flooding and soil loss downstream. Yet these hybrid approaches require exactly the kind of sustained investment and technical support that wholesale withdrawal of subsidy would make harder to fund, suggesting that the sharpest disagreements are less about whether restoration and farming can combine, and more about who bears the transition cost while both models are tested."}, {"id": 753, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the passage's main objection to identifying population growth as the underlying driver of environmental crisis?", "options": {"A": "That global population is not actually increasing in any region.", "B": "That environmental crisis is entirely unrelated to how many people exist.", "C": "That per capita emissions data does not exist for most regions.", "D": "That emissions are driven far more by consumption levels than by population size alone."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage argues that emissions correlate far more closely with consumption patterns than with population size, since regions with the fastest projected population growth currently contribute comparatively little to cumulative emissions. It does not claim population is not growing, nor that population and environmental outcomes are entirely unrelated, since the final paragraph concedes population still matters at the margins. The passage does not suggest per capita data is unavailable; it relies on such data to make its case.", "passage_id": "P189", "passage_title": "Population Growth and the Environmental Crisis", "passage_text": "It has become common, in popular discussion of environmental decline, to identify population growth as the underlying driver of the crisis, on the reasoning that more people must inevitably mean more consumption, more emissions and more pressure on finite resources. The argument has an evident arithmetic appeal, yet it obscures a distribution of responsibility that is far less even than a simple headcount would suggest.\n\nGlobal data on per capita emissions reveal enormous disparities between regions with comparable or even declining populations. The wealthiest tenth of the world's population accounts for a share of consumption based emissions vastly disproportionate to its numbers, while regions projected to see the fastest population growth over coming decades, largely across parts of sub-Saharan Africa, currently contribute a small fraction of cumulative historical emissions. If population size were the decisive variable, one would expect emissions to track population growth closely across regions, yet the opposite pattern often holds, with some of the lowest per capita emitters experiencing the highest projected growth.\n\nCritics of the population framing argue that it functions, whether intentionally or not, to relocate blame for a crisis substantially caused by high consuming nations onto the reproductive choices of poorer ones, choices that are themselves shaped by factors, including access to education and healthcare, that these countries have had comparatively little power to influence. There is also a historical dimension to this unease, since concern about population growth in the developing world has, at various points, shaded into policies that curtailed reproductive freedom, a legacy that makes many wary of reviving population as an explanatory framework without careful qualification.\n\nNone of this establishes that population is wholly irrelevant. A larger population does, all else being equal, place additional demand on food systems, water supplies and land, and this demand does not vanish simply because it is unevenly distributed across income groups. The more defensible position is not that population is irrelevant but that it is a poor single variable to isolate, since its environmental effect is so heavily mediated by consumption patterns that a doubling of population among the world's lowest consumers could leave total emissions barely altered, while comparable growth among the highest consumers would not. Attending to consumption without attending to its distribution, in other words, risks replacing one oversimplified variable with another."}, {"id": 762, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "How does the passage respond to the objection that GDP was never meant to measure welfare?", "options": {"A": "It rejects the objection outright as historically inaccurate.", "B": "It accepts the objection fully and abandons its criticism of GDP.", "C": "It concedes the point but argues this misses the real complaint about GDP's misuse.", "D": "It ignores the objection because it is irrelevant to the argument."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage states the defence has some force, granting that GDP was indeed designed for a narrower purpose. It then redirects attention to the real issue, which is that this narrow tool has been allowed to substitute for a genuine measure of wellbeing in practice. This is a concession followed by a reframing, not an outright rejection or an abandonment of the critique.", "passage_id": "P191", "passage_title": "Beyond the Ledger", "passage_text": "Gross domestic product was devised as a wartime accounting tool, a rough tally of output intended to help governments plan the allocation of scarce materials. That it has since become the principal yardstick by which nations judge their own success is an accident of history rather than a considered decision, and the accident has proved costly. A country that clears an ancient forest for timber records a rise in GDP twice over, once when the timber is sold and again when the cleared land is farmed, while the loss of the forest itself, its capacity to store carbon, regulate rainfall and shelter species, appears nowhere in the accounts. The ledger counts the felling as gain and is silent about the felled.\n\nDefenders of the measure argue that GDP was never meant to capture welfare, only economic activity, and that critics who fault it for failing to measure happiness or ecological health are attacking a straw man. This defence has some force, yet it evades the deeper complaint, which is not that GDP measures the wrong thing but that governments and voters have allowed it to stand in for the right thing. A statistic designed for a narrow purpose has, through repetition and convenience, acquired the authority of a verdict on national wellbeing, and policy is shaped accordingly. Ministers are rewarded for growth even where that growth draws down a stock of natural capital that cannot be replenished within a human lifetime.\n\nSome economists propose supplementing GDP with a parallel account that would subtract the depletion of forests, fisheries and soil from the headline figure, producing what might be called a genuine progress indicator. Sceptics object that any such account requires placing a monetary value on things that were never priced by markets, a task so laden with contestable assumptions that the resulting number would command no more confidence than the guesses of a committee. This is a fair caution, but it is not a reason for inaction. An imperfect corrective that forces policymakers to confront the question of depletion is preferable to a perfect silence that allows them to ignore it indefinitely. The choice is not between a flawed measure and a flawless one, but between a flawed measure and none at all."}, {"id": 769, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the passage's central argument about ranking competing claims to forest land?", "options": {"A": "Legal title should always take precedence because it is the most objective standard.", "B": "Indigenous communities should be granted formal title in all cases.", "C": "Conservationists have the strongest claim because their concern is universal.", "D": "Any single ranking principle unfairly privileges one claimant group over the others."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage examines three possible ranking principles in turn, legal title, economic productivity and ecological importance, and shows that each one smuggles in a bias favouring a particular party before the argument even begins. This demonstrates that no single principle offers a neutral resolution to the conflict. The passage does not endorse any one claimant's priority as correct, including legal title or indigenous title.", "passage_id": "P193", "passage_title": "Whose Trees Are They", "passage_text": "Every hectare of standing rainforest is claimed, at least in principle, by several parties at once. A national government asserts sovereignty over the land within its borders and treats the timber and the minerals beneath it as assets to be developed for the benefit of citizens who may never see the forest themselves. A logging or agribusiness concession holder asserts a contractual right, often purchased at considerable expense, to clear and use the land for a fixed term. Indigenous communities, frequently without formal title recognised by national law, assert a claim rooted in generations of continuous occupation and a relationship to the land that predates the state itself. Conservationists, speaking for no human claimant at all, assert that the forest's value as a carbon sink and a reservoir of biodiversity accrues to the whole of humanity and to generations not yet born.\n\nThese claims cannot all be honoured simultaneously, and the temptation is to resolve the conflict by ranking them according to some prior principle, such as legal title, economic productivity or ecological importance. Yet each ranking smuggles in an assumption that favours one party over the others before the argument has properly begun. To rank formal legal title first is to entrench the historical injustice by which indigenous occupation was never converted into title in the first place. To rank economic productivity first is to treat land that has stood undisturbed for millennia as though it had produced nothing merely because its yield cannot be sold at market. To rank global ecological importance first is to ask the poorest communities living within the forest's boundary to forgo development for the benefit of distant populations who will bear none of the immediate cost of that restraint.\n\nWhat follows is not that competing claims are equally valid in every instance, but that any resolution reached without acknowledging the legitimacy of all four perspectives will be experienced by someone as expropriation rather than compromise, and will therefore be resisted, litigated or simply ignored on the ground regardless of what is decided in a distant capital. A durable settlement, in other words, is likely to require some form of negotiated accommodation among the four claimants rather than a verdict handed down from above."}, {"id": 780, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What is the effect of the phrase \"the precise language of the convention\" in the first paragraph?", "options": {"A": "It implies that the convention has been recently rewritten to include climate displacement.", "B": "It suggests that the convention is deliberately vague on the question of environmental displacement.", "C": "It emphasises that the legal exclusion of environmental migrants follows strictly from the wording of the law itself.", "D": "It indicates that the author believes the convention is poorly drafted and unenforceable."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "By pointing to the precise language of the convention, the passage underscores that the exclusion of environmentally displaced people is not an oversight or ambiguity but a direct consequence of how the law is worded. This reinforces the earlier claim that such people are, in exact legal terms, simply not refugees at all. The phrase signals precision rather than vagueness, and nothing suggests recent rewriting or a judgment that the law is unenforceable.", "passage_id": "P195", "passage_title": "The Rising Tide's Neighbours", "passage_text": "The term climate refugee has no settled legal meaning, and this absence is not a mere technicality. International refugee law, framed in the aftermath of the Second World War, protects those who flee persecution on grounds of race, religion, nationality, political opinion or membership of a particular social group. A farmer whose land has turned to salt because of rising seas, or a family displaced when a glacier-fed river runs dry, fits none of these categories, however total the loss of home may be, because no one is persecuting them in the sense the law requires. They are, in the precise language of the convention, simply not refugees at all, and the receiving country therefore owes them nothing under the instrument most commonly invoked on behalf of the displaced.\n\nSome argue that this gap should be closed by treaty, extending refugee status or an equivalent protection to those displaced by environmental collapse. Others resist this extension on the grounds that it would strain a system already under considerable political pressure, diluting protections currently owed to the persecuted by adding a vastly larger and more diffuse category of claimant, since gradual environmental decline affects millions rather than the comparatively contained populations displaced by specific conflicts. There is also a harder question lurking beneath the legal one: many of the nations whose emissions have contributed most to the warming driving such displacement are not the nations from which the displaced originate, and are frequently the very nations debating whether to receive them.\n\nThis asymmetry between contribution and consequence is not new in international affairs, but it is rarely so starkly measurable as it is here, where the tonnage of historical emissions can be tabulated by country. A receiving nation might reasonably ask why it should bear responsibility for a crisis produced elsewhere; the displaced might reasonably reply that the crisis was produced disproportionately by the very nations now weighing whether to let them in, and that the absence of a persecuting government does not make the loss of a homeland any less complete. Whatever settlement eventually emerges, it will have to reconcile these competing claims rather than pretend that the legal silence surrounding them makes the underlying question disappear."}, {"id": 783, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What common ground does the passage identify between supporters and critics of renewable subsidies?", "options": {"A": "Both agree that carbon taxes are the superior policy tool.", "B": "Both agree that early adopters deserve permanent reward.", "C": "Both agree subsidies were meant to be temporary, not permanent.", "D": "Both agree that public opinion should determine energy policy."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The final paragraph states that both sides agree, when pressed, that subsidies were always intended as a bridge rather than a lasting feature of energy markets. Their disagreement is over the length of that bridge and who decides it has ended, not over the desirability of a carbon tax or public opinion's role. Reward for early adopters is mentioned only as one side's defence, not as shared ground between both camps.", "passage_id": "P196", "passage_title": "The Hidden Price of Green Subsidies", "passage_text": "Governments across Europe have spent the past two decades channelling public money into wind, solar and biomass, justifying the expense as an unavoidable correction to a market that ignores the true cost of burning fossil fuels. The reasoning runs as follows: carbon emissions impose costs on third parties, in the form of flood damage, crop failure and rising sea levels, none of which the polluter pays for directly. A subsidy to cleaner alternatives, so the argument goes, merely nudges prices back toward what they would be if those hidden costs were reflected honestly.\n\nCritics of this reasoning do not usually dispute that pollution has costs. Their objection is narrower and, in some ways, more troubling: subsidies do not simply correct a market failure, they replace one distortion with another, and the replacement is harder to unwind. A tax on carbon rises and falls with the polluting activity itself, and can in principle be calibrated to the actual damage done. A subsidy, once granted to a favoured technology, tends to persist long after the market conditions that justified it have changed, because an entire industry of investors, manufacturers and lobbyists has grown up around the promise of continued support. Withdrawing it becomes politically costly in a way that raising a tax on an unpopular activity rarely is.\n\nThere is also the question of who benefits. Subsidies for rooftop solar panels or electric vehicles have disproportionately rewarded households that could already afford the upfront cost of the technology, while the general taxpayer, including those too poor to install panels or buy a new car, has footed much of the bill through levies on energy bills or general taxation. Defenders reply that early adopters bear the risk of unproven technology and deserve some reward for lowering costs for everyone else through economies of scale, a pattern seen previously with solar panel manufacturing itself.\n\nWhat both sides tend to agree on, if pressed, is that the current arrangement was never intended as a permanent feature of energy markets but as a bridge to a point at which clean technologies could compete unaided. The disagreement is over how long that bridge should be, and over who gets to decide when it has been crossed, questions that are political as much as they are economic."}, {"id": 784, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'footed much of the bill' is used in the passage to convey what tone regarding ordinary taxpayers?", "options": {"A": "Detached amusement at the taxpayer's ignorance.", "B": "Approval of a fair and necessary contribution.", "C": "Neutral description of an unavoidable economic fact.", "D": "Quiet sympathy for an unfairly shared burden."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The phrase appears immediately after noting that poorer households could not benefit from the subsidised technology yet still contributed to its cost, framing the arrangement as lopsided rather than merely factual. This wording carries a mild sense of unfairness rather than approval or amusement. A purely neutral description would not have been paired so closely with the contrast between wealthier beneficiaries and burdened taxpayers.", "passage_id": "P196", "passage_title": "The Hidden Price of Green Subsidies", "passage_text": "Governments across Europe have spent the past two decades channelling public money into wind, solar and biomass, justifying the expense as an unavoidable correction to a market that ignores the true cost of burning fossil fuels. The reasoning runs as follows: carbon emissions impose costs on third parties, in the form of flood damage, crop failure and rising sea levels, none of which the polluter pays for directly. A subsidy to cleaner alternatives, so the argument goes, merely nudges prices back toward what they would be if those hidden costs were reflected honestly.\n\nCritics of this reasoning do not usually dispute that pollution has costs. Their objection is narrower and, in some ways, more troubling: subsidies do not simply correct a market failure, they replace one distortion with another, and the replacement is harder to unwind. A tax on carbon rises and falls with the polluting activity itself, and can in principle be calibrated to the actual damage done. A subsidy, once granted to a favoured technology, tends to persist long after the market conditions that justified it have changed, because an entire industry of investors, manufacturers and lobbyists has grown up around the promise of continued support. Withdrawing it becomes politically costly in a way that raising a tax on an unpopular activity rarely is.\n\nThere is also the question of who benefits. Subsidies for rooftop solar panels or electric vehicles have disproportionately rewarded households that could already afford the upfront cost of the technology, while the general taxpayer, including those too poor to install panels or buy a new car, has footed much of the bill through levies on energy bills or general taxation. Defenders reply that early adopters bear the risk of unproven technology and deserve some reward for lowering costs for everyone else through economies of scale, a pattern seen previously with solar panel manufacturing itself.\n\nWhat both sides tend to agree on, if pressed, is that the current arrangement was never intended as a permanent feature of energy markets but as a bridge to a point at which clean technologies could compete unaided. The disagreement is over how long that bridge should be, and over who gets to decide when it has been crossed, questions that are political as much as they are economic."}, {"id": 787, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "According to the passage, what trade-off is associated with tradeable catch quotas?", "options": {"A": "They restore fish stocks quickly but raise consumer prices sharply.", "B": "They eliminate illegal fishing but reduce the total global catch.", "C": "They satisfy large operators but ignore the health of fish stocks.", "D": "They improve fishery health while disadvantaging small scale fishers."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage states that tradeable quotas give fishers a long term stake in healthy stocks while also tending to concentrate ownership among large operators, squeezing out smaller communities lacking capital. This describes an ecological benefit paired with a social cost, matching the trade-off framed at the end of the passage. The other options invent outcomes, such as eliminating illegal fishing or ignoring stock health, that the passage never claims.", "passage_id": "P197", "passage_title": "Empty Nets and the Logic of the Commons", "passage_text": "The concept of the tragedy of the commons was popularised to describe a herder who adds one more animal to a shared pasture, reasoning that the individual benefit of the extra beast is his alone, while the cost of overgrazing is shared among everyone. Each herder follows the same logic, and the pasture is eventually ruined for all. Fishing fleets operating in international waters present a strikingly similar problem, though the pasture in question is largely invisible and its depletion far harder to notice until stocks have already collapsed.\n\nNo single trawler owner benefits from restraint if rivals continue to fish without limit, since the fish left behind will simply be caught by someone else the following season. This creates an incentive structure in which rational actors, each pursuing an entirely sensible short term interest, collectively produce an outcome that none of them would have chosen: a depleted fishery that supports far fewer boats, and far fewer livelihoods, than a properly managed one would.\n\nQuotas assigned by international bodies are the most common remedy, yet they suffer from an enforcement problem that domestic pastures do not share. A national government can fence a common field or prosecute a trespassing herder with relative ease. Policing thousands of square miles of open ocean against vessels registered in dozens of jurisdictions, some of which have little incentive to cooperate, is a different order of difficulty altogether, and illegal catches are widely believed to be underreported by a substantial margin.\n\nSome economists argue that the deeper solution lies not in policing but in property rights: granting individual fishers or companies a tradeable share of the total allowable catch gives each of them a long term stake in the health of the fishery, since the value of their share depends on stocks remaining healthy for years to come. Critics of this approach point out that tradeable quotas tend to concentrate ownership in the hands of large operators who can afford to buy up smaller shares, squeezing out small scale fishing communities that lack the capital to compete, even as the biological problem of overfishing is gradually brought under control."}, {"id": 788, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The description of the ocean's depletion as 'largely invisible' mainly serves to emphasize what?", "options": {"A": "How difficult it is to recognize the problem before it is severe.", "B": "How little scientific data exists about fish populations.", "C": "How unconcerned fishing communities are about stock decline.", "D": "How effective quotas have been at concealing overfishing."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The phrase is immediately followed by the observation that depletion is far harder to notice until stocks have already collapsed, linking invisibility to delayed recognition of the problem. This framing highlights a practical obstacle to early intervention rather than a claim about data scarcity or community attitudes. Nothing in the passage suggests quotas are designed or used to conceal overfishing.", "passage_id": "P197", "passage_title": "Empty Nets and the Logic of the Commons", "passage_text": "The concept of the tragedy of the commons was popularised to describe a herder who adds one more animal to a shared pasture, reasoning that the individual benefit of the extra beast is his alone, while the cost of overgrazing is shared among everyone. Each herder follows the same logic, and the pasture is eventually ruined for all. Fishing fleets operating in international waters present a strikingly similar problem, though the pasture in question is largely invisible and its depletion far harder to notice until stocks have already collapsed.\n\nNo single trawler owner benefits from restraint if rivals continue to fish without limit, since the fish left behind will simply be caught by someone else the following season. This creates an incentive structure in which rational actors, each pursuing an entirely sensible short term interest, collectively produce an outcome that none of them would have chosen: a depleted fishery that supports far fewer boats, and far fewer livelihoods, than a properly managed one would.\n\nQuotas assigned by international bodies are the most common remedy, yet they suffer from an enforcement problem that domestic pastures do not share. A national government can fence a common field or prosecute a trespassing herder with relative ease. Policing thousands of square miles of open ocean against vessels registered in dozens of jurisdictions, some of which have little incentive to cooperate, is a different order of difficulty altogether, and illegal catches are widely believed to be underreported by a substantial margin.\n\nSome economists argue that the deeper solution lies not in policing but in property rights: granting individual fishers or companies a tradeable share of the total allowable catch gives each of them a long term stake in the health of the fishery, since the value of their share depends on stocks remaining healthy for years to come. Critics of this approach point out that tradeable quotas tend to concentrate ownership in the hands of large operators who can afford to buy up smaller shares, squeezing out small scale fishing communities that lack the capital to compete, even as the biological problem of overfishing is gradually brought under control."}, {"id": 796, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What tone does the final paragraph adopt toward assigning blame entirely to one side?", "options": {"A": "Sympathetic, since simplicity aids public understanding.", "B": "Approving, since one party is clearly more culpable.", "C": "Critical, viewing it as sacrificing accuracy for simplicity.", "D": "Indifferent, treating the question as unimportant."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The final paragraph states that the compromise position sacrifices rhetorical simplicity but gains accuracy, implying that assigning blame entirely to one party requires ignoring complicating evidence. This framing treats one sided blame as a deliberate simplification bought at the cost of truth. The tone is neither sympathetic to simplicity nor indifferent, and it does not endorse one party as clearly more culpable in isolation.", "passage_id": "P199", "passage_title": "Whose Fault Is the Smoke: Producer or Purchaser", "passage_text": "A widely cited statistic holds that a small number of large companies are responsible for the majority of global industrial emissions, a fact frequently invoked to argue that responsibility for climate change rests overwhelmingly with corporations rather than the individuals who buy their products. Those sympathetic to this framing point out that consumers rarely have a genuine alternative: a commuter without access to public transport, a family unable to afford an electric vehicle, or a shopper confronted only with plastic packaged goods on the supermarket shelf cannot meaningfully be said to have chosen the polluting option freely.\n\nYet the corporate emissions figure conceals as much as it reveals. Those companies are counted as responsible for emissions released when their products, fuel, electricity, cement, are burned or used by someone else entirely, often the very consumers whose choices are being defended. A power station generates emissions because households and businesses demand electricity, and an oil company extracts crude because drivers fill their tanks; attributing the resulting emissions solely to the producer, while true in a narrow accounting sense, obscures the demand that makes production profitable in the first place. If every customer of a given refinery vanished overnight, the refinery would close for want of buyers long before any regulator forced it to, a fact the producer focused framing tends to leave unexamined.\n\nThis does not mean the two sides of the ledger are equally culpable. Corporations possess capital, expertise and lobbying influence that individual consumers plainly lack, and they have in many documented cases used that influence to delay regulation, fund misleading research, or resist the introduction of viable low carbon alternatives, actions no individual consumer could replicate regardless of their intentions. A more defensible position, then, treats the producer and consumer as jointly responsible but not equally so, with corporations bearing greater responsibility for shaping the choices available and greater capacity to change them, while consumers retain a narrower responsibility for the choices they make within that constrained set of options.\n\nWhat this compromise position sacrifices in rhetorical simplicity, it arguably gains in accuracy, since assigning blame entirely to one party or the other requires ignoring evidence that complicates the preferred conclusion."}, {"id": 797, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the conservationist argument for reintroducing apex predators, as described in the passage?", "options": {"A": "Predators restore ecological balance disrupted by earlier human hunting.", "B": "Predators generate more tourism revenue than livestock farming.", "C": "Predators reduce the need for compensation schemes over time.", "D": "Predators were never actually eradicated from most landscapes."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage states that conservationists present reintroduction as ecological repair, restoring a balance disturbed by earlier human hunting, with predators controlling herbivore populations and triggering wider ecological benefits. This is the specific claim made in the opening paragraph. The other options describe details raised elsewhere, such as tourism revenue, or contradict the passage's clear statement that predators were deliberately eradicated in the past.", "passage_id": "P200", "passage_title": "Bringing Back the Wolf", "passage_text": "The reintroduction of wolves, lynx and other apex predators into landscapes from which they were deliberately eradicated decades or centuries ago is often presented by conservationists as a straightforward act of ecological repair, restoring a balance that human hunting disturbed. Predators, the argument runs, control herbivore populations that would otherwise overgraze woodland and riverbank vegetation, triggering a cascade of benefits for smaller species, insects and even the physical shape of rivers, effects observed most famously following the reintroduction of wolves to Yellowstone National Park in the 1990s.\n\nFarmers and rural communities living alongside reintroduced predators frequently tell a less tidy story. Livestock losses, though statistically modest across a region as a whole, can be devastating for an individual smallholder whose entire flock is vulnerable to a single pack, and compensation schemes, where they exist, are often criticised as slow, bureaucratic and calculated using formulas that undervalue the animals actually lost. There is also a less measurable grievance: many rural residents feel that rewilding decisions are made by urban conservationists and distant governments who bear none of the practical costs, a sense of imposition that predates and outlasts any specific dispute over compensation payments. That sense of being overruled by outsiders can persist even where compensation is eventually paid in full, since the grievance concerns who decides rather than merely how much is paid.\n\nConservationists counter that this framing understates the economic benefits predators can bring, particularly through wildlife tourism, and that opposition is sometimes rooted less in measurable harm than in a broader resentment of external interference in rural life, a resentment that would persist even if compensation were generous and prompt. Both explanations likely contain some truth, and disentangling them matters enormously for policy, since a grievance rooted in inadequate compensation can be addressed through better administration, while a grievance rooted in a sense of imposed authority requires a different remedy altogether, most plausibly some meaningful form of local consultation and control over how and where reintroduction proceeds.\n\nWhat is rarely disputed, by conservationists or their critics, is that the ecological case for predators has outpaced the political groundwork needed to sustain their return, leaving successful reintroductions vulnerable to reversal whenever local hostility becomes organised and vocal enough to influence policy."}, {"id": 799, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Why does the passage suggest that distinguishing between the two possible sources of rural grievance matters for policy?", "options": {"A": "Both grievances require exactly the same administrative remedy.", "B": "Each grievance calls for a different kind of remedy to be effective.", "C": "Only one of the two grievances is ever genuinely present.", "D": "Compensation payments resolve both grievances simultaneously."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage explains that a grievance about inadequate compensation can be fixed through better administration, while a grievance about imposed authority needs a different remedy, likely local consultation and control. This distinction is presented as the reason disentangling the two sources of complaint matters for effective policy. The other options wrongly claim the remedies are identical, that only one grievance is ever real, or that compensation alone resolves both.", "passage_id": "P200", "passage_title": "Bringing Back the Wolf", "passage_text": "The reintroduction of wolves, lynx and other apex predators into landscapes from which they were deliberately eradicated decades or centuries ago is often presented by conservationists as a straightforward act of ecological repair, restoring a balance that human hunting disturbed. Predators, the argument runs, control herbivore populations that would otherwise overgraze woodland and riverbank vegetation, triggering a cascade of benefits for smaller species, insects and even the physical shape of rivers, effects observed most famously following the reintroduction of wolves to Yellowstone National Park in the 1990s.\n\nFarmers and rural communities living alongside reintroduced predators frequently tell a less tidy story. Livestock losses, though statistically modest across a region as a whole, can be devastating for an individual smallholder whose entire flock is vulnerable to a single pack, and compensation schemes, where they exist, are often criticised as slow, bureaucratic and calculated using formulas that undervalue the animals actually lost. There is also a less measurable grievance: many rural residents feel that rewilding decisions are made by urban conservationists and distant governments who bear none of the practical costs, a sense of imposition that predates and outlasts any specific dispute over compensation payments. That sense of being overruled by outsiders can persist even where compensation is eventually paid in full, since the grievance concerns who decides rather than merely how much is paid.\n\nConservationists counter that this framing understates the economic benefits predators can bring, particularly through wildlife tourism, and that opposition is sometimes rooted less in measurable harm than in a broader resentment of external interference in rural life, a resentment that would persist even if compensation were generous and prompt. Both explanations likely contain some truth, and disentangling them matters enormously for policy, since a grievance rooted in inadequate compensation can be addressed through better administration, while a grievance rooted in a sense of imposed authority requires a different remedy altogether, most plausibly some meaningful form of local consultation and control over how and where reintroduction proceeds.\n\nWhat is rarely disputed, by conservationists or their critics, is that the ecological case for predators has outpaced the political groundwork needed to sustain their return, leaving successful reintroductions vulnerable to reversal whenever local hostility becomes organised and vocal enough to influence policy."}, {"id": 800, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the final paragraph suggest about the current state of predator reintroduction programs?", "options": {"A": "Local hostility has already reversed most reintroduction efforts.", "B": "The ecological case for predators remains widely disputed.", "C": "Political support has consistently outpaced ecological research.", "D": "Reintroductions remain vulnerable due to insufficient political groundwork."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The final paragraph states that the ecological case for predators has outpaced the political groundwork needed to sustain their return, leaving reintroductions vulnerable to reversal if local hostility becomes organised. This describes an ongoing risk rather than a completed reversal or a dispute over the ecology itself. The passage never claims the ecological case is widely disputed, and it reverses the relationship described when it says political support has outpaced research.", "passage_id": "P200", "passage_title": "Bringing Back the Wolf", "passage_text": "The reintroduction of wolves, lynx and other apex predators into landscapes from which they were deliberately eradicated decades or centuries ago is often presented by conservationists as a straightforward act of ecological repair, restoring a balance that human hunting disturbed. Predators, the argument runs, control herbivore populations that would otherwise overgraze woodland and riverbank vegetation, triggering a cascade of benefits for smaller species, insects and even the physical shape of rivers, effects observed most famously following the reintroduction of wolves to Yellowstone National Park in the 1990s.\n\nFarmers and rural communities living alongside reintroduced predators frequently tell a less tidy story. Livestock losses, though statistically modest across a region as a whole, can be devastating for an individual smallholder whose entire flock is vulnerable to a single pack, and compensation schemes, where they exist, are often criticised as slow, bureaucratic and calculated using formulas that undervalue the animals actually lost. There is also a less measurable grievance: many rural residents feel that rewilding decisions are made by urban conservationists and distant governments who bear none of the practical costs, a sense of imposition that predates and outlasts any specific dispute over compensation payments. That sense of being overruled by outsiders can persist even where compensation is eventually paid in full, since the grievance concerns who decides rather than merely how much is paid.\n\nConservationists counter that this framing understates the economic benefits predators can bring, particularly through wildlife tourism, and that opposition is sometimes rooted less in measurable harm than in a broader resentment of external interference in rural life, a resentment that would persist even if compensation were generous and prompt. Both explanations likely contain some truth, and disentangling them matters enormously for policy, since a grievance rooted in inadequate compensation can be addressed through better administration, while a grievance rooted in a sense of imposed authority requires a different remedy altogether, most plausibly some meaningful form of local consultation and control over how and where reintroduction proceeds.\n\nWhat is rarely disputed, by conservationists or their critics, is that the ecological case for predators has outpaced the political groundwork needed to sustain their return, leaving successful reintroductions vulnerable to reversal whenever local hostility becomes organised and vocal enough to influence policy."}, {"id": 801, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Which best describes the overall structure of the passage's argument?", "options": {"A": "It defends the counter-speech doctrine as sufficient in all circumstances.", "B": "It rejects both extreme positions and proposes a narrow, constrained middle ground.", "C": "It argues that historical abuses prove regulation should never be attempted.", "D": "It shows that offensive speech and incitement should be treated identically."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage first presents the free speech absolutist case, then shows its limits, then explicitly proposes a narrow exception bound by institutional safeguards. This middle position is neither an unqualified defence of counter-speech nor a case for banning offensive opinion generally. The final paragraph reinforces this by calling for careful design rather than either extreme.", "passage_id": "P201", "passage_title": "The Limits of Toleration", "passage_text": "Defenders of an unregulated public square tend to argue from a single premise: that the remedy for bad speech is more speech, never censorship. On this view, a society that empowers officials to silence hateful expression has merely exchanged one harm for a worse one, since the power to decide what counts as hateful will inevitably be turned against unpopular but legitimate dissent. History offers examples enough of governments that used public order statutes to muzzle reformers, strikers and minority religions long before they were used against genuine bigots.\n\nYet this argument, however sound as a caution, does not settle the matter. It assumes that speech operates only as a contribution to debate, weighed and judged by rational listeners who can be trusted to reject the false and cruel. But some speech does not invite a reply so much as it forecloses one. A racial slur shouted at a lone commuter is not an argument to be rebutted; it is closer to an assault, delivered through sound rather than the fist, and its target is rarely in a position to answer back with a better argument. To treat every utterance as equally amenable to counter-speech is to ignore how power and vulnerability are distributed unevenly among speakers and listeners.\n\nThe more defensible position, then, is not an absolute rule in either direction but a narrow and closely policed exception. Regulation should reach only that speech which functions as targeted harassment or incitement to imminent harm, leaving untouched the vast terrain of offensive, provocative or unwelcome opinion. Such a line is admittedly harder to draw than either extreme position pretends, and it will be drawn imperfectly by fallible institutions. But the difficulty of drawing a line is not itself a reason to pretend that no line exists, and the fact that power can be abused is an argument for constraining it carefully, not for refusing to exercise it at all.\n\nWhat this middle position demands, above all, is institutional humility. Any body given authority to restrict expression must be bound by narrow definitions, subject to appeal, and periodically reviewed, precisely because the historical abuses the free speech absolutist fears are real. The answer to that risk is careful design, not abdication."}, {"id": 814, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The reference to originators who \"hold public office or command a large following\" is used to suggest that", "options": {"A": "such figures are legally immune from any consequence for false claims.", "B": "accountability is often weakest precisely where resulting harm is greatest.", "C": "ordinary individuals spread misinformation more often than public figures.", "D": "public office should be a legal barrier to originating any public statement."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage argues that consequences for spreading falsehood are unevenly applied and are often weakest exactly where the reach and resulting harm of the claim are largest, namely with prominent figures. This is a claim about uneven enforcement rather than formal legal immunity. It is also not a comparative claim about how frequently ordinary people versus public figures originate misinformation.", "passage_id": "P204", "passage_title": "Whose Job Is It to Correct a Lie?", "passage_text": "When a false claim spreads widely online, commentators reach almost immediately for the question of platform responsibility: should the company hosting the content have removed it, labelled it, or slowed its circulation. This framing, though understandable given the scale at which platforms operate, tends to crowd out other actors whose responsibility is at least as significant, and arguably more foundational, in the production and correction of public falsehood.\n\n      Consider first the originator of the claim, whose culpability is rarely disputed but often treated as a fixed cost of an open information environment rather than as a locus for intervention. Legal and social consequences for knowingly spreading falsehood remain unevenly applied, particularly when the originator holds public office or commands a large following, precisely the cases where the resulting harm is greatest. A system that reserves its heaviest scrutiny for the intermediary that merely carries a claim, while treating its author as beyond effective reach, has arguably misallocated its attention.\n\n      Consider next the traditional press, whose obligation is not merely to avoid originating falsehood but to actively investigate and correct it once in circulation. A single sceptical headline is a poor substitute for sustained reporting that traces a claim to its source, tests it against available evidence, and follows up when the claim is later shown to be false. Corrections research consistently finds that a retraction buried on a later page reaches only a fraction of the audience exposed to the original claim, which suggests that correction, to be effective, must be pursued with something like the same energy as the original story.\n\n      Finally, there is the individual reader, whose responsibility is easiest to state and hardest to enforce: to withhold belief, and above all further transmission, until a claim has been tested rather than merely found congenial. None of this is to excuse platforms from their share of responsibility, but it is to insist that treating them as the primary or sole locus of accountability lets the more consequential actors, the originator and the disseminating press, retreat from scrutiny they ought not to escape."}, {"id": 828, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'manipulation dressed in creative clothing' is used by critics, as described in the passage, to suggest which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Creativity in advertising is always a cover for outright lying.", "B": "Creative advertisements are more manipulative than plain factual ones.", "C": "What is presented as artistic invention may in substance still be manipulative influence.", "D": "Critics believe creativity and manipulation are entirely unrelated concepts."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Critics use this phrase to suggest that what advertisers present as artistic invention may still function, in substance, as an attempt to manipulate rather than merely entertain. It does not claim creativity always disguises outright lying, nor that creative advertisements are inherently worse than factual ones, since the passage is describing a tension rather than a ranking. The phrase highlights that appearance and substance can diverge.", "passage_id": "P207", "passage_title": "Persuasion's Uneasy Conscience", "passage_text": "Advertising is routinely defended on the ground that it merely persuades, and persuasion, unlike manipulation, respects the rational agency of the person being addressed. This distinction is philosophically tidy but practically slippery. Persuasion, in its idealised form, offers reasons: it tells you that a product is durable, or affordable, or effective, and invites you to weigh that information against your own preferences. Manipulation, by contrast, bypasses this weighing process altogether, working instead on psychological vulnerabilities the target may not even be aware of, such as the fear of social exclusion or the desire for status.\n\nThe difficulty is that a great deal of contemporary advertising sits uncomfortably between these two poles. Consider an advertisement that associates a fizzy drink with youthful romance and carefree summers. No literal claim is made about the drink's properties, and no falsehood is told. Yet the advertisement plainly aims to produce a favourable disposition toward the product by association rather than by argument, exploiting the mind's tendency to transfer positive feeling from one image to an unrelated object. Defenders call this creativity; critics call it manipulation dressed in creative clothing.\n\nOne tempting response is to say that as long as no false statement is made, no manipulation has occurred, since manipulation requires deception. But this conflates manipulation with lying, when the two are distinct wrongs. A magician who genuinely deceives you about how a trick works has lied to you in some loose sense, whereas an advertiser who never asserts anything false can still manipulate by engineering an emotional association that has nothing to do with the product's actual merits. The absence of falsehood does not guarantee the presence of respect for the audience's rational faculties.\n\nA further complication is that audiences are rarely passive. Many viewers know perfectly well that the summer romance has nothing to do with the drink's ingredients, and enjoy the advertisement as a piece of entertainment rather than as a source of information. If the audience is not actually being fooled, it becomes harder to say where the wrong of manipulation lies, since manipulation seems to presuppose some kind of success in altering belief or desire against the target's better judgement. Perhaps the honest conclusion is that advertising occupies a spectrum, and that condemning or excusing it wholesale mistakes a matter of degree for a matter of kind."}, {"id": 830, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What weakness in the democratic-function justification for censorship does the passage identify?", "options": {"A": "Offensive political speech may still count as a contribution to democratic deliberation despite its repugnant content.", "B": "The theory reportedly cannot explain why defamation or fraud are restricted under its own logic.", "C": "The theory relies entirely on subjective and inconsistent judgements about what counts as offensive.", "D": "The theory was apparently designed only for non-democratic states rather than liberal ones."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage notes that much hateful or offensive speech nonetheless takes the form of a political opinion, which means it can still appear to serve democratic deliberation despite its repugnant content. This is presented as a blind spot in the democratic-function theory, not a claim about defamation or a suggestion the theory was built for non-democracies. The weakness lies in the theory's own criterion being satisfied by speech many would want excluded.", "passage_id": "P208", "passage_title": "The Limits of a Free Society's Tolerance", "passage_text": "Liberal democracies profess a commitment to free expression, yet none tolerates speech without qualification. Incitement to imminent violence, defamation, and certain categories of fraud are restricted almost everywhere, and few regard these restrictions as betrayals of liberal principle. The interesting question is not whether any censorship can be justified, since evidently some can, but which principle explains why these particular restrictions are acceptable while others, such as banning unpopular political opinions, are not.\n\nOne common justification appeals to harm: speech may be restricted when it causes direct, identifiable harm to others, but not merely because it causes offence or discomfort. This harm principle has intuitive appeal, yet it struggles at the margins. Hate speech, for instance, rarely causes harm in the immediate, physical sense that incitement does, but its defenders of restriction argue that it inflicts a slower, cumulative harm on the dignity and standing of targeted groups, normalising hostility that eventually enables more direct harms. Critics reply that once harm is stretched to cover psychological and cumulative effects, the category becomes elastic enough to justify almost any restriction a government finds convenient, since nearly any speech can be alleged to harm someone's dignity eventually.\n\nA second justification, favoured by those wary of the harm principle's elasticity, looks instead to the function speech serves within democratic self-governance. On this view, speech that contributes to the collective deliberation on which self-government depends deserves the strongest protection, while speech that serves no such function, such as a deliberately false statement of fact designed to defraud, forfeits the claim to protection. This account explains the defamation and fraud exceptions neatly, since neither contributes anything to democratic deliberation, but it too has a blind spot: much genuinely offensive or hateful speech is nonetheless, in form, a political opinion, however repugnant its content, and so appears to qualify for protection under a theory built around democratic function.\n\nNeither theory, then, draws the line without remainder. This suggests that any actual policy of censorship in a liberal democracy is likely to rest on a pragmatic compromise between competing justifications rather than on the clean application of a single principle, and that citizens who demand a perfectly principled boundary may be asking for something no liberal theory has yet supplied."}, {"id": 840, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to the final paragraph, what should a careful reader do when encountering a charged political term?", "options": {"A": "Assume that all charged terms are dishonest and should be rejected outright.", "B": "Consider what persuasive work the term performs beyond simply naming its subject.", "C": "Rely on the speaker's tone of voice to judge sincerity.", "D": "Treat register and courtesy as irrelevant to political communication."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage advises that a careful reader should ask what persuasive work a charged term performs beyond simply naming its subject. It does not recommend rejecting all charged terms outright, relying on tone of voice, or dismissing register and courtesy as irrelevant, since the passage explicitly allows that some language choices are merely stylistic. The recommendation is aimed at distinguishing genuine persuasion at work from ordinary description.", "passage_id": "P210", "passage_title": "The Grammar of Evasion", "passage_text": "Politicians are frequently accused of hiding behind euphemism, yet the accusation is often levelled too broadly, as though every softened phrase were evidence of dishonesty. A more precise diagnosis distinguishes two quite different uses of indirect language. The first is genuinely deceptive: a government that describes civilian deaths as collateral damage is not merely choosing gentler words but attempting to relocate the event, in the listener's mind, from the category of tragedy requiring justification to the category of regrettable but unavoidable side effect, without offering any argument for why that recategorisation is warranted. The second use is merely diplomatic, softening language to preserve a working relationship without altering the underlying facts, as when a spokesperson describes a tense negotiation as frank rather than hostile.\n\nThe difficulty for any listener is that both uses share the same surface grammar, so the same interpretive skill is required to tell them apart, and politicians rely on this ambiguity, knowing that a genuinely deceptive euphemism can retreat into the appearance of mere diplomatic softening if challenged. When a minister who described a policy failure as a challenging period is pressed on the substance, the defence available is always that the phrase was simply tactful understatement, never an attempt to conceal.\n\nLoaded language operates by a related but distinct mechanism. Where euphemism softens, loaded language sharpens, smuggling an evaluative conclusion into what presents itself as a neutral description. To call a policy a giveaway rather than a subsidy, or a proposal reform rather than cuts, is to insert the very judgement that ought to be left to the listener, disguised as a simple label. The listener who accepts the label has, often without noticing, already accepted the argument the label was designed to win.\n\nNone of this means that all political language is manipulative, since some vocabulary choices genuinely reflect nothing more than register or courtesy. But it does mean that a careful reader must ask, of any charged term, what work the term is doing beyond naming its referent, since language that appears merely descriptive can quietly perform the persuasive labour that an explicit argument would otherwise have to do openly, and do so without ever being held to the standard of proof an open argument would require."}, {"id": 842, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to the passage, what remedy does the author favour over abolishing ranking systems entirely?", "options": {"A": "Replacing personalised feeds with a single shared national news source.", "B": "Requiring platforms to display stories in strict chronological order only.", "C": "Occasionally surfacing a well-argued opposing article within the existing feed.", "D": "Banning algorithms from using a user's prior click history altogether."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage proposes reintroducing a visible alternative at the point of reading while keeping the convenience of curation intact. This is described as restoring the cue the newsstand once provided rather than replacing ranking with an undifferentiated stream. The other proposals are not mentioned and would abolish curation, which the passage explicitly resists.", "passage_id": "P211", "passage_title": "The Curated Feed", "passage_text": "The complaint against algorithmic curation is by now familiar. Platforms that rank stories according to what a user has previously clicked on, it is said, seal each of us inside a chamber built from our own preferences, in which confirming views arrive promptly and dissenting ones are quietly filtered out. Over time, the argument runs, this produces a citizenry that cannot even agree on the basic facts of a dispute, let alone its resolution, since the two sides are no longer reading the same reports.\n\nThe difficulty with this account is that it treats the algorithm as though it introduced a distortion into an otherwise pristine information market. It did not. Readers have always sorted themselves into sympathetic newspapers, sympathetic pulpits, sympathetic dinner tables. The partisan press of earlier centuries was not a gentler predecessor to today's feeds but a comparably narrow one, minus the illusion of neutrality that a personalised homepage now supplies. What has changed is less the fact of selective exposure than its visibility to the user, who no longer chooses a title from a newsstand and can therefore no longer be reminded, by the mere existence of a rack of alternatives, that other framings exist.\n\nThat difference matters, but it points to a narrower remedy than the abolition of ranking systems. If the harm lies in the disappearance of the newsstand rather than in selection itself, the fix is to reintroduce visible alternatives at the point of reading, not to insist that every reader be shown an undifferentiated stream regardless of relevance. A feed that occasionally surfaces a well-argued opposing piece preserves the convenience that made curation popular while restoring the cue that convenience had removed.\n\nCritics who demand the wholesale dismantling of ranking overlook that an unranked feed is not a neutral one; it merely hands the sorting task back to whichever stories are loudest, a criterion no more impartial than a user's own history and considerably less transparent. The honest question is not whether feeds should be curated, since some ordering is unavoidable once volume exceeds attention, but which values that ordering should encode, and whether users can be shown, cheaply, that the ordering they see is only one of several available."}, {"id": 843, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "The comparison between personalised feeds and the partisan press of earlier centuries is used mainly to suggest that...", "options": {"A": "earlier readers were more open-minded than today's feed users.", "B": "the partisan press was actually broader in scope than modern feeds.", "C": "selective reading habits emerged only after algorithms were introduced.", "D": "selective exposure predates algorithms and is not itself the novel harm."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The comparison establishes that narrow, self-selected reading is an old habit, so algorithms cannot be blamed for inventing it. This supports the author's broader claim that visibility, not selection, is what actually changed. The remaining options invert or misstate the direction of the comparison the passage draws.", "passage_id": "P211", "passage_title": "The Curated Feed", "passage_text": "The complaint against algorithmic curation is by now familiar. Platforms that rank stories according to what a user has previously clicked on, it is said, seal each of us inside a chamber built from our own preferences, in which confirming views arrive promptly and dissenting ones are quietly filtered out. Over time, the argument runs, this produces a citizenry that cannot even agree on the basic facts of a dispute, let alone its resolution, since the two sides are no longer reading the same reports.\n\nThe difficulty with this account is that it treats the algorithm as though it introduced a distortion into an otherwise pristine information market. It did not. Readers have always sorted themselves into sympathetic newspapers, sympathetic pulpits, sympathetic dinner tables. The partisan press of earlier centuries was not a gentler predecessor to today's feeds but a comparably narrow one, minus the illusion of neutrality that a personalised homepage now supplies. What has changed is less the fact of selective exposure than its visibility to the user, who no longer chooses a title from a newsstand and can therefore no longer be reminded, by the mere existence of a rack of alternatives, that other framings exist.\n\nThat difference matters, but it points to a narrower remedy than the abolition of ranking systems. If the harm lies in the disappearance of the newsstand rather than in selection itself, the fix is to reintroduce visible alternatives at the point of reading, not to insist that every reader be shown an undifferentiated stream regardless of relevance. A feed that occasionally surfaces a well-argued opposing piece preserves the convenience that made curation popular while restoring the cue that convenience had removed.\n\nCritics who demand the wholesale dismantling of ranking overlook that an unranked feed is not a neutral one; it merely hands the sorting task back to whichever stories are loudest, a criterion no more impartial than a user's own history and considerably less transparent. The honest question is not whether feeds should be curated, since some ordering is unavoidable once volume exceeds attention, but which values that ordering should encode, and whether users can be shown, cheaply, that the ordering they see is only one of several available."}, {"id": 844, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'seal each of us inside a chamber built from our own preferences' functions in the passage chiefly to...", "options": {"A": "endorse the view that follows as the author's own settled conclusion.", "B": "vividly restate the popular objection before the author goes on to question it.", "C": "introduce a technical term that the passage will later define precisely.", "D": "summarise the remedy that the author ultimately recommends adopting."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The vivid phrase appears at the outset while the author is laying out the familiar complaint, before the second paragraph begins to complicate it. It functions rhetorically as a restatement of a widely held view rather than an endorsement. It is neither a defined technical term nor a description of the remedy proposed later in the passage.", "passage_id": "P211", "passage_title": "The Curated Feed", "passage_text": "The complaint against algorithmic curation is by now familiar. Platforms that rank stories according to what a user has previously clicked on, it is said, seal each of us inside a chamber built from our own preferences, in which confirming views arrive promptly and dissenting ones are quietly filtered out. Over time, the argument runs, this produces a citizenry that cannot even agree on the basic facts of a dispute, let alone its resolution, since the two sides are no longer reading the same reports.\n\nThe difficulty with this account is that it treats the algorithm as though it introduced a distortion into an otherwise pristine information market. It did not. Readers have always sorted themselves into sympathetic newspapers, sympathetic pulpits, sympathetic dinner tables. The partisan press of earlier centuries was not a gentler predecessor to today's feeds but a comparably narrow one, minus the illusion of neutrality that a personalised homepage now supplies. What has changed is less the fact of selective exposure than its visibility to the user, who no longer chooses a title from a newsstand and can therefore no longer be reminded, by the mere existence of a rack of alternatives, that other framings exist.\n\nThat difference matters, but it points to a narrower remedy than the abolition of ranking systems. If the harm lies in the disappearance of the newsstand rather than in selection itself, the fix is to reintroduce visible alternatives at the point of reading, not to insist that every reader be shown an undifferentiated stream regardless of relevance. A feed that occasionally surfaces a well-argued opposing piece preserves the convenience that made curation popular while restoring the cue that convenience had removed.\n\nCritics who demand the wholesale dismantling of ranking overlook that an unranked feed is not a neutral one; it merely hands the sorting task back to whichever stories are loudest, a criterion no more impartial than a user's own history and considerably less transparent. The honest question is not whether feeds should be curated, since some ordering is unavoidable once volume exceeds attention, but which values that ordering should encode, and whether users can be shown, cheaply, that the ordering they see is only one of several available."}, {"id": 851, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "The discussion of satire voicing a repugnant view is included mainly to...", "options": {"A": "show a case where offensive content is justified by its context and purpose.", "B": "demonstrate that satire is the only legitimate form of comedy.", "C": "argue that satire should be judged more harshly than other jokes.", "D": "prove that audiences always correctly interpret a satirist's intention."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Satire is presented as a case in which voicing a repugnant view serves the purpose of exposing it, with context supplying the meaning the audience is trusted to grasp. This supports the passage's broader claim that comedy should not be judged by a single uniform standard. It does not claim satire is the only legitimate comic form, nor that satirical intent is always correctly read.", "passage_id": "P213", "passage_title": "The Comedian's Licence", "passage_text": "It has become commonplace to defend a comedian accused of causing offence by appeal to a special licence supposedly attached to the craft: jokes, on this view, operate under different rules from ordinary assertions, and a line delivered for laughter should not be judged as though it were delivered as sincere testimony. There is something to this, since a joke plainly is not the same speech act as a claim, and treating every punchline as a literal proposition would make most stand-up unintelligible. But the argument is frequently stretched well beyond what that observation supports.\n\nThe mistake lies in inferring, from the fact that a joke is not literally asserted, that a joke therefore asserts nothing at all. Most jokes trade on a shared premise the audience is expected to recognise, and the humour typically depends on that premise being at least momentarily entertained as plausible. A joke that relies on a demeaning stereotype for its punchline is not neutral with respect to the stereotype merely because it is packaged as comedy; it invites the audience to find the premise recognisable, which is a cognitive transaction quite different from mere assertion but not therefore free of content.\n\nThis does not mean comedy should be judged by identical standards to a newspaper editorial, since the two forms serve different purposes and audiences bring different expectations to each. Satire in particular often works by voicing a repugnant view in order to expose it, a manoeuvre that depends on context the audience is trusted to supply. Collapsing that distinction, and treating every offensive line as sincere advocacy, would indeed misread much of what comedy does.\n\nThe more defensible position sits between the two extremes on offer. Comedy is not exempt from scrutiny simply because it is comedy, but neither is every joke a covert assertion deserving the same response as a straightforward claim. What decides the matter in a given case is not the label 'joke' but the relationship between the premise invoked and the audience's likely uptake of it, a relationship that varies from routine to routine and cannot be settled by a blanket rule in either direction."}, {"id": 852, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'a cognitive transaction quite different from mere assertion' is used to...", "options": {"A": "deny that jokes have any effect on how audiences think.", "B": "claim that jokes are legally equivalent to sincere statements.", "C": "describe how a joke can convey content without being a literal claim.", "D": "introduce a formal logical proof about the structure of humour."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The phrase captures the passage's middle position, that inviting an audience to entertain a premise is a distinct kind of engagement from stating a claim outright, yet still carries content. It directly opposes the idea that jokes have no effect on an audience's thinking. It is a descriptive characterisation rather than a legal claim or a formal proof.", "passage_id": "P213", "passage_title": "The Comedian's Licence", "passage_text": "It has become commonplace to defend a comedian accused of causing offence by appeal to a special licence supposedly attached to the craft: jokes, on this view, operate under different rules from ordinary assertions, and a line delivered for laughter should not be judged as though it were delivered as sincere testimony. There is something to this, since a joke plainly is not the same speech act as a claim, and treating every punchline as a literal proposition would make most stand-up unintelligible. But the argument is frequently stretched well beyond what that observation supports.\n\nThe mistake lies in inferring, from the fact that a joke is not literally asserted, that a joke therefore asserts nothing at all. Most jokes trade on a shared premise the audience is expected to recognise, and the humour typically depends on that premise being at least momentarily entertained as plausible. A joke that relies on a demeaning stereotype for its punchline is not neutral with respect to the stereotype merely because it is packaged as comedy; it invites the audience to find the premise recognisable, which is a cognitive transaction quite different from mere assertion but not therefore free of content.\n\nThis does not mean comedy should be judged by identical standards to a newspaper editorial, since the two forms serve different purposes and audiences bring different expectations to each. Satire in particular often works by voicing a repugnant view in order to expose it, a manoeuvre that depends on context the audience is trusted to supply. Collapsing that distinction, and treating every offensive line as sincere advocacy, would indeed misread much of what comedy does.\n\nThe more defensible position sits between the two extremes on offer. Comedy is not exempt from scrutiny simply because it is comedy, but neither is every joke a covert assertion deserving the same response as a straightforward claim. What decides the matter in a given case is not the label 'joke' but the relationship between the premise invoked and the audience's likely uptake of it, a relationship that varies from routine to routine and cannot be settled by a blanket rule in either direction."}, {"id": 862, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "How does the passage ultimately treat the postal service comparison introduced at the outset?", "options": {"A": "As an analogy that becomes weaker once algorithmic ranking is considered.", "B": "As a valid analogy that should guide future regulation unchanged.", "C": "As proof that platforms cannot be compared to any traditional institution.", "D": "As evidence that postal workers already perform a similar editorial role."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage introduces the postal comparison as initially persuasive, then shows it weakens once the amplifying effect of ranking algorithms is taken into account. This progression signals that the analogy is being questioned rather than endorsed as a permanent guide for regulation. The remaining options either overstate the analogy's continued validity, claim an impossible comparison, or reverse the roles of postal workers and platforms.", "passage_id": "P216", "passage_title": "Carriers or Curators", "passage_text": "For much of the internet's short history, the companies that host user generated content have insisted they are mere conduits, akin to a postal service that cannot be blamed for the contents of the letters it delivers. This analogy, once persuasive, grows weaker each year that the platforms refine the algorithms that decide which posts multiply and which vanish unseen. A postal worker does not read your letter and then decide, on the basis of what will most inflame you, whose reply arrives first; a social media feed does exactly that, thousands of times a second, for every user simultaneously.\n\nThe defenders of neutrality point out that holding platforms liable for everything users say would be unworkable at their scale, and that the alternative, heavy handed pre screening, would chill the very expression the internet was meant to liberate. There is real force here: a billion daily posts cannot be read by human editors before publication, and any attempt to automate the judgment risks penalising satire, dissent and minority viewpoints as readily as genuine harm. Yet this argument, focused entirely on what platforms cannot do before a post appears, quietly ignores what they plainly do after it appears, namely rank, recommend and repeatedly resurface it.\n\nThat editorial act, the choosing of what to amplify, is where the publisher analogy regains its force. Newspapers have never been required to publish every letter sent to them, but once they choose to print one on the front page rather than bury it, they accept a portion of responsibility for its prominence. Platforms make an equivalent choice millions of times an hour, dressed up as neutral machinery, when in truth the machinery was built and tuned by people pursuing engagement above all else.\n\nNone of this settles the practical question of what new rules should follow. It does, however, expose the weakness of resting an entire legal category, immunity from liability, on a metaphor of postal neutrality that the platforms themselves abandoned the day they introduced a ranking algorithm. Whatever framework replaces it will have to grapple with amplification as a distinct act from mere hosting, since the two carry very different moral weight."}, {"id": 864, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What effect does the comparison between a front-page placement and an algorithm's ranking decision have on the passage's argument?", "options": {"A": "It suggests platforms deserve less scrutiny than newspapers ever received.", "B": "It equates two acts of prominence to argue both carry moral responsibility.", "C": "It implies newspapers never exercised any editorial judgment either.", "D": "It shows that algorithms are entirely different from any editorial choice."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "By comparing an algorithm's ranking decision to a newspaper's choice of front-page placement, the passage argues that both acts confer prominence and therefore carry a similar moral weight. This comparison strengthens the case that platforms bear some responsibility once they choose what to amplify. The remaining options misread the comparison as reducing scrutiny, denying newspapers any editorial role, or separating algorithms from editorial choice altogether.", "passage_id": "P216", "passage_title": "Carriers or Curators", "passage_text": "For much of the internet's short history, the companies that host user generated content have insisted they are mere conduits, akin to a postal service that cannot be blamed for the contents of the letters it delivers. This analogy, once persuasive, grows weaker each year that the platforms refine the algorithms that decide which posts multiply and which vanish unseen. A postal worker does not read your letter and then decide, on the basis of what will most inflame you, whose reply arrives first; a social media feed does exactly that, thousands of times a second, for every user simultaneously.\n\nThe defenders of neutrality point out that holding platforms liable for everything users say would be unworkable at their scale, and that the alternative, heavy handed pre screening, would chill the very expression the internet was meant to liberate. There is real force here: a billion daily posts cannot be read by human editors before publication, and any attempt to automate the judgment risks penalising satire, dissent and minority viewpoints as readily as genuine harm. Yet this argument, focused entirely on what platforms cannot do before a post appears, quietly ignores what they plainly do after it appears, namely rank, recommend and repeatedly resurface it.\n\nThat editorial act, the choosing of what to amplify, is where the publisher analogy regains its force. Newspapers have never been required to publish every letter sent to them, but once they choose to print one on the front page rather than bury it, they accept a portion of responsibility for its prominence. Platforms make an equivalent choice millions of times an hour, dressed up as neutral machinery, when in truth the machinery was built and tuned by people pursuing engagement above all else.\n\nNone of this settles the practical question of what new rules should follow. It does, however, expose the weakness of resting an entire legal category, immunity from liability, on a metaphor of postal neutrality that the platforms themselves abandoned the day they introduced a ranking algorithm. Whatever framework replaces it will have to grapple with amplification as a distinct act from mere hosting, since the two carry very different moral weight."}, {"id": 867, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Why does the author say clickbait is difficult to regulate?", "options": {"A": "Each individual headline is a small exaggeration rather than an outright lie.", "B": "No reader has ever complained about being misled by a headline.", "C": "Regulators lack any legal basis for reviewing advertising claims.", "D": "Publishers openly admit that their headlines are intentionally false."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage explains that no single headline is dishonest enough to qualify as an outright lie, since each is only a small, plausible exaggeration, making regulation difficult to target. The harm the passage describes accumulates diffusely across many headlines rather than from one clear violation. The other options invent claims about reader complaints, legal authority, or publisher admissions that the passage never makes.", "passage_id": "P217", "passage_title": "The Price of a Promise", "passage_text": "An advertisement that lies about the product it sells is rightly condemned, yet a headline that lies, more subtly, about the article beneath it attracts remarkably little of the same censure. \"You will not believe what happened next\" promises a revelation and delivers, more often than not, something perfectly believable and faintly disappointing. The gap between promise and delivery is the entire business model of clickbait, and it survives because the cost of the small betrayal is paid by the reader in seconds and frustration, never by the publisher in reputation.\n\nDefenders of the attention economy argue that headlines have always exaggerated, that tabloids screamed sensational claims a century before any website existed, and that readers have learned, through repeated disappointment, to discount the promise before they click. If this were entirely true, however, the industry would not continue to invest so heavily in headline testing, running dozens of variants past focus groups to find the phrasing that most reliably overrides a reader's scepticism. The persistence of the technique argues against the claim that audiences have grown immune to it.\n\nA further defence holds that attention, once captured, can still be spent on worthwhile journalism, so the bait is merely a means to a legitimate end. This assumes, though, that readers who arrive under false pretences are as receptive to the substance that follows as readers who arrived because the subject genuinely interested them. Curiosity manufactured by a misleading prompt is a thinner, more resentful form of attention than curiosity that was already present, and it is far more easily lost the moment the promised revelation fails to appear.\n\nWhat makes the practice difficult to regulate is that no single headline is quite dishonest enough to be called a lie outright. Each is a small, plausible exaggeration, and the harm accumulates only across thousands of them, in the gradual erosion of a reader's trust that any headline means what it says. That cumulative, diffuse damage is precisely the sort that markets are worst at pricing and readers are slowest to notice until the trust is already gone, and by the time it is noticed the habit of clicking, formed over thousands of small disappointments, is far harder to unlearn than it ever was to acquire."}, {"id": 871, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage imply about a newly coined, preferred term?", "options": {"A": "It can mark group membership as well as express care for those affected.", "B": "It is a neutral description with no social consequence.", "C": "It is universally adopted within a single generation without resistance.", "D": "It resolves the underlying prejudice it was coined to address."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage suggests a newly preferred term functions both as an act of care toward those it concerns and as a marker separating those who adopt it from those who do not. This dual function explains why the same linguistic shift can feel like overdue justice to some and unwelcome coercion to others. The other options wrongly claim the term is neutral, universally accepted at once, or capable of resolving the prejudice it names.", "passage_id": "P218", "passage_title": "Words as Proxies", "passage_text": "Every generation accuses the one before it of using words carelessly, and every generation is in turn accused by the one that follows. What is unusual about the present dispute over so called political correctness is that both sides claim to be defending the same thing, namely the ability to speak honestly, while accusing the other of suppressing it. One side insists that policing vocabulary protects those historically mocked by careless language; the other insists that the policing itself has become a tool for silencing argument rather than refining it. Both cannot be simply dismissed, and the dispute is better understood as a contest over who gets to define acceptable speech than as a simple conflict between courtesy and honesty.\n\nLanguage has never been a neutral vessel that merely carries meaning from one mind to another; it also confers status on the speaker and withholds it from those who cannot or will not adopt the preferred terms. A newly coined phrase, gently insisted upon by those who feel it, functions simultaneously as an act of care and as a marker of group membership, separating those who keep pace with its adoption from those who lag behind, whether from ignorance or from principled objection. Both groups can therefore experience the same linguistic shift as, respectively, overdue justice or unwelcome coercion, without either being wholly mistaken about their own experience.\n\nWhat tends to be missed in the public shouting match is that the argument is rarely, at bottom, about the words themselves. Few genuinely believe that swapping one term for another cures the underlying prejudice it names, and few genuinely believe that resisting the swap proves any prejudice at all. The words are proxies, fought over because they are visible and measurable, for a deeper and less tractable argument about whose account of social reality gets to set the terms everyone else must use.\n\nRecognising the dispute as one about authority rather than etiquette does not resolve it, but it does explain why appeals to simple politeness on one side, or to simple free expression on the other, so consistently fail to persuade opponents who are actually arguing about something else entirely."}, {"id": 889, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Which of the following best summarises the passage's central concern about misinformation policy?", "options": {"A": "Governments have consistently and deliberately overstated the real harm that misinformation actually causes to ordinary citizens today.", "B": "Platforms have proven far more competent than governments at correctly identifying which claims are false.", "C": "The features that make false claims spread also characterise legitimate dissent, making the two hard to separate reliably.", "D": "Every single historical case on record confirms that misinformation policy has always been fundamentally misguided and entirely unnecessary."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The opening paragraph identifies the central concern directly, noting that the features making a false claim dangerous, its capacity to spread and challenge official accounts, are shared by legitimate minority opinion that later proves correct. This shared characteristic is what makes reliable separation of the two difficult, which the rest of the passage develops. The passage does not claim misinformation causes little harm, compare platform and government competence, or conclude that all such policy is misguided.", "passage_id": "P223", "passage_title": "Who Decides What Counts as False", "passage_text": "Governments and platforms alike have grown eager to police misinformation, and the impulse is understandable: false claims about vaccines, elections, or public health can cause real harm at scale that a single false rumour once could not achieve. Yet the machinery built to suppress falsehood has an unfortunate tendency to catch dissent in its net, since the very features that make a claim dangerous when false, namely its capacity to spread and to challenge official accounts, are also the features of legitimate minority opinion that later turns out to be correct.\n\nHistory supplies no shortage of claims once confidently labelled misinformation by authorities that were, in time, vindicated. The difficulty is not that such episodes prove misinformation policy is always wrong, but that they prove certainty about falsehood is harder to come by in the moment than it appears in hindsight. A policy that requires immediate certainty before challenging a claim will inevitably suppress some claims that are simply unfashionable rather than false, because the officials adjudicating the matter share the same uncertainty as everyone else, only with the power to act on it.\n\nSome defenders of misinformation policy respond that the standard need not be certainty but reasonable confidence, calibrated to the harm at stake, and updated as evidence develops. This is a more defensible position, yet it still leaves the awkward question of who is trusted to calibrate. If the calibrators are drawn overwhelmingly from a narrow professional or political class, their reasonable confidence will tend to track the assumptions of that class, and dissent from outside it will look, to them, indistinguishable from falsehood.\n\nNone of this means that misinformation should go unchallenged, since the alternative of complete inaction carries its own well documented costs, allowing genuinely dangerous falsehoods to spread unopposed while institutions look on. It means only that any system built to suppress falsehood should be judged not by how well it performs against claims everyone already agrees are false, but by how it treats the claims that are genuinely contested, since it is precisely there that the line between correcting error and silencing dissent will be drawn. A policy that cannot survive scrutiny on its hardest cases has not really solved the problem it was built to address."}, {"id": 892, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'catch dissent in its net' is used to suggest that misinformation policy...", "options": {"A": "is designed specifically to target political opponents.", "B": "can unintentionally ensnare legitimate minority views alongside genuine falsehoods.", "C": "has proven entirely ineffective at reducing harm.", "D": "relies on fishing metaphors common in legal drafting."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The net metaphor conveys something broad and indiscriminate that captures more than it was meant to, fitting the passage's argument that machinery built against falsehood also snares legitimate dissent. This is consistent with the following sentence's claim about shared features between dangerous falsehoods and vindicated minority opinion. The phrase does not imply deliberate targeting of opponents, complete ineffectiveness, or a comment on legal drafting conventions.", "passage_id": "P223", "passage_title": "Who Decides What Counts as False", "passage_text": "Governments and platforms alike have grown eager to police misinformation, and the impulse is understandable: false claims about vaccines, elections, or public health can cause real harm at scale that a single false rumour once could not achieve. Yet the machinery built to suppress falsehood has an unfortunate tendency to catch dissent in its net, since the very features that make a claim dangerous when false, namely its capacity to spread and to challenge official accounts, are also the features of legitimate minority opinion that later turns out to be correct.\n\nHistory supplies no shortage of claims once confidently labelled misinformation by authorities that were, in time, vindicated. The difficulty is not that such episodes prove misinformation policy is always wrong, but that they prove certainty about falsehood is harder to come by in the moment than it appears in hindsight. A policy that requires immediate certainty before challenging a claim will inevitably suppress some claims that are simply unfashionable rather than false, because the officials adjudicating the matter share the same uncertainty as everyone else, only with the power to act on it.\n\nSome defenders of misinformation policy respond that the standard need not be certainty but reasonable confidence, calibrated to the harm at stake, and updated as evidence develops. This is a more defensible position, yet it still leaves the awkward question of who is trusted to calibrate. If the calibrators are drawn overwhelmingly from a narrow professional or political class, their reasonable confidence will tend to track the assumptions of that class, and dissent from outside it will look, to them, indistinguishable from falsehood.\n\nNone of this means that misinformation should go unchallenged, since the alternative of complete inaction carries its own well documented costs, allowing genuinely dangerous falsehoods to spread unopposed while institutions look on. It means only that any system built to suppress falsehood should be judged not by how well it performs against claims everyone already agrees are false, but by how it treats the claims that are genuinely contested, since it is precisely there that the line between correcting error and silencing dissent will be drawn. A policy that cannot survive scrutiny on its hardest cases has not really solved the problem it was built to address."}, {"id": 900, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The passage's title, 'Editors Without an Editorial Page', is best understood as suggesting that platforms...", "options": {"A": "should create formal editorial pages to match traditional newspapers.", "B": "perform an editorial-like function while disclaiming the responsibility that role traditionally carries.", "C": "have abandoned all forms of content moderation entirely.", "D": "are indistinguishable from newspapers in their legal obligations."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The title plays on the idea that platforms act as editors, through curating and ranking content, without accepting the acknowledged editorial identity or the responsibility a visible editorial page implies. This captures the passage's broader argument that active curation cannot coexist with a claim to total immunity. The title does not literally call for platforms to adopt editorial pages, nor does it suggest moderation has been abandoned or that platforms are legally identical to newspapers.", "passage_id": "P225", "passage_title": "Editors Without an Editorial Page", "passage_text": "Social media companies have long resisted the label of 'publisher', preferring instead to describe themselves as neutral conduits through which users communicate with one another, rather like a telephone network that cannot be blamed for what is said over its lines. This self-description carries obvious commercial advantages, since publishers bear legal responsibility for the content they carry while conduits, on the traditional view, do not. The trouble is that the analogy has grown steadily less convincing as platforms have taken on functions no telephone network ever performed.\n\nA telephone network does not select which calls to amplify, does not rank conversations by predicted engagement, and does not intervene to keep a caller talking longer than she otherwise would. Social media platforms do all three, through algorithms that determine which posts are shown, in what order, and with what prominence. Once a company is actively curating which content reaches which audience, and profiting from the attention that curation captures, the claim to be a mere neutral conduit becomes difficult to sustain, whatever the platform's terms of service may still insist.\n\nIf curation of this kind amounts to a form of editorial judgement, however implicit, then some responsibility for the consequences of that judgement plausibly follows, in the same way that a newspaper's editor bears some responsibility for what she chooses to print prominently on the front page. This does not mean platforms should be held to exactly the standard of a newspaper, since the sheer volume of user content they carry makes line by line editorial review practically impossible in a way it never was for a newspaper.\n\nWhat follows is not a simple verdict but a demand for honesty about what platforms actually do. A company that curates, ranks, and amplifies content for profit cannot simultaneously claim the total immunity traditionally reserved for those who do none of these things. The more defensible position, though still contested, is that responsibility should track the degree of active curation involved, so that a platform bears more responsibility for content it algorithmically promotes than for content it merely stores and leaves undisturbed."}, {"id": 903, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "Which statement best captures the passage's final account of why moral responsibility survives despite determinism?", "options": {"A": "Responsibility survives because scientists have proven that some choices are genuinely uncaused.", "B": "Responsibility survives because blame is a practice justified by its usefulness in shaping conduct, not by disproving causation.", "C": "Responsibility survives because juries continue to convict regardless of scientific evidence.", "D": "Responsibility survives because most defendants do not have identifiable brain abnormalities."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The final paragraph reframes blame as a practical instrument for influencing future conduct rather than a claim resting on the falsity of determinism. Responsibility was therefore never staked on disproving causation, contrary to the suggestion of genuinely uncaused choices. The remaining options misstate the argument by appealing to jury behaviour or the rarity of brain abnormalities, neither of which the passage relies on.", "passage_id": "P226", "passage_title": "The Excuse of the Wiring", "passage_text": "Every advance in neuroscience seems to be met with a corresponding retreat in our willingness to hold people to account for what they do. A brain scan reveals an unusual pattern of activity in a defendant convicted of assault, and the courtroom is invited to conclude that his wiring, rather than his will, produced the blow. The inference is seductive because it appears to rest on hard evidence rather than moral intuition, yet it proves too much. Every action, virtuous or vicious, corresponds to some pattern of neural firing; if the presence of a physical cause excuses an act, then no act, including the charitable ones we praise, can be credited to the person who performs it. The determinist cannot logically exempt bad conduct from the causal net while leaving good conduct inside it.\n\nDefenders of the neuroscientific excuse reply that the objection is too quick, since what matters is not that behaviour has a cause but that the cause bypasses the agent's ordinary capacities for reasoning and self-control. A tumour pressing on the amygdala is different in kind from a settled character reached through years of ordinary deliberation, even though both are, in the end, physical. This distinction has some force, but it is far harder to draw in practice than in theory. Character itself is shaped by genetics, upbringing, and chance exposures that the agent never chose, so the line between an excusing malfunction and an inculpating disposition threatens to dissolve the moment one looks closely at it.\n\nWhat rescues moral responsibility from this dissolving line is not a metaphysical claim about uncaused causes but a practical one about what blame is for. We do not blame people because we have first verified that their choices floated free of prior causes; we blame them because doing so is one of the few instruments available for shaping future conduct, in ourselves and in others. A society that abandoned responsibility every time causation was demonstrated would abandon it always, since causation is always demonstrable somewhere. The practice of holding people responsible survives, then, not because determinism is false but because responsibility was never really staked on its falsity in the first place."}, {"id": 905, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Why does the author reject the seed-and-soil metaphor for describing how nature and nurture shape character?", "options": {"A": "Because it wrongly implies environment matters more than genetics.", "B": "Because it suggests environment only intensifies or diminishes a fixed trajectory, whereas the evidence shows qualitative redirection.", "C": "Because plants and humans cannot be meaningfully compared in any scientific study.", "D": "Because it was proposed before genetics existed as a field of study."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage states that the seed-and-soil metaphor implies outcomes differ only in degree, whereas human traits can be redirected into qualitatively distinct outcomes depending on environment. This is a conceptual objection about what the metaphor implies, not a claim that it favours one factor over the other. The passage never argues that plants and humans are incomparable in principle, nor does it date the metaphor's origin.", "passage_id": "P227", "passage_title": "The Garden and the Seed", "passage_text": "The old metaphor of nature and nurture, seed and soil, has outlived its usefulness, not because either factor has been shown to be unimportant but because the metaphor implies a division of labour that the evidence no longer supports. A seed planted in poor soil grows into a stunted version of the same plant it would have become in rich soil; the outcome differs in degree, not in kind. Human character does not behave this way. Identical genetic dispositions, placed in different developmental environments, can issue in outcomes that are not merely stunted or flourishing versions of one another but qualitatively distinct, because the environment does not simply feed or starve a pre-set trajectory, it interacts with genetic tendencies at every stage to redirect them.\n\nConsider the trait of impulsivity, which twin studies suggest has a substantial heritable component. In a stable, resource-rich household, a genetic predisposition toward impulsivity may express itself as entrepreneurial risk-taking or creative spontaneity, traits a family and later a workplace can reward and refine. In a chaotic or resource-poor household, the same predisposition may express itself as difficulty with authority and poor long-term planning, traits that invite punishment and exclusion rather than refinement. The genes have not changed, and neither has some fixed underlying quantity of impulsiveness; what has changed is the entire behavioural shape that the trait takes.\n\nThis gene-environment interaction, and not any simple additive formula in which a percentage of character is assigned to biology and the remainder to upbringing, is what contemporary developmental science actually finds. It follows that the popular question of how much of character is nature and how much is nurture is not merely unanswered but malformed, rather like asking how much of a river's course is owed to the water and how much to the landscape it carves. Policy debates that proceed as though the two factors could be cleanly separated and independently adjusted, whether by genetic screening on one side or social intervention on the other, are working with a model of human development that the science underlying them has already abandoned."}, {"id": 913, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "Why does the author find the minimal group experiments unsettling?", "options": {"A": "Because they show that people are naturally violent toward outsiders.", "B": "Because they prove that group identity is entirely a modern invention.", "C": "Because participants in the experiments were not properly informed of the study's purpose.", "D": "Because favouritism appears even when every plausible external motive, such as history, competition, or reciprocity, has been removed."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage explains that the finding is unsettling because it removes every plausible external motive, including grievance, competition, kinship, and reciprocity, yet favouritism still appears. This suggests loyalty attaches to a group without needing a substantive reason to justify it. The passage says nothing about violence toward outsiders, the modernity of group identity, or the informed consent of participants.", "passage_id": "P229", "passage_title": "The Colours We Cannot Help Seeing", "passage_text": "Assign a group of strangers to a red team and a blue team on no basis more meaningful than a coin toss, and within minutes they will begin favouring their own colour in the allocation of rewards, even when no future interaction, reputation, or personal gain is at stake. This finding, replicated across decades of research under the banner of minimal group experiments, is unsettling precisely because it removes every plausible external motive. There is no history of grievance, no competition for scarce resources, no kinship, and no prospect of reciprocity, and yet favouritism appears all the same, suggesting that the psychological machinery of group loyalty does not wait for a reason to attach itself to a group; it manufactures one out of whatever distinction happens to be available.\n\nThis has uncomfortable implications for how we understand more consequential forms of tribalism, such as those organised around nationality, religion, or political party. It is tempting to think that such attachments are held for the substantive reasons people offer when pressed, that a nationalist believes their nation's institutions are genuinely superior, or a partisan believes their party's policies are genuinely wiser. The minimal group findings suggest a less flattering possibility: that at least part of the attachment precedes and outruns the reasons, and that the reasons function partly as retrospective decoration on a loyalty that would have found some other justification had history handed the group a different flag.\n\nNone of this implies that substantive reasons for group allegiance never exist, since nations and parties do differ in real and important ways that can justify preference. What it implies is that we should be suspicious of the confidence with which people report that their allegiance rests purely on those substantive differences, since the same psychological mechanism that produces baseless favouritism for an arbitrary colour is still operating underneath any allegiance to which we later attach better reasons. Recognising this does not dissolve loyalty, but it should temper the certainty with which loyalty is defended as the product of clear-eyed evaluation alone."}, {"id": 916, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What conclusion does the final paragraph draw about substantive reasons for group allegiance?", "options": {"A": "They never exist because all allegiance is reducible to the mechanism seen in minimal group experiments.", "B": "They are only relevant to religious groups and not to national or political ones.", "C": "They do exist and can be legitimate, but confidence that allegiance rests purely on them should be tempered.", "D": "They should be the sole basis on which people are permitted to justify their loyalties."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The final paragraph explicitly states that substantive reasons for group allegiance do exist since groups differ in real and important ways, while also urging suspicion of the confidence with which people claim their loyalty rests purely on those reasons. This rules out the claim that such reasons never exist. The passage does not restrict substantive reasons to religious groups, nor does it argue that only substantive reasons should ever be permitted to justify loyalty.", "passage_id": "P229", "passage_title": "The Colours We Cannot Help Seeing", "passage_text": "Assign a group of strangers to a red team and a blue team on no basis more meaningful than a coin toss, and within minutes they will begin favouring their own colour in the allocation of rewards, even when no future interaction, reputation, or personal gain is at stake. This finding, replicated across decades of research under the banner of minimal group experiments, is unsettling precisely because it removes every plausible external motive. There is no history of grievance, no competition for scarce resources, no kinship, and no prospect of reciprocity, and yet favouritism appears all the same, suggesting that the psychological machinery of group loyalty does not wait for a reason to attach itself to a group; it manufactures one out of whatever distinction happens to be available.\n\nThis has uncomfortable implications for how we understand more consequential forms of tribalism, such as those organised around nationality, religion, or political party. It is tempting to think that such attachments are held for the substantive reasons people offer when pressed, that a nationalist believes their nation's institutions are genuinely superior, or a partisan believes their party's policies are genuinely wiser. The minimal group findings suggest a less flattering possibility: that at least part of the attachment precedes and outruns the reasons, and that the reasons function partly as retrospective decoration on a loyalty that would have found some other justification had history handed the group a different flag.\n\nNone of this implies that substantive reasons for group allegiance never exist, since nations and parties do differ in real and important ways that can justify preference. What it implies is that we should be suspicious of the confidence with which people report that their allegiance rests purely on those substantive differences, since the same psychological mechanism that produces baseless favouritism for an arbitrary colour is still operating underneath any allegiance to which we later attach better reasons. Recognising this does not dissolve loyalty, but it should temper the certainty with which loyalty is defended as the product of clear-eyed evaluation alone."}, {"id": 917, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "According to the passage, why does the author reject the folk explanation that crowds make people callous?", "options": {"A": "Because the phenomenon has since been shown never to occur in real emergencies.", "B": "Because callousness would predict the opposite result, with larger crowds intervening more.", "C": "Because witnesses in the 1964 case were later shown to be entirely fictional.", "D": "Because the effect is explained instead by responsibility being distributed so thinly that no one feels its full weight."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage attributes the effect to the diffusion of psychological responsibility across witnesses rather than to any coldness of feeling produced by crowds. This directly replaces the folk explanation with a structural one about how responsibility is distributed. The passage does not claim the phenomenon never occurs, does not suggest callousness would predict more intervention, and does not describe the original witnesses as fictional, only that early reports were later complicated by investigation.", "passage_id": "P230", "passage_title": "Someone Else Will Call", "passage_text": "When a woman was murdered outside her New York apartment building in 1964, early reports claimed that dozens of neighbours heard her cries and did nothing, a story that later investigation complicated but did not entirely overturn. What the case fixed in the public imagination, and what subsequent laboratory research confirmed under more controlled conditions, is a genuine and reliable phenomenon: the more people who witness an emergency, the less likely any individual among them is to intervene. This is not, as the folk explanation would have it, because crowds make people callous. It is because the presence of others distributes the psychological weight of responsibility so thinly that no single witness feels the full force of it.\n\nThe mechanism operates through at least two distinct channels. The first is a diffusion of responsibility proper, in which each witness reasons, often without articulating it, that someone else is equally positioned to act, so that the moral burden of failing to act feels divided rather than borne alone. The second is social influence, in which each witness looks to the visible reactions of the others for a cue about whether the situation truly is an emergency, and a crowd of people all privately alarmed but outwardly composed can convince each member that the calm of the others is evidence there is nothing to worry about. Both channels can operate simultaneously, and their combined effect is stronger than either alone.\n\nWhat makes this finding valuable rather than merely dispiriting is that it identifies the failure as structural rather than characterological, and structural failures can be counteracted by structural means. Training that instructs bystanders to single out one specific individual and assign them a specific task, rather than appealing to the crowd in general, reliably increases intervention, because it artificially reinstates the concentrated responsibility that a crowd naturally dilutes. The lesson is not that people are indifferent to suffering when unobserved company is present, but that responsibility, like a liquid, will spread to fill whatever container of witnesses it is poured into unless something narrows the container back down."}, {"id": 919, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "How do the two channels of the bystander effect described in the second paragraph differ from one another?", "options": {"A": "The first depends entirely on the visible cues given off by others, while the second depends purely on quiet private moral reasoning conducted alone.", "B": "The first applies only to violent street crimes, while the second applies only to certain rare medical emergencies encountered by ordinary bystanders nearby.", "C": "The first is used only to train ordinary bystanders in the field, while the second is used only within tightly controlled laboratory settings.", "D": "The first involves each witness assuming others share equal responsibility, while the second involves each witness reading the outward calm of others as a signal of safety."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage describes diffusion of responsibility as witnesses privately assuming others are equally positioned to act, while social influence involves witnesses reading each other's outward composure as evidence that no emergency exists. This is the reverse of option A, which swaps which channel depends on visible cues and which depends on private reasoning. The passage does not restrict either channel to a particular type of emergency, nor does it say one channel is used only for training and the other only in laboratories.", "passage_id": "P230", "passage_title": "Someone Else Will Call", "passage_text": "When a woman was murdered outside her New York apartment building in 1964, early reports claimed that dozens of neighbours heard her cries and did nothing, a story that later investigation complicated but did not entirely overturn. What the case fixed in the public imagination, and what subsequent laboratory research confirmed under more controlled conditions, is a genuine and reliable phenomenon: the more people who witness an emergency, the less likely any individual among them is to intervene. This is not, as the folk explanation would have it, because crowds make people callous. It is because the presence of others distributes the psychological weight of responsibility so thinly that no single witness feels the full force of it.\n\nThe mechanism operates through at least two distinct channels. The first is a diffusion of responsibility proper, in which each witness reasons, often without articulating it, that someone else is equally positioned to act, so that the moral burden of failing to act feels divided rather than borne alone. The second is social influence, in which each witness looks to the visible reactions of the others for a cue about whether the situation truly is an emergency, and a crowd of people all privately alarmed but outwardly composed can convince each member that the calm of the others is evidence there is nothing to worry about. Both channels can operate simultaneously, and their combined effect is stronger than either alone.\n\nWhat makes this finding valuable rather than merely dispiriting is that it identifies the failure as structural rather than characterological, and structural failures can be counteracted by structural means. Training that instructs bystanders to single out one specific individual and assign them a specific task, rather than appealing to the crowd in general, reliably increases intervention, because it artificially reinstates the concentrated responsibility that a crowd naturally dilutes. The lesson is not that people are indifferent to suffering when unobserved company is present, but that responsibility, like a liquid, will spread to fill whatever container of witnesses it is poured into unless something narrows the container back down."}, {"id": 920, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Why does the author describe the bystander effect as a structural failure rather than a characterological one?", "options": {"A": "Because bystanders are always legally required to intervene directly in emergencies regardless of how large the crowd actually is.", "B": "Because the 1964 case conclusively proved beyond doubt that every single witness present was of good moral character.", "C": "Because laboratory studies are simply and permanently unable to distinguish between structural and characterological explanations of human behaviour.", "D": "Because the failure arises from how responsibility is distributed among witnesses, which structural interventions like assigning a specific task can correct."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage explains that framing the failure as structural rather than characterological matters because structural failures can be counteracted by structural means, such as assigning one witness a specific task. This framing is offered as valuable precisely because it points toward practical fixes rather than judgments about individual character. The passage makes no claim about legal duties to intervene, does not treat the 1964 witnesses as having proven good character, and does not suggest laboratory studies are unable to distinguish the two types of explanation.", "passage_id": "P230", "passage_title": "Someone Else Will Call", "passage_text": "When a woman was murdered outside her New York apartment building in 1964, early reports claimed that dozens of neighbours heard her cries and did nothing, a story that later investigation complicated but did not entirely overturn. What the case fixed in the public imagination, and what subsequent laboratory research confirmed under more controlled conditions, is a genuine and reliable phenomenon: the more people who witness an emergency, the less likely any individual among them is to intervene. This is not, as the folk explanation would have it, because crowds make people callous. It is because the presence of others distributes the psychological weight of responsibility so thinly that no single witness feels the full force of it.\n\nThe mechanism operates through at least two distinct channels. The first is a diffusion of responsibility proper, in which each witness reasons, often without articulating it, that someone else is equally positioned to act, so that the moral burden of failing to act feels divided rather than borne alone. The second is social influence, in which each witness looks to the visible reactions of the others for a cue about whether the situation truly is an emergency, and a crowd of people all privately alarmed but outwardly composed can convince each member that the calm of the others is evidence there is nothing to worry about. Both channels can operate simultaneously, and their combined effect is stronger than either alone.\n\nWhat makes this finding valuable rather than merely dispiriting is that it identifies the failure as structural rather than characterological, and structural failures can be counteracted by structural means. Training that instructs bystanders to single out one specific individual and assign them a specific task, rather than appealing to the crowd in general, reliably increases intervention, because it artificially reinstates the concentrated responsibility that a crowd naturally dilutes. The lesson is not that people are indifferent to suffering when unobserved company is present, but that responsibility, like a liquid, will spread to fill whatever container of witnesses it is poured into unless something narrows the container back down."}, {"id": 921, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What does the author identify as the 'curious inversion' produced by the behavioural turn in economics?", "options": {"A": "One flawed model of human reasoning was replaced by an equally exaggerated opposite model.", "B": "Economists abandoned mathematics entirely in favour of psychology and qualitative case studies.", "C": "Rational choice theory was ultimately proven correct after decades of behavioural criticism.", "D": "Behavioural economists became measurably more rational than the subjects they studied."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage describes the classical assumption of a coolly calculating agent being replaced by an assumption that people are little more than a bundle of glitches, and calls both pictures caricatures. This is presented as an inversion because one exaggeration simply supplanted another rather than yielding a balanced view. The other options either misstate the shift or attribute claims the passage never makes.", "passage_id": "P231", "passage_title": "The Architecture of Error", "passage_text": "For a discipline that prides itself on modelling rational agents, economics spent a surprisingly long time ignoring how people actually think. The behavioural turn of the last four decades has corrected this, but in doing so it has produced a curious inversion. Where the classical economist assumed a being who calculates costs and benefits with cool precision, the new orthodoxy risks assuming a being who is little more than a bundle of glitches, forever anchored by irrelevant numbers, swayed by how a choice is phrased, and blind to its own blind spots.\n\nBoth pictures are caricatures, but the second is the more seductive because it flatters the observer. To catalogue another person's biases is to imply, tacitly, that one has escaped them oneself. Yet the very psychologists who identified confirmation bias, the tendency to seek out evidence that supports what we already believe, have been shown to display it when defending their own theories against rival explanations. The irony is not that they are hypocrites; it is that the bias is not a flaw bolted onto an otherwise sound cognitive machine. It is close to the machine's normal operating mode.\n\nThis matters because the popular response to bias research has been remedial: teach people the names of the biases, list them like sins, and expect the naming to inoculate against the disease. There is scant evidence this works. Knowing that anchoring exists does not stop a shopper from being swayed by an inflated original price beside a discounted one. The bias operates beneath the level of the deliberate, propositional reasoning that a lecture addresses, which is precisely why it survives contact with education so well.\n\nA more honest response accepts that rationality is not a default state disturbed by occasional error but an achievement, assembled from favourable environments as much as from personal discipline. Checklists, second opinions, structured deliberation and enforced delay before high stakes decisions do more work than any amount of self-knowledge, because they change the situation rather than relying on a mind to overrule itself in real time. The lesson of bias research, properly understood, is not that people are foolish. It is that good judgement is an engineering problem as much as a moral one, and the fix belongs in the design of our decisions rather than in the diagnosis of our characters."}, {"id": 925, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the central objection critics raise against calling libertarian paternalism a form of freedom preservation?", "options": {"A": "It quietly removes choices that people previously had genuinely available to them well beforehand.", "B": "It costs governments and taxpayers far too much money to design and implement this policy effectively.", "C": "The defence relies on treating an exploited tendency to stay passive as if it were genuine consent.", "D": "It has been shown not to change behaviour in any practical setting at all."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage states that critics see the defence as trading on an ambiguity, since a default chosen to exploit inertia produces an outcome that is only technically free, with revealed preference amounting to inertia rather than considered consent. No option is removed under this scheme, cost is not raised as an objection, and the passage assumes the approach is effective rather than disputing this. The objection concerns the meaning of freedom, not the mechanics or expense of the policy.", "passage_id": "P232", "passage_title": "The Quiet Hand", "passage_text": "Governments have discovered a tool more delicate than the law and more powerful than persuasion. By changing the order in which options are presented, the wording of a default, or the visibility of a healthier choice on a menu, policymakers can shift behaviour at population scale without banning anything or spending much money. Enrolling employees automatically into a pension scheme, with the option to opt out, raises participation rates far more reliably than encouraging them to opt in ever did, even though the underlying menu of choices is identical. The architecture of the choice, not its content, does the work.\n\nDefenders of this approach, sometimes called libertarian paternalism, insist that it preserves freedom while correcting for the fact that human decision making is not the frictionless process economic models once assumed. Nobody is forced to save for retirement; they are merely required to make an active choice to decline. Critics reply that this defence trades on an ambiguity. If a default is chosen precisely because it exploits inertia, a well documented tendency to stick with whatever requires no action, then calling the outcome free is a technicality. The subject's revealed preference may simply be inertia dressed up as consent.\n\nA further worry concerns who gets to design the choice architecture and by what standard. A default that improves retirement saving seems benign because most people would endorse the goal on reflection. But the same techniques that steer a shopper toward a pension can steer a citizen toward a political preference or a consumer toward an expensive subscription that renews unless cancelled. The method is neutral between good and bad ends, which is precisely why enthusiasm for it should be tempered by scrutiny of the institution wielding it rather than admiration for its efficiency.\n\nThe most defensible version of nudging, then, is not the claim that steering behaviour respects autonomy simply because no option is removed. It is the narrower claim that when a default must be set regardless, because doing nothing is itself a choice with consequences, it should be set by whichever option the well informed person would pick for themselves. That standard is demanding, and it rules out a great many nudges that would otherwise pass an easier test of merely leaving choice formally intact."}, {"id": 936, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "What is suggested by the author's description of cooperative disposition as 'a standing offer, renewed each time others appear to honour their side of it and revoked the instant they do not'?", "options": {"A": "That cooperation is a fixed personality trait unaffected by circumstance.", "B": "That cooperation is contingent and actively responsive to perceived behaviour of others.", "C": "That cooperation is a legal contract enforceable only in court.", "D": "That people cooperate only when directly rewarded with money."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The image of an offer that is renewed or revoked captures a disposition that is conditional and continuously responsive to evidence about others, matching the passage's broader claim that people withdraw sharply once they suspect exploitation. This directly opposes the idea of cooperation as a fixed, circumstance-proof trait. The phrase is figurative rather than a claim about formal legal contracts or monetary reward specifically.", "passage_id": "P234", "passage_title": "The Ledger and the Gift", "passage_text": "Every generation rediscovers the argument between two pictures of human nature and mistakes its rediscovery for a new insight. In one picture, cooperation is a thin veneer over an engine of self-interest, sustained only because it happens to pay, through reputation, reciprocity, or fear of punishment. Strip away the enforcement and the veneer cracks; underneath, the argument goes, lies a calculator tallying costs and benefits to itself alone. In the other picture, human beings are cooperative by original disposition, and selfishness is what emerges when scarcity, threat, or bad institutions corrode an otherwise generous nature.\n\nThe evidence sits awkwardly for both extremes. Laboratory games in which subjects can punish free riders at a cost to themselves, gaining nothing material from the punishment, are difficult to explain on a purely self-interested account, since the calculator has no reason to spend its own resources enforcing a norm from which it will not benefit. Yet the same experiments show contribution rates collapsing when punishment is removed, which is equally awkward for a picture of innate generosity requiring no external support. Neither pure selfishness nor pure altruism survives contact with the data intact.\n\nA more useful picture treats humans as conditional cooperators: disposed to contribute generously so long as they believe others are doing the same, and to withdraw sharply, sometimes punitively, the moment they suspect they are being exploited. This disposition is neither the cynic's calculator nor the romantic's natural saint. It is closer to a standing offer, renewed each time others appear to honour their side of it and revoked the instant they do not. Framed this way, most apparent selfishness in institutions is not evidence of an innately selfish species but evidence of a cooperative disposition that has detected, rightly or wrongly, that it is being taken for a fool.\n\nThis has a practical upshot that both camps tend to miss. Since cooperation depends so heavily on the visible behaviour of others, institutions that make free riding conspicuous and cooperation legible do more to sustain generosity than any appeal to character, on either side of the debate, ever could. The question of what people are like in some pure, isolated state may be unanswerable and beside the point; what matters is what conditions bring out."}, {"id": 947, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What does the passage suggest about two people who examine the same evidence on a contested political issue?", "options": {"A": "They will always reach the correct conclusion if they reason carefully.", "B": "They cannot form any opinion without algorithmic influence.", "C": "They will necessarily agree once shown identical evidence.", "D": "They may reach opposite conclusions due to differing standards of scrutiny."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage explains that two people exposed to identical evidence can reach opposite conclusions because each applies a different standard of proof to claims that flatter or challenge their existing view. This contradicts any suggestion that shared evidence guarantees agreement or correctness, since the passage emphasizes unequal scrutiny rather than reasoning quality. Algorithmic influence is discussed separately from this specific claim about shared evidence.", "passage_id": "P237", "passage_title": "The Comfort of Being Right", "passage_text": "Confirmation bias, the tendency to notice, accept, and recall information that supports what one already believes while overlooking or discounting what does not, was once studied mainly as a curiosity of individual reasoning. It appeared in laboratory tasks where subjects, asked to test a rule, sought examples that would confirm their initial guess rather than examples that might refute it. In the context of political belief, however, the same tendency operates with far higher stakes and far greater social reinforcement, and it is here that its consequences for public life become most visible.\n\nWhen a claim touches on group identity, whether over immigration, economic policy or the causes of some contested event, people do not process it as a neutral fact to be weighed but as a signal of loyalty to be evaluated. A story that flatters one's own side is shared and remembered; a story that flatters the other side is scrutinised for flaws, and often flaws are found, since almost any complex claim contains some imperfection if one searches hard enough for it. This asymmetry of scrutiny means that two people exposed to the same body of evidence can emerge from it holding opposite conclusions, each convinced that the evidence has vindicated their prior view, since neither one is applying the same standard of proof to congenial and uncongenial claims alike.\n\nSocial media accelerates this dynamic rather than creating it, since algorithms that maximise engagement will naturally surface content a user is likely to approve of and share, producing an environment in which confirming evidence arrives constantly while disconfirming evidence must be actively sought out. The result is not that people become unable to encounter opposing arguments, since such arguments remain widely available to anyone who looks, but that the cost of encountering them rises relative to the ease of encountering agreement. Polarisation, on this account, is less a matter of people believing outright falsehoods than of a systematic imbalance in how rigorously true and false-seeming claims are each interrogated, an imbalance that hardens over time as each side accumulates a store of confirming instances that feels, from the inside, indistinguishable from careful reasoning."}, {"id": 953, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the overall relationship the passage draws between willed self-improvement and personality change?", "options": {"A": "Willed self-improvement is the only reliable path to lasting personality change.", "B": "Personality cannot change under any circumstances, willed or otherwise.", "C": "Willed self-improvement works only when combined with serious illness or trauma.", "D": "Willed self-improvement alone is less effective than change driven by new social roles."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage argues that direct willed effort to change personality, without an accompanying shift in circumstance, is unlikely to succeed on its own, while entering new roles that demand a trait produces more durable change. This is not the same as claiming willed effort is the only reliable path, since the passage argues almost the opposite. It also does not claim personality is entirely fixed or that willed change only works alongside trauma, since neither claim appears in the passage.", "passage_id": "P239", "passage_title": "How Much of You Is Negotiable", "passage_text": "For most of the twentieth century, personality psychologists tended to describe traits such as extraversion, conscientiousness and emotional stability as remarkably stable across adulthood, changing little after early adulthood except in response to serious illness or trauma. This stability was taken as evidence that personality reflects something close to a biological set point, useful for predicting behaviour across decades but resistant to any deliberate effort at revision. Self-help literature promising rapid personal transformation was, on this view, selling something the underlying psychology could not really deliver.\n\nMore recent longitudinal research complicates this picture without overturning it entirely. Large studies that track the same individuals over many years do find modest but consistent shifts in average trait levels, with most people becoming somewhat more conscientious and emotionally stable and somewhat less extraverted as they age, a pattern robust enough to appear across different cultures and unrelated to any single life event. This suggests that personality is not fixed in the way a physical trait like height is fixed, but neither does it drift as freely as mood or opinion; it behaves more like a slow tide than either a stone or a wave.\n\nWhat seems to move the tide, when it moves faster than the typical gradual pattern, is sustained change in social role and circumstance rather than willed self-improvement in the abstract. People who take on a demanding job, become a parent, or enter a stable long-term relationship show larger shifts in relevant traits, such as increased conscientiousness following the assumption of new responsibilities, than people who simply resolve to become more conscientious without any accompanying change in circumstance. This implies that direct effort to change one's personality, unaccompanied by a change in the situations that call for and reward different behaviour, is unlikely to succeed by itself, whereas placing oneself deliberately into roles that demand a given trait may produce more durable change than introspection or resolution alone. Personality change, in other words, may be real and available to most people, but it appears to travel through altered circumstance rather than through direct, willed transformation of the self."}, {"id": 955, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "According to the passage, what typically produces the largest shifts in personality traits?", "options": {"A": "Sustained changes in social role, such as beginning a demanding job or a new relationship.", "B": "Reading self-help literature that promises rapid and effortless personal transformation to readers.", "C": "Simply resolving, without any further action, to become a completely different kind of person.", "D": "The natural passage of time alone, regardless of any accompanying circumstance whatsoever."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage states that people who take on a demanding job, become a parent, or enter a stable relationship show larger trait shifts than those who merely resolve to change without any accompanying circumstance. This directly contradicts the idea that self-help literature or bare resolution alone produces the largest shifts, since the passage treats those as less effective. Mere passage of time is described as producing only modest, gradual shifts, not the largest ones referenced.", "passage_id": "P239", "passage_title": "How Much of You Is Negotiable", "passage_text": "For most of the twentieth century, personality psychologists tended to describe traits such as extraversion, conscientiousness and emotional stability as remarkably stable across adulthood, changing little after early adulthood except in response to serious illness or trauma. This stability was taken as evidence that personality reflects something close to a biological set point, useful for predicting behaviour across decades but resistant to any deliberate effort at revision. Self-help literature promising rapid personal transformation was, on this view, selling something the underlying psychology could not really deliver.\n\nMore recent longitudinal research complicates this picture without overturning it entirely. Large studies that track the same individuals over many years do find modest but consistent shifts in average trait levels, with most people becoming somewhat more conscientious and emotionally stable and somewhat less extraverted as they age, a pattern robust enough to appear across different cultures and unrelated to any single life event. This suggests that personality is not fixed in the way a physical trait like height is fixed, but neither does it drift as freely as mood or opinion; it behaves more like a slow tide than either a stone or a wave.\n\nWhat seems to move the tide, when it moves faster than the typical gradual pattern, is sustained change in social role and circumstance rather than willed self-improvement in the abstract. People who take on a demanding job, become a parent, or enter a stable long-term relationship show larger shifts in relevant traits, such as increased conscientiousness following the assumption of new responsibilities, than people who simply resolve to become more conscientious without any accompanying change in circumstance. This implies that direct effort to change one's personality, unaccompanied by a change in the situations that call for and reward different behaviour, is unlikely to succeed by itself, whereas placing oneself deliberately into roles that demand a given trait may produce more durable change than introspection or resolution alone. Personality change, in other words, may be real and available to most people, but it appears to travel through altered circumstance rather than through direct, willed transformation of the self."}, {"id": 957, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the main point the passage makes using brain imaging evidence?", "options": {"A": "It proves that all patient reports of improvement are unreliable.", "B": "It challenges the view that the placebo effect is merely a reporting artefact.", "C": "It shows that placebo treatments work as well as antibiotics.", "D": "It demonstrates that expectation has no physiological basis at all."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage cites brain imaging showing measurable changes in pain-modulating pathways specifically to counter the dismissal of placebo effects as mere reporting bias or politeness. It does not claim all patient reports are unreliable, since the argument moves in the opposite direction, and it does not claim placebo treatments rival antibiotics, a comparison introduced later only to mark the limits of the effect. It also does not deny expectation a physiological basis, since the whole point is that imaging reveals one.", "passage_id": "P240", "passage_title": "What the Sugar Pill Reveals", "passage_text": "That an inert pill can relieve pain, ease nausea or lift depressed mood, provided the patient believes it to be an active medicine, is among the most reliably replicated findings in medicine, and yet it remains one of the least understood. The placebo effect is often dismissed as a mere artefact of measurement, as if patients who report improvement after a sham treatment were simply being polite to researchers or misremembering how bad their symptoms had been. This dismissal, however, sits uneasily beside evidence from brain imaging, which shows that placebo analgesia is accompanied by measurable changes in regions associated with the body's own pain-modulating pathways, changes that a mere reporting bias could not produce.\n\nWhat the placebo effect appears to demonstrate is that expectation is not simply a psychological add-on to an otherwise separate biological process but is itself one of the inputs that shapes that process. A patient who expects relief and receives a convincing ritual of treatment, complete with a clinician's attention, a plausible-sounding explanation, and a physical object to take, undergoes measurable neurochemical changes that overlap substantially with those produced by some active drugs. This is not to say the placebo effect can substitute for antibiotics against a bacterial infection or for insulin in diabetes, where the underlying pathology does not respond to expectation regardless of how convincingly it is staged. Its influence is largest precisely in conditions, such as pain, nausea and mood, where the brain's own regulatory systems are already part of the mechanism being treated.\n\nThe practical implication is not that inert treatments should be substituted for effective ones, which would be both unethical and ineffective outside this narrow range of conditions, but that the ritual and relationship surrounding any treatment, active or not, are doing real physiological work that clinical practice often ignores. A rushed consultation delivering an effective drug with no explanation and no reassurance may achieve a smaller total effect than the same drug delivered with attention and a credible account of how it will help, since the expectation component adds to, rather than merely accompanies, the pharmacological one. The placebo effect, properly understood, is less a nuisance to be controlled out of drug trials than a demonstration of how thoroughly mind and body are entangled in the production of symptoms and their relief."}, {"id": 959, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "What practical conclusion does the passage draw about clinical practice?", "options": {"A": "Inert treatments should replace active drugs whenever a patient requests it be done.", "B": "Explanation and reassurance make no measurable difference at all to treatment outcomes.", "C": "The manner in which an effective treatment is delivered can add to its total effect.", "D": "Rushed consultations always produce outcomes identical to those of far more attentive consultations."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage concludes that the ritual and relationship surrounding a treatment can add to its pharmacological effect, so a drug delivered with attention and explanation may outperform the same drug delivered without them. This is not a recommendation to replace active drugs with inert ones, which the passage explicitly calls unethical outside narrow conditions, nor does it claim explanation makes no difference, since the opposite is argued. It also does not claim rushed and attentive consultations produce identical outcomes, since the passage contrasts them directly.", "passage_id": "P240", "passage_title": "What the Sugar Pill Reveals", "passage_text": "That an inert pill can relieve pain, ease nausea or lift depressed mood, provided the patient believes it to be an active medicine, is among the most reliably replicated findings in medicine, and yet it remains one of the least understood. The placebo effect is often dismissed as a mere artefact of measurement, as if patients who report improvement after a sham treatment were simply being polite to researchers or misremembering how bad their symptoms had been. This dismissal, however, sits uneasily beside evidence from brain imaging, which shows that placebo analgesia is accompanied by measurable changes in regions associated with the body's own pain-modulating pathways, changes that a mere reporting bias could not produce.\n\nWhat the placebo effect appears to demonstrate is that expectation is not simply a psychological add-on to an otherwise separate biological process but is itself one of the inputs that shapes that process. A patient who expects relief and receives a convincing ritual of treatment, complete with a clinician's attention, a plausible-sounding explanation, and a physical object to take, undergoes measurable neurochemical changes that overlap substantially with those produced by some active drugs. This is not to say the placebo effect can substitute for antibiotics against a bacterial infection or for insulin in diabetes, where the underlying pathology does not respond to expectation regardless of how convincingly it is staged. Its influence is largest precisely in conditions, such as pain, nausea and mood, where the brain's own regulatory systems are already part of the mechanism being treated.\n\nThe practical implication is not that inert treatments should be substituted for effective ones, which would be both unethical and ineffective outside this narrow range of conditions, but that the ritual and relationship surrounding any treatment, active or not, are doing real physiological work that clinical practice often ignores. A rushed consultation delivering an effective drug with no explanation and no reassurance may achieve a smaller total effect than the same drug delivered with attention and a credible account of how it will help, since the expectation component adds to, rather than merely accompanies, the pharmacological one. The placebo effect, properly understood, is less a nuisance to be controlled out of drug trials than a demonstration of how thoroughly mind and body are entangled in the production of symptoms and their relief."}, {"id": 960, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase \"mind and body are entangled\" is used near the end of the passage mainly to emphasize:", "options": {"A": "that psychological expectation and physiological response are deeply interconnected rather than separate.", "B": "that the mind can fully replace the body's need for medicine.", "C": "that physiological processes are entirely independent of belief.", "D": "that entanglement is a scientifically unproven and speculative idea."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The phrase is used to stress that psychological expectation and bodily response are not separate tracks but are interwoven in producing symptoms and relief, which is the passage's central claim throughout. It does not suggest the mind can replace medicine outright, since earlier text explicitly denies this for conditions like infection. It also does not suggest physiological processes are independent of belief or that entanglement is unproven, both of which contradict the evidence the passage presents.", "passage_id": "P240", "passage_title": "What the Sugar Pill Reveals", "passage_text": "That an inert pill can relieve pain, ease nausea or lift depressed mood, provided the patient believes it to be an active medicine, is among the most reliably replicated findings in medicine, and yet it remains one of the least understood. The placebo effect is often dismissed as a mere artefact of measurement, as if patients who report improvement after a sham treatment were simply being polite to researchers or misremembering how bad their symptoms had been. This dismissal, however, sits uneasily beside evidence from brain imaging, which shows that placebo analgesia is accompanied by measurable changes in regions associated with the body's own pain-modulating pathways, changes that a mere reporting bias could not produce.\n\nWhat the placebo effect appears to demonstrate is that expectation is not simply a psychological add-on to an otherwise separate biological process but is itself one of the inputs that shapes that process. A patient who expects relief and receives a convincing ritual of treatment, complete with a clinician's attention, a plausible-sounding explanation, and a physical object to take, undergoes measurable neurochemical changes that overlap substantially with those produced by some active drugs. This is not to say the placebo effect can substitute for antibiotics against a bacterial infection or for insulin in diabetes, where the underlying pathology does not respond to expectation regardless of how convincingly it is staged. Its influence is largest precisely in conditions, such as pain, nausea and mood, where the brain's own regulatory systems are already part of the mechanism being treated.\n\nThe practical implication is not that inert treatments should be substituted for effective ones, which would be both unethical and ineffective outside this narrow range of conditions, but that the ritual and relationship surrounding any treatment, active or not, are doing real physiological work that clinical practice often ignores. A rushed consultation delivering an effective drug with no explanation and no reassurance may achieve a smaller total effect than the same drug delivered with attention and a credible account of how it will help, since the expectation component adds to, rather than merely accompanies, the pharmacological one. The placebo effect, properly understood, is less a nuisance to be controlled out of drug trials than a demonstration of how thoroughly mind and body are entangled in the production of symptoms and their relief."}, {"id": 965, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "What is the main claim of the passage regarding factual disagreement between supporters?", "options": {"A": "People often dispute plain facts because identity, not evidence, drives their reasoning.", "B": "People dispute facts mainly because the media reports statistics inaccurately.", "C": "Supporters agree on facts but differ only in preferred policy solutions.", "D": "Facts about unemployment are inherently more ambiguous than sporting decisions."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage's central claim is that disagreement over facts admitting a single correct answer arises because reasoning is driven by group identity and belonging rather than by the evidence itself. It illustrates this through both the stadium example and the political example, showing the same backward reasoning in each. The final section reinforces this by showing that supplying more accurate information fails to resolve the disagreement, which would not be expected if the dispute were purely factual in origin.", "passage_id": "P242", "passage_title": "The Grammar of Sides", "passage_text": "Watch a stadium crowd turn on a linesman whose flag has, by any neutral replay, been raised correctly, and you witness a psychological mechanism far older than the offside rule. Supporters do not process the decision as an isolated fact to be weighed against video evidence; they process it as an act committed against their side, and the reasoning that follows works backward from loyalty to justification rather than forward from evidence to conclusion. Precisely the same mechanism operates, with graver consequences, in the fortunes of political parties.\n\nVoters presented with identical economic data, a rise in unemployment say, will interpret it in strikingly different ways depending on which party currently holds office and which party they themselves support. A supporter of the governing party will note temporary global headwinds beyond any minister's control; a supporter of the opposition will see it as proof of incompetence long suspected. What is remarkable is not that people disagree about policy, which is only to be expected, but that they disagree about the plain facts underlying it, facts that in principle admit of a single correct answer.\n\nSocial psychologists have long attributed this to the drive to belong, the sense that one's identity is bound up with the group's standing rather than merely with one's private opinions. To concede that one's team's supporters behaved badly, or that one's party's policy has failed, is experienced not as an update to a belief but as a small betrayal of the tribe, and betrayal carries a social cost that a mere factual correction does not. The brain, faced with a choice between accuracy and belonging, appears reliably to favour the latter.\n\nIt would be comforting to think that better information could dissolve this loyalty, that supplying fans with slow motion replays or voters with verified statistics would gradually correct the bias. The evidence points the other way: partisans shown corrective information often emerge more confident in their original view, not less, having generated new reasons to dismiss the correction as itself partisan. This suggests that tribal loyalty is not a deficiency of information but a feature of how identity is constructed, one that facts alone are poorly equipped to dismantle."}, {"id": 968, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'working backward from loyalty to justification' emphasizes that", "options": {"A": "conclusions are fixed first and reasons are supplied to fit them afterward.", "B": "loyalty and justification are two separate processes of equal importance.", "C": "supporters justify their loyalty using slow motion technology.", "D": "political reasoning is more backward than sporting reasoning."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "This phrase is contrasted directly with reasoning forward from evidence to conclusion, marking a reversal in the usual order of rational judgment. It suggests that the supporter's conclusion, that their side has been wronged, comes first and the search for reasons follows afterward to support it. This reading is confirmed later in the passage when corrective evidence fails to change minds and instead prompts new justifications for the original view.", "passage_id": "P242", "passage_title": "The Grammar of Sides", "passage_text": "Watch a stadium crowd turn on a linesman whose flag has, by any neutral replay, been raised correctly, and you witness a psychological mechanism far older than the offside rule. Supporters do not process the decision as an isolated fact to be weighed against video evidence; they process it as an act committed against their side, and the reasoning that follows works backward from loyalty to justification rather than forward from evidence to conclusion. Precisely the same mechanism operates, with graver consequences, in the fortunes of political parties.\n\nVoters presented with identical economic data, a rise in unemployment say, will interpret it in strikingly different ways depending on which party currently holds office and which party they themselves support. A supporter of the governing party will note temporary global headwinds beyond any minister's control; a supporter of the opposition will see it as proof of incompetence long suspected. What is remarkable is not that people disagree about policy, which is only to be expected, but that they disagree about the plain facts underlying it, facts that in principle admit of a single correct answer.\n\nSocial psychologists have long attributed this to the drive to belong, the sense that one's identity is bound up with the group's standing rather than merely with one's private opinions. To concede that one's team's supporters behaved badly, or that one's party's policy has failed, is experienced not as an update to a belief but as a small betrayal of the tribe, and betrayal carries a social cost that a mere factual correction does not. The brain, faced with a choice between accuracy and belonging, appears reliably to favour the latter.\n\nIt would be comforting to think that better information could dissolve this loyalty, that supplying fans with slow motion replays or voters with verified statistics would gradually correct the bias. The evidence points the other way: partisans shown corrective information often emerge more confident in their original view, not less, having generated new reasons to dismiss the correction as itself partisan. This suggests that tribal loyalty is not a deficiency of information but a feature of how identity is constructed, one that facts alone are poorly equipped to dismantle."}, {"id": 970, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The statistic on DNA exonerations is introduced chiefly to", "options": {"A": "suggest that DNA evidence is itself sometimes unreliable.", "B": "show that most witnesses deliberately lie under oath.", "C": "argue that lineups should be replaced with photographs.", "D": "provide evidence that mistaken identification is a leading cause of wrongful conviction."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The statistic is presented directly after the discussion of memory's reconstructive nature to give concrete, real-world evidence that mistaken identification is not merely a laboratory curiosity. It is described as outweighing any other single cause of wrongful conviction, which supports the passage's broader argument that confident testimony is being trusted more than the science justifies. The passage explicitly notes the witnesses were not lying, which rules out deliberate dishonesty as the intended point.", "passage_id": "P243", "passage_title": "Confident, and Wrong", "passage_text": "Jurors place extraordinary weight on the confidence with which a witness identifies a defendant, and it is not difficult to see why. A witness who hesitates, who qualifies their identification with careful uncertainty, seems less trustworthy than one who points across the courtroom without a flicker of doubt. The trouble is that confidence and accuracy, while correlated under carefully controlled laboratory conditions, come apart badly in the messier circumstances of an actual crime, and it is precisely those circumstances that make eyewitness testimony least reliable and most persuasive at once.\n\nMemory, contrary to the intuitive picture of a video recording stored intact and replayed on demand, is reconstructive. Each recollection is assembled afresh from fragments, filled in with plausible detail, and subtly reshaped by whatever information reaches the witness after the event, a police officer's stray comment, a photograph glimpsed in a lineup, even the retelling of the story to a sympathetic friend. None of this reshaping feels to the witness like distortion; it feels like remembering, which is exactly what makes it dangerous in a courtroom.\n\nStudies of exonerations secured through DNA evidence have found mistaken eyewitness identification present in a substantial majority of cases, far outweighing any other single cause of wrongful conviction. What is striking about many of these cases is that the witness was not lying, nor even especially careless; the witness genuinely believed the identification to be correct, often becoming more certain with each retelling long after the trial had concluded. Certainty, it turns out, can grow through repetition and social reinforcement quite independently of whether the underlying memory was accurate to begin with.\n\nNone of this implies that eyewitness testimony should be discarded altogether, since in many cases it remains the only evidence available and is sometimes accurate. What it does imply is that the legal system's habit of treating a confident witness as a reliable one rests on a psychological assumption that the science does not support. A more defensible practice would weigh eyewitness testimony as one fallible strand among others, corroborated wherever possible, rather than as the decisive proof it is so often taken to be."}, {"id": 971, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "The claim that reshaped memory 'feels like remembering' is used to explain why", "options": {"A": "witnesses often lie deliberately to please investigators.", "B": "witnesses cannot detect their own memory's distortion from the inside.", "C": "juries are trained to distrust overly confident witnesses.", "D": "police officers rarely comment on a witness's identification."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "This claim follows the description of memory being reshaped by post-event information without the witness experiencing this as distortion. Its purpose is to explain why the resulting false confidence is so convincing, since the witness has no internal signal that their memory has been altered. This supports the later point that certainty can grow through retelling regardless of accuracy, since the witness has no way to distinguish a genuine memory from a reconstructed one.", "passage_id": "P243", "passage_title": "Confident, and Wrong", "passage_text": "Jurors place extraordinary weight on the confidence with which a witness identifies a defendant, and it is not difficult to see why. A witness who hesitates, who qualifies their identification with careful uncertainty, seems less trustworthy than one who points across the courtroom without a flicker of doubt. The trouble is that confidence and accuracy, while correlated under carefully controlled laboratory conditions, come apart badly in the messier circumstances of an actual crime, and it is precisely those circumstances that make eyewitness testimony least reliable and most persuasive at once.\n\nMemory, contrary to the intuitive picture of a video recording stored intact and replayed on demand, is reconstructive. Each recollection is assembled afresh from fragments, filled in with plausible detail, and subtly reshaped by whatever information reaches the witness after the event, a police officer's stray comment, a photograph glimpsed in a lineup, even the retelling of the story to a sympathetic friend. None of this reshaping feels to the witness like distortion; it feels like remembering, which is exactly what makes it dangerous in a courtroom.\n\nStudies of exonerations secured through DNA evidence have found mistaken eyewitness identification present in a substantial majority of cases, far outweighing any other single cause of wrongful conviction. What is striking about many of these cases is that the witness was not lying, nor even especially careless; the witness genuinely believed the identification to be correct, often becoming more certain with each retelling long after the trial had concluded. Certainty, it turns out, can grow through repetition and social reinforcement quite independently of whether the underlying memory was accurate to begin with.\n\nNone of this implies that eyewitness testimony should be discarded altogether, since in many cases it remains the only evidence available and is sometimes accurate. What it does imply is that the legal system's habit of treating a confident witness as a reliable one rests on a psychological assumption that the science does not support. A more defensible practice would weigh eyewitness testimony as one fallible strand among others, corroborated wherever possible, rather than as the decisive proof it is so often taken to be."}, {"id": 977, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "Which best captures the passage's central argument about adversity and character?", "options": {"A": "Adversity builds character only when enough support and control are present.", "B": "Adversity always builds character regardless of how it is endured.", "C": "Adversity never has any lasting positive psychological effect.", "D": "Post traumatic growth is simply a flattering story people tell afterward."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The passage identifies both post traumatic growth and lasting psychological damage as genuine outcomes of adversity, and argues that the distinguishing factor is the degree of control retained and the support available rather than the severity of the hardship itself. It explicitly reframes the popular maxim as backward, proposing instead that suffering combined with sufficient resource is what allows growth. This conditional claim is more precise than either a blanket endorsement or a blanket denial of adversity's benefits.", "passage_id": "P245", "passage_title": "What Doesn't Kill You", "passage_text": "The maxim that suffering builds character carries an air of hard won wisdom, repeated by those who survived hardship and, less often, by those who merely observed it from comfort. It is worth asking whether the maxim describes a genuine psychological pattern or merely flatters those who have already endured adversity by retroactively assigning it a purpose. The honest answer, unfashionable as it is in an age fond of tidy resilience narratives, appears to be both, depending on factors the maxim itself never mentions.\n\nLongitudinal studies of people who have faced serious adversity, bereavement, financial ruin, serious illness, find a genuine phenomenon researchers term post traumatic growth, a reported increase in appreciation for life, closer relationships, and a clearer sense of priorities following the hardship. This is not merely people telling a flattering story after the fact, since the same pattern appears, though less pronounced, in measures less susceptible to self serving retelling. Adversity, it seems, can indeed sharpen certain capacities that comfort leaves dull.\n\nYet the same body of research records an equally genuine opposite pattern, adversity that leaves lasting psychological damage, eroded trust, chronic anxiety, a diminished capacity for closeness, particularly where the hardship was prolonged, inescapable, or suffered without support from others. The distinguishing factor is rarely the severity of the adversity itself but the degree of control the person retained during it and the quality of support available afterward. A brief hardship endured with the steady presence of others differs enormously, in its aftermath, from a prolonged one endured alone.\n\nThis suggests the popular maxim gets the causal story backward. It is not suffering as such that builds character, but suffering combined with sufficient resource, whether internal or social, to make sense of it and recover. Remove that resource and the same suffering, no more severe on paper, tends to damage rather than strengthen. The comforting slogan survives, one suspects, because those who did have the resources to grow from adversity are the ones left able to voice the lesson, while those who were merely broken by it are rarely in a position to correct the record."}, {"id": 984, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The description of the phone as 'less villain than symptom' in the final sentence serves mainly to", "options": {"A": "suggest that phone manufacturers bear no responsibility whatsoever.", "B": "introduce a legal metaphor to describe policy failure.", "C": "mock legislators for exaggerating the dangers of technology.", "D": "reframe blame away from the device and toward broader social conditions."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The villain-symptom contrast redirects responsibility from the device itself to the social conditions that create a need the phone merely absorbs. This phrase caps an argument built throughout the passage about deeper causes rather than the technology itself. It is not making a claim about manufacturer liability, invoking a legal framework, or ridiculing legislators, though it does imply their focus is misplaced.", "passage_id": "P246", "passage_title": "The Sociable Screen", "passage_text": "It is now a commonplace of cultural criticism that the smartphone has hollowed out the texture of human company, replacing the murmur of conversation with the silent scroll of a feed. Surveys report that young adults who spend the most hours on social platforms also report the highest rates of loneliness, and this correlation is routinely presented as proof that the technology itself is corrosive. Yet correlation of this kind conceals as much as it reveals. Those already prone to isolation, whether through shyness, geographic distance from family, or simple temperament, may gravitate toward a medium that promises company without the risks of face-to-face rejection. The screen may be less a cause of loneliness than a refuge sought by the already lonely, in which case reducing screen time would do nothing to address the underlying deficit.\n\nThere is a further complication. Loneliness is not simply the absence of contact but the perceived gap between the relationships one has and the relationships one wants. A person might exchange messages with dozens of acquaintances daily and still feel unseen, because digital exchange so often substitutes breadth for depth. The architecture of most platforms rewards the pithy, the visual, and the performative, none of which is well suited to the slow disclosure on which intimacy depends. It is telling that users who report using social media chiefly to arrange or sustain specific offline friendships show no rise in loneliness at all, while those who use it as a passive substitute for company report the sharpest increases.\n\nThis suggests that the relevant variable is not the technology but the purpose to which it is put. Banning or restricting platforms, a policy now fashionable among some legislators, treats the symptom as though it were the disease. A more exacting response would distinguish between social media used as a bridge to embodied relationships and social media used as their replacement, and would ask why so many users drift toward the latter. That drift may owe less to the seductions of the app than to the diminishing opportunities, in an atomised and time-poor society, for the unscripted encounters from which friendship has traditionally grown. The phone, on this account, is less villain than symptom, absorbing a need that the wider society has become poorly equipped to satisfy."}, {"id": 986, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The phrase 'glues for in-group solidarity' is used to convey that shared hostility toward outsiders", "options": {"A": "is a rare and unstable basis for group cohesion.", "B": "only occurs in societies with weak existing institutions.", "C": "is condemned by the author as morally indefensible.", "D": "functions efficiently to bind an accusing group together."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Calling shared hostility one of the most efficient glues signals that it works remarkably well, not rarely or unstably, to hold an accusing group together. The passage presents this as a descriptive psychological observation rather than a moral judgement or a claim tied to institutional weakness. The word glue conveys binding strength and reliability, which fits option D directly.", "passage_id": "P247", "passage_title": "The Uses of Blame", "passage_text": "When a community suffers a shock it cannot easily explain, whether an economic collapse, a plague, or a military defeat, it rarely rests content with an account that assigns responsibility to impersonal forces. Diffuse causes offer no target for grievance and no occasion for the cathartic relief that comes from punishing a wrongdoer. Historians and social psychologists have long observed that societies under such strain tend instead to identify a bounded group, frequently one already marked by some visible difference, and to fix upon it the blame for a suffering it did not create. The mechanism is not simply malice but a kind of cognitive economy: a single, nameable culprit is easier to hold in mind and easier to act against than a tangle of structural causes.\n\nWhat makes the scapegoat mechanism so durable is that it performs two functions simultaneously. It supplies an explanation, however spurious, for otherwise bewildering misfortune, and it binds the accusing group more tightly together, since shared hostility toward an outsider is among the most efficient glues for in-group solidarity. This second function helps explain why the identity of the scapegoat matters less than the act of scapegoating itself. Historically unrelated groups, Jews in medieval Europe, immigrants in periods of economic downturn, and religious minorities in times of political upheaval, have each at different moments occupied the same structural role, suggesting that the group selected is less important than the psychological needs the accusation satisfies.\n\nIt would be a mistake, however, to conclude that scapegoating is purely irrational or that it serves no one's interests. Those who direct public blame toward a vulnerable minority often have much to gain: rulers deflect scrutiny from their own failures, and rival factions consolidate power by presenting themselves as defenders against the invented threat. The psychological comfort scapegoating offers to ordinary people is thus frequently manufactured and sustained from above, even as it answers a genuine appetite, among the frightened and the humiliated, for a story simpler than the truth. Recognising this dual character, spontaneous popular need and deliberate elite exploitation, is essential to understanding why the pattern recurs with such reliability across societies with little else in common."}, {"id": 993, "domain": "argument_analysis", "question": "The critics' objection concerning 'genuine deliberation' is best understood as an argument that", "options": {"A": "nudges are largely ineffective at changing behaviour in any real practical setting.", "B": "opt-out schemes ought to be replaced entirely by outright government bans instead.", "C": "preserving a formal right to opt out does not by itself respect real autonomy.", "D": "pension enrolment schemes financially harm employees who fail to opt out."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The passage states that a government which manipulates choice architecture while leaving the choice nominally open has redefined autonomy to exclude genuine deliberation, meaning formal freedom alone is insufficient. This is not a claim about the effectiveness of nudges, a call for bans, or a claim about financial harm to employees. The objection is specifically about what autonomy actually requires beyond a nominal opt-out.", "passage_id": "P249", "passage_title": "The Architecture of Choice", "passage_text": "Governments have long possessed two blunt instruments for shaping behaviour: the mandate, which compels, and the ban, which forbids. In the last two decades a third instrument has gained favour among policymakers, the nudge, which neither compels nor forbids but redesigns the context in which people choose, so that the default option, the visual layout, or the timing of a request steers behaviour without foreclosing any alternative. Automatically enrolling employees in a pension scheme, from which they may opt out at any time, is the paradigm case: participation rises sharply compared with schemes requiring an opt-in, yet no one is prevented from declining.\n\nProponents defend nudging on the ground that some default is unavoidable, since any enrolment scheme must be designed one way or another, and that choosing the default which serves people's own long-term interests, as they themselves would articulate those interests on reflection, is preferable to choosing one at random or one that serves some other party's interest. On this view, nudging respects autonomy precisely because it preserves the formal freedom to choose otherwise, unlike a mandate, while improving upon the inertia and short-sightedness that often govern unprompted decisions.\n\nCritics reply that this defence trades on an equivocal notion of autonomy. Formal freedom to opt out means little if the entire apparatus is engineered, often without the chooser's awareness, to make one path the path of least resistance. A government that manipulates the architecture of choice while leaving the choice nominally open has not respected autonomy so much as redefined it to exclude the requirement of genuine deliberation. The worry deepens once one considers that nudges depend for their effectiveness on the very inattention and bias they are supposedly correcting, since a fully attentive, rational chooser would be immune to a change in default and would select according to their own settled preference regardless of framing.\n\nThere is also a question of who decides which interest the nudge should serve. The architect of any choice environment must have some view, however implicit, of what outcome counts as an improvement, and that view is not neutral. A policy that nudges toward saving assumes a particular ranking of present consumption against future security, a ranking not everyone shares, and one that citizens have had little opportunity to contest, since the manipulation, by design, mostly proceeds beneath the level of conscious notice."}, {"id": 995, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "The final paragraph's point about 'who decides which interest the nudge should serve' raises the concern that", "options": {"A": "policymakers lack the technical skill to design choice architecture.", "B": "nudges are illegal under most systems of government.", "C": "citizens always reject the outcomes that nudges are designed to produce.", "D": "the value judgements built into a nudge are not neutral and go largely unexamined."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The passage states that the architect of any choice environment holds an implicit view of what counts as an improvement, and that this ranking is not neutral and rarely contested since the manipulation proceeds beneath conscious notice. This is a concern about hidden value judgements, not about technical competence, legality, or citizens uniformly rejecting outcomes. The emphasis falls on the unexamined and non-neutral nature of the underlying assumptions.", "passage_id": "P249", "passage_title": "The Architecture of Choice", "passage_text": "Governments have long possessed two blunt instruments for shaping behaviour: the mandate, which compels, and the ban, which forbids. In the last two decades a third instrument has gained favour among policymakers, the nudge, which neither compels nor forbids but redesigns the context in which people choose, so that the default option, the visual layout, or the timing of a request steers behaviour without foreclosing any alternative. Automatically enrolling employees in a pension scheme, from which they may opt out at any time, is the paradigm case: participation rises sharply compared with schemes requiring an opt-in, yet no one is prevented from declining.\n\nProponents defend nudging on the ground that some default is unavoidable, since any enrolment scheme must be designed one way or another, and that choosing the default which serves people's own long-term interests, as they themselves would articulate those interests on reflection, is preferable to choosing one at random or one that serves some other party's interest. On this view, nudging respects autonomy precisely because it preserves the formal freedom to choose otherwise, unlike a mandate, while improving upon the inertia and short-sightedness that often govern unprompted decisions.\n\nCritics reply that this defence trades on an equivocal notion of autonomy. Formal freedom to opt out means little if the entire apparatus is engineered, often without the chooser's awareness, to make one path the path of least resistance. A government that manipulates the architecture of choice while leaving the choice nominally open has not respected autonomy so much as redefined it to exclude the requirement of genuine deliberation. The worry deepens once one considers that nudges depend for their effectiveness on the very inattention and bias they are supposedly correcting, since a fully attentive, rational chooser would be immune to a change in default and would select according to their own settled preference regardless of framing.\n\nThere is also a question of who decides which interest the nudge should serve. The architect of any choice environment must have some view, however implicit, of what outcome counts as an improvement, and that view is not neutral. A policy that nudges toward saving assumes a particular ranking of present consumption against future security, a ranking not everyone shares, and one that citizens have had little opportunity to contest, since the manipulation, by design, mostly proceeds beneath the level of conscious notice."}, {"id": 996, "domain": "literary_style_and_word_choice", "question": "The description of the opt-out default as 'the path of least resistance' is used to emphasise that", "options": {"A": "people tend to accept whatever option requires the least effort to follow.", "B": "opting out is technically impossible under current pension law.", "C": "the government actively forbids employees from opting out.", "D": "employees carefully weigh the merits of each pension option."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The phrase describes how defaults exploit a tendency to follow whatever requires the least effort, which is precisely the inertia the critics say nudges depend upon. It does not claim opting out is legally impossible or forbidden, since the passage repeatedly stresses that the choice remains formally open. Nor does it suggest employees deliberate carefully, since the whole point is that most do not.", "passage_id": "P249", "passage_title": "The Architecture of Choice", "passage_text": "Governments have long possessed two blunt instruments for shaping behaviour: the mandate, which compels, and the ban, which forbids. In the last two decades a third instrument has gained favour among policymakers, the nudge, which neither compels nor forbids but redesigns the context in which people choose, so that the default option, the visual layout, or the timing of a request steers behaviour without foreclosing any alternative. Automatically enrolling employees in a pension scheme, from which they may opt out at any time, is the paradigm case: participation rises sharply compared with schemes requiring an opt-in, yet no one is prevented from declining.\n\nProponents defend nudging on the ground that some default is unavoidable, since any enrolment scheme must be designed one way or another, and that choosing the default which serves people's own long-term interests, as they themselves would articulate those interests on reflection, is preferable to choosing one at random or one that serves some other party's interest. On this view, nudging respects autonomy precisely because it preserves the formal freedom to choose otherwise, unlike a mandate, while improving upon the inertia and short-sightedness that often govern unprompted decisions.\n\nCritics reply that this defence trades on an equivocal notion of autonomy. Formal freedom to opt out means little if the entire apparatus is engineered, often without the chooser's awareness, to make one path the path of least resistance. A government that manipulates the architecture of choice while leaving the choice nominally open has not respected autonomy so much as redefined it to exclude the requirement of genuine deliberation. The worry deepens once one considers that nudges depend for their effectiveness on the very inattention and bias they are supposedly correcting, since a fully attentive, rational chooser would be immune to a change in default and would select according to their own settled preference regardless of framing.\n\nThere is also a question of who decides which interest the nudge should serve. The architect of any choice environment must have some view, however implicit, of what outcome counts as an improvement, and that view is not neutral. A policy that nudges toward saving assumes a particular ranking of present consumption against future security, a ranking not everyone shares, and one that citizens have had little opportunity to contest, since the manipulation, by design, mostly proceeds beneath the level of conscious notice."}, {"id": 999, "domain": "analysis_and_interpretation", "question": "According to the passage, what do 'levelling mechanisms' such as ridicule of boastful hunters primarily indicate", "options": {"A": "that hunter-gatherer societies lacked any concept of individual achievement.", "B": "that egalitarianism required active enforcement rather than arising by default.", "C": "that dominance behaviour was entirely absent from early human societies.", "D": "that food sharing was economically inefficient for small-scale groups."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The passage describes these mechanisms as systematic and fiercely enforced, and later clarifies that egalitarian bands are societies that organised themselves with unusual effectiveness to suppress dominance rather than societies where the desire for dominance was absent. This means egalitarianism was actively maintained rather than a passive default. The passage does not discuss economic efficiency of food sharing or claim achievement was conceptually absent.", "passage_id": "P250", "passage_title": "Rank and Its Discontents", "passage_text": "Debate over whether human beings are naturally hierarchical or naturally egalitarian has tended to be conducted as though the two possibilities were mutually exclusive, with each side marshalling anthropological and primatological evidence to prove that one pattern is the default toward which unconstrained human groups will drift. Advocates of an innate hierarchical tendency point to the near universality of status ranking, dominance displays, and deference behaviour across recorded societies, and to comparable patterns among primate relatives, as evidence that humans possess an evolved disposition to sort themselves into ranked orders whenever left to their own devices.\n\nAdvocates of an egalitarian default make a different appeal, chiefly to the ethnographic record of small-scale, mobile hunter-gatherer societies, in which anthropologists have documented systematic and often fiercely enforced levelling mechanisms: ridicule of boastful hunters, collective ostracism of those who attempt to dominate others, and norms of food sharing that prevent any individual from accumulating disproportionate resources. These societies, which represent the condition in which humans lived for the overwhelming majority of their evolutionary history, suggest to some researchers that egalitarianism, far from being a fragile modern invention, is our oldest and most deeply practised political arrangement.\n\nA synthesis increasingly favoured by researchers in this area treats the apparent contradiction as evidence not of one true human nature but of two competing evolved capacities held in tension. Humans, on this account, retain a residual appetite for dominance inherited from a hierarchical primate ancestry, but they also evolved, uniquely among the great apes, a countervailing capacity for coalition-building that allows subordinates to combine forces against any individual who attempts to seize disproportionate power. Egalitarian hunter-gatherer bands are not, on this reading, societies in which the desire for dominance is absent, but societies that have organised themselves with unusual effectiveness to suppress it.\n\nThis reframing carries an important implication: the emergence of stratified, hierarchical states in the archaeological record need not be read as humanity finally reverting to type after millennia of egalitarian deviation. It may instead reflect the historical conditions, storable surpluses, standing armies, and administrative technologies, under which the older coalition-based checks on aspiring dominators simply stopped working, allowing a suppressed tendency to resurface rather than a repressed truth to be revealed for the first time."}];
